         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Hunger_Games:_Mockingjay_%E2%80%93_Part_1" title="The Hunger Games: Mockingjay – Part 1">The Hunger Games: Mockingjay – Part 1</a> (<small>2014 film by Francis Lawrence</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>The Hunger Games: Mockingjay – Part 1</i> is a 2014 American <a href="/wiki/Utopian_and_dystopian_fiction" title="Utopian and dystopian fiction">dystopian</a> <a href="/wiki/Science_fiction_film" title="Science fiction film">science fiction</a> <a href="/wiki/Adventure_film" title="Adventure film">adventure film</a> directed by <a href="/wiki/Francis_Lawrence" title="Francis Lawrence">Francis Lawrence</a> with a screenplay by <a href="/wiki/Peter_Craig" title="Peter Craig">Peter Craig</a> and <a href="/wiki/Danny_Strong" title="Danny Strong">Danny Strong</a>. It is the first of two films based on <a href="/wiki/Suzanne_Collins" title="Suzanne Collins">Suzanne Collins</a>' 2010 novel <i> <a href="/wiki/Mockingjay" title="Mockingjay">Mockingjay</a></i>, the final book in <i><a href="/wiki/The_Hunger_Games" title="The Hunger Games">The Hunger Games</a></i> trilogy, and the third installment in <a href="/wiki/The_Hunger_Games_(film_series)" title="The Hunger Games (film series)"><i>The Hunger Games</i> film series</a>, produced by <a href="/wiki/Nina_Jacobson" title="Nina Jacobson">Nina Jacobson</a> and Jon Kilik and distributed by <a href="/wiki/Lionsgate" title="Lionsgate">Lionsgate</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Some_Dude_From_North_Carolina" title="User:Some Dude From North Carolina">Some Dude From North Carolina</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Some_Dude_From_North_Carolina" title="User talk:Some Dude From North Carolina">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Hunger_Games:_Catching_Fire" title="The Hunger Games: Catching Fire">The Hunger Games: Catching Fire</a> (<small>2013 film by Francis Lawrence</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>The Hunger Games: Catching Fire</i> is a 2013 American <a href="/wiki/Utopian_and_dystopian_fiction" title="Utopian and dystopian fiction">dystopian</a> <a href="/wiki/Science_fiction_film" title="Science fiction film">science fiction</a> <a href="/wiki/Adventure_film" title="Adventure film">adventure film</a> based on <a href="/wiki/Suzanne_Collins" title="Suzanne Collins">Suzanne Collins</a>' <a href="/wiki/Dystopian_novel" class="mw-redirect" title="Dystopian novel">dystopian novel</a> <i><a href="/wiki/Catching_Fire" title="Catching Fire">Catching Fire</a></i> (2009), the second installment in <a href="/wiki/The_Hunger_Games" title="The Hunger Games"><i>The Hunger Games</i> trilogy</a>. The film is the sequel to <i><a href="/wiki/The_Hunger_Games_(film)" title="The Hunger Games (film)">The Hunger Games</a></i> (2012) and the second installment in <a href="/wiki/The_Hunger_Games_(film_series)" title="The Hunger Games (film series)"><i>The Hunger Games</i> film series</a>, produced by <a href="/wiki/Nina_Jacobson" title="Nina Jacobson">Nina Jacobson</a> and Jon Kilik, with co-production by <a href="/wiki/Lionsgate_Films" title="Lionsgate Films">Lionsgate Films</a> and distributed by <a href="/wiki/Lionsgate_Entertainment" class="mw-redirect" title="Lionsgate Entertainment">Lionsgate Entertainment</a>. </td>

         <td><i>The Hunger Games: Mockingjay – Part 2</i> is a 2015 American <a href="/wiki/Utopian_and_dystopian_fiction" title="Utopian and dystopian fiction">dystopian</a> <a href="/wiki/Science_fiction_film" title="Science fiction film">science fiction</a> <a href="/wiki/Adventure_film" title="Adventure film">adventure film</a> directed by <a href="/wiki/Francis_Lawrence" title="Francis Lawrence">Francis Lawrence</a>, with a screenplay by <a href="/wiki/Peter_Craig" title="Peter Craig">Peter Craig</a> and <a href="/wiki/Danny_Strong" title="Danny Strong">Danny Strong</a>. It is the fourth and final installment in <a href="/wiki/The_Hunger_Games_(film_series)" title="The Hunger Games (film series)"><i>The Hunger Games</i> film series</a>, and the second of two films based on the 2010 novel <i><a href="/wiki/Mockingjay" title="Mockingjay">Mockingjay</a></i>, the final book in <a href="/wiki/The_Hunger_Games" title="The Hunger Games"><i>The Hunger Games</i> trilogy</a> by <a href="/wiki/Suzanne_Collins" title="Suzanne Collins">Suzanne Collins</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Tetris_Holding,_LLC_v._Xio_Interactive,_Inc." title="Tetris Holding, LLC v. Xio Interactive, Inc.">Tetris Holding, LLC v. Xio Interactive, Inc.</a> (<small>2012 legal decision</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Tetris Holding, LLC v. Xio Interactive, Inc.</i>, 863 F.Supp.2d 394 (D.N.J. 2012), is a legal case related to <a href="/wiki/Copyright_of_video_games" class="mw-redirect" title="Copyright of video games">copyright of video games</a> confirming that a video game's <a href="/wiki/Look_and_feel" title="Look and feel">look and feel</a> can be protected under copyright law. Tetris Holding is a company that holds the Copyright to the original <i><a href="/wiki/Tetris" title="Tetris">Tetris</a> </i> game from 1984, and licenses those rights to other game developers. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Genshin_Impact" title="Genshin Impact">Genshin Impact</a> (<small>2020 action role-playing video game</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Genshin Impact</i> is an <a href="/wiki/Action_role-playing_game" title="Action role-playing game">action role-playing game</a> developed and published by <a href="/wiki/MiHoYo" title="MiHoYo">miHoYo</a>. The game features an <a href="/wiki/Open-world" class="mw-redirect" title="Open-world">open-world</a> environment and action-based battle system using elemental <a href="/wiki/Magic_(game_terminology)" title="Magic (game terminology)">magic</a> and character-switching, and uses <a href="/wiki/Gacha_game" title="Gacha game">gacha game</a> <a href="/wiki/Video_game_monetization" title="Video game monetization">monetization</a> for players to obtain new characters, weapons, and other resources. </td>

         <td class="recent">2021-04-01 17:48 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Dragon_Age:_Origins_%E2%80%93_Return_to_Ostagar" title="Dragon Age: Origins – Return to Ostagar">Dragon Age: Origins – Return to Ostagar</a> </td> 
         <td><i>Dragon Age: Origins – Return to Ostagar</i> is a <a href="/wiki/Downloadable_content" title="Downloadable content">downloadable content</a> (DLC) pack developed by <a href="/wiki/BioWare" title="BioWare">BioWare</a> and published by <a href="/wiki/Electronic_Arts" title="Electronic Arts">Electronic Arts</a> for the 2009 video game <i><a href="/wiki/Dragon_Age:_Origins" title="Dragon Age: Origins">Dragon Age: Origins</a></i>.          <td><a href="/wiki/Kiki_Wolfkill" title="Kiki Wolfkill">Kiki Wolfkill</a> (<small>Video game developer</small>) </td> 
         <td>Kiki Wolfkill is an American <a href="/wiki/Video_game_developer" title="Video game developer">video game developer</a>. Wolfkill grew up in <a href="/wiki/Pennsylvania" title="Pennsylvania">Pennsylvania</a> and studied journalism and art at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Washington" title="University of Washington">University of Washington</a>, racing competitively on the side. At <a href="/wiki/Microsoft" title="Microsoft">Microsoft</a>, she transitioned from developing multimedia for <i><a href="/wiki/Encarta" title="Encarta">Microsoft Encarta</a></i> to working on art for Microsoft's video games, including the racing series <i><a href="/wiki/Midtown_Madness" title="Midtown Madness">Midtown Madness</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Project_Gotham_Racing" title="Project Gotham Racing">Project Gotham Racing</a></i>. </td>

         <td><i>Celeste</i> is a 2018 <a href="/wiki/Platform_game" title="Platform game">platforming</a> <a href="/wiki/Video_game" title="Video game">video game</a> designed, directed and written by <a href="/wiki/Maddy_Thorson" title="Maddy Thorson">Maddy Thorson</a> and programmed by Thorson and Noel Berry. It is a fully-fleshed version of the 2016 <a href="/wiki/Pico-8" title="Pico-8">PICO-8</a> game of the same name, which was made in four days solely by Thorson and Berry during a <a href="/wiki/Game_jam" title="Game jam">game jam</a>. Set on a fictional version of <a href="/wiki/Mount_Celeste" title="Mount Celeste">Mount Celeste</a>, it follows a young woman named <a href="/wiki/Madeline_(Celeste)" title="Madeline (Celeste)">Madeline</a> who attempts to climb the mountain, and must face her inner demons in her quest to reach the summit. </td>

         <td>James Charles Dickinson (born 1999) is an American <a href="/wiki/Beauty_YouTuber" title="Beauty YouTuber">beauty YouTuber</a> and <a href="/wiki/Make-up_artist" title="Make-up artist">make-up artist</a>. While working as a local makeup artist in his hometown of <a href="/wiki/Bethlehem,_New_York" title="Bethlehem, New York">Bethlehem, New York</a>, he started a YouTube channel, posting makeup tutorials. In 2016, he became the first male <a href="/wiki/Brand_ambassador" title="Brand ambassador">brand ambassador</a> for <a href="/wiki/CoverGirl" title="CoverGirl">CoverGirl</a> after a tweet featuring his makeup went viral online. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Tomba!" title="Tomba!">Tomba!</a> </td> 
         <td><i>Tomba!</i> is a <a href="/wiki/Platform-adventure_game" class="mw-redirect" title="Platform-adventure game">platform-adventure game</a> developed by Whoopee Camp and published by <a href="/wiki/Sony_Computer_Entertainment" class="mw-redirect" title="Sony Computer Entertainment">Sony Computer Entertainment</a> for the <a href="/wiki/PlayStation_(console)" title="PlayStation (console)">PlayStation</a>. It was released in Japan in 1997 and in other territories the following year. The game centers on the exploits of a pink-haired <a href="/wiki/Feral_child" title="Feral child">feral child</a> named Tomba as he attempts to recover his grandfather's bracelet from an evil race of anthropomorphic pigs. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Leave_Me_Be" title="Leave Me Be">Leave Me Be</a> (<small>1964 single by the Zombies</small>) </td> 
         <td>"Leave Me Be" is a song written by British bassist <a href="/wiki/Chris_White_(musician)" title="Chris White (musician)">Chris White</a> and initially recorded by his band <a href="/wiki/The_Zombies" title="The Zombies">the Zombies</a>. Following the release of their debut single "<a href="/wiki/She%27s_Not_There" title="She's Not There">She's Not There</a>" in July 1964, White wrote a handful of songs in between performances during their hectic schedule. Characterized by its usage of <a href="/wiki/Minor_chord" title="Minor chord">minor chords</a> and <a href="/wiki/Chord_progression" title="Chord progression">chord progression</a>, the song lyrically deals with loneliness, a common theme in the Zombies music. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Blue_Murder_(album)" title="Blue Murder (album)">Blue Murder (album)</a> (<small>1989 studio album by Blue Murder</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Blue Murder</i> is the eponymous debut album by English <a href="/wiki/Hard_rock" title="Hard rock">hard rock</a> band <a href="/wiki/Blue_Murder_(band)" title="Blue Murder (band)">Blue Murder</a>. Released on 24 April 1989 by <a href="/wiki/Geffen_Records" title="Geffen Records">Geffen Records</a>, it was produced by <a href="/wiki/Bob_Rock" title="Bob Rock">Bob Rock</a>. The band was formed by guitarist <a href="/wiki/John_Sykes" title="John Sykes">John Sykes</a> after his dismissal from <a href="/wiki/Whitesnake" title="Whitesnake">Whitesnake</a>. He recruited drummer <a href="/wiki/Cozy_Powell" title="Cozy Powell">Cozy Powell</a>, bassist <a href="/wiki/Tony_Franklin_(musician)" title="Tony Franklin (musician)">Tony Franklin</a> and vocalist <a href="/wiki/Ray_Gillen" title="Ray Gillen">Ray Gillen</a> in early 1987. </td>

        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-06-04 20:19 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/English_determiners" title="English determiners">English determiners</a> </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/English_language" title="English language">English</a> <a href="/wiki/Determiner_(linguistics)" class="mw-redirect" title="Determiner (linguistics)">determiners</a> (also known as determinatives)<sup class="reference" style="white-space:nowrap;">:<span>354</span></sup> are <a href="/wiki/Word" title="Word">words</a> – such as <i>the</i>, <i>a</i>, <i>each</i>, <i>some</i>, <i>which</i>, <i>this</i>, <i>no</i>, etc. – such as <i>the</i>, <i>a</i>, <i>each</i>, <i>some</i>, <i>which</i>, <i>this</i>, <i>no</i>, etc. – that are used with <a href="/wiki/Noun" title="Noun">nouns</a> to specify their <a href="/wiki/Referent" title="Referent">referents</a>. The determiners form a <a href="/wiki/Lexical_category" class="mw-redirect" title="Lexical category">lexical category</a> in English. Their most characteristic syntactic position is at the beginning of a <a href="/wiki/Noun_phrase" title="Noun phrase">noun phrase</a>, before any <a href="/wiki/Grammatical_modifier" title="Grammatical modifier">modifiers</a> (e.g., <i><u>some</u> very pretty wool sweaters</i>). </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Brett" title="User:Brett">Brett</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Brett" title="User talk:Brett">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>
       </tbody>
      </table>

         <td><a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>, a fantasy author and professional <a href="/wiki/Philologist" class="mw-redirect" title="Philologist">philologist</a>, drew on the <a href="/wiki/Old_English" title="Old English">Old English</a> poem <i><a href="/wiki/Beowulf" title="Beowulf">Beowulf</a></i> for multiple aspects of his <a href="/wiki/Middle-earth" title="Middle-earth">Middle-earth</a> legendarium: in terms of elements such as names, monsters, and the structure of society in a heroic age; in terms of style such as creating an <a href="/wiki/Impression_of_depth_in_The_Lord_of_the_Rings" title="Impression of depth in The Lord of the Rings">impression of depth</a> and adopting an <a href="/wiki/Decline_and_fall_in_Middle-earth#Fading" title="Decline and fall in Middle-earth">elegiac tone</a>; and in terms of its larger but hidden symbolism. </td>

         <td>"The Man in the Moon Stayed Up Too Late" is <a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s imagined original ditty behind the <a href="/wiki/Nursery_rhyme" title="Nursery rhyme">nursery rhyme</a> "<a href="/wiki/Hey_Diddle_Diddle" title="Hey Diddle Diddle">Hey Diddle Diddle</a> (The Cat and the Fiddle)", invented by <a href="/wiki/Back_formation" class="mw-redirect" title="Back formation">back formation</a>. The title of the extended 1962 version is given in <i><a href="/wiki/The_Adventures_of_Tom_Bombadil" title="The Adventures of Tom Bombadil">The Adventures of Tom Bombadil</a></i>. It was first published in <i>Yorkshire Poetry</i> in 1923. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Lev_Levanda" title="Lev Levanda">Lev Levanda</a> (<small>Russian author (1935-1888)</small>) </td> 
         <td>Lev (Yehuda Leyb) Osipovitch Levanda (Russian: <span lang="ru">??? ???????? ???????</span>, <a href="/wiki/Yiddish_language" class="mw-redirect" title="Yiddish language">Yiddish</a>: <span lang="yi" dir="rtl">????? ???? ?????????</span>?; June 1835 – 18 June 1888) was a Russian author, <a href="/wiki/Belles-lettres" title="Belles-lettres">belletrist</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Publication" title="Publication">publicist</a>. His literary work made him a leading figure in the circles of the Russian-Jewish intelligentsia. Originally a vocal proponent of the <a href="/wiki/Jewish_assimilation" title="Jewish assimilation">assimilation of Jews</a> into Russian culture, Levanda became a strong supporter of their <a href="/wiki/Aliyah" title="Aliyah">emigration</a> to <a href="/wiki/Palestine_(region)" title="Palestine (region)">Palestine</a> following the <a href="/wiki/Anti-Jewish_pogroms_in_the_Russian_Empire#1881–84" class="mw-redirect" title="Anti-Jewish pogroms in the Russian Empire">1881–82 pogroms</a> across the <a href="/wiki/Russian_Empire" title="Russian Empire">Russian Empire</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Man_(Middle-earth)" title="Man (Middle-earth)">Man (Middle-earth)</a> (<small>The human race as it appears in J. R. R. Tolkien's Middle-earth fiction</small>) </td> 
         <td>In <a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Middle-earth" title="Middle-earth">Middle-earth</a> fiction, Man and Men denote <a href="/wiki/Human" title="Human">humans</a>, whether male or female, in contrast to <a href="/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)" title="Elf (Middle-earth)">Elves</a>, <a href="/wiki/Dwarf_(Middle-earth)" title="Dwarf (Middle-earth)">Dwarves</a>, <a href="/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)" class="mw-redirect" title="Orc (Middle-earth)">Orcs</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Middle-earth_peoples" title="Middle-earth peoples">other humanoid races</a>. <p>Men are described as the second or younger people, created after the Elves, and differing from them in being mortal. Along with <a href="/wiki/Ent" title="Ent">Ents</a> and Dwarves, these are the "free peoples" of Middle-earth, differing from the enslaved peoples such as <a href="/wiki/Orc" title="Orc">Orcs</a>. </p> </td>

         <td>Goldberry is a character from the works of author <a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>. She first appeared in print in a 1934 poem called <i>The Adventures of Tom Bombadil</i>, where she appears as the wife of <a href="/wiki/Tom_Bombadil" title="Tom Bombadil">Tom Bombadil</a>. Also known as the "River-woman's daughter", she is described as a beautiful, youthful woman with golden hair. </td>

         <td class="recent">2021-03-25 23:44 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Dream_of_Ossian" title="The Dream of Ossian">The Dream of Ossian</a> (<small>Painting by Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>The Dream of Ossian</i> is an 1813 painting by the French artist <a href="/wiki/Jean-Auguste-Dominique_Ingres" title="Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres">Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres</a>. The work depicts the legendary poet <a href="/wiki/Ossian" title="Ossian">Ossian</a> sleeping while he dreams of relatives, warriors, and maidens, which appear above him on the canvas. Ingres was likely influenced by his contemporaries' Ossianic works, such as <a href="/wiki/Fran%C3%A7ois_G%C3%A9rard" title="François Gérard">François Gérard</a>'s 1801 painting <i>Ossian Evoking Phantoms</i>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:GeneralPoxter" title="User:GeneralPoxter">GeneralPoxter</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:GeneralPoxter" title="User talk:GeneralPoxter">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Berliner_Journal" title="Berliner Journal">Berliner Journal</a> (<small>19th and 20th-century Berlin-Kitchener newspaper</small>) </td> 
         <td>The <i>Berliner Journal</i> (later the <i>Ontario Journal</i>) was a German language <a href="/wiki/Weekly_newspaper" title="Weekly newspaper">weekly newspaper</a> published in <a href="/wiki/Berlin,_Ontario" class="mw-redirect" title="Berlin, Ontario">Berlin, Ontario</a> (later Kitchener) from 1859 to 1918. Founded by German immigrants <a href="/w/index.php?title=Friedrich_Rittinger&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Friedrich Rittinger (page does not exist)">Friedrich Rittinger</a><span class="noprint" style="font-size:85%; font-style: normal;">&nbsp;[<a href="https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Rittinger" class="extiw" title="de:Friedrich Rittinger">de</a>]</span> and <a href="/w/index.php?title=John_Motz&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="John Motz (page does not exist)">John Motz</a><span class="noprint" style="font-size:85%; font-style: normal;">&nbsp;[<a href="https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Motz" class="extiw" title="de:John Motz">de</a>]</span>, they operated the paper through most of its existence until their sons – <a href="/w/index.php?title=William_John_Motz&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="William John Motz (page does not exist)">William John Motz</a>, Herman Rittinger and <a href="/wiki/John_Adam_Rittinger" title="John Adam Rittinger">John Adam Rittinger</a> – took over the operation at the turn of the century. </td> 
         <td><span style="font-weight:bold;text-shadow:1px 1px 40px black"><a href="/wiki/User:Tkbrett" title="User:Tkbrett"><b><span style="color: #000000;">Tkbrett</span></b></a><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Tkbrett" title="User talk:Tkbrett"><span style="color: #FF0000;"> (?)</span></a></span> </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Zygmunt_Krasi%C5%84ski" title="Zygmunt Krasi?ski">Zygmunt Krasi?ski</a> (<small>Polish poet</small>) </td> 
         <td>Napoleon Stanis?aw Adam Feliks Zygmunt Krasi?ski (; 19 February 1812 – 23 February 1859) was a <a href="/wiki/Polish_people" class="mw-redirect" title="Polish people">Polish</a> poet traditionally ranked with <a href="/wiki/Adam_Mickiewicz" title="Adam Mickiewicz">Adam Mickiewicz</a> and <a href="/wiki/Juliusz_S%C5%82owacki" title="Juliusz S?owacki">Juliusz S?owacki</a> as one of <a href="/wiki/Poland" title="Poland">Poland</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Three_Bards" title="Three Bards">Three Bards</a> – the trio of <a href="/wiki/Romanticism" title="Romanticism">Romantic</a> poets who influenced national consciousness in the <a href="/wiki/Partitions_of_Poland" title="Partitions of Poland">period of Poland's political bondage</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/England_in_Middle-earth" title="England in Middle-earth">England in Middle-earth</a> (<small>Theme of England and Englishness in Tolkien's Middle-earth</small>) </td> 
         <td>England and <a href="/wiki/English_national_identity" title="English national identity">Englishness</a> appear in <a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s Middle-earth, more or less thinly disguised, in the form of <a href="/wiki/The_Shire" title="The Shire">the Shire</a> and the lands close to it; in kindly characters such as <a href="/wiki/Treebeard" title="Treebeard">Treebeard</a>, <a href="/wiki/Faramir" title="Faramir">Faramir</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Th%C3%A9oden" title="Théoden">Théoden</a>; in its industrialised state as <a href="/wiki/Isengard" title="Isengard">Isengard</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mordor" title="Mordor">Mordor</a>; and as <a href="/wiki/Anglo-Saxon_England" class="mw-redirect" title="Anglo-Saxon England">Anglo-Saxon England</a> in <a href="/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)" title="Rohan (Middle-earth)">Rohan</a>. Lastly, and most pervasively, Englishness appears in the words and behaviour of the hobbits, both in <i><a href="/wiki/The_Hobbit" title="The Hobbit">The Hobbit</a></i> and in <i><a href="/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings" title="The Lord of the Rings">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Chiswick_Chap" title="User:Chiswick Chap">Chiswick Chap</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Chiswick_Chap" title="User talk:Chiswick Chap">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Judge_Doom" title="Judge Doom">Judge Doom</a> (<small>Fictional character in the film Who Framed Roger Rabbit</small>) </td>

He is depicted as a much feared, cruel, and evil <a href="/wiki/Judge" title="Judge">judge</a> of Toontown, who is later to be revealed as the mastermind for the titular framing of the <a href="/wiki/Roger_Rabbit" title="Roger Rabbit">title character</a> and the killing of protagonist <a href="/wiki/Eddie_Valiant" title="Eddie Valiant">Eddie Valiant</a>'s brother within the film. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Tolkien%27s_frame_stories" title="Tolkien's frame stories">Tolkien's frame stories</a> (<small>J. R. R. Tolkien's use of stories to frame his novels</small>) </td> 
         <td>Tolkien's frame stories are the narrative devices that <a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien">J. R. R. Tolkien</a> chose to use throughout his <a href="/wiki/Middle-earth" title="Middle-earth">Middle-earth</a> writings, especially <a href="/wiki/Tolkien%27s_legendarium" title="Tolkien's legendarium">his legendarium</a>, to make the works <a href="/wiki/Mythopoeia" title="Mythopoeia">resemble a genuine mythology</a> written and edited by many hands over a long period of time. He described in detail how his fictional characters wrote their books and transmitted them to others, and showed how later editors annotated the material. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Japanese_idol" title="Japanese idol">Japanese idol</a> (<small>Japanese type of entertainer</small>) </td> 
         <td>An idol<span style="font-weight: normal"> (<span lang="ja" title="Japanese-language text">????</span>, <i lang="ja-Latn" title="Hepburn transliteration">aidoru</i>)</span> is a type of entertainer manufactured and marketed for image, attractiveness, and personality in Japanese pop culture. Idols are primarily singers with training in acting, dancing, and modeling. Idols are commercialized through merchandise and endorsements by <a href="/wiki/Talent_agent" title="Talent agent">talent agencies</a>, while maintaining a <a href="/wiki/Parasocial_relationship" class="mw-redirect" title="Parasocial relationship">parasocial relationship</a> with a passionate consumer fan base. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/George_Livermore" title="George Livermore">George Livermore</a> </td> 
         <td>George Livermore (July 10, 1809 – August 30, 1865) was an American <a href="/wiki/Antiquarian" title="Antiquarian">antiquarian</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bibliographer" class="mw-redirect" title="Bibliographer">bibliographer</a>, and historian, known chiefly as a book collector, who had many valuable old books. He developed in his lifetime what was recognized as one of the finest private libraries in the United States. His library included many rare and one-of-a-kind bibles including some printed by <a href="/wiki/Gutenberg" class="mw-redirect" title="Gutenberg">Gutenberg</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Doug_Coldwell" title="User:Doug Coldwell">Doug Coldwell</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Doug_Coldwell" title="User talk:Doug Coldwell">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="new">2021-05-21 19:32 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Time_travel_in_The_Lord_of_the_Rings" title="Time travel in The Lord of the Rings">Time travel in The Lord of the Rings</a> (<small>distortions of time in fantasy by J. R. R. Tolkien</small>) </td> 
         <td>Tolkien embedded time travel in <i>The Lord of the Rings</i> in a variety of ways. The passage of time in the book is uneven, seeming to run at differing speeds in the realms of <a href="/wiki/Men_(Middle-earth)" class="mw-redirect" title="Men (Middle-earth)">Men</a> and of <a href="/wiki/Elves_(Middle-Earth)" class="mw-redirect" title="Elves (Middle-Earth)">Elves</a>. In this, <a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien">Tolkien</a> was following medieval tradition in which time proceeds differently in <a href="/wiki/Elfland" class="mw-redirect" title="Elfland">Elfland</a>. The whole work, too, following the theory he spelt out in his essay "<a href="/wiki/On_Fairy-Stories" title="On Fairy-Stories">On Fairy-Stories</a>", is meant to transport the reader into another time. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Chiswick_Chap" title="User:Chiswick Chap">Chiswick Chap</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Chiswick_Chap" title="User talk:Chiswick Chap">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="new">2021-05-21 21:28 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Callimachus" title="Callimachus">Callimachus</a> (<small>Ancient poet and librarian</small>) </td> 
         <td>Callimachus was an <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greek" title="Ancient Greek">ancient Greek</a> <a href="/wiki/Poet" title="Poet">poet</a>, <a href="/wiki/Scholar" title="Scholar">scholar</a> and <a href="/wiki/Librarian" title="Librarian">librarian</a> who was active in <a href="/wiki/Alexandria" title="Alexandria">Alexandria</a> during the 3rd century BC. A representative of <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greek_literature" title="Ancient Greek literature">Ancient Greek literature</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Hellenistic_period" title="Hellenistic period">Hellenistic period</a>, he wrote over 800 literary works in a wide variety of genres, most of which did not survive. He espoused an <a href="/wiki/Aesthetic_philosophy" class="mw-redirect" title="Aesthetic philosophy">aesthetic philosophy</a>, known as Callimacheanism, which exerted a strong influence on the poets of the <a href="/wiki/Roman_Empire" title="Roman Empire">Roman Empire</a> and, through them, on all subsequent <a href="/wiki/Western_canon" title="Western canon">Western literature</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Modussiccandi" title="User:Modussiccandi">Modussiccandi</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Modussiccandi" title="User talk:Modussiccandi">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-24 19:16 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Robert_Ludwig_Kahn" title="Robert Ludwig Kahn">Robert Ludwig Kahn</a> </td> 
         <td>Robert Ludwig Kahn (April 22, 1923 – March 22, 1970) was a German-American scholar of German studies and poet. He grew up in Nuremberg and Leipzig as the son of Jewish parents who, before they perished in the Holocaust, sent him abroad on a <a href="/wiki/Kindertransport" title="Kindertransport">Kindertransport</a>. After internment on the Isle of Man and in Canada, he studied at <a href="/wiki/Dalhousie_University" title="Dalhousie University">Dalhousie University</a> and the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Toronto" title="University of Toronto">University of Toronto</a>. </td> 
         <td>—<a href="/wiki/User:Kusma" title="User:Kusma">Kusma</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Kusma" title="User talk:Kusma">t</a>·<a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/Kusma" title="Special:Contributions/Kusma">c</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Frances_Spatz_Leighton" title="Frances Spatz Leighton">Frances Spatz Leighton</a> (<small>American author</small>) </td> 
         <td>Frances Spatz Ornstein Leighton (September 4, 1919&nbsp;– April 6, 2007) was an American author best known for her <a href="/wiki/Ghostwriting" class="mw-redirect" title="Ghostwriting">ghostwriting</a> of accounts of Washington, D.C., life. Leighton wrote or ghostwrote over 30 books, including <i><a href="/wiki/My_Thirty_Years_Backstairs_at_the_White_House" title="My Thirty Years Backstairs at the White House">My Thirty Years Backstairs at the White House</a></i> (1961) and <i><a href="/wiki/My_Life_with_Jacqueline_Kennedy" title="My Life with Jacqueline Kennedy">My Life with Jacqueline Kennedy</a></i> (1969). </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Hill_We_Climb" title="The Hill We Climb">The Hill We Climb</a> (<small>Poem by Amanda Gorman</small>) </td> 
         <td>"The Hill We Climb" is a <a href="/wiki/Spoken_word" title="Spoken word">spoken word</a> poem written by American poet <a href="/wiki/Amanda_Gorman" title="Amanda Gorman">Amanda Gorman</a> and recited by her at the <a href="/wiki/Inauguration_of_Joe_Biden" title="Inauguration of Joe Biden">inauguration of Joe Biden</a> on January 20, 2021. The poem was written in the weeks following the <a href="/wiki/2020_United_States_presidential_election" title="2020 United States presidential election">2020 United States presidential election</a>, with significant passages written on the night of January 6, 2021, in response to the <a href="/wiki/2021_storming_of_the_United_States_Capitol" class="mw-redirect" title="2021 storming of the United States Capitol">storming of the United States Capitol</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/2020_World_Rally_Championship" title="2020 World Rally Championship">2020 World Rally Championship</a> (<small>48th running of the World Rally Championship</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 2020 FIA World Rally Championship was the forty-eighth season of the <a href="/wiki/World_Rally_Championship" title="World Rally Championship">World Rally Championship</a>, an <a href="/wiki/Auto_racing" title="Auto racing">auto racing</a> competition recognised by the <a href="/wiki/F%C3%A9d%C3%A9ration_Internationale_de_l%27Automobile" title="Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile">Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile</a> (FIA) as the highest class of international <a href="/wiki/Rallying" title="Rallying">rallying</a>. Teams and crews were competing in seven rallies for the <a href="/wiki/List_of_World_Rally_Championship_Drivers%27_champions" title="List of World Rally Championship Drivers' champions">World Rally Championships for Drivers</a>, <a href="/wiki/Co-driver" title="Co-driver">Co-drivers</a> and <a href="/wiki/List_of_World_Rally_Championship_Constructors%27_champions" title="List of World Rally Championship Constructors' champions">Manufacturers</a>. </td>

Nicknamed "The Springfield Rifle," he was one of the top pitchers for the <a href="/wiki/New_York_Yankees" title="New York Yankees">New York Yankees</a> in the late 1940s and early 1950s, forming (with <a href="/wiki/Allie_Reynolds" title="Allie Reynolds">Allie Reynolds</a> and <a href="/wiki/Eddie_Lopat" title="Eddie Lopat">Eddie Lopat</a>) the "Big Three" of the Yankees' pitching staff. </td>

         <td>John Caldwell (4 July 1849 – 7 March 1916) was a nineteenth century farmer and timber man of <a href="/wiki/Northern_Michigan" title="Northern Michigan">northern Michigan</a>, especially associated with <a href="/wiki/Missaukee_County,_Michigan" title="Missaukee County, Michigan">Missaukee County, Michigan</a>. For several years he was employed by the Mitchell Brothers Company, a land agent firm in several states associated large tracts of timber for making lumber. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Mike_Cuellar" title="Mike Cuellar">Mike Cuellar</a> (<small>Cuban baseball player</small>) </td> 
         <td>Miguel Ángel Cuellar Santana (<a href="/wiki/Help:Pronunciation_respelling_key" title="Help:Pronunciation respelling key"><i title="English pronunciation respelling"><span style="font-size:90%">KWAY</span>-ar</i></a>; May 8, 1937 – April 2, 2010) was a <a href="/wiki/Cubans" title="Cubans">Cuban</a> professional <a href="/wiki/Baseball" title="Baseball">baseball</a> player. He played for 15 seasons in <a href="/wiki/Major_League_Baseball" title="Major League Baseball">Major League Baseball</a> as a left-handed <a href="/wiki/Pitcher" title="Pitcher">pitcher</a> in 1959 and from 1964 through 1977. His longest tenure was eight years with the <a href="/wiki/Baltimore_Orioles" title="Baltimore Orioles">Baltimore Orioles</a>, who won the <a href="/wiki/List_of_American_League_pennant_winners" title="List of American League pennant winners">American League (AL) pennant</a> in each of Cuellar's first three seasons with the team. </td>

He was the manager, director, or trustee in several firms and organizations.          <td><a href="/wiki/K._T._Oslin" title="K. T. Oslin">K. T. Oslin</a> (<small>American singer-songwriter</small>) </td> 
         <td>Kay Toinette Oslin (May 15, 1942 – December 21, 2020) was an American <a href="/wiki/Country_music" title="Country music">country music</a> singer–songwriter. Oslin had several years of major commercial success in the late 1980s after signing a record deal at age 45. She had four number one hits and placed additional singles on the <i><a href="/wiki/Billboard_(magazine)" title="Billboard (magazine)">Billboard</a></i> country chart during that timespan; in addition, she won three <a href="/wiki/Grammy_Awards" title="Grammy Awards">Grammy Awards</a> and is an inductee of the <a href="/wiki/Nashville_Songwriters_Hall_of_Fame" title="Nashville Songwriters Hall of Fame">Nashville Songwriters Hall of Fame</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:ChrisTofu11961" title="User:ChrisTofu11961">ChrisTofu11961</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:ChrisTofu11961" title="User talk:ChrisTofu11961">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="old">2021-02-05 15:16 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Ink_wash_painting" title="Ink wash painting">Ink wash painting</a> (<small>East Asian painting style using black ink of different concentrations</small>) </td> 
         <td>Ink wash painting is a type of <a href="/wiki/East_Asia" title="East Asia">East Asian</a> <a href="/wiki/Ink_brush" title="Ink brush">brush</a> <a href="/wiki/Painting" title="Painting">painting</a> that uses the same <a href="/wiki/Black_ink" class="mw-redirect" title="Black ink">black ink</a> used in <a href="/wiki/East_Asian_calligraphy" class="mw-redirect" title="East Asian calligraphy">East Asian calligraphy</a> in different concentrations. Emerging in <a href="/wiki/Tang_dynasty" title="Tang dynasty">Tang dynasty</a> China (618–907), it overturned earlier, more <a href="/wiki/Realism_(arts)" title="Realism (arts)">realistic</a> techniques. It is typically <a href="/wiki/Monochrome" title="Monochrome">monochrome</a>, using only shades of black, with a great emphasis on virtuoso brushwork and conveying the perceived "spirit" or "essence" of a subject over the direct <a href="/wiki/Mimesis" title="Mimesis">imitation</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Jujiang" title="User:Jujiang">Jujiang</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Jujiang" title="User talk:Jujiang">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td>The 2020 Salvadoran political crisis, commonly referred to as 9F or 9-F, occurred on 9 February 2020 when Salvadoran President <a href="/wiki/Nayib_Bukele" title="Nayib Bukele">Nayib Bukele</a> sent forty soldiers from the <a href="/wiki/Salvadoran_Army" title="Salvadoran Army">Salvadoran Army</a> into the <a href="/wiki/Legislative_Assembly_of_El_Salvador" title="Legislative Assembly of El Salvador">Legislative Assembly</a> building in an effort to coerce politicians to approve a loan request of 109 million dollars from the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> for Bukele's security plan for the country. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Lev_Levanda" title="Lev Levanda">Lev Levanda</a> (<small>Russian author (1935-1888)</small>) </td> 
         <td>Lev (Yehuda Leyb) Osipovitch Levanda (Russian: <span lang="ru">??? ???????? ???????</span>, <a href="/wiki/Yiddish_language" class="mw-redirect" title="Yiddish language">Yiddish</a>: <span lang="yi" dir="rtl">????? ???? ?????????</span>?; June 1835 – 18 June 1888) was a Russian author, <a href="/wiki/Belles-lettres" title="Belles-lettres">belletrist</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Publication" title="Publication">publicist</a>. His literary work made him a leading figure in the circles of the Russian-Jewish intelligentsia.          <td>Archibald Spencer (January 1, 1698 – January 13, 1760) was a businessman, scientist, doctor, clergyman, and lecturer.          <td><a href="/wiki/Amasa_Holcomb" title="Amasa Holcomb">Amasa Holcomb</a> (<small>American manufacturer of surveying instruments and telescopes</small>) </td> 
         <td>Amasa Holcomb (1787–1875) was an American farmer, surveyor, <a href="/wiki/Civil_engineer" title="Civil engineer">civil engineer</a>, businessman, politician, and <a href="/wiki/Manufacturer" class="mw-redirect" title="Manufacturer">manufacturer</a> of surveying instruments and <a href="/wiki/Telescopes" class="mw-redirect" title="Telescopes">telescopes</a>. From instruments he made he could observe the total solar eclipse of June&nbsp;16, 1806. He made astronomical computations from his observations and published almanacs for the partial solar eclipses of 1807 and 1808 from his work. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Charles_A._Cheever" title="Charles A. Cheever">Charles A. Cheever</a> </td> 
         <td>Charles Augustus Cheever (September 7, 1852 – May 2, 1900) was an American industrialist and inventor. He was affiliated with <a href="/wiki/Alexander_Graham_Bell" title="Alexander Graham Bell">Alexander Graham Bell</a> and <a href="/wiki/Thomas_Edison" title="Thomas Edison">Thomas Edison</a> improving their inventions. He patented 100 of these improvements, most related to the telephone. Cheever formed the Telephone Company of New York and constructed the first telephone line in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. </td>

         <td>Synge Street CBS&nbsp;(colloquially&nbsp;Synger) is a boys'&nbsp;non-fee-paying state school, under the auspices of the <a href="/wiki/Edmund_Rice_Schools_Trust" title="Edmund Rice Schools Trust">Edmund Rice Schools Trust</a>, located in the&nbsp;<a href="/wiki/Dublin_8" class="mw-redirect" title="Dublin 8">Dublin 8</a> area of&nbsp;Dublin, Ireland. The school was founded in 1864 by Canon <a href="/wiki/Edward_McCabe_(bishop)" class="mw-redirect" title="Edward McCabe (bishop)">Edward McCabe</a> and Brother Edward O’Flaherty, as part of a mid-nineteenth century programme to expand the provision of Catholic schooling across the city, particularly for poorer boys. </td>

"Dutch" Ulrich (November 18, 1899 – February 11, 1929) was a <a href="/wiki/Czech_Americans" title="Czech Americans">Czech-American</a> professional <a href="/wiki/Baseball" title="Baseball">baseball</a> player who played three seasons for the <a href="/wiki/Philadelphia_Phillies" title="Philadelphia Phillies">Philadelphia Phillies</a> from <a href="/wiki/1925_in_baseball" title="1925 in baseball">1925</a> through <a href="/wiki/1927_in_baseball" title="1927 in baseball">1927</a>. In 1927, he had the seventh-best <a href="/wiki/Earned_run_average" title="Earned run average">earned run average</a> (ERA) in the <a href="/wiki/National_League" title="National League">National League</a> (NL). </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Bill_Steele_(baseball)" title="Bill Steele (baseball)">Bill Steele (baseball)</a> (<small>American baseball player</small>) </td> 
         <td>William Mitchell Steele (October 5, 1885 – October 19, 1949) was a <a href="/wiki/Pitcher" title="Pitcher">pitcher</a> in <a href="/wiki/Major_League_Baseball" title="Major League Baseball">Major League Baseball</a> (MLB). He pitched from 1910 to 1914 with the <a href="/wiki/St._Louis_Cardinals" title="St. Louis Cardinals">St. Louis Cardinals</a> and <a href="/wiki/Brooklyn_Robins" class="mw-redirect" title="Brooklyn Robins">Brooklyn Robins</a>. Nicknamed "Big Bill", at 5&nbsp;feet 11&nbsp;inches (1.80&nbsp;m), he was one of the larger players of his era. His main pitch was a <a href="/wiki/Spitball" title="Spitball">spitball</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Josiah_Holbrook" title="Josiah Holbrook">Josiah Holbrook</a> </td> 
         <td>Josiah Holbrook (1788–1854) was the initiator and organizer of the <a href="/wiki/Lyceum_movement" title="Lyceum movement">lyceum movement</a> in the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>. He formed the first <a href="/wiki/Lyceum" title="Lyceum">lyceum</a> school in the United States in 1826. His design and system was duplicated throughout the United states by hundreds of similar associations within a few years and the first nationwide organization of lyceum schools was formed. </td>

         <td>Charles Corydon Hall (July 3, 1860 – August 19, 1935) was an American businessman, chemist, engineer and industrialist. He developed a process of converting molten <a href="/wiki/Limestone" title="Limestone">limestone</a> into fibers that would become an insulation material. He initiated the <a href="/wiki/Rock_wool" class="mw-redirect" title="Rock wool">rock wool</a> insulation industry in America and is considered its progenitor. </td>

         <td>Julius Kahn (March 8, 1874 – November 4, 1942) was an American engineer, industrialist, and manufacturer. He was the inventor of the <a href="/wiki/Kahn_System" class="mw-redirect" title="Kahn System">Kahn System</a>, a reinforced concrete engineering technique for building construction. The Kahn System, which he patented in 1903, was used worldwide for housing, factories, offices and industrial buildings. </td>

Managed by <a href="/wiki/Harry_Potts" title="Harry Potts">Harry Potts</a>, the team endured a tense season, in which <a href="/wiki/Tottenham_Hotspur_F.C." title="Tottenham Hotspur F.C.">Tottenham Hotspur</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wolverhampton_Wanderers_F.C." title="Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.">Wolverhampton Wanderers</a> were the other protagonists for the league title. Burnley won their second <a href="/wiki/List_of_English_football_champions" title="List of English football champions">First Division championship</a>, and their first since <a href="/wiki/1920%E2%80%9321_Burnley_F.C._season" title="1920–21 Burnley F.C. season">1920–21</a>, on the last matchday with a 2–1 victory at <a href="/wiki/Manchester_City_F.C." title="Manchester City F.C.">Manchester City</a>; they had not topped the table until the last match was played out. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Crewe_Alexandra_F.C." title="Crewe Alexandra F.C.">Crewe Alexandra F.C.</a> (<small>Association football club in England</small>) </td> 
         <td>Crewe Alexandra Football Club is an English professional <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> club based in the town of <a href="/wiki/Crewe" title="Crewe">Crewe</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cheshire" title="Cheshire">Cheshire</a>, that competes in <a href="/wiki/EFL_League_One" title="EFL League One">League One</a>, the third tier of the <a href="/wiki/English_football_league_system" title="English football league system">English football league system</a>. Nicknamed "The Railwaymen" because of the town's <a href="/wiki/Crewe_Works" title="Crewe Works">links with the rail industry</a>, and also commonly known as "The Alex", they have played at <a href="/wiki/Gresty_Road" title="Gresty Road">Gresty Road</a> since 1906. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1988_Football_League_Third_Division_play-off_Final" title="1988 Football League Third Division play-off Final">1988 Football League Third Division play-off Final</a> (<small>Association football match</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 1988 Football League Third Division play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match contested by <a href="/wiki/Walsall_F.C." title="Walsall F.C.">Walsall</a> and <a href="/wiki/Bristol_City_F.C." title="Bristol City F.C.">Bristol City</a> over <a href="/wiki/Two-legged_tie" title="Two-legged tie">two legs</a> on 25 and 28 May 1988, and then a <a href="/wiki/Replay_(sports)" title="Replay (sports)">replay</a> on 30 May 1988, to determine which club would play the following season in the <a href="/wiki/1988%E2%80%9389_Football_League#Second_Division" title="1988–89 Football League">Second Division</a>. Walsall had finished in third place in the <a href="/wiki/1987%E2%80%9388_Football_League#Third_Division" title="1987–88 Football League">Third Division</a> while Bristol City finished fifth. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1999_Football_League_Second_Division_play-off_Final" title="1999 Football League Second Division play-off Final">1999 Football League Second Division play-off Final</a> (<small>Football match</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 1999 Football League Second Division play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match which was played on 30 May 1999 at <a href="/wiki/Wembley_Stadium_(1923)" title="Wembley Stadium (1923)">Wembley Stadium</a>, London, between <a href="/wiki/Manchester_City_F.C." title="Manchester City F.C.">Manchester City</a> and <a href="/wiki/Gillingham_F.C." title="Gillingham F.C.">Gillingham</a>. The match was to determine the third and final team to gain <a href="/wiki/Promotion_and_relegation" title="Promotion and relegation">promotion</a> from the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_Second_Division" title="Football League Second Division">Football League Second Division</a>, the third tier of <a href="/wiki/English_football_league_system" title="English football league system">English football</a>, to the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_First_Division" title="Football League First Division">First Division</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Eric_Anthony_Abrahams" title="Eric Anthony Abrahams">Eric Anthony Abrahams</a> (<small>Jamaican public servant</small>) </td> 
         <td>Eric Anthony Abrahams (5 May 1940&nbsp;– 7 August 2011) was a Jamaican public servant. He served as Director of Tourism from 1970 to 1975, and Minister of Tourism and Communication from 1980 to 1985. He attended the <a href="/wiki/University_of_the_West_Indies" title="University of the West Indies">University of the West Indies</a> and <a href="/wiki/University_of_Oxford" title="University of Oxford">University of Oxford</a> (a <a href="/wiki/Rhodes_Scholar" class="mw-redirect" title="Rhodes Scholar">Rhodes Scholar</a>), and briefly worked for the <a href="/wiki/BBC" title="BBC">BBC</a> as their first black TV reporter. </td>

         <td class="recent">2021-04-15 21:47 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Shooting_of_Vivian_Strong" title="Shooting of Vivian Strong">Shooting of Vivian Strong</a> </td> 
         <td>On June 24, 1969, Vivian Strong, a 14-year-old African American girl, was killed in Omaha, Nebraska, United States, when a white police officer shot Strong in the back of the head without warning. The white police officer, and his Black partner, had been dispatched to the location because there were "juveniles breaking in." When they arrived at the scene a small group of teens fled out of an abandoned apartment where they had been dancing. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Bridges2Information" title="User:Bridges2Information">Bridges2Information</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Bridges2Information" title="User talk:Bridges2Information">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="recent">2021-04-16 09:55 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Henry_Fitz" title="Henry Fitz">Henry Fitz</a> </td> 
         <td>Henry Fitz was an American engineer, scientist, locksmith, <a href="/wiki/Optician" title="Optician">optician</a>, and inventor. As a teenager, one of his hobbies was <a href="/wiki/Astronomy" title="Astronomy">astronomy</a>, which led to him making telescopes. Fritz became a manufacturer of telescopes and the first American to make large high-end sophisticated <a href="/wiki/Refracting_telescope" title="Refracting telescope">refracting telescopes</a>. He made telescopes for wealthy individuals, institutions, colleges, and universities throughout the United States, some of which are still in use. </td>

         <td>Kiki Wolfkill is an American <a href="/wiki/Video_game_developer" title="Video game developer">video game developer</a>. Wolfkill grew up in <a href="/wiki/Pennsylvania" title="Pennsylvania">Pennsylvania</a> and studied journalism and art at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Washington" title="University of Washington">University of Washington</a>, racing competitively on the side. At <a href="/wiki/Microsoft" title="Microsoft">Microsoft</a>, she transitioned from developing multimedia for <i><a href="/wiki/Encarta" title="Encarta">Microsoft Encarta</a></i> to working on art for Microsoft's video games, including the racing series <i><a href="/wiki/Midtown_Madness" title="Midtown Madness">Midtown Madness</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Project_Gotham_Racing" title="Project Gotham Racing">Project Gotham Racing</a></i>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Berliner_Journal" title="Berliner Journal">Berliner Journal</a> (<small>19th and 20th-century Berlin-Kitchener newspaper</small>) </td> 
         <td>The <i>Berliner Journal</i> (later the <i>Ontario Journal</i>) was a German language <a href="/wiki/Weekly_newspaper" title="Weekly newspaper">weekly newspaper</a> published in <a href="/wiki/Berlin,_Ontario" class="mw-redirect" title="Berlin, Ontario">Berlin, Ontario</a> (later Kitchener) from 1859 to 1918. Founded by German immigrants <a href="/w/index.php?title=Friedrich_Rittinger&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Friedrich Rittinger (page does not exist)">Friedrich Rittinger</a><span class="noprint" style="font-size:85%; font-style: normal;">&nbsp;[<a href="https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Rittinger" class="extiw" title="de:Friedrich Rittinger">de</a>]</span> and <a href="/w/index.php?title=John_Motz&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="John Motz (page does not exist)">John Motz</a><span class="noprint" style="font-size:85%; font-style: normal;">&nbsp;[<a href="https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Motz" class="extiw" title="de:John Motz">de</a>]</span>, they operated the paper through most of its existence until their sons – <a href="/w/index.php?title=William_John_Motz&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="William John Motz (page does not exist)">William John Motz</a>, Herman Rittinger and <a href="/wiki/John_Adam_Rittinger" title="John Adam Rittinger">John Adam Rittinger</a> – took over the operation at the turn of the century. </td> 
         <td><span style="font-weight:bold;text-shadow:1px 1px 40px black"><a href="/wiki/User:Tkbrett" title="User:Tkbrett"><b><span style="color: #000000;">Tkbrett</span></b></a><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Tkbrett" title="User talk:Tkbrett"><span style="color: #FF0000;"> (?)</span></a></span> </td>

         <td>Robert Marion "Fighting Bob" La Follette Sr. (June 14, 1855&nbsp;– June 18, 1925), was an American lawyer and politician. He represented <a href="/wiki/Wisconsin" title="Wisconsin">Wisconsin</a> in both chambers of Congress and served as the <a href="/wiki/Governor_of_Wisconsin" title="Governor of Wisconsin">Governor of Wisconsin</a>. A <a href="/wiki/Republican_Party_(United_States)" title="Republican Party (United States)">Republican</a> for most of his career, he ran for <a href="/wiki/President_of_the_United_States" title="President of the United States">President of the United States</a> as the nominee of his own <a href="/wiki/Progressive_Party_(United_States,_1924%E2%80%9334)" title="Progressive Party (United States, 1924–34)">Progressive Party</a> in the <a href="/wiki/U.S._presidential_election,_1924" class="mw-redirect" title="U.S. presidential election, 1924">1924 presidential election</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1930%E2%80%9331_Cardiff_City_F.C._season" title="1930–31 Cardiff City F.C. season">1930–31 Cardiff City F.C. season</a> (<small>Cardiff City 1930–31 football season</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 1930–31 season was the 30th season of competitive <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">football</a> played by <a href="/wiki/Cardiff_City_F.C." title="Cardiff City F.C.">Cardiff City F.C.</a>. It the team's second season in the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_Second_Division" title="Football League Second Division">Second Division</a> of <a href="/wiki/English_Football_League" title="English Football League">the Football League</a> since being relegated from the First Division during the <a href="/wiki/1928%E2%80%9329_Cardiff_City_F.C._season" title="1928–29 Cardiff City F.C. season">1928–29 season</a>. They finished bottom of the Second Division after winning only 8 of their 42 league matches and scoring the fewest amount of goals in the league and were relegated to the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_Third_Division_South" title="Football League Third Division South">Third Division South</a>. </td>

         <td>John Rolph (4&nbsp;March 1793 – 19&nbsp;October 1870) was a physician, lawyer, and political figure in <a href="/wiki/Upper_Canada" title="Upper Canada">Upper Canada</a>. He was elected to the <a href="/wiki/Parliament_of_Upper_Canada" title="Parliament of Upper Canada">Parliament of Upper Canada</a> in 1824 to represent <a href="/wiki/Middlesex_County,_Ontario" title="Middlesex County, Ontario">Middlesex County</a> and was considered the leader of the Reform faction in the 1820s. In 1837 he helped plan the <a href="/wiki/Upper_Canada_Rebellion" title="Upper Canada Rebellion">Upper Canada Rebellion</a>, but acted as the government's emissary to negotiate a truce once the rebellion began. </td>

         <td>Alexander Ross Sutherland <span class="noexcerpt nowraplinks" style="font-size:85%;"><a href="/wiki/Order_of_the_British_Empire" title="Order of the British Empire">MBE</a></span> (19 August 1922 – 16 April 2014) was a Scottish <a href="/wiki/Royal_Air_Force" title="Royal Air Force">Royal Air Force</a> (RAF) aviator. As a teenager he helped establish the Inverness squadron of the Air Training Corps, becoming their first senior non-commissioned officer.          <td>The 2008 Football League Two play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match which was played on 26 May 2008 at <a href="/wiki/Wembley_Stadium" title="Wembley Stadium">Wembley Stadium</a>, London, between <a href="/wiki/Stockport_County_F.C." title="Stockport County F.C.">Stockport County</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rochdale_A.F.C." title="Rochdale A.F.C.">Rochdale</a> to determine the third and final team to gain <a href="/wiki/Promotion_and_relegation" title="Promotion and relegation">promotion</a> from <a href="/wiki/EFL_League_Two" title="EFL League Two">Football League Two</a> to the <a href="/wiki/EFL_League_One" title="EFL League One">Football League One</a>. The top three teams of the <a href="/wiki/2008%E2%80%9309_Football_League_One" title="2008–09 Football League One">2008–09 Football League One</a> season, <a href="/wiki/Milton_Keynes_Dons_F.C." title="Milton Keynes Dons F.C.">Milton Keynes Dons</a>, <a href="/wiki/Peterborough_United_F.C." title="Peterborough United F.C.">Peterborough United</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hereford_United_F.C." title="Hereford United F.C.">Hereford Unnited</a>, gained automatic promotion to League One, while those placed from fourth to seventh in the table took part in <a href="/wiki/2009_Football_League_play-offs" title="2009 Football League play-offs">play-offs</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:The_Rambling_Man" title="User:The Rambling Man">The Rambling Man</a> <small>(<a href="/wiki/User_talk:The_Rambling_Man" title="User talk:The Rambling Man">Stay alert! Control the virus! Save lives!!!!</a>)</small> </td>

         <td>Thomas Tuchel (; born 29 August 1973) is a German professional <a href="/wiki/Manager_(association_football)" title="Manager (association football)">football manager</a> and former <a href="/wiki/Football_player" title="Football player">player</a> who is the current head coach of <a href="/wiki/Premier_League" title="Premier League">Premier League</a> club <a href="/wiki/Chelsea_F.C." title="Chelsea F.C.">Chelsea</a>. <p>Born in <a href="/wiki/Krumbach,_Bavaria" title="Krumbach, Bavaria">Krumbach</a>, Tuchel's playing career ended at age 25, as a result of a chronic knee cartilage injury, and in 2000, he began his coaching career, working for the youth teams at <a href="/wiki/VfB_Stuttgart" title="VfB Stuttgart">VfB Stuttgart</a> for five years. </p> </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/John_B._Curtis" title="John B. Curtis">John B. Curtis</a> </td> 
         <td>John Bacon Curtis (October 10, 1827 – June 13, 1897) was an American businessman from <a href="/wiki/Maine" title="Maine">Maine</a>. He is credited as the inventor of chewing gum, as well as the first person to commercialize it using natural products and flavorings. He got the idea for making chewing gum after seeing loggers chew spruce resin. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Henry_W._Maxwell_Memorial" title="Henry W. Maxwell Memorial">Henry W. Maxwell Memorial</a> (<small>Memorial in Brooklyn, New York, U.S.</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Henry W. Maxwell Memorial is a public memorial located in <a href="/wiki/Brooklyn" title="Brooklyn">Brooklyn</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Grand_Army_Plaza" title="Grand Army Plaza">Grand Army Plaza</a> in New York City. The memorial, designed by sculptor <a href="/wiki/Augustus_Saint-Gaudens" title="Augustus Saint-Gaudens">Augustus Saint-Gaudens</a>, consists of a <a href="/wiki/Bronze" title="Bronze">bronze</a> tablet featuring a <a href="/wiki/Relief" title="Relief">relief</a> of Maxwell, a local philanthropist and park commissioner, affixed to a <a href="/wiki/Boulder" title="Boulder">boulder</a>. The memorial was dedicated in 1903. </td>

         <td>Tom Hull (born 1950) is an American music critic, <a href="/wiki/Web_designer" class="mw-redirect" title="Web designer">web designer</a>, and former <a href="/wiki/Software_developer" class="mw-redirect" title="Software developer">software developer</a>. A native of <a href="/wiki/Wichita,_Kansas" title="Wichita, Kansas">Wichita, Kansas</a>, Hull had an isolated childhood marked by a deep interest in reading, particularly works by <a href="/wiki/Absurdist_fiction" title="Absurdist fiction">absurdist</a> writers and <a href="/wiki/Leftist" class="mw-redirect" title="Leftist">leftist</a> thinkers. While studying at <a href="/wiki/Washington_University_in_St._Louis" title="Washington University in St. Louis">Washington University in St. Louis</a> in the early 1970s, he pursued courses of a similar political vein before a friend introduced him to <a href="/wiki/Rock_criticism" class="mw-redirect" title="Rock criticism">rock criticism</a>, a flourishing field at the time. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Statue_of_William_Francis_Bartlett" title="Statue of William Francis Bartlett">Statue of William Francis Bartlett</a> (<small>Statue in Boston, Massachusetts, U.S.</small>) </td> 
         <td>A <a href="/wiki/Statue" title="Statue">statue</a> of <a href="/wiki/William_Francis_Bartlett" title="William Francis Bartlett">William Francis Bartlett</a> stands inside the <a href="/wiki/Massachusetts_State_House" title="Massachusetts State House">Massachusetts State House</a> in <a href="/wiki/Boston" title="Boston">Boston</a>, <a href="/wiki/Massachusetts" title="Massachusetts">Massachusetts</a>, <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>. The bronze statue was designed by sculptor <a href="/wiki/Daniel_Chester_French" title="Daniel Chester French">Daniel Chester French</a> and honors Bartlett, who had served as a <a href="/wiki/General" class="mw-redirect" title="General">general</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Union_Army" title="Union Army">Union Army</a> during the <a href="/wiki/American_Civil_War" title="American Civil War">American Civil War</a>. The statue was dedicated in 1904. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/George_Livermore" title="George Livermore">George Livermore</a> </td> 
         <td>George Livermore (July 10, 1809 – August 30, 1865) was an American <a href="/wiki/Antiquarian" title="Antiquarian">antiquarian</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bibliographer" class="mw-redirect" title="Bibliographer">bibliographer</a>, and historian, known chiefly as a book collector, who had many valuable old books. He developed in his lifetime what was recognized as one of the finest private libraries in the United States. His library included many rare and one-of-a-kind bibles including some printed by <a href="/wiki/Gutenberg" class="mw-redirect" title="Gutenberg">Gutenberg</a>. </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-21 21:28 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Callimachus" title="Callimachus">Callimachus</a> (<small>Ancient poet and librarian</small>) </td> 
         <td>Callimachus was an <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greek" title="Ancient Greek">ancient Greek</a> <a href="/wiki/Poet" title="Poet">poet</a>, <a href="/wiki/Scholar" title="Scholar">scholar</a> and <a href="/wiki/Librarian" title="Librarian">librarian</a> who was active in <a href="/wiki/Alexandria" title="Alexandria">Alexandria</a> during the 3rd century BC. A representative of <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greek_literature" title="Ancient Greek literature">Ancient Greek literature</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Hellenistic_period" title="Hellenistic period">Hellenistic period</a>, he wrote over 800 literary works in a wide variety of genres, most of which did not survive. He espoused an <a href="/wiki/Aesthetic_philosophy" class="mw-redirect" title="Aesthetic philosophy">aesthetic philosophy</a>, known as Callimacheanism, which exerted a strong influence on the poets of the <a href="/wiki/Roman_Empire" title="Roman Empire">Roman Empire</a> and, through them, on all subsequent <a href="/wiki/Western_canon" title="Western canon">Western literature</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Modussiccandi" title="User:Modussiccandi">Modussiccandi</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Modussiccandi" title="User talk:Modussiccandi">talk</a>) </td>

         <td>John Adam Rittinger (16 February 1855&nbsp;– 29 July 1915) was a Canadian German-language newspaper proprietor, <a href="/wiki/Editor-in-chief" title="Editor-in-chief">editor</a> and <a href="/wiki/Pennsylvania_Dutch_language" title="Pennsylvania Dutch language">Pennsylvania German</a> <a href="/wiki/Humorist" title="Humorist">humorist</a>. In 1875, he and Aaron Eby purchased <a href="/wiki/Walkerton,_Ontario" title="Walkerton, Ontario">Walkerton, Ontario</a>'s German language newspaper, the <i lang="de" title="German-language text">Walkerton Glocke</i>. Affectionately known by locals as the "<span lang="de" style="font-style: normal;" title="German-language text">Glockemann</span>" ("Bell Ringer"), he became the paper's sole-owner in 1878, renaming it <i lang="de" title="German-language text">Die Ontario Glocke</i> in 1882. </td>

         <td>Anushtegin Gharchai (also spelled Anush-Tegin; <a href="/wiki/Persian_language" title="Persian language">Persian</a>: <span lang="fa" dir="rtl"><span class="Nastaliq" dir="rtl" title="Nastaliq" style="font-family: 'Jameel Noori Nastaleeq', 'Urdu Typesetting', 'Noto Nastaliq Urdu', 'Noto Nastaliq Urdu Draft', 'Hussaini Nastaleeq', 'AlQalam Taj Nastaleeq', IranNastaliq, 'Awami Nastaliq', 'Awami Nastaliq Beta3', 'Awami Nastaliq Beta2', 'Awami Nastaliq Beta1', 'Nafees Nastaleeq', 'Nafees Nastaleeq v1.01', 'Pak Nastaleeq', 'PDMS_Jauhar', 'Alvi Lahori Nastaleeq'; font-size: 110%; font-style: normal;">??????? ????</span></span>?, <small><a href="/wiki/Romanization_of_Persian" title="Romanization of Persian">romanized</a>:&nbsp;</small><i lang="fa-Latn" title="Persian-language romanization">An?štigin ?a??a??</i>; died 1097) was a <a href="/wiki/Turkic_peoples" title="Turkic peoples">Turkic</a> slave commander (<i lang="ar" title="Arabic-language text"><a href="/wiki/Ghilman" title="Ghilman">ghulam</a></i>) of the <a href="/wiki/Seljuk_Empire" title="Seljuk Empire">Seljuks</a> and the governor of <a href="/wiki/Khwarazm" title="Khwarazm">Khwarazm</a> from approximately 1077 until 1097. He was the first member of his family to rule Khwarazm, and the <a href="/wiki/Anushtegin_dynasty" title="Anushtegin dynasty">namesake for the dynasty</a> that would <a href="/wiki/Khwarazmian_Empire" title="Khwarazmian Empire">rule the province</a> in the 12th and early 13th centuries. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Robert_Ludwig_Kahn" title="Robert Ludwig Kahn">Robert Ludwig Kahn</a> </td> 
         <td>Robert Ludwig Kahn (April 22, 1923 – March 22, 1970) was a German-American scholar of German studies and poet. He grew up in Nuremberg and Leipzig as the son of Jewish parents who, before they perished in the Holocaust, sent him abroad on a <a href="/wiki/Kindertransport" title="Kindertransport">Kindertransport</a>. After internment on the Isle of Man and in Canada, he studied at <a href="/wiki/Dalhousie_University" title="Dalhousie University">Dalhousie University</a> and the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Toronto" title="University of Toronto">University of Toronto</a>. </td>

         <td>Nebuchadnezzar II (<a href="/wiki/Babylonian_cuneiform" class="mw-redirect" title="Babylonian cuneiform">Babylonian cuneiform</a>: <i>Nabû-kudurri-u?ur</i>, meaning "<a href="/wiki/Nabu" title="Nabu">Nabu</a>, watch over my heir"), also spelled Nebuchadrezzar II and historically known as Nebuchadnezzar the Great, was the second and greatest king of the <a href="/wiki/Neo-Babylonian_Empire" title="Neo-Babylonian Empire">Neo-Babylonian Empire</a>, ruling from the death of his father <a href="/wiki/Nabopolassar" title="Nabopolassar">Nabopolassar</a> in 605 BC to his own death in 562 BC. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Ichthyovenator" title="User:Ichthyovenator">Ichthyovenator</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Ichthyovenator" title="User talk:Ichthyovenator">talk</a>) </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-25 21:19 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Ikeji_festival" title="Ikeji festival">Ikeji festival</a> (<small>Festival observed annually by the Igbo people of Nigeria</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Ikeji festival is an annual four-day festival held by the <a href="/wiki/Igbo_people" title="Igbo people">Igbo people</a> of <a href="/wiki/Arondizuogu" title="Arondizuogu">Arondizuogu</a>, in <a href="/wiki/Imo_state" class="mw-redirect" title="Imo state">Imo state</a>, <a href="/wiki/Nigeria" title="Nigeria">Nigeria</a>, between the months of March and April to celebrate the harvest of new yams and the Igbo culture. The inception of the Ikeji festival dates back five centuries and is an Igbo festival which unites all Igbo race across the globe as they return to the south-eastern regions of Nigeria to witness and partake in the festival. </td> 
         <td><b><a href="/wiki/User:Celestina007" title="User:Celestina007">Celestina007</a></b> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Celestina007" title="User talk:Celestina007">talk</a>) </td>

He played for 10 different teams in <a href="/wiki/Major_League_Baseball" title="Major League Baseball">Major League Baseball</a> (MLB): the <a href="/wiki/Colorado_Rockies" title="Colorado Rockies">Colorado Rockies</a>, <a href="/wiki/Milwaukee_Brewers" title="Milwaukee Brewers">Milwaukee Brewers</a>, <a href="/wiki/St._Louis_Cardinals" title="St. Louis Cardinals">St. Louis Cardinals</a>, <a href="/wiki/Kansas_City_Royals" title="Kansas City Royals">Kansas City Royals</a>, <a href="/wiki/San_Francisco_Giants" title="San Francisco Giants">San Francisco Giants</a>, <a href="/wiki/Texas_Rangers_(baseball)" title="Texas Rangers (baseball)">Texas Rangers</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cleveland_Indians" title="Cleveland Indians">Cleveland Indians</a>, <a href="/wiki/Seattle_Mariners" title="Seattle Mariners">Seattle Mariners</a>, <a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles_Dodgers" title="Los Angeles Dodgers">Los Angeles Dodgers</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Tampa_Bay_Rays" title="Tampa Bay Rays">Tampa Bay Rays</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1995_Football_League_Third_Division_play-off_Final" title="1995 Football League Third Division play-off Final">1995 Football League Third Division play-off Final</a> (<small>Football match</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 1995 Football League Third Division play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match which was played on 27 May 1995 at <a href="/wiki/Wembley_Stadium_(1923)" title="Wembley Stadium (1923)">Wembley Stadium</a>, London, between <a href="/wiki/Chesterfield_F.C." title="Chesterfield F.C.">Chesterfield</a> and <a href="/wiki/Bury_F.C." title="Bury F.C.">Bury</a> to determine the third and final team to gain <a href="/wiki/Promotion_and_relegation" title="Promotion and relegation">promotion</a> from the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_Third_Division" title="Football League Third Division">Football League Third Division</a> to the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_Second_Division" title="Football League Second Division">Second Division</a>. The top two teams of the <a href="/wiki/1997%E2%80%9398_Football_League_Third_Division" class="mw-redirect" title="1997–98 Football League Third Division">1997–98 Football League Third Division</a>, <a href="/wiki/Carlisle_United_F.C." title="Carlisle United F.C.">Carlisle United</a> and <a href="/wiki/Walsall_F.C." title="Walsall F.C.">Walsall</a>, gained automatic promotion to the Second Division, while the teams placed from third to sixth place in the table took part in <a href="/wiki/1995_Football_League_play-offs" title="1995 Football League play-offs">play-offs</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Socrates_Nelson" title="Socrates Nelson">Socrates Nelson</a> (<small>American politician (1814–1867)</small>) </td> 
         <td>Socrates Nelson (January 11, 1814 – May 6, 1867) was an American businessman, politician, and pioneer who served one term as a <a href="/wiki/Minnesota_Senate" title="Minnesota Senate">Minnesota state senator</a> from 1859 to 1861. He was heavily involved in the community of early <a href="/wiki/Stillwater,_Minnesota" title="Stillwater, Minnesota">Stillwater</a>, being a founding member of the first <a href="/wiki/Independent_Order_of_Odd_Fellows" title="Independent Order of Odd Fellows">Independent Order of Odd Fellows</a> lodge in Minnesota as well one of the earliest members of the <a href="/wiki/Minnesota_Historical_Society" title="Minnesota Historical Society">Minnesota Historical Society</a>. </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-29 02:34 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Pacific_Salmon_War" title="Pacific Salmon War">Pacific Salmon War</a> (<small>1990s fishing dispute between American and Canadian fishers</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Pacific Salmon War was a period of heightened tensions between <a href="/wiki/Canada" title="Canada">Canada</a> and the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> over the <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Salmon" class="mw-redirect" title="Pacific Salmon">Pacific Salmon</a> catch. It began in 1992 after the first <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Salmon_Treaty" class="mw-redirect" title="Pacific Salmon Treaty">Pacific Salmon Treaty</a>, which had been ratified in 1985, expired, and lasted until a new agreement was signed in 1999. Disagreements were high in 1994, when a transit fee was set on American fishing vessels using the <a href="/wiki/Inside_Passage" title="Inside Passage">Inside Passage</a> and a ferry was blockaded by fishing boats in <a href="/wiki/Friday_Harbor,_Washington" title="Friday Harbor, Washington">Friday Harbor, Washington</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Eddie891" title="User:Eddie891">Eddie891</a> <small><i><sup> <a href="/wiki/User_talk:Eddie891" title="User talk:Eddie891">Talk</a></sup> <sub><a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/Eddie891" title="Special:Contributions/Eddie891">Work</a></sub></i> </small> </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/John_Mason_Loomis" title="John Mason Loomis">John Mason Loomis</a> </td> 
         <td>John Mason Loomis (January 5, 1825 – August 2, 1900) was a nineteenth-century American businessman and <a href="/wiki/Lumber_tycoon" class="mw-redirect" title="Lumber tycoon">lumber tycoon</a> from Chicago who was known for developing the city of <a href="/wiki/Ludington,_Michigan" title="Ludington, Michigan">Ludington, Michigan</a>. He served as a Colonel in the Illinois militia, mobilized as part of the <a href="/wiki/Union_Army" title="Union Army">Union Army</a> during the <a href="/wiki/American_Civil_War" title="American Civil War">American Civil War</a>, and fought in several major battles. </td>

This was the nation's ninth consecutive appearance at the Summer Olympics. Four Omani athletes, two per gender, were selected to compete in athletics and shooting at the Games.          <td>Clarence William Nelson II (born September 29, 1942) is an American attorney, politician, and <a href="/wiki/Payload_specialist" title="Payload specialist">NASA payload specialist</a> who is currently the <a href="/wiki/Administrator_of_NASA" class="mw-redirect" title="Administrator of NASA">Administrator</a> of the <a href="/wiki/National_Aeronautics_and_Space_Administration" class="mw-redirect" title="National Aeronautics and Space Administration">National Aeronautics and Space Administration</a>.          <td><a href="/wiki/Therapy_(New_York_City)" title="Therapy (New York City)">Therapy (New York City)</a> (<small>Defunct gay bar and nightclub in Manhattan, New York, U.S.</small>) </td> 
         <td>Therapy was a bilevel <a href="/wiki/Gay_bar" title="Gay bar">gay bar</a> and nightclub in the <a href="/wiki/Hell%27s_Kitchen,_Manhattan" title="Hell's Kitchen, Manhattan">Hell's Kitchen</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. Prior to its closure in March 2020 due to the <a href="/wiki/COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_York_City" title="COVID-19 pandemic in New York City">COVID-19 pandemic</a>, it hosted frequent drag shows, some of which featured performers who later rose to prominence on <i><a href="/wiki/RuPaul%27s_Drag_Race" title="RuPaul's Drag Race">RuPaul's Drag Race</a></i>. The venue was a favorite Monday-night stop for off-duty <a href="/wiki/Broadway_(theatre)" class="mw-redirect" title="Broadway (theatre)">Broadway</a> actors, who sometimes participated in that evening's show. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Spencer_Heath_(baseball)" title="Spencer Heath (baseball)">Spencer Heath (baseball)</a> (<small>American baseball player</small>) </td> 
         <td>Spencer Paul Heath, Jr. (November 5, 1893 – January 25, 1930), was a <a href="/wiki/Relief_pitcher" title="Relief pitcher">relief pitcher</a> who played in four games for the <a href="/wiki/Chicago_White_Sox" title="Chicago White Sox">Chicago White Sox</a> during the 1920 season. Listed at 6'0", 170&nbsp;lb., Heath was a <a href="/wiki/Switch-hitter" class="mw-redirect" title="Switch-hitter">switch-hitter</a> and threw <a href="/wiki/Right-handed" class="mw-redirect" title="Right-handed">right-handed</a>. He was born and died in <a href="/wiki/Chicago" title="Chicago">Chicago</a>, <a href="/wiki/Illinois" title="Illinois">Illinois</a>, where he lived much of his life. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Sanfranciscogiants17" title="User:Sanfranciscogiants17">Sanfranciscogiants17</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Sanfranciscogiants17" title="User talk:Sanfranciscogiants17">talk</a>) </td>

Hale (born September 27, 1987) is an American <a href="/wiki/Professional_baseball" title="Professional baseball">professional baseball</a> pitcher for the <a href="/wiki/Philadelphia_Phillies" title="Philadelphia Phillies">Philadelphia Phillies</a> of <a href="/wiki/Major_League_Baseball" title="Major League Baseball">Major League Baseball</a> (MLB).          <td class="new">2021-06-02 05:14 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Cyprien_Ntaryamira" title="Cyprien Ntaryamira">Cyprien Ntaryamira</a> (<small>5th President of Burundi, from February 1994 until his assassination that April</small>) </td> 
         <td>Cyprien Ntaryamira (6 March 1955 – 6 April 1994) was a Burundian politician who served as President of <a href="/wiki/Burundi" title="Burundi">Burundi</a> from 5 February 1994 until his death two months later. A <a href="/wiki/Hutu" title="Hutu">Hutu</a> born in Burundi, Ntaryamira studied there before fleeing to Rwanda to avoid ethnic violence and complete his education. Active in a Burundian student movement, he cofounded the socialist <a href="/wiki/Burundi_Workers%27_Party" title="Burundi Workers' Party">Burundi Workers' Party</a> and earned an agricultural degree. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Indy_beetle" title="User:Indy beetle">Indy beetle</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Indy_beetle" title="User talk:Indy beetle">talk</a>) </td>

He is considered as one of the most important designers of his generation, his products typically featuring a combination of technical innovation, simplicity of form and an element of wit and surprise. </td>
