         <td>The 2021 EFL League Two play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match which was played on 31 May 2021 at <a href="/wiki/Wembley_Stadium" title="Wembley Stadium">Wembley Stadium</a>, London, between <a href="/wiki/Morecambe_F.C." title="Morecambe F.C.">Morecambe</a> and <a href="/wiki/Newport_County_A.F.C." title="Newport County A.F.C.">Newport County</a>.          <td>Albon Man (June 29, 1826 – February 18, 1905) was a nineteenth century American lawyer, scientist, and inventor. He was associated with the early technology of the electric <a href="/wiki/Incandescent_light_bulb" title="Incandescent light bulb">incandescent light bulb</a>. He joined with <a href="/wiki/William_Edward_Sawyer" class="mw-redirect" title="William Edward Sawyer">William Edward Sawyer</a> in 1878 to start a company pertaining to incandescent electric lamp development and electric power distribution. </td>

She is the reigning Olympic Champion, three-time World Champion, five-time European Champion, and the former World's No. 1 in <a href="/wiki/Badminton_World_Federation" title="Badminton World Federation">BWF</a> rankings for the women's singles discipline, holding the World No. 1 title for 66 weeks. </td>

She was a teacher of history in the <a href="/wiki/Milwaukee" title="Milwaukee">Milwaukee</a> school system for over 40 years. </td>

         <td class="recent">2021-05-06 10:07 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Juliana_R._Force" title="Juliana R. Force">Juliana R. Force</a> (<small>American art museum administrator</small>) </td> 
         <td>Juliana R. Force (December 25, 1876&nbsp;– August 28, 1948) was an American art museum administrator and director. Force started her career as a collector of <a href="/wiki/Folk_art" title="Folk art">folk art</a> and as a secretary to <a href="/wiki/Socialite" title="Socialite">socialite</a> art collectors. She initiated the first display of American folk art in the United States. Force became a director of art galleries and of a temporary museum of American art in <a href="/wiki/Greenwich_Village" title="Greenwich Village">Greenwich Village</a> in New York City that became the <a href="/wiki/Whitney_Museum_of_American_Art" title="Whitney Museum of American Art">Whitney Museum of American Art</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Doug_Coldwell" title="User:Doug Coldwell">Doug Coldwell</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Doug_Coldwell" title="User talk:Doug Coldwell">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-07 23:08 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Nadia_Fink" title="Nadia Fink">Nadia Fink</a> (<small>Argentine author</small>) </td> 
         <td>Nadia Fink is an Argentine author, journalist, and editor known for writing the works in the <i><a href="/wiki/Anti-Princess_Series_and_Anti-Hero_Series" title="Anti-Princess Series and Anti-Hero Series">Anti-Princess Series</a></i> of <a href="/wiki/Picture_book" title="Picture book">picture book</a> biographies of Latin American women. After studying proofreading, she began working as a copyeditor at the magazine <i>Sudestada</i> and later began to write articles for the periodical. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Bachelor%27s_Day_(tradition)" title="Bachelor's Day (tradition)">Bachelor's Day (tradition)</a> (<small>Tradition associated with February 29</small>) </td> 
         <td>Bachelor's Day, sometimes known as Ladies' Privilege, is an <a href="/wiki/Irish_folklore" title="Irish folklore">Irish tradition</a> by which women are allowed to propose to men on <a href="/wiki/Leap_Day" class="mw-redirect" title="Leap Day">Leap Day</a>, 29 February, based on a legend of Saint Bridget and Saint Patrick. It once had legal basis in Scotland and England. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Fierce_Femmes_and_Notorious_Liars" title="Fierce Femmes and Notorious Liars">Fierce Femmes and Notorious Liars</a> (<small>2016 novel</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Fierce Femmes and Notorious Liars: A Dangerous Trans Girl's Confabulous Memoir</i> is a 2016 Canadian book by <a href="/wiki/Kai_Cheng_Thom" title="Kai Cheng Thom">Kai Cheng Thom</a>. A <a href="/wiki/Surrealist" class="mw-redirect" title="Surrealist">surrealist</a> novel, it follows an unnamed <a href="/wiki/Transgender_woman" class="mw-redirect" title="Transgender woman">transgender woman</a> protagonist who leaves home at a young age to live on the Street of Miracles—where various <a href="/wiki/Sex_work" title="Sex work">sex work</a> takes place—with other "<a href="/wiki/Femme" title="Femme">femmes</a>" (trans women). </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Frances_Spatz_Leighton" title="Frances Spatz Leighton">Frances Spatz Leighton</a> (<small>American author</small>) </td> 
         <td>Frances Spatz Ornstein Leighton (September 4, 1919&nbsp;– April 6, 2007) was an American author best known for her <a href="/wiki/Ghostwriting" class="mw-redirect" title="Ghostwriting">ghostwriting</a> of accounts of Washington, D.C., life. Leighton wrote or ghostwrote over 30 books, including <i><a href="/wiki/My_Thirty_Years_Backstairs_at_the_White_House" title="My Thirty Years Backstairs at the White House">My Thirty Years Backstairs at the White House</a></i> (1961) and <i><a href="/wiki/My_Life_with_Jacqueline_Kennedy" title="My Life with Jacqueline Kennedy">My Life with Jacqueline Kennedy</a></i> (1969). </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Hill_We_Climb" title="The Hill We Climb">The Hill We Climb</a> (<small>Poem by Amanda Gorman</small>) </td> 
         <td>"The Hill We Climb" is a <a href="/wiki/Spoken_word" title="Spoken word">spoken word</a> poem written by American poet <a href="/wiki/Amanda_Gorman" title="Amanda Gorman">Amanda Gorman</a> and recited by her at the <a href="/wiki/Inauguration_of_Joe_Biden" title="Inauguration of Joe Biden">inauguration of Joe Biden</a> on January 20, 2021. The poem was written in the weeks following the <a href="/wiki/2020_United_States_presidential_election" title="2020 United States presidential election">2020 United States presidential election</a>, with significant passages written on the night of January 6, 2021, in response to the <a href="/wiki/2021_storming_of_the_United_States_Capitol" class="mw-redirect" title="2021 storming of the United States Capitol">storming of the United States Capitol</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Eddie891" title="User:Eddie891">Eddie891</a> <small><i><sup> <a href="/wiki/User_talk:Eddie891" title="User talk:Eddie891">Talk</a></sup> <sub><a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/Eddie891" title="Special:Contributions/Eddie891">Work</a></sub></i> </small> </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Lilly_Dach%C3%A9" title="Lilly Daché">Lilly Daché</a> </td> 
         <td>Lilly Daché {1892 – 31 December 1989) was a French-born American <a href="/wiki/Hatmaking" title="Hatmaking">milliner</a> and fashion merchandiser. She started her career in a small bonnet shop, advanced to being a sales lady at <a href="/wiki/Macy%27s" title="Macy's">Macy's</a> department store, and from there started her own <a href="/wiki/Haberdasher" title="Haberdasher">hat business</a>. She was at the peak of her business career in the 1930s and 1940s. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Elephant_6" title="Elephant 6">Elephant 6</a> (<small>American musical collective</small>) </td> 
         <td>Elephant 6 (sometimes referred to as the Elephant 6 Recording Company) is a loosely defined <a href="/wiki/Musical_collective" title="Musical collective">musical collective</a> in the United States. Notable bands associated with the collective include <a href="/wiki/The_Apples_in_Stereo" title="The Apples in Stereo">the Apples in Stereo</a>, <a href="/wiki/Beulah_(band)" title="Beulah (band)">Beulah</a>, <a href="/wiki/Circulatory_System_(band)" title="Circulatory System (band)">Circulatory System</a>, <a href="/wiki/Elf_Power" title="Elf Power">Elf Power</a>, <a href="/wiki/The_Minders" title="The Minders">the Minders</a>, <a href="/wiki/Neutral_Milk_Hotel" title="Neutral Milk Hotel">Neutral Milk Hotel</a>, <a href="/wiki/Of_Montreal" title="Of Montreal">of Montreal</a>, and <a href="/wiki/The_Olivia_Tremor_Control" title="The Olivia Tremor Control">the Olivia Tremor Control</a>. </td>

         <td>Chely Wright (born Richell Rene Wright; October 25, 1970) is an American <a href="/wiki/Activism" title="Activism">activist</a>, <a href="/wiki/Author" title="Author">author</a> and <a href="/wiki/Country_music" title="Country music">country music</a> artist. She initially rose to fame as a commercial country recording artist with several charting singles, including the number one hit, "<a href="/wiki/Single_White_Female_(song)" title="Single White Female (song)">Single White Female</a>." She later became known for her role in <a href="/wiki/LGBT_social_movements" title="LGBT social movements">LGBT activism</a> after publicly <a href="/wiki/Coming_out" title="Coming out">coming out</a>. </td>

         <td>Julio and Marisol was a bilingual (English/Spanish) <a href="/wiki/Public_service_announcement" title="Public service announcement">public-service advertising</a> campaign which ran in the <a href="/wiki/New_York_City_Subway" title="New York City Subway">New York City Subway</a>, promoting <a href="/wiki/Condom" title="Condom">condom</a> use to prevent <a href="/wiki/HIV/AIDS" title="HIV/AIDS">AIDS</a>. The well-known <a href="/wiki/Catchphrase" title="Catchphrase">catchphrase</a> was a line from the first installment, in which Marisol sobs, "I love you, but not enough to die for you". </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/David_Berman_(musician)" title="David Berman (musician)">David Berman (musician)</a> </td> 
         <td>David Cloud Berman (David Craig Berman; January 4, 1967&nbsp;– August 7, 2019) was an American musician, singer, poet and <a href="/wiki/Cartoonist" title="Cartoonist">cartoonist</a>. In 1989, he founded the <a href="/wiki/Indie-rock" class="mw-redirect" title="Indie-rock">indie-rock</a> band <a href="/wiki/Silver_Jews" title="Silver Jews">Silver Jews</a> with <a href="/wiki/Stephen_Malkmus" title="Stephen Malkmus">Stephen Malkmus</a> and <a href="/wiki/Bob_Nastanovich" title="Bob Nastanovich">Bob Nastanovich</a>. He was the only constant member during the band's discography, which concluded in 2009, following the band's sixth and final album <i><a href="/wiki/Lookout_Mountain,_Lookout_Sea" title="Lookout Mountain, Lookout Sea">Lookout Mountain, Lookout Sea</a></i> (2008). </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Berliner_Journal" title="Berliner Journal">Berliner Journal</a> (<small>19th and 20th-century Berlin-Kitchener newspaper</small>) </td> 
         <td>The <i>Berliner Journal</i> (later the <i>Ontario Journal</i>) was a German language <a href="/wiki/Weekly_newspaper" title="Weekly newspaper">weekly newspaper</a> published in <a href="/wiki/Berlin,_Ontario" class="mw-redirect" title="Berlin, Ontario">Berlin, Ontario</a> (later Kitchener) from 1859 to 1918. Founded by German immigrants <a href="/w/index.php?title=Friedrich_Rittinger&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Friedrich Rittinger (page does not exist)">Friedrich Rittinger</a><span class="noprint" style="font-size:85%; font-style: normal;">&nbsp;[<a href="https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Rittinger" class="extiw" title="de:Friedrich Rittinger">de</a>]</span> and <a href="/w/index.php?title=John_Motz&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="John Motz (page does not exist)">John Motz</a><span class="noprint" style="font-size:85%; font-style: normal;">&nbsp;[<a href="https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Motz" class="extiw" title="de:John Motz">de</a>]</span>, they operated the paper through most of its existence until their sons – <a href="/w/index.php?title=William_John_Motz&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="William John Motz (page does not exist)">William John Motz</a>, Herman Rittinger and <a href="/wiki/John_Adam_Rittinger" title="John Adam Rittinger">John Adam Rittinger</a> – took over the operation at the turn of the century. </td> 
         <td><span style="font-weight:bold;text-shadow:1px 1px 40px black"><a href="/wiki/User:Tkbrett" title="User:Tkbrett"><b><span style="color: #000000;">Tkbrett</span></b></a><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Tkbrett" title="User talk:Tkbrett"><span style="color: #FF0000;"> (?)</span></a></span> </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Everywhere_at_the_End_of_Time" title="Everywhere at the End of Time">Everywhere at the End of Time</a> (<small>albums depicting the stages of dementia</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Everywhere at the End of Time</i> is the eleventh recording by <a href="/wiki/The_Caretaker_(musician)" title="The Caretaker (musician)">the Caretaker</a>, an alias of English musician Leyland Kirby. Released from September 2016 to March 2019, it is a six-album series depicting the stages of <a href="/wiki/Dementia" title="Dementia">dementia</a> by deteriorating several samples of <a href="/wiki/1920s" title="1920s">1920s</a> <a href="/wiki/Ballroom" title="Ballroom">ballroom</a> music. Inspired by the success of his previous record <i><a href="/wiki/An_Empty_Bliss_Beyond_This_World" title="An Empty Bliss Beyond This World">An Empty Bliss Beyond This World</a></i> (2011), Kirby decided to produce <i>Everywhere at the End of Time</i> as the culmination of the Caretaker alias. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Wetrorave" title="User:Wetrorave">Wetrorave</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Wetrorave" title="User talk:Wetrorave">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><i>Khraniteli</i> is a live-action Soviet <a href="/wiki/Television_play" title="Television play">television play</a> adaptation of <a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien"><span class="nowrap">J. R. R.</span> Tolkien</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/The_Fellowship_of_the_Ring" title="The Fellowship of the Ring">The Fellowship of the Ring</a></i>, aired once in 1991 by <a href="/wiki/5TV_(Russian_TV_channel)" title="5TV (Russian TV channel)">Leningrad Television</a> and then thought <a href="/wiki/Lost_film" title="Lost film">lost</a>. It was rediscovered in 2021. It includes scenes of <a href="/wiki/Tom_Bombadil" title="Tom Bombadil">Tom Bombadil</a> and <a href="/wiki/Goldberry" title="Goldberry">Goldberry</a> that were omitted from Peter Jackson's <a href="/wiki/Lord_of_the_Rings_film_trilogy" class="mw-redirect" title="Lord of the Rings film trilogy"><i>Lord of the Rings</i> film trilogy</a>. </td>

         <td>Regina Encarnacion Ansong Velasquez ( <a href="/wiki/Help:Pronunciation_respelling_key" title="Help:Pronunciation respelling key"><i title="English pronunciation respelling"><span style="font-size:90%">REE</span>-jeen <span style="font-size:90%">VEH</span>-las-<span style="font-size:90%">KEZ</span></i></a>) (born April 22, 1970) is a <a href="/wiki/Filipinos" title="Filipinos">Filipino</a> singer, actor, and record producer who came to prominence after winning the 1984 <i><a href="/wiki/Ang_Bagong_Kampeon" title="Ang Bagong Kampeon">Ang Bagong Kampeon</a></i> and the 1989 <a href="/wiki/ABU_Song_Festivals" title="ABU Song Festivals">Asia Pacific Singing Contest</a>.          <td><a href="/wiki/IBM_ThinkPad_701" title="IBM ThinkPad 701">IBM ThinkPad 701</a> (<small>Subnotebook computer with foldout keyboard</small>) </td> 
         <td>The IBM ThinkPad 701 is a discontinued <a href="/wiki/Subnotebook" title="Subnotebook">subnotebook</a> series from the <a href="/wiki/ThinkPad" title="ThinkPad">ThinkPad</a> line by <a href="/wiki/IBM" title="IBM">IBM</a> consisting of the 701C and 701Cs models. The 701 is colloquially known as the Butterfly due to its sliding keyboards and was developed from 1993. The sale was from March 1995 until later that year. It is based on the <a href="/wiki/I486" title="I486">Intel 486</a> and priced between 1499 and 3299 USD. </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-11 07:57 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/United_States_v._McMahon" title="United States v. McMahon">United States v. McMahon</a> (<small>1994 criminal court case</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>United States v. McMahon et al</i> (9:93-cr-01276) is a 1994 <a href="/wiki/United_States_District_Court_for_the_Eastern_District_of_New_York" title="United States District Court for the Eastern District of New York">United States District Court for the Eastern District of New York</a> criminal court case brought against <a href="/wiki/Vince_McMahon" title="Vince McMahon">Vince McMahon</a>, chairman of the <a href="/wiki/WWE" title="WWE">World Wrestling Federation</a> on suspicion of supplying illegal <a href="/wiki/Anabolic_steroids" class="mw-redirect" title="Anabolic steroids">anabolic steroids</a> to his professional wrestlers. The jury found McMahon not guilty on July 23, 1994. </td> 
         <td><span style="text-shadow:grey 0.5em 0.5em 0.6em;"> <b><a href="/wiki/User:The_C_of_E" title="User:The C of E"><font color="red">The C of E </font><font color="blue"> God Save the Queen!</font></a></b> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:The_C_of_E" title="User talk:The C of E"><font color="darkblue">talk</font></a>)</span> </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Japanese_idol" title="Japanese idol">Japanese idol</a> (<small>Japanese type of entertainer</small>) </td> 
         <td>An idol<span style="font-weight: normal"> (<span lang="ja" title="Japanese-language text">????</span>, <i lang="ja-Latn" title="Hepburn transliteration">aidoru</i>)</span> is a type of entertainer manufactured and marketed for image, attractiveness, and personality in Japanese pop culture. Idols are primarily singers with training in acting, dancing, and modeling. Idols are commercialized through merchandise and endorsements by <a href="/wiki/Talent_agent" title="Talent agent">talent agencies</a>, while maintaining a <a href="/wiki/Parasocial_relationship" class="mw-redirect" title="Parasocial relationship">parasocial relationship</a> with a passionate consumer fan base. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Tom_Hull_(critic)" title="Tom Hull (critic)">Tom Hull (critic)</a> (<small>American music critic, web designer and former software developer</small>) </td> 
         <td>Tom Hull (born 1950) is an American music critic, <a href="/wiki/Web_designer" class="mw-redirect" title="Web designer">web designer</a>, and former <a href="/wiki/Software_developer" class="mw-redirect" title="Software developer">software developer</a>. A native of <a href="/wiki/Wichita,_Kansas" title="Wichita, Kansas">Wichita, Kansas</a>, Hull had an isolated childhood marked by a deep interest in reading, particularly works by <a href="/wiki/Absurdist_fiction" title="Absurdist fiction">absurdist</a> writers and <a href="/wiki/Leftist" class="mw-redirect" title="Leftist">leftist</a> thinkers. While studying at <a href="/wiki/Washington_University_in_St._Louis" title="Washington University in St. Louis">Washington University in St. Louis</a> in the early 1970s, he pursued courses of a similar political vein before a friend introduced him to <a href="/wiki/Rock_criticism" class="mw-redirect" title="Rock criticism">rock criticism</a>, a flourishing field at the time. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Isento" title="User:Isento">isento</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Isento" title="User talk:Isento">talk</a>) </td>

Gladwell stated the <a href="/wiki/Audiobook" title="Audiobook">audiobook</a> for <i>The Bomber Mafia</i> came about as an expansion of material from his <a href="/wiki/Podcast" title="Podcast">podcast</a> <i><a href="/wiki/Revisionist_History_(podcast)" title="Revisionist History (podcast)">Revisionist History</a></i>, and that the print book originated from the audiobook. </td>

         <td>Nzube Udezue (born 19 August 1986), better known by his <a href="/wiki/Stage_name" title="Stage name">stage name</a> Zuby, is a British rapper. In July 2008, Udezue was misidentified and arrested by police at gunpoint at <a href="/wiki/Bournemouth_railway_station" title="Bournemouth railway station">Bournemouth railway station</a> due to miscommunication regarding a suspect's description. The incident received media coverage and the police apologized for the incident, which was compared to the <a href="/wiki/Shooting_of_Jean_Charles_de_Menezes" title="Shooting of Jean Charles de Menezes">shooting of Jean Charles de Menezes</a>. </td>

While working as a local makeup artist in his hometown of <a href="/wiki/Bethlehem,_New_York" title="Bethlehem, New York">Bethlehem, New York</a>, he started a YouTube channel, posting makeup tutorials.          <td>BTS (<a href="/wiki/Korean_language" title="Korean language">Korean</a>:&nbsp;<span lang="ko" title="Korean-language text">?????</span>; <a href="/wiki/Revised_Romanization_of_Korean" title="Revised Romanization of Korean">RR</a>:&nbsp;<i><i lang="ko-Latn" title="Korean-language romanization">Bangtan Sonyeondan</i></i>), also known as the Bangtan Boys, is a seven-member South Korean <a href="/wiki/Boy_band" title="Boy band">boy band</a> that began formation in 2010 and debuted in 2013 under <a href="/wiki/Big_Hit_Music" title="Big Hit Music">Big Hit Entertainment</a>. The septet—composed of <a href="/wiki/Kim_Seok-jin" title="Kim Seok-jin">Jin</a>, <a href="/wiki/Suga_(rapper)" title="Suga (rapper)">Suga</a>, <a href="/wiki/J-Hope" title="J-Hope">J-Hope</a>, <a href="/wiki/RM_(rapper)" title="RM (rapper)">RM</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jimin_(singer,_born_1995)" title="Jimin (singer, born 1995)">Jimin</a>, <a href="/wiki/V_(singer)" title="V (singer)">V</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Jungkook" title="Jungkook">Jungkook</a>—co-writes and co-produces much of their own output. </td>

         <td class="old">2021-02-12 11:10 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Beowulf_in_Middle-earth" title="Beowulf in Middle-earth">Beowulf in Middle-earth</a> </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>, a fantasy author and professional <a href="/wiki/Philologist" class="mw-redirect" title="Philologist">philologist</a>, drew on the <a href="/wiki/Old_English" title="Old English">Old English</a> poem <i><a href="/wiki/Beowulf" title="Beowulf">Beowulf</a></i> for multiple aspects of his <a href="/wiki/Middle-earth" title="Middle-earth">Middle-earth</a> legendarium: in terms of elements such as names, monsters, and the structure of society in a heroic age; in terms of style such as creating an <a href="/wiki/Impression_of_depth_in_The_Lord_of_the_Rings" title="Impression of depth in The Lord of the Rings">impression of depth</a> and adopting an <a href="/wiki/Decline_and_fall_in_Middle-earth#Fading" title="Decline and fall in Middle-earth">elegiac tone</a>; and in terms of its larger but hidden symbolism. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Chiswick_Chap" title="User:Chiswick Chap">Chiswick Chap</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Chiswick_Chap" title="User talk:Chiswick Chap">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="old">2021-02-15 16:33 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Man_in_the_Moon_Stayed_Up_Too_Late" title="The Man in the Moon Stayed Up Too Late">The Man in the Moon Stayed Up Too Late</a> (<small>Poem in The Lord of the Rings</small>) </td> 
         <td>"The Man in the Moon Stayed Up Too Late" is <a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s imagined original ditty behind the <a href="/wiki/Nursery_rhyme" title="Nursery rhyme">nursery rhyme</a> "<a href="/wiki/Hey_Diddle_Diddle" title="Hey Diddle Diddle">Hey Diddle Diddle</a> (The Cat and the Fiddle)", invented by <a href="/wiki/Back_formation" class="mw-redirect" title="Back formation">back formation</a>. The title of the extended 1962 version is given in <i><a href="/wiki/The_Adventures_of_Tom_Bombadil" title="The Adventures of Tom Bombadil">The Adventures of Tom Bombadil</a></i>. It was first published in <i>Yorkshire Poetry</i> in 1923. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Chiswick_Chap" title="User:Chiswick Chap">Chiswick Chap</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Chiswick_Chap" title="User talk:Chiswick Chap">talk</a>) </td>

         <td class="old">2021-02-17 16:23 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Th%C3%A9oden" title="Théoden">Théoden</a> </td> 
         <td>Théoden is a fictional character in <a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Fantasy" title="Fantasy">fantasy</a> novel, <i><a href="/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings" title="The Lord of the Rings">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. The King and Lord of the Mark of <a href="/wiki/Rohan_(Middle-earth)" title="Rohan (Middle-earth)">Rohan</a>, he appears as a major supporting character in <i><a href="/wiki/The_Two_Towers" title="The Two Towers">The Two Towers</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/The_Return_of_the_King" title="The Return of the King">The Return of the King</a></i>. When first introduced, Théoden is weak with age and sorrow and the machinations of his top advisor, <a href="/wiki/Gr%C3%ADma_Wormtongue" title="Gríma Wormtongue">Gríma Wormtongue</a>, and he does nothing as his kingdom is crumbling. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Chiswick_Chap" title="User:Chiswick Chap">Chiswick Chap</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Chiswick_Chap" title="User talk:Chiswick Chap">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Denethor" title="Denethor">Denethor</a> (<small>Fictional character, steward of Gondor, in "The Lord of the Rings"</small>) </td> 
         <td>Denethor II, son of Ecthelion II, is a fictional character in <a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s novel <i><a href="/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings" title="The Lord of the Rings">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>. He was the 26th Ruling <a href="/wiki/Steward_of_Gondor" class="mw-redirect" title="Steward of Gondor">Steward of Gondor</a>, committing suicide in the besieged city of <a href="/wiki/Minas_Tirith" class="mw-redirect" title="Minas Tirith">Minas Tirith</a> during the <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_the_Pelennor_Fields" title="Battle of the Pelennor Fields">Battle of the Pelennor Fields</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Chiswick_Chap" title="User:Chiswick Chap">Chiswick Chap</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Chiswick_Chap" title="User talk:Chiswick Chap">talk</a>) </td>

        <tr> 
         <td class="recent">2021-03-13 19:48 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Man_(Middle-earth)" title="Man (Middle-earth)">Man (Middle-earth)</a> (<small>The human race as it appears in J. R. R. Tolkien's Middle-earth fiction</small>) </td> 
         <td>In <a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Middle-earth" title="Middle-earth">Middle-earth</a> fiction, Man and Men denote <a href="/wiki/Human" title="Human">humans</a>, whether male or female, in contrast to <a href="/wiki/Elf_(Middle-earth)" title="Elf (Middle-earth)">Elves</a>, <a href="/wiki/Dwarf_(Middle-earth)" title="Dwarf (Middle-earth)">Dwarves</a>, <a href="/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)" class="mw-redirect" title="Orc (Middle-earth)">Orcs</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Middle-earth_peoples" title="Middle-earth peoples">other humanoid races</a>. <p>Men are described as the second or younger people, created after the Elves, and differing from them in being mortal. Along with <a href="/wiki/Ent" title="Ent">Ents</a> and Dwarves, these are the "free peoples" of Middle-earth, differing from the enslaved peoples such as <a href="/wiki/Orc" title="Orc">Orcs</a>. </p> </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Chiswick_Chap" title="User:Chiswick Chap">Chiswick Chap</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Chiswick_Chap" title="User talk:Chiswick Chap">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="recent">2021-03-24 22:35 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Goldberry" title="Goldberry">Goldberry</a> </td> 
         <td>Goldberry is a character from the works of author <a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>. She first appeared in print in a 1934 poem called <i>The Adventures of Tom Bombadil</i>, where she appears as the wife of <a href="/wiki/Tom_Bombadil" title="Tom Bombadil">Tom Bombadil</a>. Also known as the "River-woman's daughter", she is described as a beautiful, youthful woman with golden hair. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Chiswick_Chap" title="User:Chiswick Chap">Chiswick Chap</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Chiswick_Chap" title="User talk:Chiswick Chap">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="recent">2021-04-19 14:01 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Peter_Jackson%27s_interpretation_of_The_Lord_of_the_Rings" title="Peter Jackson's interpretation of The Lord of the Rings">Peter Jackson's interpretation of The Lord of the Rings</a> (<small>Commentators' analysis of Peter Jackson's film interpretation of J. R. R. Tolkien's Lord of the Rings</small>) </td> 
         <td>Commentators have compared <a href="/wiki/Peter_Jackson" title="Peter Jackson">Peter Jackson</a>'s 2001–2003 <a href="/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings_(film_series)" title="The Lord of the Rings (film series)"><i>The Lord of the Rings</i> film trilogy</a> with the book on which it was based, <a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>'s 1954–1955 <i><a href="/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings" title="The Lord of the Rings">The Lord of the Rings</a></i>, remarking that while both have been extremely successful commercially, the film version does not necessarily capture the intended meaning of the book. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Chiswick_Chap" title="User:Chiswick Chap">Chiswick Chap</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Chiswick_Chap" title="User talk:Chiswick Chap">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-09 11:18 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Tolkien%27s_frame_stories" title="Tolkien's frame stories">Tolkien's frame stories</a> (<small>J. R. R. Tolkien's use of stories to frame his novels</small>) </td> 
         <td>Tolkien's frame stories are the narrative devices that <a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien">J. R. R. Tolkien</a> chose to use throughout his <a href="/wiki/Middle-earth" title="Middle-earth">Middle-earth</a> writings, especially <a href="/wiki/Tolkien%27s_legendarium" title="Tolkien's legendarium">his legendarium</a>, to make the works <a href="/wiki/Mythopoeia" title="Mythopoeia">resemble a genuine mythology</a> written and edited by many hands over a long period of time. He described in detail how his fictional characters wrote their books and transmitted them to others, and showed how later editors annotated the material. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Chiswick_Chap" title="User:Chiswick Chap">Chiswick Chap</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Chiswick_Chap" title="User talk:Chiswick Chap">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-18 23:54 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Fierce_Femmes_and_Notorious_Liars" title="Fierce Femmes and Notorious Liars">Fierce Femmes and Notorious Liars</a> (<small>2016 novel</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Fierce Femmes and Notorious Liars: A Dangerous Trans Girl's Confabulous Memoir</i> is a 2016 Canadian book by <a href="/wiki/Kai_Cheng_Thom" title="Kai Cheng Thom">Kai Cheng Thom</a>. A <a href="/wiki/Surrealist" class="mw-redirect" title="Surrealist">surrealist</a> novel, it follows an unnamed <a href="/wiki/Transgender_woman" class="mw-redirect" title="Transgender woman">transgender woman</a> protagonist who leaves home at a young age to live on the Street of Miracles—where various <a href="/wiki/Sex_work" title="Sex work">sex work</a> takes place—with other "<a href="/wiki/Femme" title="Femme">femmes</a>" (trans women). </td> 
         <td>— <a href="/wiki/User:Bilorv" title="User:Bilorv">Bilorv</a> (<b><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Bilorv" title="User talk:Bilorv"><span style="color:purple">talk</span></a></b>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-21 19:32 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Time_travel_in_The_Lord_of_the_Rings" title="Time travel in The Lord of the Rings">Time travel in The Lord of the Rings</a> (<small>distortions of time in fantasy by J. R. R. Tolkien</small>) </td> 
         <td>Tolkien embedded time travel in <i>The Lord of the Rings</i> in a variety of ways. The passage of time in the book is uneven, seeming to run at differing speeds in the realms of <a href="/wiki/Men_(Middle-earth)" class="mw-redirect" title="Men (Middle-earth)">Men</a> and of <a href="/wiki/Elves_(Middle-Earth)" class="mw-redirect" title="Elves (Middle-Earth)">Elves</a>. In this, <a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien">Tolkien</a> was following medieval tradition in which time proceeds differently in <a href="/wiki/Elfland" class="mw-redirect" title="Elfland">Elfland</a>. The whole work, too, following the theory he spelt out in his essay "<a href="/wiki/On_Fairy-Stories" title="On Fairy-Stories">On Fairy-Stories</a>", is meant to transport the reader into another time. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Chiswick_Chap" title="User:Chiswick Chap">Chiswick Chap</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Chiswick_Chap" title="User talk:Chiswick Chap">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

      </table> 
      <h2><span id="Culture.2FMedia.2FFilms"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Culture/Media/Films">Culture/Media/Films</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=User:SDZeroBot/GAN_sorting&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Culture/Media/Films">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <table class="wikitable sortable">

         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Hunger_Games:_Mockingjay_%E2%80%93_Part_1" title="The Hunger Games: Mockingjay – Part 1">The Hunger Games: Mockingjay – Part 1</a> (<small>2014 film by Francis Lawrence</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>The Hunger Games: Mockingjay – Part 1</i> is a 2014 American <a href="/wiki/Utopian_and_dystopian_fiction" title="Utopian and dystopian fiction">dystopian</a> <a href="/wiki/Science_fiction_film" title="Science fiction film">science fiction</a> <a href="/wiki/Adventure_film" title="Adventure film">adventure film</a> directed by <a href="/wiki/Francis_Lawrence" title="Francis Lawrence">Francis Lawrence</a> with a screenplay by <a href="/wiki/Peter_Craig" title="Peter Craig">Peter Craig</a> and <a href="/wiki/Danny_Strong" title="Danny Strong">Danny Strong</a>. It is the first of two films based on <a href="/wiki/Suzanne_Collins" title="Suzanne Collins">Suzanne Collins</a>' 2010 novel <i> <a href="/wiki/Mockingjay" title="Mockingjay">Mockingjay</a></i>, the final book in <i><a href="/wiki/The_Hunger_Games" title="The Hunger Games">The Hunger Games</a></i> trilogy, and the third installment in <a href="/wiki/The_Hunger_Games_(film_series)" title="The Hunger Games (film series)"><i>The Hunger Games</i> film series</a>, produced by <a href="/wiki/Nina_Jacobson" title="Nina Jacobson">Nina Jacobson</a> and Jon Kilik and distributed by <a href="/wiki/Lionsgate" title="Lionsgate">Lionsgate</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Hunger_Games:_Catching_Fire" title="The Hunger Games: Catching Fire">The Hunger Games: Catching Fire</a> (<small>2013 film by Francis Lawrence</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>The Hunger Games: Catching Fire</i> is a 2013 American <a href="/wiki/Utopian_and_dystopian_fiction" title="Utopian and dystopian fiction">dystopian</a> <a href="/wiki/Science_fiction_film" title="Science fiction film">science fiction</a> <a href="/wiki/Adventure_film" title="Adventure film">adventure film</a> based on <a href="/wiki/Suzanne_Collins" title="Suzanne Collins">Suzanne Collins</a>' <a href="/wiki/Dystopian_novel" class="mw-redirect" title="Dystopian novel">dystopian novel</a> <i><a href="/wiki/Catching_Fire" title="Catching Fire">Catching Fire</a></i> (2009), the second installment in <a href="/wiki/The_Hunger_Games" title="The Hunger Games"><i>The Hunger Games</i> trilogy</a>. The film is the sequel to <i><a href="/wiki/The_Hunger_Games_(film)" title="The Hunger Games (film)">The Hunger Games</a></i> (2012) and the second installment in <a href="/wiki/The_Hunger_Games_(film_series)" title="The Hunger Games (film series)"><i>The Hunger Games</i> film series</a>, produced by <a href="/wiki/Nina_Jacobson" title="Nina Jacobson">Nina Jacobson</a> and Jon Kilik, with co-production by <a href="/wiki/Lionsgate_Films" title="Lionsgate Films">Lionsgate Films</a> and distributed by <a href="/wiki/Lionsgate_Entertainment" class="mw-redirect" title="Lionsgate Entertainment">Lionsgate Entertainment</a>. </td>

         <td><i>Jojo Rabbit</i> is a 2019 <a href="/wiki/Comedy-drama_film" class="mw-redirect" title="Comedy-drama film">comedy-drama film</a> written and directed by <a href="/wiki/Taika_Waititi" title="Taika Waititi">Taika Waititi</a>, adapted from <a href="/wiki/Christine_Leunens" title="Christine Leunens">Christine Leunens</a>'s 2008 book <i>Caging Skies</i>. <a href="/wiki/Roman_Griffin_Davis" title="Roman Griffin Davis">Roman Griffin Davis</a> portrays the title character, Johannes "Jojo" Betzler, a ten-year-old <a href="/wiki/Hitler_Youth" title="Hitler Youth">Hitler Youth</a> member who finds out that his mother (<a href="/wiki/Scarlett_Johansson" title="Scarlett Johansson">Scarlett Johansson</a>) is hiding a <a href="/wiki/History_of_the_Jews_in_Germany" title="History of the Jews in Germany">Jewish</a> girl (<a href="/wiki/Thomasin_McKenzie" title="Thomasin McKenzie">Thomasin McKenzie</a>) in their attic. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Shape_of_Water" title="The Shape of Water">The Shape of Water</a> (<small>2017 film by Guillermo del Toro</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>The Shape of Water</i> is a 2017 American <a href="/wiki/Romantic_fantasy" title="Romantic fantasy">romantic fantasy</a> film directed by <a href="/wiki/Guillermo_del_Toro" title="Guillermo del Toro">Guillermo del Toro</a> and written by del Toro and <a href="/wiki/Vanessa_Taylor" title="Vanessa Taylor">Vanessa Taylor</a>. It stars <a href="/wiki/Sally_Hawkins" title="Sally Hawkins">Sally Hawkins</a>, <a href="/wiki/Michael_Shannon" title="Michael Shannon">Michael Shannon</a>, <a href="/wiki/Richard_Jenkins" title="Richard Jenkins">Richard Jenkins</a>, <a href="/wiki/Doug_Jones_(actor)" title="Doug Jones (actor)">Doug Jones</a>, <a href="/wiki/Michael_Stuhlbarg" title="Michael Stuhlbarg">Michael Stuhlbarg</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Octavia_Spencer" title="Octavia Spencer">Octavia Spencer</a>. Set in <a href="/wiki/Baltimore" title="Baltimore">Baltimore</a>, <a href="/wiki/Maryland" title="Maryland">Maryland</a>, in 1962, the story follows a mute cleaner at a high-security government laboratory who falls in love with a captured <a href="/wiki/Humanoid" title="Humanoid">humanoid</a> <a href="/wiki/Amphibian" title="Amphibian">amphibian</a> creature. </td>

Produced by <a href="/wiki/Sam_Raimi" title="Sam Raimi">Sam Raimi</a>, the plot follows <a href="/wiki/Kaya_Scodelario" title="Kaya Scodelario">Kaya Scodelario</a> and <a href="/wiki/Barry_Pepper" title="Barry Pepper">Barry Pepper</a> as a daughter and father who, along with their dog, are hunted by alligators after being trapped in their home during a <a href="/wiki/Category_5_hurricane" class="mw-redirect" title="Category 5 hurricane">Category 5 hurricane</a> in Florida. </td>

Produced by <a href="/wiki/Lorenzo_di_Bonaventura" title="Lorenzo di Bonaventura">Lorenzo di Bonaventura</a> through <a href="/wiki/Di_Bonaventura_Pictures" title="Di Bonaventura Pictures">Di Bonaventura Pictures</a>, the feature was created on an estimated budget of $21 million. </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-12 14:18 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Cinema_of_Sudan" title="Cinema of Sudan">Cinema of Sudan</a> (<small>History of films and cinema in Sudan</small>) </td> 
         <td>Cinema of Sudan refers to both the <a href="/wiki/History_of_film" title="History of film">history</a> and present of the <a href="/wiki/Filmmaking" title="Filmmaking">making</a> or screening of films in <a href="/wiki/Movie_theater" title="Movie theater">cinemas</a> or <a href="/wiki/Film_festival" title="Film festival">film festivals</a>, as well as to the persons involved in this form of <a href="/wiki/Audiovisual" title="Audiovisual">audiovisual</a> culture of the Sudan and its <a href="/wiki/History_of_Sudan" title="History of Sudan">history</a> from the late nineteenth century onwards. It began with <a href="/wiki/Cinematography" title="Cinematography">cinematography</a> during the <a href="/wiki/History_of_Anglo-Egyptian_Sudan" title="History of Anglo-Egyptian Sudan">British colonial presence</a> in 1898 and developed along with advances in <a href="/wiki/Cinematography" title="Cinematography">film technology</a> during the twentieth century. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Munfarid1" title="User:Munfarid1">Munfarid1</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Munfarid1" title="User talk:Munfarid1">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="new">2021-06-02 08:59 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Maine_Pyar_Kiya" title="Maine Pyar Kiya">Maine Pyar Kiya</a> (<small>1989 film by Sooraj Barjatya</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Maine Pyar Kiya</i> (<abbr title="translation">transl.</abbr><span>?<i>I Loved</i></span>) is an 1989 Indian <a href="/wiki/Hindi" title="Hindi">Hindi</a>-language romantic musical film directed by <a href="/wiki/Sooraj_Barjatya" title="Sooraj Barjatya">Sooraj Barjatya</a> in his directorial debut, produced by <a href="/wiki/Rajshri_Productions" title="Rajshri Productions">Rajshri Productions</a> and co-written by S. M. Ahale with Sooraj Barjatya. It starring <a href="/wiki/Salman_Khan" title="Salman Khan">Salman Khan</a> and <a href="/wiki/Bhagyashree" title="Bhagyashree">Bhagyashree</a> in their acting debut, with <a href="/wiki/Alok_Nath" title="Alok Nath">Alok Nath</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mohnish_Bahl" title="Mohnish Bahl">Mohnish Bahl</a>, <a href="/wiki/Reema_Lagoo" title="Reema Lagoo">Reema Lagoo</a>, <a href="/wiki/Rajeev_Verma" title="Rajeev Verma">Rajeev Verma</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ajit_Vachani" title="Ajit Vachani">Ajit Vachani</a> and <a href="/wiki/Laxmikant_Berde" title="Laxmikant Berde">Laxmikant Berde</a> in supporting roles. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:25_Cents_FC" title="User:25 Cents FC"><span style="font-family:Brush Script MT;color:MediumSlateBlue">25 CENTS VICTORIOUS</span></a>&nbsp;<sup><a href="/wiki/User_talk:25_Cents_FC" title="User talk:25 Cents FC"><span style="font-family:Bradley Hand ITC;color:black">??</span></a></sup> </td>

         <td class="old">2021-01-30 08:30 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Progressive_soul" title="Progressive soul">Progressive soul</a> </td> 
         <td>Progressive soul (often shortened to prog-soul; also called black prog) is a type of <a href="/wiki/African-American_music" title="African-American music">African-American music</a> that utilizes a <a href="/wiki/Progressive_music" title="Progressive music">progressive</a> approach, particularly in the context of the <a href="/wiki/Soul_music" title="Soul music">soul</a> and <a href="/wiki/Funk" title="Funk">funk</a> genres. It developed in the late 1960s and early 1970s through the recordings of innovative black musicians who pushed the structural and stylistic boundaries of those genres, influenced by philosophies and characteristics from <a href="/wiki/Progressive_rock" title="Progressive rock">progressive rock</a>, <a href="/wiki/Psychedelic_soul" title="Psychedelic soul">psychedelic soul</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Jazz_fusion" title="Jazz fusion">jazz fusion</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Isento" title="User:Isento">isento</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Isento" title="User talk:Isento">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="old">2021-02-02 04:19 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/K._T._Oslin" title="K. T. Oslin">K. T. Oslin</a> (<small>American singer-songwriter</small>) </td> 
         <td>Kay Toinette Oslin (May 15, 1942 – December 21, 2020) was an American <a href="/wiki/Country_music" title="Country music">country music</a> singer–songwriter. Oslin had several years of major commercial success in the late 1980s after signing a record deal at age 45. She had four number one hits and placed additional singles on the <i><a href="/wiki/Billboard_(magazine)" title="Billboard (magazine)">Billboard</a></i> country chart during that timespan; in addition, she won three <a href="/wiki/Grammy_Awards" title="Grammy Awards">Grammy Awards</a> and is an inductee of the <a href="/wiki/Nashville_Songwriters_Hall_of_Fame" title="Nashville Songwriters Hall of Fame">Nashville Songwriters Hall of Fame</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:ChrisTofu11961" title="User:ChrisTofu11961">ChrisTofu11961</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:ChrisTofu11961" title="User talk:ChrisTofu11961">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="old">2021-02-09 01:09 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Lap_steel_guitar" title="Lap steel guitar">Lap steel guitar</a> </td> 
         <td>The lap steel guitar, also known as a Hawaiian guitar, is a type of <a href="/wiki/Steel_guitar" title="Steel guitar">steel guitar</a> without pedals that is typically played with the instrument in a horizontal position across the performer's <a href="/wiki/Lap" title="Lap">lap</a>. Unlike the normal manner of playing a traditional <a href="/wiki/Acoustic_guitar" title="Acoustic guitar">acoustic guitar</a>, in which the performer's fingertips press the strings against <a href="/wiki/Frets" class="mw-redirect" title="Frets">frets</a>, the pitch of a lap steel guitar is changed by pressing a polished <a href="/wiki/Steel_bar" title="Steel bar">steel bar</a> against plucked strings (from which the name "steel guitar" derives). </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Eagledj" title="User:Eagledj">Eagledj</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Eagledj" title="User talk:Eagledj">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="old">2021-02-16 05:07 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Mickey_Guyton" title="Mickey Guyton">Mickey Guyton</a> (<small>American country music singer</small>) </td> 
         <td>Mickey Guyton (born Candace Mycale Guyton; June 17, 1983) is an American <a href="/wiki/Country_music" title="Country music">country music</a> artist. Her material incorporates elements of contemporary country and <a href="/wiki/Country_pop" title="Country pop">country pop</a>. Raised in Texas, Guyton was exposed to various types of music at a young age, notably country. Moving to <a href="/wiki/Nashville,_Tennessee" title="Nashville, Tennessee">Nashville, Tennessee</a>, she would later sign a recording contract with <a href="/wiki/Capitol_Records_Nashville" title="Capitol Records Nashville">Capitol Records Nashville</a>. </td> 
         <td><span style="color:green"><b>Ten Pound Hammer</b></span> • <sup>(<a href="/wiki/User_talk:TenPoundHammer" title="User talk:TenPoundHammer">What did I screw up now?</a>)</sup> </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="recent">2021-03-21 19:55 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Doug_Sahm" title="Doug Sahm">Doug Sahm</a> </td> 
         <td>Douglas Wayne Sahm (November 6, 1941 – November 18, 1999) was an American musician, singer-songwriter and <a href="/wiki/Multi-instrumentalist" title="Multi-instrumentalist">multi-instrumentalist</a> born in <a href="/wiki/San_Antonio,_Texas" class="mw-redirect" title="San Antonio, Texas">San Antonio, Texas</a>. Sahm began singing at age five and learned to play the steel guitar at age six. He was considered a <a href="/wiki/Child_prodigy" title="Child prodigy">child prodigy</a> on the instrument. By the age of eight, he had appeared on the <i><a href="/wiki/Louisiana_Hayride" title="Louisiana Hayride">Louisiana Hayride</a></i>. </td> 
         <td><span style="background:#75B2DD; padding:2px;"><a href="/wiki/User:GDuwen" title="User:GDuwen"><b style="color:#E62020">GD</b><b style="color:#273BE2">uwen</b></a></span><a href="/wiki/User_talk:GDuwen" title="User talk:GDuwen"><b style="background:#318CE7; padding:2px; color:cyan"><small>Holler!</small></b></a> </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="recent">2021-03-24 15:26 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Pop_Smoke" title="Pop Smoke">Pop Smoke</a> (<small>American rapper from New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>Bashar Barakah Jackson (July 20, 1999 – February 19, 2020), known professionally as Pop Smoke, was an American rapper, singer, and songwriter. He was considered by many to be the face of <a href="/wiki/Brooklyn_drill" title="Brooklyn drill">Brooklyn drill</a>. Born and raised in <a href="/wiki/Canarsie,_Brooklyn" title="Canarsie, Brooklyn">Canarsie, Brooklyn</a>, Pop Smoke began his musical career in late 2018 after releasing his debut single titled "Mpr (Panic Part 3 Remix)". </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:The_Ultimate_Boss" class="mw-redirect" title="User:The Ultimate Boss">The Ultimate Boss</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:The_Ultimate_Boss" class="mw-redirect" title="User talk:The Ultimate Boss">talk</a>) </td>

Kelly">R. Kelly</a> and <a href="/wiki/Polow_da_Don" title="Polow da Don">Polow da Don</a>; Kelly also produced the song. Kelly">child pornography in 2002</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1977_(Ash_album)" title="1977 (Ash album)">1977 (Ash album)</a> (<small>1996 studio album by Ash</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>1977</i> is the debut studio album by Northern Irish <a href="/wiki/Rock_music" title="Rock music">rock</a> band <a href="/wiki/Ash_(band)" title="Ash (band)">Ash</a>. It was released on 6&nbsp;May 1996, through <a href="/wiki/Infectious_Music" title="Infectious Music">Infectious Records</a> with whom the band had signed following the release of several demo tapes. They released the <a href="/wiki/Mini-album" class="mw-redirect" title="Mini-album">mini-album</a> <i><a href="/wiki/Trailer_(album)" title="Trailer (album)">Trailer</a></i> (1994) in 1994, and followed it with three <a href="/wiki/Single_(music)" title="Single (music)">singles</a> "<a href="/wiki/Kung_Fu_(song)" title="Kung Fu (song)">Kung Fu</a>", "<a href="/wiki/Girl_from_Mars" title="Girl from Mars">Girl from Mars</a>", and "<a href="/wiki/Angel_Interceptor" title="Angel Interceptor">Angel Interceptor</a>", all of which would reappear on <i>1977</i>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/We_Are_Paintermen" title="We Are Paintermen">We Are Paintermen</a> (<small>1967 studio album by the Creation</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>We Are Paintermen</i> is the debut studio album by British rock band <a href="/wiki/The_Creation_(band)" title="The Creation (band)">the Creation</a>, initially released through Hit-Ton records in <a href="/wiki/West_Germany" title="West Germany">West Germany</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sonet_Records" title="Sonet Records">Sonet Records</a> in <a href="/wiki/Denmark" title="Denmark">Denmark</a> in June 1967. The album acts as a <a href="/wiki/Compilation_album" title="Compilation album">compilation album</a>, containing virtually all their recorded material, from "<a href="/wiki/Making_Time" title="Making Time">Making Time</a>" in 1966 to "If I Stay Too Long", which was released as a single in West Germany the same month. </td>

         <td><i>Kristofferson</i> is the debut album of singer-songwriter <a href="/wiki/Kris_Kristofferson" title="Kris Kristofferson">Kris Kristofferson</a>, which was produced by <a href="/wiki/Fred_Foster" title="Fred Foster">Fred Foster</a> and released in June 1970 by <a href="/wiki/Monument_Records" title="Monument Records">Monument Records</a>. Kristofferson aspired to become a writer when he finished high school. After graduating from <a href="/wiki/Pomona_College" title="Pomona College">Pomona College</a>, he was granted a <a href="/wiki/Rhodes_Scholarship" title="Rhodes Scholarship">Rhodes Scholarship</a> and attended <a href="/wiki/Oxford_University" class="mw-redirect" title="Oxford University">Oxford University</a>. </td>

         <td><i>Among the Living</i> is the third studio album by American <a href="/wiki/Thrash_metal" title="Thrash metal">thrash metal</a> band <a href="/wiki/Anthrax_(American_band)" title="Anthrax (American band)">Anthrax</a>. It was released on March 22, 1987 by <a href="/wiki/Megaforce_Records" title="Megaforce Records">Megaforce Records</a> in the US and by <a href="/wiki/Island_Records" title="Island Records">Island Records</a> in the rest of the world. The album is dedicated to <a href="/wiki/Cliff_Burton" title="Cliff Burton">Cliff Burton</a> of <a href="/wiki/Metallica" title="Metallica">Metallica</a>, who died in a bus accident six months before its release while on tour with Anthrax as the opening act. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Willow_(song)" title="Willow (song)">Willow (song)</a> (<small>2020 single by Taylor Swift</small>) </td> 
         <td>"Willow" (stylized in <a href="/wiki/All_lowercase" class="mw-redirect" title="All lowercase">all lowercase</a>) is a song recorded by American singer-songwriter <a href="/wiki/Taylor_Swift" title="Taylor Swift">Taylor Swift</a>, released on December 11, 2020, through <a href="/wiki/Republic_Records" title="Republic Records">Republic Records</a>. It is the opening track of her ninth studio album, <i><a href="/wiki/Evermore_(Taylor_Swift_album)" title="Evermore (Taylor Swift album)">Evermore</a></i> (2020), serving as its <a href="/wiki/Lead_single" title="Lead single">lead single</a>. A <a href="/wiki/Folk_baroque" title="Folk baroque">chamber-folk</a> love song built around <a href="/wiki/Guitar_picking" title="Guitar picking">picked</a> guitars, <a href="/wiki/Glockenspiel" title="Glockenspiel">glockenspiel</a>, flute, strings, and percussions, "Willow" makes use of several <a href="/wiki/Metaphor" title="Metaphor">metaphors</a> to convey the singer's romantic state of mind, such as portraying her life as a <a href="/wiki/Willow" title="Willow">willow</a> tree. </td> 
         <td><span class="nowrap"><a href="/wiki/User:Doggy54321" title="User:Doggy54321">D?ggy54321</a></span> <span class="nowrap"><sup>(<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Doggy54321" title="User talk:Doggy54321">let's chat!</a>)</sup></span> and <a href="/wiki/User:BawinV" title="User:BawinV">BawinV</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:BawinV#top" title="User talk:BawinV">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Sex_(The_1975_EP)" title="Sex (The 1975 EP)">Sex (The 1975 EP)</a> (<small>2012 EP by the 1975</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Sex</i> is the second <a href="/wiki/Extended_play" title="Extended play">extended play</a> (EP) by English band <a href="/wiki/The_1975" title="The 1975">the 1975</a>. It was released on 19 November 2012 by <a href="/wiki/Dirty_Hit" title="Dirty Hit">Dirty Hit</a>. A modified version was released in the US on 1 January 2013 by Dirty Hit and <a href="/wiki/Polydor_Records" title="Polydor Records">Polydor Records</a>. The band produced the EP alongside Michael Coles, Robert Coles and <a href="/wiki/Mike_Crossey" title="Mike Crossey">Mike Crossey</a>. They drew musical inspiration from <a href="/wiki/Sigur_R%C3%B3s" title="Sigur Rós">Sigur Rós</a>, <a href="/wiki/Brian_Eno" title="Brian Eno">Brian Eno</a> and filmmaker <a href="/wiki/John_Hughes_(filmmaker)" title="John Hughes (filmmaker)">John Hughes</a> while thematically focusing on the passage of time. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Leave_Me_Be" title="Leave Me Be">Leave Me Be</a> (<small>1964 single by the Zombies</small>) </td> 
         <td>"Leave Me Be" is a song written by British bassist <a href="/wiki/Chris_White_(musician)" title="Chris White (musician)">Chris White</a> and initially recorded by his band <a href="/wiki/The_Zombies" title="The Zombies">the Zombies</a>. Following the release of their debut single "<a href="/wiki/She%27s_Not_There" title="She's Not There">She's Not There</a>" in July 1964, White wrote a handful of songs in between performances during their hectic schedule. Characterized by its usage of <a href="/wiki/Minor_chord" title="Minor chord">minor chords</a> and <a href="/wiki/Chord_progression" title="Chord progression">chord progression</a>, the song lyrically deals with loneliness, a common theme in the Zombies music. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:VirreFriberg" title="User:VirreFriberg">VirreFriberg</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:VirreFriberg" title="User talk:VirreFriberg">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Stardust_(1927_song)" title="Stardust (1927 song)">Stardust (1927 song)</a> (<small>American popular song</small>) </td> 
         <td>"Stardust" is a <a href="/wiki/Jazz" title="Jazz">jazz</a> song composed by <a href="/wiki/Hoagy_Carmichael" title="Hoagy Carmichael">Hoagy Carmichael</a>. Now considered a <a href="/wiki/Standard_(music)" title="Standard (music)">standard</a> and part of the <a href="/wiki/Great_American_Songbook" title="Great American Songbook">Great American Songbook</a>, the song has been recorded over 1,500 times either as an <a href="/wiki/Instrumental" title="Instrumental">instrumental</a> or <a href="/wiki/Human_voice" title="Human voice">vocal</a> track featuring different performers. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Scary_Monsters_(and_Super_Creeps)" title="Scary Monsters (and Super Creeps)">Scary Monsters (and Super Creeps)</a> (<small>1980 studio album by David Bowie</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Scary Monsters (and Super Creeps)</i>, also known simply as <i>Scary Monsters</i>, is the 14th studio album by English musician <a href="/wiki/David_Bowie" title="David Bowie">David Bowie</a>, released on 12 September 1980 by <a href="/wiki/RCA_Records" title="RCA Records">RCA Records</a>. Over the past three years, Bowie garnered massive artistic success with the "<a href="/wiki/Berlin_Trilogy" title="Berlin Trilogy">Berlin Trilogy</a>", which consisted of <i><a href="/wiki/Low_(David_Bowie_album)" title="Low (David Bowie album)">Low</a></i>, <i><a href="/wiki/%22Heroes%22_(David_Bowie_album)" title="&quot;Heroes&quot; (David Bowie album)">"Heroes"</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Lodger_(album)" title="Lodger (album)">Lodger</a></i> (1977–1979). </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Ctrl_(SZA_album)" title="Ctrl (SZA album)">Ctrl (SZA album)</a> (<small>2017 studio album by SZA</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Ctrl</i> (pronounced "control") is the debut studio album by American singer <a href="/wiki/SZA" title="SZA">SZA</a>. It was released on June 9, 2017, on <a href="/wiki/Top_Dawg_Entertainment" title="Top Dawg Entertainment">Top Dawg Entertainment</a> and <a href="/wiki/RCA_Records" title="RCA Records">RCA Records</a>. It features guest appearances from <a href="/wiki/Travis_Scott" title="Travis Scott">Travis Scott</a>, <a href="/wiki/Kendrick_Lamar" title="Kendrick Lamar">Kendrick Lamar</a>, <a href="/wiki/James_Fauntleroy" title="James Fauntleroy">James Fauntleroy</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Isaiah_Rashad" title="Isaiah Rashad">Isaiah Rashad</a>. Originally scheduled for release in late 2015, it was delayed by SZA's experience of "a kind of blinding paralysis brought on by anxiety." She reworked the album until her record company took away her hard drive in the spring of 2017. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Meet_the_Woo" title="Meet the Woo">Meet the Woo</a> (<small>2019 mixtape by Pop Smoke</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Meet the Woo</i> (alternatively titled <i>Meet the Woo, Vol. 1</i>) is the debut <a href="/wiki/Mixtape" title="Mixtape">mixtape</a> by American rapper <a href="/wiki/Pop_Smoke" title="Pop Smoke">Pop Smoke</a>. It was released by <a href="/wiki/Steven_Victor#Victor_Victor_Worldwide" title="Steven Victor">Victor Victor Worldwide</a> and <a href="/wiki/Republic_Records" title="Republic Records">Republic Records</a> on July 26, 2019. <i>Meet the Woo</i> is a <a href="/wiki/Drill_music" title="Drill music">drill</a> and <a href="/wiki/Grime_music" class="mw-redirect" title="Grime music">grime</a> record. All the tracks were mostly written by Pop Smoke and British producer <a href="/wiki/808Melo" title="808Melo">808Melo</a>, with production from the latter, <a href="/wiki/Rico_Beats" title="Rico Beats">Rico Beats</a>, and Yoz Beats. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Shoot_for_the_Stars" title="User:Shoot for the Stars">Shoot for the Stars ?</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Shoot_for_the_Stars" title="User talk:Shoot for the Stars">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-21 22:45 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Canci%C3%B3n_Bonita" title="Canción Bonita">Canción Bonita</a> (<small>2021 single by Carlos Vives and Ricky Martin</small>) </td> 
         <td>"Canción Bonita" (<abbr title="translation">transl.</abbr><span>?"Beautiful Song"</span>) is a song recorded by Colombian singer <a href="/wiki/Carlos_Vives" title="Carlos Vives">Carlos Vives</a> and Puerto Rican singer <a href="/wiki/Ricky_Martin" title="Ricky Martin">Ricky Martin</a>. The song was written by <a href="/wiki/Andr%C3%A9s_Torres_(producer)" title="Andrés Torres (producer)">Andrés Torres</a>, Rafa Arcaute, Martin, Vives, and <a href="/wiki/Cali_y_El_Dandee" title="Cali y El Dandee">Mauricio Rengifo</a>, while the production was handled by Torres, Rengifo and Arcaute. The song was released for <a href="/wiki/Music_download" title="Music download">digital download</a> and <a href="/wiki/Streaming_media" title="Streaming media">streaming</a> by <a href="/wiki/Sony_Music_Latin" title="Sony Music Latin">Sony Music Latin</a> on April 13, 2021 as a <a href="/wiki/Single_(music)" title="Single (music)">single</a>. </td> 
         <td><b><a href="/wiki/User:Rodney_Araujo" title="User:Rodney Araujo">Rodney Araujo</a></b> <i><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Rodney_Araujo" title="User talk:Rodney Araujo">Tell me</a></i> - <a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/Rodney_Araujo" title="Special:Contributions/Rodney Araujo">My contributions</a> </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-23 03:34 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Loco_de_Amor_(Jerry_Rivera_song)" title="Loco de Amor (Jerry Rivera song)">Loco de Amor (Jerry Rivera song)</a> (<small>1996 song by Jerry Rivera</small>) </td> 
         <td>"Loco de Amor" is a song by Puerto Rican singer <a href="/wiki/Jerry_Rivera" title="Jerry Rivera">Jerry Rivera</a> from his seventh studio album <i><a href="/wiki/Fresco_(Jerry_Rivera_album)" title="Fresco (Jerry Rivera album)">Fresco</a></i> (1996). The song was written by Mary Lauret and produced by <a href="/wiki/Sergio_George" title="Sergio George">Sergio George</a> and Cuto Soto. The song, along with the rest of the album, is a <a href="/wiki/Salsa_music" title="Salsa music">salsa</a> tune in which Rivera confesses that he is crazy in love. The song was met with positive reactions from <a href="/wiki/Music_journalism" title="Music journalism">music critics</a> who called it a standout from <i>Fresco</i>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Magiciandude" title="User:Magiciandude">Erick</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Magiciandude" title="User talk:Magiciandude">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="new">2021-05-23 18:58 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Blue_Murder_(album)" title="Blue Murder (album)">Blue Murder (album)</a> (<small>1989 studio album by Blue Murder</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Blue Murder</i> is the eponymous debut album by English <a href="/wiki/Hard_rock" title="Hard rock">hard rock</a> band <a href="/wiki/Blue_Murder_(band)" title="Blue Murder (band)">Blue Murder</a>. Released on 24 April 1989 by <a href="/wiki/Geffen_Records" title="Geffen Records">Geffen Records</a>, it was produced by <a href="/wiki/Bob_Rock" title="Bob Rock">Bob Rock</a>. The band was formed by guitarist <a href="/wiki/John_Sykes" title="John Sykes">John Sykes</a> after his dismissal from <a href="/wiki/Whitesnake" title="Whitesnake">Whitesnake</a>. He recruited drummer <a href="/wiki/Cozy_Powell" title="Cozy Powell">Cozy Powell</a>, bassist <a href="/wiki/Tony_Franklin_(musician)" title="Tony Franklin (musician)">Tony Franklin</a> and vocalist <a href="/wiki/Ray_Gillen" title="Ray Gillen">Ray Gillen</a> in early 1987. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:SilverBullitt" title="User:SilverBullitt">SilverBullitt</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:SilverBullitt" title="User talk:SilverBullitt">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="new">2021-05-23 19:02 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Whitesnake" title="Whitesnake">Whitesnake</a> (<small>British hard rock band</small>) </td> 
         <td>Whitesnake are a <a href="/wiki/Hard_rock" title="Hard rock">hard rock</a> band formed in England in 1978. The group was originally put together as the backing band for singer <a href="/wiki/David_Coverdale" title="David Coverdale">David Coverdale</a>, who had recently left <a href="/wiki/Deep_Purple" title="Deep Purple">Deep Purple</a>. Though the band quickly developed into their own entity, Coverdale is the only constant member throughout their history. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:SilverBullitt" title="User:SilverBullitt">SilverBullitt</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:SilverBullitt" title="User talk:SilverBullitt">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Wish_You_Were_Gay" title="Wish You Were Gay">Wish You Were Gay</a> (<small>2019 single by Billie Eilish</small>) </td> 
         <td>"Wish You Were Gay" (stylized in <a href="/wiki/Letter_case#All_lowercase" title="Letter case">all lowercase</a>) is the fourth single on American singer <a href="/wiki/Billie_Eilish" title="Billie Eilish">Billie Eilish</a>'s debut studio album <i><a href="/wiki/When_We_All_Fall_Asleep,_Where_Do_We_Go%3F" title="When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?">When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?</a></i> (2019). It was written by Eilish and her brother <a href="/wiki/Finneas_O%27Connell" title="Finneas O'Connell">Finneas O'Connell</a>, while the latter solely handled the production. The song was release as the fourth single from the album on March 4, 2019, through Darkroom and <a href="/wiki/Interscope_Records" title="Interscope Records">Interscope Records</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Shoot_for_the_Stars" title="User:Shoot for the Stars">Shoot for the Stars ?</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Shoot_for_the_Stars" title="User talk:Shoot for the Stars">talk</a>) </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-24 14:24 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Most_of_the_Time" title="Most of the Time">Most of the Time</a> (<small>1989 song by Bob Dylan</small>) </td> 
         <td>"Most of the Time" is a song written and performed by American singer-songwriter <a href="/wiki/Bob_Dylan" title="Bob Dylan">Bob Dylan</a>, released as the sixth track (or the first song on Side Two of the vinyl) of his 1989 album <i><a href="/wiki/Oh_Mercy" title="Oh Mercy">Oh Mercy</a></i>. The song was written by Dylan and produced by <a href="/wiki/Daniel_Lanois" title="Daniel Lanois">Daniel Lanois</a>. The album version of "Most of the Time" was recorded on March 12, 1989 in a mobile studio at 1305 Soniat St., New Orleans, and released on <i>Oh Mercy</i> in September of that year. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:BennyOnTheLoose" title="User:BennyOnTheLoose">BennyOnTheLoose</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:BennyOnTheLoose" title="User talk:BennyOnTheLoose">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="new">2021-05-24 20:53 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Into_You_(Ariana_Grande_song)" title="Into You (Ariana Grande song)">Into You (Ariana Grande song)</a> (<small>2016 single by Ariana Grande</small>) </td> 
         <td>"Into You" is a song by American singer <a href="/wiki/Ariana_Grande" title="Ariana Grande">Ariana Grande</a> from her third studio <a href="/wiki/Album" title="Album">album</a>, <i><a href="/wiki/Dangerous_Woman" title="Dangerous Woman">Dangerous Woman</a></i> (2016). Grande co-wrote the song with <a href="/wiki/Savan_Kotecha" title="Savan Kotecha">Savan Kotecha</a>, <a href="/wiki/Alexander_Kronlund" title="Alexander Kronlund">Alexander Kronlund</a>, and its producers <a href="/wiki/Max_Martin" title="Max Martin">Max Martin</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ilya_Salmanzadeh" title="Ilya Salmanzadeh">Ilya Salmanzadeh</a>. The song was made available by digital download on May 6, 2016 via pre-order of the album, and was later serviced to <a href="/wiki/Contemporary_hit_radio" title="Contemporary hit radio">contemporary hit</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rhythmic_contemporary" title="Rhythmic contemporary">rhythmic</a> radio on June 28, 2016 as the second <a href="/wiki/Single_(music)" title="Single (music)">single</a> from <i>Dangerous Woman</i>. </td> 
         <td>-- <a href="/wiki/User:Dylx" title="User:Dylx"><span style="color:dodgerblue;"><b>dyl</b></span></a><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Dylx" title="User talk:Dylx"><span style="color:hotpink;"><b>x</b></span></a> </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Milk_(The_1975_song)" title="Milk (The 1975 song)">Milk (The 1975 song)</a> (<small>2017 single by The 1975</small>) </td> 
         <td>"Milk" is a song by English band <a href="/wiki/The_1975" title="The 1975">the 1975</a> originally included as a <a href="/wiki/Hidden_track" title="Hidden track">hidden track</a> on the band's second <a href="/wiki/Extended_play" title="Extended play">extended play</a> (EP), <i><a href="/wiki/Sex_(The_1975_EP)" title="Sex (The 1975 EP)">Sex</a></i> (2012). It was written by George Daniel, Matthew Healy, Adam Hann and Ross MacDonald. The band produced the song alongside Michael and Robert Coles. In 2013, the track served as the <a href="/wiki/A-side_and_B-side" title="A-side and B-side">B-side</a> on a limited edition <a href="/wiki/7_inch" class="mw-redirect" title="7 inch">7-inch</a> <a href="/wiki/Phonograph_record" title="Phonograph record">vinyl</a> <a href="/wiki/Single_(music)" title="Single (music)">single</a> for <a href="/wiki/The_Neighbourhood" title="The Neighbourhood">the Neighbourhood</a>'s "No Grey". </td> 
         <td><b><a href="/wiki/User:(CA)Giacobbe" title="User:(CA)Giacobbe"><font color="3399FF" size="3px">Gia</font><font color="FF66CC" size="3px">co</font><font color="3399FF" size="3px">bbe</font></a></b> <sup><a href="/wiki/User_talk:(CA)Giacobbe" title="User talk:(CA)Giacobbe"><font color="#FF66CC">talk</font></a></sup> </td>

         <td>"No Quiero Na' Regala'o" ("I Do Not Want it Given") is a song by Puerto Rican singer <a href="/wiki/Gilberto_Santa_Rosa" title="Gilberto Santa Rosa">Gilberto Santa Rosa</a> from his tenth studio album <i><a href="/wiki/Esencia" title="Esencia">Esencia</a></i> (1996). The song was written by Perín Vasquez and originally performed by Puerto Rican <a href="/wiki/Salsa_music" title="Salsa music">salsa</a> band <a href="/wiki/El_Gran_Combo_de_Puerto_Rico" title="El Gran Combo de Puerto Rico">El Gran Combo de Puerto Rico</a> on their studio album <i>De Punta a Punta</i> (1971). </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-26 14:23 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/If_You_See_Her,_Say_Hello" title="If You See Her, Say Hello">If You See Her, Say Hello</a> (<small>1975 song by Bob Dylan</small>) </td> 
         <td>"If You See Her, Say Hello" is a song by <a href="/wiki/Bob_Dylan" title="Bob Dylan">Bob Dylan</a> released in 1975 on his 15th studio album, <i><a href="/wiki/Blood_on_the_Tracks" title="Blood on the Tracks">Blood on the Tracks</a></i>, and as a single <a href="/wiki/A-side_and_B-side" title="A-side and B-side">B-side</a>. It is one of five songs on the album that Dylan initially recorded in New York City in September 1974 and then re-recorded in Minneapolis in December that year. The later recording, made on December 30, 1974, produced by Dylan's brother David Zimmerman, who was not credited, became the album track and the B-side of the "<a href="/wiki/Tangled_Up_in_Blue" title="Tangled Up in Blue">Tangled Up in Blue</a>" single. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:BennyOnTheLoose" title="User:BennyOnTheLoose">BennyOnTheLoose</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:BennyOnTheLoose" title="User talk:BennyOnTheLoose">talk</a>) </td>

         <td>"Freak the Freak Out" is a song by the <i><a href="/wiki/Victorious" title="Victorious">Victorious</a></i> cast featuring American actress and singer <a href="/wiki/Victoria_Justice" title="Victoria Justice">Victoria Justice</a> from the <a href="/wiki/Soundtrack_album" title="Soundtrack album">soundtrack album</a> <i><a href="/wiki/Victorious:_Music_from_the_Hit_TV_Show" title="Victorious: Music from the Hit TV Show">Victorious: Music from the Hit TV Show</a></i> (2011). It was produced by The Super Chris and <a href="/wiki/Michael_Corcoran_(musician)" title="Michael Corcoran (musician)">Michael Corcoran</a>, who also co-wrote the song with C.J. Abraham, <a href="/wiki/Nick_Hexum" title="Nick Hexum">Nick Hexum</a>, <a href="/wiki/Zack_Hexum" title="Zack Hexum">Zack Hexum</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Dan_Schneider_(TV_producer)" title="Dan Schneider (TV producer)">Dan Schneider</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Mount_Eerie_(album)" title="Mount Eerie (album)">Mount Eerie (album)</a> (<small>2003 folk album by the Microphones</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Mount Eerie</i> is the fourth studio album by American <a href="/wiki/Indie_rock" title="Indie rock">indie rock</a> band <a href="/wiki/The_Microphones" title="The Microphones">the Microphones</a>, released by <a href="/wiki/K_Records" title="K Records">K Records</a> on January 21, 2003. The band's frontman Phil Elverum later used the same name for his <a href="/wiki/Mount_Eerie" title="Mount Eerie">next musical project</a>. He also released a <a href="/wiki/Mount_Eerie_pts._6_%26_7" title="Mount Eerie pts. 6 &amp; 7">sequel EP</a> to the original album in 2007. The album is named after <a href="/wiki/Mount_Erie_(Washington)" title="Mount Erie (Washington)">Mount Erie</a> near <a href="/wiki/Anacortes,_Washington" title="Anacortes, Washington">Anacortes, Washington</a>, Elverum's hometown. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Mcguy15" title="User:Mcguy15"><span style="letter-spacing:0.1em;">Mcguy15</span> </a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Mcguy15" title="User talk:Mcguy15">talk</a>, <a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/Mcguy15" title="Special:Contributions/Mcguy15">contribs</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/What%27s_Your_Country_Song" title="What's Your Country Song">What's Your Country Song</a> (<small>2020 single by Thomas Rhett</small>) </td> 
         <td>"What's Your Country Song" is a song recorded by American <a href="/wiki/Country_music" title="Country music">country music</a> singer <a href="/wiki/Thomas_Rhett" title="Thomas Rhett">Thomas Rhett</a>. It was released on November 11, 2020, as the lead single from his fifth studio album <i><a href="/wiki/Country_Again:_Side_A" title="Country Again: Side A">Country Again: Side A</a></i>. The song was written by Rhett, his father <a href="/wiki/Rhett_Akins" title="Rhett Akins">Rhett Akins</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ashley_Gorley" title="Ashley Gorley">Ashley Gorley</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jesse_Frasure" title="Jesse Frasure">Jesse Frasure</a>, and Parker Welling, and produced by Frasure and <a href="/wiki/Dann_Huff" title="Dann Huff">Dann Huff</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/22_(Taylor_Swift_song)" title="22 (Taylor Swift song)">22 (Taylor Swift song)</a> (<small>2013 single by Taylor Swift</small>) </td> 
         <td>"22" is a song recorded by American singer-songwriter <a href="/wiki/Taylor_Swift" title="Taylor Swift">Taylor Swift</a> for her fourth studio album, <i><a href="/wiki/Red_(Taylor_Swift_album)" title="Red (Taylor Swift album)">Red</a></i> (2012). The sixth track on the album, it was written by Swift along with its producers <a href="/wiki/Max_Martin" title="Max Martin">Max Martin</a> and <a href="/wiki/Shellback_(record_producer)" title="Shellback (record producer)">Shellback</a>. It was released as the album's fourth single on March 12, 2013. "22" has been described as a thunderous <a href="/wiki/Pop_music" title="Pop music">pop</a> song. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Pic-Nic" title="Pic-Nic">Pic-Nic</a> </td> 
         <td>Pic-Nic was a Spanish teenage <a href="/wiki/Folk-pop" title="Folk-pop">folk-pop</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sunshine_pop" title="Sunshine pop">sunshine pop</a> band formed in <a href="/wiki/Barcelona" title="Barcelona">Barcelona</a> in the mid-to-late 1960s, composed of lead singer <a href="/wiki/Jeanette_(singer)" title="Jeanette (singer)">Jeanette</a>, guitarists <a href="/wiki/Toti_Soler" title="Toti Soler">Toti Soler</a> and Al Cárdenas, drummer Jordi Barangé and bassist Isidoro "Doro" de Montaberry. Contrary to popular belief, keyboardist <a href="/wiki/Jordi_Sabat%C3%A9s" title="Jordi Sabatés">Jordi Sabatés</a> does not appear in any of the group's releases, as he joined the band after their only published recordings sessions had taken place. </td>

The song was written by band members George Daniel, Matthew Healy, Adam Hann and Ross MacDonald. <a href="/wiki/Mike_Crossey" title="Mike Crossey">Mike Crossey</a> handled the production alongside Daniel and Healy. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Wait_a_Minute_(The_Pussycat_Dolls_song)" title="Wait a Minute (The Pussycat Dolls song)">Wait a Minute (The Pussycat Dolls song)</a> (<small>2006 single by The Pussycat Dolls</small>) </td> 
         <td>"Wait a Minute" is a song recorded by American girl group <a href="/wiki/The_Pussycat_Dolls" title="The Pussycat Dolls">the Pussycat Dolls</a> for their debut studio album, <i><a href="/wiki/PCD_(album)" title="PCD (album)">PCD</a></i> (2005).          <td class="old">2021-02-28 20:58 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Tetris_Holding,_LLC_v._Xio_Interactive,_Inc." title="Tetris Holding, LLC v. Xio Interactive, Inc.">Tetris Holding, LLC v. Xio Interactive, Inc.</a> (<small>2012 legal decision</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Tetris Holding, LLC v. Xio Interactive, Inc.</i>, 863 F.Supp.2d 394 (D.N.J. 2012), is a legal case related to <a href="/wiki/Copyright_of_video_games" class="mw-redirect" title="Copyright of video games">copyright of video games</a> confirming that a video game's <a href="/wiki/Look_and_feel" title="Look and feel">look and feel</a> can be protected under copyright law. Tetris Holding is a company that holds the Copyright to the original <i><a href="/wiki/Tetris" title="Tetris">Tetris</a> </i> game from 1984, and licenses those rights to other game developers. </td> 
         <td><a href="/w/index.php?title=User:Jorahm&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="User:Jorahm (page does not exist)">Jorahm</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Jorahm" title="User talk:Jorahm">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="recent">2021-05-05 12:49 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Dot-com_bubble" title="Dot-com bubble">Dot-com bubble</a> (<small>Tech stock speculative craze, c. 1997-2003</small>) </td> 
         <td>The dot-com bubble (also known as the dot-com boom, the tech bubble, and the Internet bubble) was a <a href="/wiki/Stock_market_bubble" title="Stock market bubble">stock market bubble</a> caused by excessive <a href="/wiki/Speculation" title="Speculation">speculation</a> of Internet-related companies in the late 1990s, a period of massive growth in the use and adoption of the <a href="/wiki/Internet" title="Internet">Internet</a>. </td>

        </tr>
