         <td class="new">2021-05-31 20:41 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Mac_Mini" title="Mac Mini">Mac Mini</a> (<small>Desktop computer by Apple</small>) </td> 
         <td>Mac Mini (stylized as Mac mini) is a <a href="/wiki/Small_form_factor_(desktop_and_motherboard)" title="Small form factor (desktop and motherboard)">SFF</a>-class <a href="/wiki/Desktop_computer" title="Desktop computer">desktop computer</a> developed and marketed by <a href="/wiki/Apple_Inc." title="Apple Inc.">Apple Inc.</a> It is one of four desktop computers in the current <a href="/wiki/Macintosh" title="Macintosh">Macintosh</a> lineup, serving as an alternative to the all-in-one <a href="/wiki/IMac_(Intel-based)" title="IMac (Intel-based)">iMac</a>, and sitting below the performance range <a href="/wiki/IMac_Pro" title="IMac Pro">iMac Pro</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mac_Pro" title="Mac Pro">Mac Pro</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Albania_in_the_Eurovision_Song_Contest" title="Albania in the Eurovision Song Contest">Albania</a> participated in the <a href="/wiki/Eurovision_Song_Contest_2021" title="Eurovision Song Contest 2021">Eurovision Song Contest 2021</a> in <a href="/wiki/Rotterdam" title="Rotterdam">Rotterdam</a>, the Netherlands, with the song "<a href="/wiki/Karma_(Anxhela_Peristeri_song)" title="Karma (Anxhela Peristeri song)">Karma</a>" performed by <a href="/wiki/Anxhela_Peristeri" title="Anxhela Peristeri">Anxhela Peristeri</a>. Its entry was selected through the national selection competition <a href="/wiki/Festivali_i_K%C3%ABng%C3%ABs" title="Festivali i Këngës">Festivali i Këngës</a> organised by <a href="/wiki/Radio_Televizioni_Shqiptar" class="mw-redirect" title="Radio Televizioni Shqiptar">Radio Televizioni Shqiptar</a> (RTSH) in December 2020. To this point, the nation had participated in the <a href="/wiki/Eurovision_Song_Contest" title="Eurovision Song Contest">Eurovision Song Contest</a> sixteen times since its first entry in <a href="/wiki/Eurovision_Song_Contest_2004" title="Eurovision Song Contest 2004">2004</a>. </td>

         <td>Kiki Wolfkill is an American <a href="/wiki/Video_game_developer" title="Video game developer">video game developer</a>. Wolfkill grew up in <a href="/wiki/Pennsylvania" title="Pennsylvania">Pennsylvania</a> and studied journalism and art at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Washington" title="University of Washington">University of Washington</a>, racing competitively on the side. At <a href="/wiki/Microsoft" title="Microsoft">Microsoft</a>, she transitioned from developing multimedia for <i><a href="/wiki/Encarta" title="Encarta">Microsoft Encarta</a></i> to working on art for Microsoft's video games, including the racing series <i><a href="/wiki/Midtown_Madness" title="Midtown Madness">Midtown Madness</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Project_Gotham_Racing" title="Project Gotham Racing">Project Gotham Racing</a></i>. </td>

Set on a fictional version of <a href="/wiki/Mount_Celeste" title="Mount Celeste">Mount Celeste</a>, it follows a young woman named <a href="/wiki/Madeline_(Celeste)" title="Madeline (Celeste)">Madeline</a> who attempts to climb the mountain, and must face her inner demons in her quest to reach the summit. </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-22 14:51 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/John_Adam_Rittinger" title="John Adam Rittinger">John Adam Rittinger</a> (<small>Canadian newspaper editor, humorist</small>) </td> 
         <td>John Adam Rittinger (16 February 1855&nbsp;– 29 July 1915) was a Canadian German-language newspaper proprietor, <a href="/wiki/Editor-in-chief" title="Editor-in-chief">editor</a> and <a href="/wiki/Pennsylvania_Dutch_language" title="Pennsylvania Dutch language">Pennsylvania German</a> <a href="/wiki/Humorist" title="Humorist">humorist</a>. In 1875, he and Aaron Eby purchased <a href="/wiki/Walkerton,_Ontario" title="Walkerton, Ontario">Walkerton, Ontario</a>'s German language newspaper, the <i lang="de" title="German-language text">Walkerton Glocke</i>. Affectionately known by locals as the "<span lang="de" style="font-style: normal;" title="German-language text">Glockemann</span>" ("Bell Ringer"), he became the paper's sole-owner in 1878, renaming it <i lang="de" title="German-language text">Die Ontario Glocke</i> in 1882. </td> 
         <td><span style="font-weight:bold;text-shadow:1px 1px 40px black"><a href="/wiki/User:Tkbrett" title="User:Tkbrett"><b><span style="color: #000000;">Tkbrett</span></b></a><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Tkbrett" title="User talk:Tkbrett"><span style="color: #FF0000;"> (?)</span></a></span> </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="old">2021-02-19 04:50 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Lev_Levanda" title="Lev Levanda">Lev Levanda</a> (<small>Russian author (1935-1888)</small>) </td> 
         <td>Lev (Yehuda Leyb) Osipovitch Levanda (Russian: <span lang="ru">??? ???????? ???????</span>, <a href="/wiki/Yiddish_language" class="mw-redirect" title="Yiddish language">Yiddish</a>: <span lang="yi" dir="rtl">????? ???? ?????????</span>?; June 1835 – 18 June 1888) was a Russian author, <a href="/wiki/Belles-lettres" title="Belles-lettres">belletrist</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Publication" title="Publication">publicist</a>. His literary work made him a leading figure in the circles of the Russian-Jewish intelligentsia. Originally a vocal proponent of the <a href="/wiki/Jewish_assimilation" title="Jewish assimilation">assimilation of Jews</a> into Russian culture, Levanda became a strong supporter of their <a href="/wiki/Aliyah" title="Aliyah">emigration</a> to <a href="/wiki/Palestine_(region)" title="Palestine (region)">Palestine</a> following the <a href="/wiki/Anti-Jewish_pogroms_in_the_Russian_Empire#1881–84" class="mw-redirect" title="Anti-Jewish pogroms in the Russian Empire">1881–82 pogroms</a> across the <a href="/wiki/Russian_Empire" title="Russian Empire">Russian Empire</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Kyuko" title="User:Kyuko">Kyuko</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Kyuko" title="User talk:Kyuko">talk</a>) </td>

The largest group who self-identify as Arabs are <a href="/wiki/Antiochian_Greek_Christians" title="Antiochian Greek Christians">Antiochian Greek Christians</a>, who are estimated to number between 520,000–703,000 in <a href="/wiki/Syria" title="Syria">Syria</a>, 350,000 in <a href="/wiki/Lebanon" title="Lebanon">Lebanon</a>, 221,000 in <a href="/wiki/Jordan" title="Jordan">Jordan</a>, 133,130 in <a href="/wiki/Israel" title="Israel">Israel</a> and 50,000 in the <a href="/wiki/State_of_Palestine" title="State of Palestine">State of Palestine</a>. </td>

         <td class="new">2021-06-03 19:14 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Holocaust_in_Greece" title="The Holocaust in Greece">The Holocaust in Greece</a> (<small>Systematic dispossession, deportation, and murder of Jews in Greece</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Holocaust in Greece was the deportation and murder of the <a href="/wiki/Greek_Jews" class="mw-redirect" title="Greek Jews">Greek Jews</a>, mostly a result of their deportation to <a href="/wiki/Auschwitz_concentration_camp" title="Auschwitz concentration camp">Auschwitz concentration camp</a>, during <a href="/wiki/World_War_II" title="World War II">World War II</a>. By 1945, between 83 and 87 percent of Greek Jews were dead, among the highest proportion in Europe. </td> 
         <td>(<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Buidhe" title="User talk:Buidhe">t</a> · <a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/Buidhe" title="Special:Contributions/Buidhe">c</a>) <b><a href="/wiki/User:Buidhe" title="User:Buidhe"><span style="color: black">buidhe</span></a></b> </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-06-05 16:42 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Asikni_(goddess)" title="Asikni (goddess)">Asikni (goddess)</a> (<small>Consort of the Hindu god Daksha</small>) </td> 
         <td>Asikni , also known as Panchajani and Virani, is a consort of <a href="/wiki/Daksha" title="Daksha">Daksha</a>, one of the <i><a href="/wiki/Prajapati_(title)" class="mw-redirect" title="Prajapati (title)">Prajapati</a></i> (agents of creation). Most legends describe her as the daughter of Virana or Panchajana and the mother of various children — 5000 Haryasvas, 1000 Sabalasvas and 60 daughters. Asikni is sometimes equated with Daksha's other wife named <a href="/wiki/Prasuti" title="Prasuti">Prasuti</a>, but many texts mention them as separate goddesses. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:245CMR" title="User:245CMR"><span style="background:maroon;border:solid 1px;border-radius:8px;">.<span style="color:yellow; background:maroon;"><i>245</i><b>CMR</b></span>.</span></a>•<sup><a href="/wiki/User_talk:245CMR" title="User talk:245CMR">?</a><a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/245CMR" title="Special:Contributions/245CMR">?</a></sup> </td>
        </tr>
       </tbody>
      </table>

         <td><a href="/wiki/2020_World_Rally_Championship" title="2020 World Rally Championship">2020 World Rally Championship</a> (<small>48th running of the World Rally Championship</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 2020 FIA World Rally Championship was the forty-eighth season of the <a href="/wiki/World_Rally_Championship" title="World Rally Championship">World Rally Championship</a>, an <a href="/wiki/Auto_racing" title="Auto racing">auto racing</a> competition recognised by the <a href="/wiki/F%C3%A9d%C3%A9ration_Internationale_de_l%27Automobile" title="Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile">Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile</a> (FIA) as the highest class of international <a href="/wiki/Rallying" title="Rallying">rallying</a>. Teams and crews were competing in seven rallies for the <a href="/wiki/List_of_World_Rally_Championship_Drivers%27_champions" title="List of World Rally Championship Drivers' champions">World Rally Championships for Drivers</a>, <a href="/wiki/Co-driver" title="Co-driver">Co-drivers</a> and <a href="/wiki/List_of_World_Rally_Championship_Constructors%27_champions" title="List of World Rally Championship Constructors' champions">Manufacturers</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Unnamelessness" title="User:Unnamelessness">Unnamelessness</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Unnamelessness" title="User talk:Unnamelessness">talk</a>) </td>

Nicknamed "The Springfield Rifle," he was one of the top pitchers for the <a href="/wiki/New_York_Yankees" title="New York Yankees">New York Yankees</a> in the late 1940s and early 1950s, forming (with <a href="/wiki/Allie_Reynolds" title="Allie Reynolds">Allie Reynolds</a> and <a href="/wiki/Eddie_Lopat" title="Eddie Lopat">Eddie Lopat</a>) the "Big Three" of the Yankees' pitching staff. </td>

He played for 15 seasons in <a href="/wiki/Major_League_Baseball" title="Major League Baseball">Major League Baseball</a> as a left-handed <a href="/wiki/Pitcher" title="Pitcher">pitcher</a> in 1959 and from 1964 through 1977.          <td>Marcelo Daniel Gallardo (; born 18 January 1976) is an Argentine <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">football</a> coach and former professional player who is manager of <a href="/wiki/Club_Atl%C3%A9tico_River_Plate" title="Club Atlético River Plate">River Plate</a>. Gallardo began his career in the club's youth divisions, and made his debut in the <a href="/wiki/Argentine_Primera_Divisi%C3%B3n" title="Argentine Primera División">Argentine Primera División</a> at age 17 in 1993. After a six-year period in which he won five local league championships, the <a href="/wiki/1996_Copa_Libertadores" title="1996 Copa Libertadores">1996 Copa Libertadores</a> and the <a href="/wiki/1997_Supercopa_Libertadores" title="1997 Supercopa Libertadores">1997 Supercopa Libertadores</a>, he transferred to France's <a href="/wiki/Ligue_1" title="Ligue 1">Ligue 1</a> <a href="/wiki/AS_Monaco_FC" title="AS Monaco FC">AS Monaco FC</a> and was named French League Footballer of the Year in 2000. </td>

         <td>The 88th 24 Hours of Le Mans (French: <i>88<sup>e</sup> 24 Heures du Mans</i>) was an <a href="/wiki/Endurance_racing_(motorsport)" title="Endurance racing (motorsport)">automobile endurance race</a> for <a href="/wiki/Le_Mans_Prototype" title="Le Mans Prototype">Le Mans Prototype</a> (LMP) and <a href="/wiki/LM_GTE" title="LM GTE">Le Mans Grand Touring Endurance</a> (LMGTE) cars held from 19 to 20&nbsp;September 2020 at the <a href="/wiki/Circuit_de_la_Sarthe" title="Circuit de la Sarthe">Circuit de la Sarthe</a> at <a href="/wiki/Le_Mans,_France" class="mw-redirect" title="Le Mans, France">Le Mans, France</a>. It was the 88th running of the event, as organised by the automotive group, the <a href="/wiki/Automobile_Club_de_l%27Ouest" title="Automobile Club de l'Ouest">Automobile Club de l'Ouest</a> (ACO) since <a href="/wiki/1923_24_Hours_of_Le_Mans" title="1923 24 Hours of Le Mans">1923</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1987_Football_League_Third_Division_play-off_Final" title="1987 Football League Third Division play-off Final">1987 Football League Third Division play-off Final</a> (<small>Football match</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 1987 Football League Third Division play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match contested by <a href="/wiki/Gillingham_F.C." title="Gillingham F.C.">Gillingham</a> and <a href="/wiki/Swindon_Town_F.C." title="Swindon Town F.C.">Swindon Town</a> over <a href="/wiki/Two-legged_tie" title="Two-legged tie">two legs</a> on 22 May 1987 and 25 May 1987 to determine which club would play the next season in the <a href="/wiki/1987%E2%80%9388_Football_League#Second_Division" title="1987–88 Football League">Second Division</a>. Gillingham had finished in fifth place in the <a href="/wiki/1986%E2%80%9387_Football_League#Third_Division" title="1986–87 Football League">Third Division</a> while Swindon finished third. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1959%E2%80%9360_Burnley_F.C._season" title="1959–60 Burnley F.C. season">1959–60 Burnley F.C. season</a> (<small>Burnley 1959–60 football season</small>) </td> 
         <td>The <a href="/wiki/1959%E2%80%9360_in_English_football" title="1959–60 in English football">1959–60 season</a> was <a href="/wiki/Burnley_F.C." title="Burnley F.C.">Burnley</a>'s <a href="/wiki/List_of_Burnley_F.C._seasons" title="List of Burnley F.C. seasons">61st season</a> in the <a href="/wiki/English_Football_League" title="English Football League">Football League</a>, and their 13th consecutive campaign in the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_First_Division" title="Football League First Division">First Division</a>. Managed by <a href="/wiki/Harry_Potts" title="Harry Potts">Harry Potts</a>, the team endured a tense season, in which <a href="/wiki/Tottenham_Hotspur_F.C." title="Tottenham Hotspur F.C.">Tottenham Hotspur</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wolverhampton_Wanderers_F.C." title="Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.">Wolverhampton Wanderers</a> were the other protagonists for the league title. Burnley won their second <a href="/wiki/List_of_English_football_champions" title="List of English football champions">First Division championship</a>, and their first since <a href="/wiki/1920%E2%80%9321_Burnley_F.C._season" title="1920–21 Burnley F.C. season">1920–21</a>, on the last matchday with a 2–1 victory at <a href="/wiki/Manchester_City_F.C." title="Manchester City F.C.">Manchester City</a>; they had not topped the table until the last match was played out. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:WA8MTWAYC" title="User:WA8MTWAYC">WA8MTWAYC</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:WA8MTWAYC" title="User talk:WA8MTWAYC">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Venezuela_at_the_1956_Summer_Olympics" title="Venezuela at the 1956 Summer Olympics">Venezuela at the 1956 Summer Olympics</a> (<small>Sporting event delegation</small>) </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Republic_of_Venezuela" title="Republic of Venezuela">Venezuela</a> competed at the <a href="/wiki/1956_Summer_Olympics" title="1956 Summer Olympics">1956 Summer Olympics</a> held in <a href="/wiki/Melbourne" title="Melbourne">Melbourne</a>, <a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">Australia</a>, and in the <a href="/wiki/Equestrian_at_the_1956_Summer_Olympics" title="Equestrian at the 1956 Summer Olympics">equestrian events</a> held in <a href="/wiki/Stockholm" title="Stockholm">Stockholm</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sweden" title="Sweden">Sweden</a>. Twenty-two competitors, all men, were selected by the <a href="/wiki/Venezuelan_Olympic_Committee" title="Venezuelan Olympic Committee">Venezuelan Olympic Committee</a> to take part in 16 events across 5 sports. The delegation featured no female competitors, for the second time, and won no medals. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1744_English_cricket_season" title="1744 English cricket season">1744 English cricket season</a> (<small>Cricket season review</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 1744 <a href="/wiki/Cricket" title="Cricket">cricket</a> season in England was pivotal in the sport's history because the earliest known codification of the <i><a href="/wiki/Laws_of_Cricket" title="Laws of Cricket">Laws of Cricket</a></i> was drafted by members of several cricket clubs, though the code was not published until 1755. The season is also notable for the two earliest known surviving match scorecards. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:No_Great_Shaker" title="User:No Great Shaker">No Great Shaker</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:No_Great_Shaker" title="User talk:No Great Shaker">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Crewe_Alexandra_F.C." title="Crewe Alexandra F.C.">Crewe Alexandra F.C.</a> (<small>Association football club in England</small>) </td> 
         <td>Crewe Alexandra Football Club is an English professional <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> club based in the town of <a href="/wiki/Crewe" title="Crewe">Crewe</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cheshire" title="Cheshire">Cheshire</a>, that competes in <a href="/wiki/EFL_League_One" title="EFL League One">League One</a>, the third tier of the <a href="/wiki/English_football_league_system" title="English football league system">English football league system</a>. Nicknamed "The Railwaymen" because of the town's <a href="/wiki/Crewe_Works" title="Crewe Works">links with the rail industry</a>, and also commonly known as "The Alex", they have played at <a href="/wiki/Gresty_Road" title="Gresty Road">Gresty Road</a> since 1906. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Paul_W" title="User:Paul W">Paul W</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Paul_W" title="User talk:Paul W">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1988_Football_League_Third_Division_play-off_Final" title="1988 Football League Third Division play-off Final">1988 Football League Third Division play-off Final</a> (<small>Association football match</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 1988 Football League Third Division play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match contested by <a href="/wiki/Walsall_F.C." title="Walsall F.C.">Walsall</a> and <a href="/wiki/Bristol_City_F.C." title="Bristol City F.C.">Bristol City</a> over <a href="/wiki/Two-legged_tie" title="Two-legged tie">two legs</a> on 25 and 28 May 1988, and then a <a href="/wiki/Replay_(sports)" title="Replay (sports)">replay</a> on 30 May 1988, to determine which club would play the following season in the <a href="/wiki/1988%E2%80%9389_Football_League#Second_Division" title="1988–89 Football League">Second Division</a>. Walsall had finished in third place in the <a href="/wiki/1987%E2%80%9388_Football_League#Third_Division" title="1987–88 Football League">Third Division</a> while Bristol City finished fifth. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1999_Football_League_Second_Division_play-off_Final" title="1999 Football League Second Division play-off Final">1999 Football League Second Division play-off Final</a> (<small>Football match</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 1999 Football League Second Division play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match which was played on 30 May 1999 at <a href="/wiki/Wembley_Stadium_(1923)" title="Wembley Stadium (1923)">Wembley Stadium</a>, London, between <a href="/wiki/Manchester_City_F.C." title="Manchester City F.C.">Manchester City</a> and <a href="/wiki/Gillingham_F.C." title="Gillingham F.C.">Gillingham</a>. The match was to determine the third and final team to gain <a href="/wiki/Promotion_and_relegation" title="Promotion and relegation">promotion</a> from the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_Second_Division" title="Football League Second Division">Football League Second Division</a>, the third tier of <a href="/wiki/English_football_league_system" title="English football league system">English football</a>, to the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_First_Division" title="Football League First Division">First Division</a>. </td>

         <td>The 1989 Football League Fourth Division play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match played over <a href="/wiki/Two-legged_tie" title="Two-legged tie">two legs</a> between <a href="/wiki/Wrexham_A.F.C." title="Wrexham A.F.C.">Wrexham</a> and <a href="/wiki/Leyton_Orient_F.C." title="Leyton Orient F.C.">Leyton Orient</a> on 30 May and 3 June 1989.          <td>The 2013–14 Victory Day T20 Cup was a <a href="/wiki/Twenty20_cricket" class="mw-redirect" title="Twenty20 cricket">Twenty20 cricket</a> competition that was held in Bangladesh. It was played by four teams, during December 2013. Four <a href="/wiki/Dhaka_Premier_League" class="mw-redirect" title="Dhaka Premier League">Dhaka Premier League</a> teams took part in a lottery to determine who picked one each of the Yellow, Blue, Green and Red teams. Announcing the schedule of the tournament at a press conference on 21st of December, the <a href="/wiki/Bangladesh_Cricket_Board" title="Bangladesh Cricket Board">Bangladesh Cricket Board</a> (BCB) confirmed that four teams would participate in the T20 series and AMBER Group would be the title sponsors of the event. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1873%E2%80%9374_Scottish_Cup" title="1873–74 Scottish Cup">1873–74 Scottish Cup</a> (<small>football tournament season</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 1873–74 <a href="/wiki/Scottish_Cup" title="Scottish Cup">Scottish Cup</a> – officially the Scottish Football Association Challenge Cup – was the first season of Scotland's most prestigious <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">football</a> knockout competition. A total of 16 teams from the west of Scotland entered the competition, however only 14 would play a match after two withdrawals. The competition began on 18 October 1873 and concluded with <a href="/wiki/1874_Scottish_Cup_Final" title="1874 Scottish Cup Final">the final</a> on 21 March 1874. </td>

         <td>The 1930–31 season was the 30th season of competitive <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">football</a> played by <a href="/wiki/Cardiff_City_F.C." title="Cardiff City F.C.">Cardiff City F.C.</a>. It the team's second season in the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_Second_Division" title="Football League Second Division">Second Division</a> of <a href="/wiki/English_Football_League" title="English Football League">the Football League</a> since being relegated from the First Division during the <a href="/wiki/1928%E2%80%9329_Cardiff_City_F.C._season" title="1928–29 Cardiff City F.C. season">1928–29 season</a>. They finished bottom of the Second Division after winning only 8 of their 42 league matches and scoring the fewest amount of goals in the league and were relegated to the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_Third_Division_South" title="Football League Third Division South">Third Division South</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/2003_Football_League_Third_Division_play-off_Final" title="2003 Football League Third Division play-off Final">2003 Football League Third Division play-off Final</a> (<small>Football match</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 2003 Football League Third Division play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match which was played on 24 May 2003 at the <a href="/wiki/Millennium_Stadium" title="Millennium Stadium">Millennium Stadium</a>, Cardiff, between <a href="/wiki/AFC_Bournemouth" title="AFC Bournemouth">Bournemouth</a> and <a href="/wiki/Lincoln_City_F.C." title="Lincoln City F.C.">Lincoln City</a> to determine the fourth and final team to gain <a href="/wiki/Promotion_and_relegation" title="Promotion and relegation">promotion</a> from the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_Third_Division" title="Football League Third Division">Football League Third Division</a> to the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_Second_Division" title="Football League Second Division">Second Division</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:The_Rambling_Man" title="User:The Rambling Man">The Rambling Man</a> <small>(<a href="/wiki/User_talk:The_Rambling_Man" title="User talk:The Rambling Man">Stay alert! Control the virus! Save lives!!!!</a>)</small> </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/EFL_League_Two_play-offs" title="EFL League Two play-offs">EFL League Two play-offs</a> </td> 
         <td>The EFL League Two play-offs are a series of <a href="/wiki/Play-offs" class="mw-redirect" title="Play-offs">play-off</a> matches contested by the <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> teams finishing from fourth to seventh in the <a href="/wiki/EFL_League_Two" title="EFL League Two">EFL League Two</a> table and are part of the <a href="/wiki/English_Football_League_play-offs" title="English Football League play-offs">English Football League play-offs</a>. As of 2021<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=SDZeroBot/GAN_sorting&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, the play-offs comprise two semi-finals, where the team finishing fourth plays the team finishing seventh, and the team finishing fifth plays the team finishing sixth, each conducted as a <a href="/wiki/Two-legged_tie" title="Two-legged tie">two-legged tie</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:The_Rambling_Man" title="User:The Rambling Man">The Rambling Man</a> <small>(<a href="/wiki/User_talk:The_Rambling_Man" title="User talk:The Rambling Man">Stay alert! Control the virus! Save lives!!!!</a>)</small> </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/2011_Football_League_Two_play-off_Final" title="2011 Football League Two play-off Final">2011 Football League Two play-off Final</a> (<small>Football match</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 2011 Football League Two play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match which was played on 28 May 2011 at <a href="/wiki/Old_Trafford" title="Old Trafford">Old Trafford</a> in Manchester, between <a href="/wiki/Stevenage_F.C." title="Stevenage F.C.">Stevenage</a> and <a href="/wiki/Torquay_United_F.C." title="Torquay United F.C.">Torquay United</a>, to determine the fourth and final team to gain <a href="/wiki/Promotion_and_relegation" title="Promotion and relegation">promotion</a> from <a href="/wiki/EFL_League_Two" title="EFL League Two">Football League Two</a> to the <a href="/wiki/EFL_League_One" title="EFL League One">League One</a>. The top three teams of the <a href="/wiki/2010%E2%80%9311_Football_League_Two" title="2010–11 Football League Two">2010–11 Football League Two</a> season, <a href="/wiki/Chesterfield_F.C." title="Chesterfield F.C.">Chesterfield</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bury_F.C." title="Bury F.C.">Bury</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wycombe_Wanderers_F.C." title="Wycombe Wanderers F.C.">Wycombe Wanderers</a>, gained automatic promotion to League One, while those placed from fourth to seventh position took part in <a href="/wiki/2011_Football_League_play-offs" title="2011 Football League play-offs">play-offs</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:The_Rambling_Man" title="User:The Rambling Man">The Rambling Man</a> <small>(<a href="/wiki/User_talk:The_Rambling_Man" title="User talk:The Rambling Man">Stay alert! Control the virus! Save lives!!!!</a>)</small> </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Ramsey_Dardar" title="Ramsey Dardar">Ramsey Dardar</a> </td> 
         <td>James Ramsey Dardar (born October 3, 1959) is a former <a href="/wiki/National_Football_League" title="National Football League">National Football League</a> (NFL) <a href="/wiki/Lineman_(gridiron_football)" title="Lineman (gridiron football)">defensive lineman</a>. He appeared in 16 NFL games, all for the <a href="/wiki/1984_St._Louis_Cardinals_(NFL)_season" title="1984 St. Louis Cardinals (NFL) season">1984 St. Louis Cardinals</a>, and he spent brief periods on the rosters of the <a href="/wiki/New_York_Giants" title="New York Giants">New York Giants</a> and <a href="/wiki/History_of_the_Houston_Oilers" title="History of the Houston Oilers">Houston Oilers</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/2001_International_Formula_3000_Championship" title="2001 International Formula 3000 Championship">2001 International Formula 3000 Championship</a> </td> 
         <td>The 2001 International Formula 3000 Championship was the 35th season of the second-tier motorsport feeder championship of <a href="/wiki/Formula_One" title="Formula One">Formula One</a> and the 17th season to be held under the <a href="/wiki/International_Formula_3000_Championship" class="mw-redirect" title="International Formula 3000 Championship">International Formula 3000 Championship</a> name. It featured the 2001 FIA International Formula 3000 Championship, a <a href="/wiki/One-Design" title="One-Design">one-make motor racing series</a>, recognised by the sport's governing body, the <a href="/wiki/F%C3%A9d%C3%A9ration_Internationale_de_l%27Automobile" title="Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile">Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile</a> (FIA), as the second highest class of competition of <a href="/wiki/Formula_racing" title="Formula racing">single seater racing cars</a>. </td>

         <td>Hélio Castroneves () (born Hélio Alves de Castro Neves; 10 May 1975), is a Brazilian <a href="/wiki/Auto_racing" title="Auto racing">auto racing</a> driver. He has won the <a href="/wiki/Indianapolis_500" title="Indianapolis 500">Indianapolis 500</a> four times: in <a href="/wiki/2001_Indianapolis_500" title="2001 Indianapolis 500">2001</a>, <a href="/wiki/2002_Indianapolis_500" title="2002 Indianapolis 500">2002</a>, <a href="/wiki/2009_Indianapolis_500" title="2009 Indianapolis 500">2009</a>, and <a href="/wiki/2021_Indianapolis_500" title="2021 Indianapolis 500">2021</a>. He won the <a href="/wiki/2021_24_Hours_of_Daytona" title="2021 24 Hours of Daytona">2021 24 Hours of Daytona</a> with <a href="/wiki/Wayne_Taylor_Racing" title="Wayne Taylor Racing">Wayne Taylor Racing</a>, and was runner-up in the <a href="/wiki/IndyCar_Series" title="IndyCar Series">IndyCar Series</a> drivers' championship in <a href="/wiki/2002_Indy_Racing_League" title="2002 Indy Racing League">2002</a>, <a href="/wiki/2008_IndyCar_Series" title="2008 IndyCar Series">2008</a>, <a href="/wiki/2013_IndyCar_Series" title="2013 IndyCar Series">2013</a>, and <a href="/wiki/2014_IndyCar_Series" title="2014 IndyCar Series">2014</a>. </td>

         <td>Gerald Donald Kindall (May 27, 1935 – December 24, 2017) was an American <a href="/wiki/Professional_baseball" title="Professional baseball">professional baseball</a> <a href="/wiki/Baseball_player" class="mw-redirect" title="Baseball player">player</a> and <a href="/wiki/College_baseball" title="College baseball">college baseball</a> player and <a href="/wiki/Head_coach_(baseball)" class="mw-redirect" title="Head coach (baseball)">coach</a>.          <td><a href="/wiki/2021_EFL_Championship_play-off_Final" title="2021 EFL Championship play-off Final">2021 EFL Championship play-off Final</a> (<small>Football match</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 2021 EFL Championship play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match which was played on 29 May 2021 at <a href="/wiki/Wembley_Stadium" title="Wembley Stadium">Wembley Stadium</a>, <a href="/wiki/London" title="London">London</a>, to determine the third and final team to gain <a href="/wiki/Promotion_and_relegation" title="Promotion and relegation">promotion</a> from the <a href="/wiki/EFL_Championship" title="EFL Championship">EFL Championship</a>, the second tier of <a href="/wiki/English_football_league_system" title="English football league system">English football</a>, to the <a href="/wiki/Premier_League" title="Premier League">Premier League</a>. The top two teams of the <a href="/wiki/2020%E2%80%9321_EFL_Championship" title="2020–21 EFL Championship">2020–21 EFL Championship</a>, <a href="/wiki/Norwich_City_F.C." title="Norwich City F.C.">Norwich City</a> and <a href="/wiki/Watford_F.C." title="Watford F.C.">Watford</a>, gained automatic promotion to the Premier League, while the clubs placed from third to sixth place in the table took part in <a href="/wiki/2021_English_Football_League_play-offs" title="2021 English Football League play-offs">2021 English Football League play-offs</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:The_Rambling_Man" title="User:The Rambling Man">The Rambling Man</a> <small>(<a href="/wiki/User_talk:The_Rambling_Man" title="User talk:The Rambling Man">Stay alert! Control the virus! Save lives!!!!</a>)</small> </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Oman_at_the_2016_Summer_Olympics" title="Oman at the 2016 Summer Olympics">Oman at the 2016 Summer Olympics</a> (<small>Sporting event delegation</small>) </td> 
         <td>Oman competed at the 2016 Summer Olympics in <a href="/wiki/Rio_de_Janeiro" title="Rio de Janeiro">Rio de Janeiro</a>, Brazil when the event was held from 5 to 21 August 2016. This was the nation's ninth consecutive appearance at the Summer Olympics. Four Omani athletes, two per gender, were selected to compete in athletics and shooting at the Games. Among them were sprinter <a href="/wiki/Barakat_Al-Harthi" title="Barakat Al-Harthi">Barakat Al-Harthi</a>, the lone returning Olympian from the previous Games. </td>

A St. Louis native, he was hitless in four <a href="/wiki/At_bats" class="mw-redirect" title="At bats">at bats</a> as the Orioles lost 10–5 to the <a href="/wiki/St._Louis_Cardinals" title="St. Louis Cardinals">St. Louis Browns</a> at <a href="/wiki/Sportsman%27s_Park" title="Sportsman's Park">Sportsman's Park</a>. </td>

         <td>Spencer Paul Heath, Jr. (November 5, 1893 – January 25, 1930), was a <a href="/wiki/Relief_pitcher" title="Relief pitcher">relief pitcher</a> who played in four games for the <a href="/wiki/Chicago_White_Sox" title="Chicago White Sox">Chicago White Sox</a> during the 1920 season. Listed at 6'0", 170&nbsp;lb., Heath was a <a href="/wiki/Switch-hitter" class="mw-redirect" title="Switch-hitter">switch-hitter</a> and threw <a href="/wiki/Right-handed" class="mw-redirect" title="Right-handed">right-handed</a>. He was born and died in <a href="/wiki/Chicago" title="Chicago">Chicago</a>, <a href="/wiki/Illinois" title="Illinois">Illinois</a>, where he lived much of his life. </td>

         <td class="old">2021-01-25 11:38 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Khalili_Collection_of_Enamels_of_the_World" title="Khalili Collection of Enamels of the World">Khalili Collection of Enamels of the World</a> (<small>Private art collection</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Khalili Collection of Enamels of the World is a <a href="/wiki/Private_collection" title="Private collection">private collection</a> of <a href="/wiki/Vitreous_enamel" title="Vitreous enamel">enamel</a> artworks from the period 1700 to 2000, assembled by the British-Iranian scholar, collector and philanthropist <a href="/wiki/Nasser_Khalili" title="Nasser Khalili">Nasser D. Khalili</a>. It is one of the eight <a href="/wiki/Khalili_Collections" title="Khalili Collections">Khalili Collections</a>, each of which contains works from specific time periods and categories. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:MartinPoulter" title="User:MartinPoulter">MartinPoulter</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:MartinPoulter" title="User talk:MartinPoulter">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="old">2021-02-05 15:16 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Ink_wash_painting" title="Ink wash painting">Ink wash painting</a> (<small>East Asian painting style using black ink of different concentrations</small>) </td> 
         <td>Ink wash painting is a type of <a href="/wiki/East_Asia" title="East Asia">East Asian</a> <a href="/wiki/Ink_brush" title="Ink brush">brush</a> <a href="/wiki/Painting" title="Painting">painting</a> that uses the same <a href="/wiki/Black_ink" class="mw-redirect" title="Black ink">black ink</a> used in <a href="/wiki/East_Asian_calligraphy" class="mw-redirect" title="East Asian calligraphy">East Asian calligraphy</a> in different concentrations. Emerging in <a href="/wiki/Tang_dynasty" title="Tang dynasty">Tang dynasty</a> China (618–907), it overturned earlier, more <a href="/wiki/Realism_(arts)" title="Realism (arts)">realistic</a> techniques. It is typically <a href="/wiki/Monochrome" title="Monochrome">monochrome</a>, using only shades of black, with a great emphasis on virtuoso brushwork and conveying the perceived "spirit" or "essence" of a subject over the direct <a href="/wiki/Mimesis" title="Mimesis">imitation</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Jujiang" title="User:Jujiang">Jujiang</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Jujiang" title="User talk:Jujiang">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="old">2021-03-03 15:04 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Fourth_Estate_(painting)" title="The Fourth Estate (painting)">The Fourth Estate (painting)</a> (<small>Early 20th-century proletarian painting by Giuseppe Pellizza</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>The Fourth Estate</i> is an oil painting by <a href="/wiki/Giuseppe_Pellizza_da_Volpedo" title="Giuseppe Pellizza da Volpedo">Giuseppe Pellizza da Volpedo</a>, originally titled <i>The Path of Workers</i> and made between 1899 and 1901. It depicts a moment during a <a href="/wiki/Strike_action" title="Strike action">labor strike</a> when workers' representatives calmly and confidently stride out of a crowd to negotiate for the workers' rights. Its name refers to the <a href="/wiki/Proletariat" title="Proletariat">working class</a> as standing alongside the <a href="/wiki/Estates_of_the_realm" title="Estates of the realm">three traditional estates</a> that divided power between the nobility, clergy, and commoners. </td> 
         <td>—<u><i><a href="/wiki/User:Wingedserif" title="User:Wingedserif">Wingedserif</a></i></u> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Wingedserif" title="User talk:Wingedserif">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="recent">2021-03-25 23:44 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Dream_of_Ossian" title="The Dream of Ossian">The Dream of Ossian</a> (<small>Painting by Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>The Dream of Ossian</i> is an 1813 painting by the French artist <a href="/wiki/Jean-Auguste-Dominique_Ingres" title="Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres">Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres</a>. The work depicts the legendary poet <a href="/wiki/Ossian" title="Ossian">Ossian</a> sleeping while he dreams of relatives, warriors, and maidens, which appear above him on the canvas. Ingres was likely influenced by his contemporaries' Ossianic works, such as <a href="/wiki/Fran%C3%A7ois_G%C3%A9rard" title="François Gérard">François Gérard</a>'s 1801 painting <i>Ossian Evoking Phantoms</i>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:GeneralPoxter" title="User:GeneralPoxter">GeneralPoxter</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:GeneralPoxter" title="User talk:GeneralPoxter">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="recent">2021-04-12 12:51 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Khalili_Imperial_Garniture" title="Khalili Imperial Garniture">Khalili Imperial Garniture</a> (<small>Trio of enamel artworks</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Khalili Imperial Garniture is a trio of <a href="/wiki/Cloisonn%C3%A9" title="Cloisonné">cloisonné</a> vases created for a <a href="/wiki/Japan" title="Japan">Japanese</a> Imperial commission during the <a href="/wiki/Meiji_(era)" title="Meiji (era)">Meiji era</a>. The items were exhibited at the <a href="/wiki/World%27s_Columbian_Exposition" title="World's Columbian Exposition">World's Columbian Exposition</a> in <a href="/wiki/Chicago" title="Chicago">Chicago</a>, United States, in 1893, where they were described as "the largest examples of cloisonné enamel ever made". </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:MartinPoulter" title="User:MartinPoulter">MartinPoulter</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:MartinPoulter" title="User talk:MartinPoulter">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="recent">2021-04-17 20:28 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Resolute_desk" title="Resolute desk">Resolute desk</a> (<small>Oval office desk</small>) </td> 
         <td>The <i>Resolute</i> desk, also known as the Hayes desk, is a nineteenth-century <a href="/wiki/Partners_desk" title="Partners desk">partners' desk</a> used by several <a href="/wiki/President_of_the_United_States" title="President of the United States">presidents</a> of the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> in the <a href="/wiki/White_House" title="White House">White House</a> as the <a href="/wiki/List_of_Oval_Office_desks" title="List of Oval Office desks">Oval Office desk</a>, including the five most recent presidents. The desk was a gift from <a href="/wiki/Queen_Victoria" title="Queen Victoria">Queen Victoria</a> to President <a href="/wiki/Rutherford_B._Hayes" title="Rutherford B. Hayes">Rutherford B. Hayes</a> in 1880 and was built from the <a href="/wiki/Oak" title="Oak">oak</a> timbers of the British Arctic exploration ship . </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Found5dollar" title="User:Found5dollar">Found5dollar</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Found5dollar" title="User talk:Found5dollar">talk</a>) </td>

         <td class="recent">2021-05-04 10:03 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Lohn_Estate" title="Lohn Estate">Lohn Estate</a> (<small>Manor in Kehrsatz, Switzerland</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Lohn Estate is a <a href="/wiki/Manor_house" title="Manor house">manor</a> and <a href="/wiki/Estate_(land)" title="Estate (land)">estate</a> located in <a href="/wiki/Kehrsatz" title="Kehrsatz">Kehrsatz</a>, <a href="/wiki/Canton_of_Bern" title="Canton of Bern">canton of Bern</a>, <a href="/wiki/Switzerland" title="Switzerland">Switzerland</a>. It serves as the official <a href="/wiki/Estate_(house)" class="mw-redirect" title="Estate (house)">estate</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Swiss_Federal_Council" class="mw-redirect" title="Swiss Federal Council">Swiss Federal Council</a>. From 1942 to 1994, the Lohn Estate accommodated the official guests of the <a href="/wiki/Swiss_Confederation" class="mw-redirect" title="Swiss Confederation">Swiss Confederation</a>. It is a Swiss <a href="/wiki/Swiss_inventory_of_cultural_property_of_national_and_regional_significance" class="mw-redirect" title="Swiss inventory of cultural property of national and regional significance">heritage site of national significance</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:JBchrch" title="User:JBchrch">JBchrch</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:JBchrch" title="User talk:JBchrch">talk</a>) </td>

         <td class="recent">2021-05-06 10:07 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Juliana_R._Force" title="Juliana R. Force">Juliana R. Force</a> (<small>American art museum administrator</small>) </td> 
         <td>Juliana R. Force (December 25, 1876&nbsp;– August 28, 1948) was an American art museum administrator and director. Force started her career as a collector of <a href="/wiki/Folk_art" title="Folk art">folk art</a> and as a secretary to <a href="/wiki/Socialite" title="Socialite">socialite</a> art collectors. She initiated the first display of American folk art in the United States. Force became a director of art galleries and of a temporary museum of American art in <a href="/wiki/Greenwich_Village" title="Greenwich Village">Greenwich Village</a> in New York City that became the <a href="/wiki/Whitney_Museum_of_American_Art" title="Whitney Museum of American Art">Whitney Museum of American Art</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Doug_Coldwell" title="User:Doug Coldwell">Doug Coldwell</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Doug_Coldwell" title="User talk:Doug Coldwell">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/400_Madison_Avenue" title="400 Madison Avenue">400 Madison Avenue</a> (<small>Office building in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>400 Madison Avenue is a 22-story office building in <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. It is along <a href="/wiki/Madison_Avenue" title="Madison Avenue">Madison Avenue</a>'s western sidewalk between <a href="/wiki/47th_Street_(Manhattan)" title="47th Street (Manhattan)">47th</a> and 48th Streets, near <a href="/wiki/Grand_Central_Terminal" title="Grand Central Terminal">Grand Central Terminal</a>. 400 Madison Avenue was designed by <a href="/wiki/H._Craig_Severance" title="H. Craig Severance">H. Craig Severance</a> with <a href="/wiki/Gothic_Revival_architecture" title="Gothic Revival architecture">Neo-Gothic</a> architectural detailing. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/18_East_50th_Street" title="18 East 50th Street">18 East 50th Street</a> (<small>Building in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td>

        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-19 10:52 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Vincent_Figgins" title="Vincent Figgins">Vincent Figgins</a> </td> 
         <td>Vincent Figgins (1766 – 29 February 1844) was a British <a href="/wiki/Typefounding" class="mw-redirect" title="Typefounding">typefounder</a> based in <a href="/wiki/London" title="London">London</a>. After an apprenticeship with Joseph Jackson, he established his own type foundry in 1792. His company was extremely successful and, with its range of <a href="/wiki/Didone_(typography)" title="Didone (typography)">modern serif</a> faces and <a href="/wiki/Display_typeface" title="Display typeface">display typefaces</a>, had a strong influence on the styles of British printing in the <a href="/wiki/Nineteenth_century" class="mw-redirect" title="Nineteenth century">nineteenth century</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Blythwood" title="User:Blythwood">Blythwood</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Blythwood" title="User talk:Blythwood">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-19 20:41 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Henry_W._Maxwell_Memorial" title="Henry W. Maxwell Memorial">Henry W. Maxwell Memorial</a> (<small>Memorial in Brooklyn, New York, U.S.</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Henry W. Maxwell Memorial is a public memorial located in <a href="/wiki/Brooklyn" title="Brooklyn">Brooklyn</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Grand_Army_Plaza" title="Grand Army Plaza">Grand Army Plaza</a> in New York City. The memorial, designed by sculptor <a href="/wiki/Augustus_Saint-Gaudens" title="Augustus Saint-Gaudens">Augustus Saint-Gaudens</a>, consists of a <a href="/wiki/Bronze" title="Bronze">bronze</a> tablet featuring a <a href="/wiki/Relief" title="Relief">relief</a> of Maxwell, a local philanthropist and park commissioner, affixed to a <a href="/wiki/Boulder" title="Boulder">boulder</a>. The memorial was dedicated in 1903. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:JJonahJackalope" title="User:JJonahJackalope">JJonahJackalope</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:JJonahJackalope" title="User talk:JJonahJackalope">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-20 16:54 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Statue_of_George_H._Perkins" title="Statue of George H. Perkins">Statue of George H. Perkins</a> </td> 
         <td>A <a href="/wiki/Bronze" title="Bronze">bronze</a> <a href="/wiki/Statue" title="Statue">statue</a> of <a href="/wiki/George_H._Perkins" title="George H. Perkins">George H. Perkins</a> stands on the grounds of the <a href="/wiki/New_Hampshire_State_House" title="New Hampshire State House">New Hampshire State House</a> in <a href="/wiki/Concord,_New_Hampshire" title="Concord, New Hampshire">Concord</a>, <a href="/wiki/New_Hampshire" title="New Hampshire">New Hampshire</a>, <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>. The statue was designed by sculptor <a href="/wiki/Daniel_Chester_French" title="Daniel Chester French">Daniel Chester French</a>, with <a href="/wiki/Architect" title="Architect">architect</a> <a href="/wiki/Henry_Bacon" title="Henry Bacon">Henry Bacon</a> designing the remainder of the public <a href="/wiki/Monument" title="Monument">monument</a>. It honors Perkins, a New Hampshire native who had served as an <a href="/wiki/Officer_(armed_forces)" title="Officer (armed forces)">officer</a> in the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Navy" title="United States Navy">United States Navy</a> during the <a href="/wiki/American_Civil_War" title="American Civil War">American Civil War</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:JJonahJackalope" title="User:JJonahJackalope">JJonahJackalope</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:JJonahJackalope" title="User talk:JJonahJackalope">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-21 03:09 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Statue_of_William_Francis_Bartlett" title="Statue of William Francis Bartlett">Statue of William Francis Bartlett</a> (<small>Statue in Boston, Massachusetts, U.S.</small>) </td> 
         <td>A <a href="/wiki/Statue" title="Statue">statue</a> of <a href="/wiki/William_Francis_Bartlett" title="William Francis Bartlett">William Francis Bartlett</a> stands inside the <a href="/wiki/Massachusetts_State_House" title="Massachusetts State House">Massachusetts State House</a> in <a href="/wiki/Boston" title="Boston">Boston</a>, <a href="/wiki/Massachusetts" title="Massachusetts">Massachusetts</a>, <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>. The bronze statue was designed by sculptor <a href="/wiki/Daniel_Chester_French" title="Daniel Chester French">Daniel Chester French</a> and honors Bartlett, who had served as a <a href="/wiki/General" class="mw-redirect" title="General">general</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Union_Army" title="Union Army">Union Army</a> during the <a href="/wiki/American_Civil_War" title="American Civil War">American Civil War</a>. The statue was dedicated in 1904. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:JJonahJackalope" title="User:JJonahJackalope">JJonahJackalope</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:JJonahJackalope" title="User talk:JJonahJackalope">talk</a>) </td>

        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-26 16:35 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/A_Boy_with_a_Flying_Squirrel" title="A Boy with a Flying Squirrel">A Boy with a Flying Squirrel</a> (<small>Painting by John Singleton Copley</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>A Boy with a Flying Squirrel (Henry Pelham)</i>, or simply <i>Boy with a Squirrel</i>, is a 1765 painting by the American-born painter <a href="/wiki/John_Singleton_Copley" title="John Singleton Copley">John Singleton Copley</a>. The painting depicts Copley's half-brother <a href="/wiki/Henry_Pelham_(engraver)" title="Henry Pelham (engraver)">Henry Pelham</a> with a pet <a href="/wiki/Flying_squirrel" title="Flying squirrel">flying squirrel</a> on a table. It was brought to <a href="/wiki/London" title="London">London</a> for a 1766 exhibition, where it was met with both praise and criticism for Copley's artistry. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:GeneralPoxter" title="User:GeneralPoxter">GeneralPoxter</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:GeneralPoxter" title="User talk:GeneralPoxter">talk</a> • <a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/GeneralPoxter" title="Special:Contributions/GeneralPoxter">contribs</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-28 02:18 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Statue_of_James_S._T._Stranahan" title="Statue of James S. T. Stranahan">Statue of James S. T. Stranahan</a> (<small>Statue of James S. T. Stranahan in Brooklyn, New York, U.S.</small>) </td> 
         <td>A <a href="/wiki/Statue" title="Statue">statue</a> of <a href="/wiki/James_S._T._Stranahan" title="James S. T. Stranahan">James S. T. Stranahan</a> stands in <a href="/wiki/Brooklyn" title="Brooklyn">Brooklyn</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Prospect_Park_(Brooklyn)" title="Prospect Park (Brooklyn)">Prospect Park</a> in New York City. Designed by sculptor <a href="/wiki/Frederick_William_MacMonnies" title="Frederick William MacMonnies">Frederick William MacMonnies</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Bronze" title="Bronze">bronze</a> statue honors Stranahan, a businessman from Brooklyn who served on the city's park commission and was instrumental in the creation of Prospect Park. It was dedicated in 1891 and stands near the park's entrance at <a href="/wiki/Grand_Army_Plaza" title="Grand Army Plaza">Grand Army Plaza</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:JJonahJackalope" title="User:JJonahJackalope">JJonahJackalope</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:JJonahJackalope" title="User talk:JJonahJackalope">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="new">2021-06-02 15:39 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Richard_Sapper" title="Richard Sapper">Richard Sapper</a> </td> 
         <td>Richard Sapper (30 May 1932 – 31 December 2015) was a German <a href="/wiki/Industrial_design" title="Industrial design">industrial designer</a> based in <a href="/wiki/Milan,_Italy" class="mw-redirect" title="Milan, Italy">Milan, Italy</a>. He is considered as one of the most important designers of his generation, his products typically featuring a combination of technical innovation, simplicity of form and an element of wit and surprise. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:PhotographyEdits" title="User:PhotographyEdits">PhotographyEdits</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:PhotographyEdits" title="User talk:PhotographyEdits">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="new">2021-06-04 19:38 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/689_Fifth_Avenue" title="689 Fifth Avenue">689 Fifth Avenue</a> (<small>Office building in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>689 Fifth Avenue (originally the Aeolian Building and later the Elizabeth Arden Building) is a commercial building in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>, at the northeast corner of <a href="/wiki/Fifth_Avenue" title="Fifth Avenue">Fifth Avenue</a> and <a href="/wiki/54th_Street_(Manhattan)" title="54th Street (Manhattan)">54th Street</a>. The building was designed by <a href="/wiki/Warren_and_Wetmore" title="Warren and Wetmore">Warren and Wetmore</a> and constructed from 1925 to 1927. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Battery_Maritime_Building" title="Battery Maritime Building">Battery Maritime Building</a> (<small>Ferry terminal in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Battery Maritime Building is a building at <a href="/wiki/South_Ferry_(Manhattan)" title="South Ferry (Manhattan)">South Ferry</a> on the southern tip of <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a> Island in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. Located at 10 <a href="/wiki/South_Street_(Manhattan)" title="South Street (Manhattan)">South Street</a>, near the intersection with <a href="/wiki/Whitehall_Street" title="Whitehall Street">Whitehall Street</a>, it is composed of an operational <a href="/wiki/Passenger_terminal_(maritime)" title="Passenger terminal (maritime)">ferry terminal</a> at ground level, as well as a hotel and event space on the upper stories. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="old">2021-03-07 18:12 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/New_York_World_Building" title="New York World Building">New York World Building</a> (<small>Former skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The New York World Building (also the Pulitzer Building) was a building in the <a href="/wiki/Civic_Center,_Manhattan" title="Civic Center, Manhattan">Civic Center</a> of <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>, across from <a href="/wiki/New_York_City_Hall" title="New York City Hall">City Hall</a> along <a href="/wiki/Park_Row_(Manhattan)" title="Park Row (Manhattan)">Park Row</a> between Frankfort Street and the <a href="/wiki/Brooklyn_Bridge" title="Brooklyn Bridge">Brooklyn Bridge</a>. Part of the former "<a href="/wiki/Park_Row_(Manhattan)#Newspaper_era" title="Park Row (Manhattan)">Newspaper Row</a>", it was designed by <a href="/wiki/George_B._Post" title="George B. Post">George B. Post</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Renaissance_Revival_architecture" title="Renaissance Revival architecture">Renaissance Revival</a> style, and served as the headquarters of the <i><a href="/wiki/New_York_World" title="New York World">New York World</a></i> after its completion in 1890. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="old">2021-03-07 18:12 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/New_York_Tribune_Building" title="New York Tribune Building">New York Tribune Building</a> (<small>Former skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The New York Tribune Building (also the Nassau-Tribune Building) was a building in the <a href="/wiki/Financial_District,_Manhattan" title="Financial District, Manhattan">Financial District</a> of <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>, across from <a href="/wiki/New_York_City_Hall" title="New York City Hall">City Hall</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Civic_Center,_Manhattan" title="Civic Center, Manhattan">Civic Center</a>. It was at the intersection of <a href="/wiki/Nassau_Street_(Manhattan)" title="Nassau Street (Manhattan)">Nassau</a> and <a href="/wiki/Spruce_Street_(Manhattan)" title="Spruce Street (Manhattan)">Spruce Streets</a>, at 154 Printing House Square. Part of the former "<a href="/wiki/Park_Row_(Manhattan)#Newspaper_era" title="Park Row (Manhattan)">Newspaper Row</a>", it operated as the headquarters of the <i><a href="/wiki/New-York_Tribune" title="New-York Tribune">New-York Tribune</a></i> from 1875 to 1923. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="recent">2021-03-13 00:32 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Knickerbocker_Hotel" title="The Knickerbocker Hotel">The Knickerbocker Hotel</a> (<small>Hotel in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Knickerbocker Hotel is a hotel at <a href="/wiki/Times_Square" title="Times Square">Times Square</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>, on the southeastern corner of <a href="/wiki/Broadway_(Manhattan)" title="Broadway (Manhattan)">Broadway</a> and <a href="/wiki/42nd_Street_(Manhattan)" title="42nd Street (Manhattan)">42nd Street</a>. Built by <a href="/wiki/John_Jacob_Astor_IV" title="John Jacob Astor IV">John Jacob Astor IV</a>, the hostelry was designed in 1901 and opened in 1906. Its location near the <a href="/wiki/Theater_District,_Manhattan" title="Theater District, Manhattan">Theater District</a> around Times Square was intended to attract not only residential guests but also theater visitors. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="recent">2021-03-24 02:15 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/330_West_42nd_Street" title="330 West 42nd Street">330 West 42nd Street</a> (<small>Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>330 West 42nd Street (also the McGraw-Hill Building and formerly the GHI Building) is a skyscraper in the <a href="/wiki/Hell%27s_Kitchen,_Manhattan" title="Hell's Kitchen, Manhattan">Hell's Kitchen</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. Designed by <a href="/wiki/Raymond_Hood" title="Raymond Hood">Raymond Hood</a> and <a href="/wiki/J._Andr%C3%A9_Fouilhoux" title="J. André Fouilhoux">J. André Fouilhoux</a> in a mixture of the <a href="/wiki/International_Style_(architecture)" title="International Style (architecture)">International Style</a>, <a href="/wiki/Art_Deco" title="Art Deco">Art Deco</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Art_Moderne" class="mw-redirect" title="Art Moderne">Art Moderne</a> styles, the building was constructed from 1930 to 1931 and originally served as the headquarters of <a href="/wiki/McGraw-Hill_Companies" class="mw-redirect" title="McGraw-Hill Companies">McGraw-Hill Companies</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="recent">2021-04-14 06:15 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Crusader_states" title="Crusader states">Crusader states</a> (<small>The four feudal Catholic Christian states created in the Levant by a series of religious wars</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Crusader states were <a href="/wiki/Feudalism" title="Feudalism">feudal</a> <a href="/wiki/Polity" title="Polity">polities</a> created by the <a href="/wiki/Latin_Church" title="Latin Church">Latin Catholic</a> leaders of the <a href="/wiki/First_Crusade" title="First Crusade">First Crusade</a> through <a href="/wiki/Conquest" title="Conquest">conquest</a> and political subterfuge. Four states were established: the <a href="/wiki/County_of_Edessa" title="County of Edessa">county of Edessa</a> (1098–1150); the <a href="/wiki/Principality_of_Antioch" title="Principality of Antioch">principality of Antioch</a> (1098–1287), the <a href="/wiki/County_of_Tripoli" title="County of Tripoli">county of Tripoli</a> (1102–1289), and the <a href="/wiki/Kingdom_of_Jerusalem" title="Kingdom of Jerusalem">kingdom of Jerusalem</a> (1099–1291). </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Norfolkbigfish" title="User:Norfolkbigfish">Norfolkbigfish</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Norfolkbigfish" title="User talk:Norfolkbigfish">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="recent">2021-04-16 20:20 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Flat_Top_Manor" title="Flat Top Manor">Flat Top Manor</a> </td> 
         <td>Flat Top Manor, as it is most commonly known, is also called the Moses Cone Manor, Moses Cone Estate, and the Moses H. Cone Mansion. It is at <a href="/wiki/Milepost" class="mw-redirect" title="Milepost">Milepost</a> 294 of the <a href="/wiki/Blue_Ridge_Parkway" title="Blue Ridge Parkway">Blue Ridge Parkway</a> in <a href="/wiki/Blowing_Rock,_North_Carolina" title="Blowing Rock, North Carolina">Blowing Rock, North Carolina</a>. It was built by American <a href="/wiki/Textile" title="Textile">textile</a> <a href="/wiki/Entrepreneur" class="mw-redirect" title="Entrepreneur">entrepreneur</a> <a href="/wiki/Moses_H._Cone" title="Moses H. Cone">Moses H. Cone</a> for his home and based on the idea of replicating George Vanderbilt's <a href="/wiki/Biltmore_Estate" title="Biltmore Estate">Biltmore Estate</a>, the largest privately owned house in the United States. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Doug_Coldwell" title="User:Doug Coldwell">Doug Coldwell</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Doug_Coldwell" title="User talk:Doug Coldwell">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Lever_House" title="Lever House">Lever House</a> (<small>Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>Lever House is a glass-box skyscraper at 390 <a href="/wiki/Park_Avenue_(Manhattan)" class="mw-redirect" title="Park Avenue (Manhattan)">Park Avenue</a> in <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a>, <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. The building was designed in the <a href="/wiki/International_style_(architecture)" class="mw-redirect" title="International style (architecture)">International Style</a> by <a href="/wiki/Gordon_Bunshaft" title="Gordon Bunshaft">Gordon Bunshaft</a> and <a href="/wiki/Natalie_de_Blois" title="Natalie de Blois">Natalie de Blois</a> of <a href="/wiki/Skidmore,_Owings_and_Merrill" class="mw-redirect" title="Skidmore, Owings and Merrill">Skidmore, Owings and Merrill</a> (SOM) as the headquarters of soap company Lever Brothers, a subsidiary of <a href="/wiki/Unilever" title="Unilever">Unilever</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/MetLife_Building" title="MetLife Building">MetLife Building</a> (<small>Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The MetLife Building (also 200 Park Avenue and formerly the Pan Am Building) is a <a href="/wiki/Skyscraper" title="Skyscraper">skyscraper</a> at <a href="/wiki/Park_Avenue" title="Park Avenue">Park Avenue</a> and <a href="/wiki/45th_Street_(Manhattan)" class="mw-redirect" title="45th Street (Manhattan)">45th Street</a>, north of <a href="/wiki/Grand_Central_Terminal" title="Grand Central Terminal">Grand Central Terminal</a>, in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. Designed in the <a href="/wiki/International_style_(architecture)" class="mw-redirect" title="International style (architecture)">International style</a> by Richard Roth, <a href="/wiki/Walter_Gropius" title="Walter Gropius">Walter Gropius</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Pietro_Belluschi" title="Pietro Belluschi">Pietro Belluschi</a>, the MetLife Building is 808 feet (246&nbsp;m) tall with 59 stories. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="recent">2021-04-29 20:35 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Seagram_Building" title="Seagram Building">Seagram Building</a> (<small>Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Seagram Building is a <a href="/wiki/Skyscraper" title="Skyscraper">skyscraper</a> at 375 <a href="/wiki/Park_Avenue" title="Park Avenue">Park Avenue</a>, between <a href="/wiki/52nd_Street_(Manhattan)" title="52nd Street (Manhattan)">52nd</a> and <a href="/wiki/53rd_Street_(Manhattan)" title="53rd Street (Manhattan)">53rd Streets</a>, in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. The building, measuring 515 feet (157&nbsp;m) tall with 38 stories and a large plaza, was designed in the <a href="/wiki/International_Style_(architecture)" title="International Style (architecture)">International Style</a> by <a href="/wiki/Ludwig_Mies_van_der_Rohe" title="Ludwig Mies van der Rohe">Ludwig Mies van der Rohe</a> and associate architect <a href="/wiki/Kahn_%26_Jacobs" class="mw-redirect" title="Kahn &amp; Jacobs">Kahn &amp; Jacobs</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="recent">2021-04-29 20:35 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Citigroup_Center" title="Citigroup Center">Citigroup Center</a> (<small>Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Citigroup Center (formerly Citicorp Center and also known by its address, 601 Lexington Avenue) is an office skyscraper in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. Built in 1977 to house the headquarters of <a href="/wiki/Citibank" title="Citibank">Citibank</a>, it is 915 feet (279&nbsp;m) tall and has 59 floors with 1.3&nbsp;million square feet (120,000&nbsp;m<sup>2</sup>) of office space. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="recent">2021-04-29 20:35 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/550_Madison_Avenue" title="550 Madison Avenue">550 Madison Avenue</a> (<small>Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>550 Madison Avenue (formerly known as the Sony Tower, Sony Plaza, and AT&amp;T Building) is a <a href="/wiki/Postmodern_architecture" title="Postmodern architecture">postmodern</a> skyscraper at <a href="/wiki/Madison_Avenue" title="Madison Avenue">Madison Avenue</a> between <a href="/wiki/55th_Street_(Manhattan)" title="55th Street (Manhattan)">55th</a> and 56th Streets in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. Designed by <a href="/wiki/Philip_Johnson" title="Philip Johnson">Philip Johnson</a> and <a href="/wiki/John_Burgee" title="John Burgee">John Burgee</a> with associate architect Simmons Architects, the building was completed in 1984 as the headquarters of <a href="/wiki/AT%26T" title="AT&amp;T">AT&amp;T</a> and later became the American headquarters of <a href="/wiki/Sony" title="Sony">Sony</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="recent">2021-04-29 20:37 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/500_Park_Avenue" title="500 Park Avenue">500 Park Avenue</a> (<small>Skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>500 Park Avenue is an office and condominium building on the southwest corner of <a href="/wiki/Park_Avenue" title="Park Avenue">Park Avenue</a> and <a href="/wiki/59th_Street_(Manhattan)" title="59th Street (Manhattan)">59th Street</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>, composed of the 11-story Pepsi-Cola Building and the 40-story 500 Park Tower. The original Pepsi-Cola Building along Park Avenue was constructed from 1958 to 1960 and designed by <a href="/wiki/Gordon_Bunshaft" title="Gordon Bunshaft">Gordon Bunshaft</a> and <a href="/wiki/Natalie_de_Blois" title="Natalie de Blois">Natalie de Blois</a> of <a href="/wiki/Skidmore,_Owings_and_Merrill" class="mw-redirect" title="Skidmore, Owings and Merrill">Skidmore, Owings and Merrill</a> (SOM). </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="recent">2021-05-01 04:43 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Henderson_Hall_Historic_District" title="Henderson Hall Historic District">Henderson Hall Historic District</a> (<small>NRHP-listed historic district in Wood County, West Virginia</small>) </td> 
         <td>Henderson Hall Historic District is a <a href="/wiki/National_Register_of_Historic_Places" title="National Register of Historic Places">National Register of Historic Places</a> (NRHP)-listed <a href="/wiki/Historic_district_(United_States)" class="mw-redirect" title="Historic district (United States)">historic district</a> in <a href="/wiki/Wood_County,_West_Virginia" title="Wood County, West Virginia">Wood County, West Virginia</a>. The primary <a href="/wiki/Contributing_property" title="Contributing property">contributing property</a> is Henderson Hall, a home in the <a href="/wiki/Italianate" class="mw-redirect" title="Italianate">Italianate</a> style from the first half of the 19th century. Other residences at the site are a tenant house from the end of the 19th century and "Woodhaven", the 1877 home of Henry Clay Henderson. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Hog_Farm" title="User:Hog Farm">Hog Farm</a> <sub> <a href="/wiki/User_talk:Hog_Farm" title="User talk:Hog Farm">Talk</a></sub> </td>

         <td class="recent">2021-05-04 22:18 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Burwell" title="The Burwell">The Burwell</a> (<small>United States historic place</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Burwell building is situated on the landmark corner of Gay Street and Clinch Avenue in <a href="/wiki/Knoxville,_Tennessee" title="Knoxville, Tennessee">Knoxville</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tennessee" title="Tennessee">Tennessee</a> above the majestic <a href="/wiki/Tennessee_Theatre" title="Tennessee Theatre">Tennessee Theatre</a>, and is the oldest of <a href="/wiki/List_of_tallest_buildings_in_Knoxville" title="List of tallest buildings in Knoxville">Knoxville’s historic skyscrapers</a>. Views from the Burwell include the <a href="/wiki/Sunsphere" title="Sunsphere">Sunsphere</a>, <a href="/wiki/Charles_Krutch" title="Charles Krutch">Krutch Park</a>, <a href="/wiki/Gay_Street_(Knoxville)" title="Gay Street (Knoxville)">Gay Street</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Women%27s_Basketball_Hall_of_Fame" title="Women's Basketball Hall of Fame">Women's Basketball Hall of Fame</a>, <a href="/wiki/Clingmans_Dome" title="Clingmans Dome">Clingmans Dome</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mount_Le_Conte_(Tennessee)" title="Mount Le Conte (Tennessee)">Mount Le Conte</a>, and the <a href="/wiki/Tennessee_River" title="Tennessee River">Tennessee River</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Fuller_Building" title="Fuller Building">Fuller Building</a> (<small>Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Fuller Building is a <a href="/wiki/Skyscraper" title="Skyscraper">skyscraper</a> at <a href="/wiki/57th_Street_(Manhattan)" title="57th Street (Manhattan)">57th Street</a> and <a href="/wiki/Madison_Avenue" title="Madison Avenue">Madison Avenue</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. Designed by <a href="/wiki/Walker_%26_Gillette" title="Walker &amp; Gillette">Walker &amp; Gillette</a>, it was erected between 1928 and 1929. The building is named for its original main occupant, the <a href="/wiki/Fuller_Construction_Company" class="mw-redirect" title="Fuller Construction Company">Fuller Construction Company</a>, which moved from the <a href="/wiki/Flatiron_Building" title="Flatiron Building">Flatiron Building</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Lescaze_House" title="Lescaze House">Lescaze House</a> (<small>House in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Lescaze House is a four-story house at 211 East 48th Street in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">East Midtown</a> and <a href="/wiki/Turtle_Bay,_Manhattan" title="Turtle Bay, Manhattan">Turtle Bay</a> neighborhoods of <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. It is along the northern sidewalk of 48th Street between <a href="/wiki/Second_Avenue_(Manhattan)" title="Second Avenue (Manhattan)">Second Avenue</a> and <a href="/wiki/Third_Avenue" title="Third Avenue">Third Avenue</a>. The Lescaze House at 211 East 48th Street was designed by <a href="/wiki/William_Lescaze" title="William Lescaze">William Lescaze</a> in the <a href="/wiki/International_Style_(architecture)" title="International Style (architecture)">International Style</a> between 1933 and 1934 as a renovation of a 19th-century brownstone <a href="/wiki/Townhouse" title="Townhouse">townhouse</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Rockefeller_Guest_House" title="Rockefeller Guest House">Rockefeller Guest House</a> (<small>House in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Rockefeller Guest House is a building at 242 East 52nd Street in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">East Midtown</a> and <a href="/wiki/Turtle_Bay,_Manhattan" title="Turtle Bay, Manhattan">Turtle Bay</a> neighborhoods of <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. Situated on the southern sidewalk of <a href="/wiki/52nd_Street_(Manhattan)" title="52nd Street (Manhattan)">52nd Street</a> between <a href="/wiki/Second_Avenue_(Manhattan)" title="Second Avenue (Manhattan)">Second Avenue</a> and <a href="/wiki/Third_Avenue" title="Third Avenue">Third Avenue</a>, it was designed by <a href="/wiki/Philip_C._Johnson" class="mw-redirect" title="Philip C. Johnson">Philip C. Johnson</a> and completed in 1950. The residence was constructed as a guest house for philanthropist <a href="/wiki/Blanchette_Ferry_Rockefeller" title="Blanchette Ferry Rockefeller">Blanchette Rockefeller</a>, who was married to <a href="/wiki/John_D._Rockefeller_III" title="John D. Rockefeller III">John D. Rockefeller III</a>. </td>
