         <td><a href="/wiki/488_Madison_Avenue" title="488 Madison Avenue">488 Madison Avenue</a> (<small>Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>488 Madison Avenue, also known as the Look Building, is a 25-story office building in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. It is along <a href="/wiki/Madison_Avenue" title="Madison Avenue">Madison Avenue</a>'s western sidewalk between <a href="/wiki/51st_Street_(Manhattan)" title="51st Street (Manhattan)">51st</a> and <a href="/wiki/52nd_Street_(Manhattan)" title="52nd Street (Manhattan)">52nd Streets</a>, near <a href="/wiki/St._Patrick%27s_Cathedral_(Manhattan)" title="St. Patrick's Cathedral (Manhattan)">St. Patrick's Cathedral</a>. 488 Madison Avenue was designed by <a href="/wiki/Emery_Roth_%26_Sons" class="mw-redirect" title="Emery Roth &amp; Sons">Emery Roth &amp; Sons</a> in the <a href="/wiki/International_Style_(architecture)" title="International Style (architecture)">International Style</a>, and it was constructed and developed by <a href="/wiki/Uris_Brothers" class="mw-redirect" title="Uris Brothers">Uris Brothers</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>

         <td>The Dorchester Heights Monument is a large public <a href="/wiki/Monument" title="Monument">monument</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Dorchester_Heights" title="Dorchester Heights">Dorchester Heights</a> area of <a href="/wiki/Boston" title="Boston">Boston</a>, <a href="/wiki/Massachusetts" title="Massachusetts">Massachusetts</a>, <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>. The monument, consisting of a 115-foot (35&nbsp;m) <a href="/wiki/Marble" title="Marble">marble</a> <a href="/wiki/Tower" title="Tower">tower</a>, honors the <a href="/wiki/Evacuation_of_Boston" class="mw-redirect" title="Evacuation of Boston">evacuation of Boston</a> during the <a href="/wiki/American_Revolutionary_War" title="American Revolutionary War">American Revolutionary War</a>, an early American victory in the conflict. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Greenwich_Savings_Bank_Building" title="Greenwich Savings Bank Building">Greenwich Savings Bank Building</a> (<small>United States historic place</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Greenwich Savings Bank Building (also known as the Haier Building and 1356 Broadway) is an office building at 1352–1362 Broadway in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. Constructed as the headquarters of the <a href="/wiki/Greenwich_Savings_Bank" title="Greenwich Savings Bank">Greenwich Savings Bank</a> from 1922 to 1924, it occupies a trapezoidal parcel bounded by 36th Street on the south, <a href="/wiki/Sixth_Avenue" title="Sixth Avenue">Sixth Avenue</a> on the east, and <a href="/wiki/Broadway_(Manhattan)" title="Broadway (Manhattan)">Broadway</a> on the west. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Center_Square/Hudson%E2%80%93Park_Historic_District" title="Center Square/Hudson–Park Historic District">Center Square/Hudson–Park Historic District</a> (<small>Residential neighborhood in Albany, New York, USA</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Center Square/Hudson–Park Historic District is located between <a href="/wiki/Empire_State_Plaza" title="Empire State Plaza">Empire State Plaza</a> and <a href="/wiki/Washington_Park_Historic_District_(Albany,_New_York)" title="Washington Park Historic District (Albany, New York)">Washington Park</a> in <a href="/wiki/Albany,_New_York" title="Albany, New York">Albany</a>, New York, United States. It is a 27-<a href="/wiki/City_block" title="City block">block</a>, 99-acre (40&nbsp;ha) area taking in both the <a href="/wiki/Neighborhoods_of_Albany,_New_York#Center_Square" title="Neighborhoods of Albany, New York">Center Square</a> and <a href="/wiki/Neighborhoods_of_Albany,_New_York#Hudson/Park" title="Neighborhoods of Albany, New York">Hudson/Park</a> neighborhoods, and <a href="/wiki/Lark_Street" title="Lark Street">Lark Street</a> on the west. In 1980 it was recognized as a <a href="/wiki/Historic_district_(United_States)" class="mw-redirect" title="Historic district (United States)">historic district</a> and listed on the <a href="/wiki/National_Register_of_Historic_Places" title="National Register of Historic Places">National Register of Historic Places</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Daniel_Case" title="User:Daniel Case">Daniel Case</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Daniel_Case" title="User talk:Daniel Case">talk</a>) </td>

         <td>The Rockefeller Apartments is a residential building at 17 West <a href="/wiki/54th_Street_(Manhattan)" title="54th Street (Manhattan)">54th Street</a> and 24 West <a href="/wiki/55th_Street_(Manhattan)" title="55th Street (Manhattan)">55th Street</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>.          <td class="new">2021-05-12 20:45 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Japanese_idol" title="Japanese idol">Japanese idol</a> (<small>Japanese type of entertainer</small>) </td> 
         <td>An idol<span style="font-weight: normal"> (<span lang="ja" title="Japanese-language text">????</span>, <i lang="ja-Latn" title="Hepburn transliteration">aidoru</i>)</span> is a type of entertainer manufactured and marketed for image, attractiveness, and personality in Japanese pop culture. Idols are primarily singers with training in acting, dancing, and modeling. Idols are commercialized through merchandise and endorsements by <a href="/wiki/Talent_agent" title="Talent agent">talent agencies</a>, while maintaining a <a href="/wiki/Parasocial_relationship" class="mw-redirect" title="Parasocial relationship">parasocial relationship</a> with a passionate consumer fan base. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Lullabying" title="User:Lullabying">lullabying</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Lullabying" title="User talk:Lullabying">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

      <h2><span id="Culture.2FVisual_arts.2FFashion"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Culture/Visual_arts/Fashion">Culture/Visual arts/Fashion</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=User:SDZeroBot/GAN_sorting&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Culture/Visual arts/Fashion">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>

        <tr> 
         <td class="recent">2021-04-03 16:08 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Cone_Mills_Corporation" title="Cone Mills Corporation">Cone Mills Corporation</a> (<small>American textile manufacturer (1895–2004)</small>) </td> 
         <td>Cone Mills Corporation was a twentieth century <a href="/wiki/Textile_manufacturing" title="Textile manufacturing">manufacturer</a> of <a href="/wiki/Cotton" title="Cotton">cotton</a> fabrics that included <a href="/wiki/Corduroy" title="Corduroy">corduroy</a>, <a href="/wiki/Flannel" title="Flannel">flannel</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Denim" title="Denim">denim</a>. The company headquartered in <a href="/wiki/Greensboro,_North_Carolina" title="Greensboro, North Carolina">Greensboro, North Carolina</a> and had its factory mills in parts of <a href="/wiki/North_Carolina" title="North Carolina">North</a> and <a href="/wiki/South_Carolina" title="South Carolina">South Carolina</a>. The company has its base roots in a family operated <a href="/wiki/Baltimore" title="Baltimore">Baltimore</a> grocery business in that was managed mostly by <a href="/wiki/Moses_H._Cone" title="Moses H. Cone">Moses H. Cone</a> and his brother Caesar. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Doug_Coldwell" title="User:Doug Coldwell">Doug Coldwell</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Doug_Coldwell" title="User talk:Doug Coldwell">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-29 13:33 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Lilly_Dach%C3%A9" title="Lilly Daché">Lilly Daché</a> </td> 
         <td>Lilly Daché {1892 – 31 December 1989) was a French-born American <a href="/wiki/Hatmaking" title="Hatmaking">milliner</a> and fashion merchandiser. She started her career in a small bonnet shop, advanced to being a sales lady at <a href="/wiki/Macy%27s" title="Macy's">Macy's</a> department store, and from there started her own <a href="/wiki/Haberdasher" title="Haberdasher">hat business</a>. She was at the peak of her business career in the 1930s and 1940s. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Doug_Coldwell" title="User:Doug Coldwell">Doug Coldwell</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Doug_Coldwell" title="User talk:Doug Coldwell">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>
       </tbody>
      </table>

         <td class="new">2021-05-17 18:25 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Vellar_River_(Northern_Tamil_Nadu)" title="Vellar River (Northern Tamil Nadu)">Vellar River (Northern Tamil Nadu)</a> </td> 
         <td>The Vellar River is a river in the <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">Indian</a> state of <a href="/wiki/Tamil_Nadu" title="Tamil Nadu">Tamil Nadu</a>. It originates in the <a href="/wiki/Kalrayan_Hills" title="Kalrayan Hills">Kalrayan Hills</a>, and flows generally eastward through <a href="/wiki/Salem_district" title="Salem district">Salem</a>, <a href="/wiki/Perambalur_district" title="Perambalur district">Perambalur</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Cuddalore_district" title="Cuddalore district">Cuddalore districts</a>, before flowing into the <a href="/wiki/Bay_of_Bengal" title="Bay of Bengal">Bay of Bengal</a> near <a href="/wiki/Parangipettai" title="Parangipettai">Parangipettai</a>. The river has a total length of 150 kilometres (93&nbsp;mi), and its drainage basin covers an area of 7,504.346 square kilometres (2,897.444&nbsp;sq&nbsp;mi) in Cuddalore, Perambalur, Salem, <a href="/wiki/Kallakurichi_district" title="Kallakurichi district">Kallakurichi</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ariyalur_district" title="Ariyalur district">Ariyalur</a>, <a href="/wiki/Namakkal_district" title="Namakkal district">Namakkal</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tiruchirappalli_district" title="Tiruchirappalli district">Tiruchirappalli</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Dharmapuri_district" title="Dharmapuri district">Dharmapuri districts</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Starkenborgher" title="User:Starkenborgher">Starkenborgher</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Starkenborgher" title="User talk:Starkenborgher">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-23 08:03 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Serengeti_National_Park" title="Serengeti National Park">Serengeti National Park</a> (<small>National park in Tanzania, Africa</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Serengeti National Park is a <a href="/wiki/National_park" title="National park">national park</a> in <a href="/wiki/Tanzania" title="Tanzania">Tanzania</a> that stretches over 14,763&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (5,700&nbsp;sq&nbsp;mi). It is located in the <a href="/wiki/Mara_Region" title="Mara Region">Mara</a> and <a href="/wiki/Simiyu_Region" title="Simiyu Region">Simiyu</a> regions and contains 1.5 million ha of <a href="/wiki/Savanna" title="Savanna">savanna</a>. It is well known for the largest annual migration of over 1.5 million <a href="/wiki/Blue_wildebeest" title="Blue wildebeest">blue wildebeest</a> and 250,000 <a href="/wiki/Zebra" title="Zebra">zebra</a> and for its numerous <a href="/wiki/Nile_crocodile" title="Nile crocodile">Nile crocodile</a> and <a href="/wiki/Honey_badger" title="Honey badger">honey badger</a>. </td> 
         <td><span style="background-color: azure"><a href="/wiki/User:TheEpicSnek" title="User:TheEpicSnek"><span style="color: #008080">EpicSnek </span></a> <a href="/wiki/User_talk:TheEpicSnek" title="User talk:TheEpicSnek"><sup><span style="color: RoyalBlue"> Talk to me here </span></sup></a> </span> </td>
        </tr>
       </tbody>
      </table>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Report_on_the_restitution_of_African_cultural_heritage" title="Report on the restitution of African cultural heritage">Report on the restitution of African cultural heritage</a> (<small>Report on cultural relations between France and Africa south of the Sahara</small>) </td> 
         <td>The report on the Restitution of African Cultural Heritage. Toward a New Relational Ethics (in French: Rapport sur la restitution du patrimoine culturel africain. Vers une nouvelle éthique relationnelle) is a report written by the Senegalese academic and writer <a href="/wiki/Felwine_Sarr" title="Felwine Sarr">Felwine Sarr</a> and the French art historian <a href="/wiki/B%C3%A9n%C3%A9dicte_Savoy" title="Bénédicte Savoy">Bénédicte Savoy</a>, first published online in November 2018 in a French original version and an authorised English translation. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Munfarid1" title="User:Munfarid1">Munfarid1</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Munfarid1" title="User talk:Munfarid1">talk</a>) </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-12 14:18 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Cinema_of_Sudan" title="Cinema of Sudan">Cinema of Sudan</a> (<small>History of films and cinema in Sudan</small>) </td> 
         <td>Cinema of Sudan refers to both the <a href="/wiki/History_of_film" title="History of film">history</a> and present of the <a href="/wiki/Filmmaking" title="Filmmaking">making</a> or screening of films in <a href="/wiki/Movie_theater" title="Movie theater">cinemas</a> or <a href="/wiki/Film_festival" title="Film festival">film festivals</a>, as well as to the persons involved in this form of <a href="/wiki/Audiovisual" title="Audiovisual">audiovisual</a> culture of the Sudan and its <a href="/wiki/History_of_Sudan" title="History of Sudan">history</a> from the late nineteenth century onwards. It began with <a href="/wiki/Cinematography" title="Cinematography">cinematography</a> during the <a href="/wiki/History_of_Anglo-Egyptian_Sudan" title="History of Anglo-Egyptian Sudan">British colonial presence</a> in 1898 and developed along with advances in <a href="/wiki/Cinematography" title="Cinematography">film technology</a> during the twentieth century. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Munfarid1" title="User:Munfarid1">Munfarid1</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Munfarid1" title="User talk:Munfarid1">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Serengeti_National_Park" title="Serengeti National Park">Serengeti National Park</a> (<small>National park in Tanzania, Africa</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Serengeti National Park is a <a href="/wiki/National_park" title="National park">national park</a> in <a href="/wiki/Tanzania" title="Tanzania">Tanzania</a> that stretches over 14,763&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (5,700&nbsp;sq&nbsp;mi). It is located in the <a href="/wiki/Mara_Region" title="Mara Region">Mara</a> and <a href="/wiki/Simiyu_Region" title="Simiyu Region">Simiyu</a> regions and contains 1.5 million ha of <a href="/wiki/Savanna" title="Savanna">savanna</a>. It is well known for the largest annual migration of over 1.5 million <a href="/wiki/Blue_wildebeest" title="Blue wildebeest">blue wildebeest</a> and 250,000 <a href="/wiki/Zebra" title="Zebra">zebra</a> and for its numerous <a href="/wiki/Nile_crocodile" title="Nile crocodile">Nile crocodile</a> and <a href="/wiki/Honey_badger" title="Honey badger">honey badger</a>. </td> 
         <td><span style="background-color: azure"><a href="/wiki/User:TheEpicSnek" title="User:TheEpicSnek"><span style="color: #008080">EpicSnek </span></a> <a href="/wiki/User_talk:TheEpicSnek" title="User talk:TheEpicSnek"><sup><span style="color: RoyalBlue"> Talk to me here </span></sup></a> </span> </td>

         <td class="new">2021-06-02 05:14 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Cyprien_Ntaryamira" title="Cyprien Ntaryamira">Cyprien Ntaryamira</a> (<small>5th President of Burundi, from February 1994 until his assassination that April</small>) </td> 
         <td>Cyprien Ntaryamira (6 March 1955 – 6 April 1994) was a Burundian politician who served as President of <a href="/wiki/Burundi" title="Burundi">Burundi</a> from 5 February 1994 until his death two months later. A <a href="/wiki/Hutu" title="Hutu">Hutu</a> born in Burundi, Ntaryamira studied there before fleeing to Rwanda to avoid ethnic violence and complete his education. Active in a Burundian student movement, he cofounded the socialist <a href="/wiki/Burundi_Workers%27_Party" title="Burundi Workers' Party">Burundi Workers' Party</a> and earned an agricultural degree. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Indy_beetle" title="User:Indy beetle">Indy beetle</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Indy_beetle" title="User talk:Indy beetle">talk</a>) </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-24 00:18 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Clifford_Orji" title="Clifford Orji">Clifford Orji</a> (<small>Nigeria's first documented cannibal</small>) </td> 
         <td>Clifford Nwa Orji (died August 17, 2012) was the first documented Nigerian cannibal. He was also indicted in serial killings, kidnappings, and sale of human body parts and was arrested in 1999. Orji died in Nigeria's only super-maximum penitentiary, where he spent 13 years, having never been tried for his crimes. </td> 
         <td><b><a href="/wiki/User:Celestina007" title="User:Celestina007">Celestina007</a></b> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Celestina007" title="User talk:Celestina007">talk</a>) </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-25 21:19 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Ikeji_festival" title="Ikeji festival">Ikeji festival</a> (<small>Festival observed annually by the Igbo people of Nigeria</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Ikeji festival is an annual four-day festival held by the <a href="/wiki/Igbo_people" title="Igbo people">Igbo people</a> of <a href="/wiki/Arondizuogu" title="Arondizuogu">Arondizuogu</a>, in <a href="/wiki/Imo_state" class="mw-redirect" title="Imo state">Imo state</a>, <a href="/wiki/Nigeria" title="Nigeria">Nigeria</a>, between the months of March and April to celebrate the harvest of new yams and the Igbo culture. The inception of the Ikeji festival dates back five centuries and is an Igbo festival which unites all Igbo race across the globe as they return to the south-eastern regions of Nigeria to witness and partake in the festival. </td> 
         <td><b><a href="/wiki/User:Celestina007" title="User:Celestina007">Celestina007</a></b> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Celestina007" title="User talk:Celestina007">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/2020_Salvadoran_political_crisis" title="2020 Salvadoran political crisis">2020 Salvadoran political crisis</a> (<small>Political crisis in El Salvador</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 2020 Salvadoran political crisis, commonly referred to as 9F or 9-F, occurred on 9 February 2020 when Salvadoran President <a href="/wiki/Nayib_Bukele" title="Nayib Bukele">Nayib Bukele</a> sent forty soldiers from the <a href="/wiki/Salvadoran_Army" title="Salvadoran Army">Salvadoran Army</a> into the <a href="/wiki/Legislative_Assembly_of_El_Salvador" title="Legislative Assembly of El Salvador">Legislative Assembly</a> building in an effort to coerce politicians to approve a loan request of 109 million dollars from the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> for Bukele's security plan for the country. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Eric_Anthony_Abrahams" title="Eric Anthony Abrahams">Eric Anthony Abrahams</a> (<small>Jamaican public servant</small>) </td> 
         <td>Eric Anthony Abrahams (5 May 1940&nbsp;– 7 August 2011) was a Jamaican public servant. He served as Director of Tourism from 1970 to 1975, and Minister of Tourism and Communication from 1980 to 1985. He attended the <a href="/wiki/University_of_the_West_Indies" title="University of the West Indies">University of the West Indies</a> and <a href="/wiki/University_of_Oxford" title="University of Oxford">University of Oxford</a> (a <a href="/wiki/Rhodes_Scholar" class="mw-redirect" title="Rhodes Scholar">Rhodes Scholar</a>), and briefly worked for the <a href="/wiki/BBC" title="BBC">BBC</a> as their first black TV reporter. </td>

         <td>John Caldwell (4 July 1849 – 7 March 1916) was a nineteenth century farmer and timber man of <a href="/wiki/Northern_Michigan" title="Northern Michigan">northern Michigan</a>, especially associated with <a href="/wiki/Missaukee_County,_Michigan" title="Missaukee County, Michigan">Missaukee County, Michigan</a>. For several years he was employed by the Mitchell Brothers Company, a land agent firm in several states associated large tracts of timber for making lumber. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Austin_Cornelius_Dunham" title="Austin Cornelius Dunham">Austin Cornelius Dunham</a> </td> 
         <td>Austin Cornelius Dunham (June 10, 1833 – March 17, 1918) was an American businessman, executive, merchandiser, inventor and <a href="/wiki/Philanthropist" class="mw-redirect" title="Philanthropist">philanthropist</a>. He was the manager, director, or trustee in several firms and organizations. He was involved with the <a href="/wiki/Textile_industry" title="Textile industry">textile industry</a> and manufactured yarns and clothing. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/K._T._Oslin" title="K. T. Oslin">K. T. Oslin</a> (<small>American singer-songwriter</small>) </td> 
         <td>Kay Toinette Oslin (May 15, 1942 – December 21, 2020) was an American <a href="/wiki/Country_music" title="Country music">country music</a> singer–songwriter. Oslin had several years of major commercial success in the late 1980s after signing a record deal at age 45. She had four number one hits and placed additional singles on the <i><a href="/wiki/Billboard_(magazine)" title="Billboard (magazine)">Billboard</a></i> country chart during that timespan; in addition, she won three <a href="/wiki/Grammy_Awards" title="Grammy Awards">Grammy Awards</a> and is an inductee of the <a href="/wiki/Nashville_Songwriters_Hall_of_Fame" title="Nashville Songwriters Hall of Fame">Nashville Songwriters Hall of Fame</a>. </td>

         <td class="old">2021-02-09 01:09 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Lap_steel_guitar" title="Lap steel guitar">Lap steel guitar</a> </td> 
         <td>The lap steel guitar, also known as a Hawaiian guitar, is a type of <a href="/wiki/Steel_guitar" title="Steel guitar">steel guitar</a> without pedals that is typically played with the instrument in a horizontal position across the performer's <a href="/wiki/Lap" title="Lap">lap</a>. Unlike the normal manner of playing a traditional <a href="/wiki/Acoustic_guitar" title="Acoustic guitar">acoustic guitar</a>, in which the performer's fingertips press the strings against <a href="/wiki/Frets" class="mw-redirect" title="Frets">frets</a>, the pitch of a lap steel guitar is changed by pressing a polished <a href="/wiki/Steel_bar" title="Steel bar">steel bar</a> against plucked strings (from which the name "steel guitar" derives). </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Eagledj" title="User:Eagledj">Eagledj</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Eagledj" title="User talk:Eagledj">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Gertrude_Hull" title="Gertrude Hull">Gertrude Hull</a> (<small>Teacher of history for over 40 years at the Milwaukee school system</small>) </td> 
         <td>Gertrude Hull (November 16, 1866 – March 22, 1947) was an educator. She received a teacher's degree in 1894 from the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Michigan" title="University of Michigan">University of Michigan</a> and was <a href="/wiki/Salutatorian" title="Salutatorian">salutatorian</a> when she received another degree in 1895 from <a href="/wiki/Southern_Illinois_Normal_College" class="mw-redirect" title="Southern Illinois Normal College">Southern Illinois Normal College</a>. She was a teacher of history in the <a href="/wiki/Milwaukee" title="Milwaukee">Milwaukee</a> school system for over 40 years. </td>

         <td>Robert Alexander Unglaub (July 31, 1881 – November 29, 1916) was an American <a href="/wiki/First_baseman" title="First baseman">first baseman</a>, <a href="/wiki/Utility_infielder" class="mw-redirect" title="Utility infielder">utility infielder</a> and <a href="/wiki/Manager_(baseball)" title="Manager (baseball)">manager</a> in <a href="/wiki/Major_League_Baseball" title="Major League Baseball">Major League Baseball</a> who played for the <a href="/wiki/New_York_Highlanders" class="mw-redirect" title="New York Highlanders">New York Highlanders</a>, <a href="/wiki/Boston_Americans" class="mw-redirect" title="Boston Americans">Boston Americans</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Washington_Senators_(1901%E2%80%9360)" class="mw-redirect" title="Washington Senators (1901–60)">Washington Senators</a>. He batted and threw right-handed. Unglaub stood 5&nbsp;feet 11&nbsp;inches (1.80&nbsp;m) and weighed 178 pounds (81&nbsp;kg). </td>

         <td>James Hood Wright (known professionally as J. Hood Wright; November 4, 1836 – November 12, 1894) was an American <a href="/wiki/Bank" title="Bank">banker</a>, <a href="/wiki/Financier" class="mw-redirect" title="Financier">financier</a>, <a href="/wiki/Management" title="Management">corporate director</a>, <a href="/wiki/Business_magnate" title="Business magnate">business magnate</a>, and reorganizer of US railroads. He began as a bookkeeper but his management talents led him to becoming a partner in <a href="/wiki/J._P._Morgan" title="J. P. Morgan">J. P. Morgan</a>'s banking firms. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Amasa_Holcomb" title="Amasa Holcomb">Amasa Holcomb</a> (<small>American manufacturer of surveying instruments and telescopes</small>) </td> 
         <td>Amasa Holcomb (1787–1875) was an American farmer, surveyor, <a href="/wiki/Civil_engineer" title="Civil engineer">civil engineer</a>, businessman, politician, and <a href="/wiki/Manufacturer" class="mw-redirect" title="Manufacturer">manufacturer</a> of surveying instruments and <a href="/wiki/Telescopes" class="mw-redirect" title="Telescopes">telescopes</a>. From instruments he made he could observe the total solar eclipse of June&nbsp;16, 1806. He made astronomical computations from his observations and published almanacs for the partial solar eclipses of 1807 and 1808 from his work. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Doug_Coldwell" title="User:Doug Coldwell">Doug Coldwell</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Doug_Coldwell" title="User talk:Doug Coldwell">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/2010_United_States_Senate_election_in_Pennsylvania" title="2010 United States Senate election in Pennsylvania">2010 United States Senate election in Pennsylvania</a> (<small>Class III U.S. Senate election in Pennsylvania</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 2010 United States Senate election in Pennsylvania took place on November 2, 2010, during the <a href="/wiki/United_States_elections,_2010" class="mw-redirect" title="United States elections, 2010">2010 midterm elections</a>. Incumbent Republican-turned-Democrat <a href="/wiki/United_States_Senate" title="United States Senate">U.S. Senator</a> <a href="/wiki/Arlen_Specter" title="Arlen Specter">Arlen Specter</a> ran for reelection to a sixth term, but lost in <a href="/wiki/2010_United_States_Senate_Democratic_primary_election_in_Pennsylvania" title="2010 United States Senate Democratic primary election in Pennsylvania">the Democratic primary</a> to <a href="/wiki/Joe_Sestak" title="Joe Sestak">Joe Sestak</a>. Republican nominee <a href="/wiki/Pat_Toomey" title="Pat Toomey">Pat Toomey</a> then won the seat. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Battery_Maritime_Building" title="Battery Maritime Building">Battery Maritime Building</a> (<small>Ferry terminal in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Battery Maritime Building is a building at <a href="/wiki/South_Ferry_(Manhattan)" title="South Ferry (Manhattan)">South Ferry</a> on the southern tip of <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a> Island in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. Located at 10 <a href="/wiki/South_Street_(Manhattan)" title="South Street (Manhattan)">South Street</a>, near the intersection with <a href="/wiki/Whitehall_Street" title="Whitehall Street">Whitehall Street</a>, it is composed of an operational <a href="/wiki/Passenger_terminal_(maritime)" title="Passenger terminal (maritime)">ferry terminal</a> at ground level, as well as a hotel and event space on the upper stories. </td>

         <td class="old">2021-03-01 21:00 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Charles_A._Cheever" title="Charles A. Cheever">Charles A. Cheever</a> </td> 
         <td>Charles Augustus Cheever (September 7, 1852 – May 2, 1900) was an American industrialist and inventor. He was affiliated with <a href="/wiki/Alexander_Graham_Bell" title="Alexander Graham Bell">Alexander Graham Bell</a> and <a href="/wiki/Thomas_Edison" title="Thomas Edison">Thomas Edison</a> improving their inventions. He patented 100 of these improvements, most related to the telephone. Cheever formed the Telephone Company of New York and constructed the first telephone line in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Doug_Coldwell" title="User:Doug Coldwell">Doug Coldwell</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Doug_Coldwell" title="User talk:Doug Coldwell">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Astoria_Park" title="Astoria Park">Astoria Park</a> (<small>Public park in Queens, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>Astoria Park is a 59.96-acre (24.26&nbsp;ha) public park in the <a href="/wiki/Astoria,_Queens" title="Astoria, Queens">Astoria</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/Queens" title="Queens">Queens</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. The park is situated on the eastern shore of the <a href="/wiki/Hell_Gate" title="Hell Gate">Hell Gate</a>, a strait of the <a href="/wiki/East_River" title="East River">East River</a>, between <a href="/wiki/Ditmars_Boulevard" title="Ditmars Boulevard">Ditmars Boulevard</a> to the north and Hoyt Avenue to the south. The <a href="/wiki/Triborough_Bridge" title="Triborough Bridge">Triborough (Robert F. Kennedy)</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hell_Gate_Bridge" title="Hell Gate Bridge">Hell Gate Bridges</a> respectively pass over the park's southern and northern sections. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/New_York_World_Building" title="New York World Building">New York World Building</a> (<small>Former skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The New York World Building (also the Pulitzer Building) was a building in the <a href="/wiki/Civic_Center,_Manhattan" title="Civic Center, Manhattan">Civic Center</a> of <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>, across from <a href="/wiki/New_York_City_Hall" title="New York City Hall">City Hall</a> along <a href="/wiki/Park_Row_(Manhattan)" title="Park Row (Manhattan)">Park Row</a> between Frankfort Street and the <a href="/wiki/Brooklyn_Bridge" title="Brooklyn Bridge">Brooklyn Bridge</a>. Part of the former "<a href="/wiki/Park_Row_(Manhattan)#Newspaper_era" title="Park Row (Manhattan)">Newspaper Row</a>", it was designed by <a href="/wiki/George_B._Post" title="George B. Post">George B. Post</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Renaissance_Revival_architecture" title="Renaissance Revival architecture">Renaissance Revival</a> style, and served as the headquarters of the <i><a href="/wiki/New_York_World" title="New York World">New York World</a></i> after its completion in 1890. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>

         <td>The New York Tribune Building (also the Nassau-Tribune Building) was a building in the <a href="/wiki/Financial_District,_Manhattan" title="Financial District, Manhattan">Financial District</a> of <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>, across from <a href="/wiki/New_York_City_Hall" title="New York City Hall">City Hall</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Civic_Center,_Manhattan" title="Civic Center, Manhattan">Civic Center</a>. It was at the intersection of <a href="/wiki/Nassau_Street_(Manhattan)" title="Nassau Street (Manhattan)">Nassau</a> and <a href="/wiki/Spruce_Street_(Manhattan)" title="Spruce Street (Manhattan)">Spruce Streets</a>, at 154 Printing House Square. Part of the former "<a href="/wiki/Park_Row_(Manhattan)#Newspaper_era" title="Park Row (Manhattan)">Newspaper Row</a>", it operated as the headquarters of the <i><a href="/wiki/New-York_Tribune" title="New-York Tribune">New-York Tribune</a></i> from 1875 to 1923. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Meatballs_(advertisement)" title="Meatballs (advertisement)">Meatballs (advertisement)</a> (<small>2000 US presidential election campaign political commercial</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Meatballs</i> (also known as <i>Meatball</i> and <i>For Spanish Press 1</i>) was a <a href="/wiki/Campaign_advertising" title="Campaign advertising">political commercial</a> aired during the <a href="/wiki/2000_United_States_presidential_election" title="2000 United States presidential election">2000 United States presidential campaign</a> in support of <a href="/wiki/Reform_Party_of_the_United_States_of_America" title="Reform Party of the United States of America">Reform Party</a> candidate <a href="/wiki/Pat_Buchanan" title="Pat Buchanan">Pat Buchanan</a>. The commercial, which was created by <a href="/wiki/Houston" title="Houston">Houston</a>-based agency Love Advertising, depicts a white man choking on a meatball while attempting to dial 911, but keeling over before the automated menu reaches the option for English. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Knickerbocker_Hotel" title="The Knickerbocker Hotel">The Knickerbocker Hotel</a> (<small>Hotel in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Knickerbocker Hotel is a hotel at <a href="/wiki/Times_Square" title="Times Square">Times Square</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>, on the southeastern corner of <a href="/wiki/Broadway_(Manhattan)" title="Broadway (Manhattan)">Broadway</a> and <a href="/wiki/42nd_Street_(Manhattan)" title="42nd Street (Manhattan)">42nd Street</a>. Built by <a href="/wiki/John_Jacob_Astor_IV" title="John Jacob Astor IV">John Jacob Astor IV</a>, the hostelry was designed in 1901 and opened in 1906. Its location near the <a href="/wiki/Theater_District,_Manhattan" title="Theater District, Manhattan">Theater District</a> around Times Square was intended to attract not only residential guests but also theater visitors. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="recent">2021-03-19 20:58 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Josiah_Holbrook" title="Josiah Holbrook">Josiah Holbrook</a> </td> 
         <td>Josiah Holbrook (1788–1854) was the initiator and organizer of the <a href="/wiki/Lyceum_movement" title="Lyceum movement">lyceum movement</a> in the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>. He formed the first <a href="/wiki/Lyceum" title="Lyceum">lyceum</a> school in the United States in 1826. His design and system was duplicated throughout the United states by hundreds of similar associations within a few years and the first nationwide organization of lyceum schools was formed. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Doug_Coldwell" title="User:Doug Coldwell">Doug Coldwell</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Doug_Coldwell" title="User talk:Doug Coldwell">talk</a>) </td>

         <td>Douglas Wayne Sahm (November 6, 1941 – November 18, 1999) was an American musician, singer-songwriter and <a href="/wiki/Multi-instrumentalist" title="Multi-instrumentalist">multi-instrumentalist</a> born in <a href="/wiki/San_Antonio,_Texas" class="mw-redirect" title="San Antonio, Texas">San Antonio, Texas</a>. Sahm began singing at age five and learned to play the steel guitar at age six. He was considered a <a href="/wiki/Child_prodigy" title="Child prodigy">child prodigy</a> on the instrument. By the age of eight, he had appeared on the <i><a href="/wiki/Louisiana_Hayride" title="Louisiana Hayride">Louisiana Hayride</a></i>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Charles_Corydon_Hall" title="Charles Corydon Hall">Charles Corydon Hall</a> (<small>American businessman, chemist, engineer and industrialist</small>) </td> 
         <td>Charles Corydon Hall (July 3, 1860 – August 19, 1935) was an American businessman, chemist, engineer and industrialist. He developed a process of converting molten <a href="/wiki/Limestone" title="Limestone">limestone</a> into fibers that would become an insulation material. He initiated the <a href="/wiki/Rock_wool" class="mw-redirect" title="Rock wool">rock wool</a> insulation industry in America and is considered its progenitor. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/330_West_42nd_Street" title="330 West 42nd Street">330 West 42nd Street</a> (<small>Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>330 West 42nd Street (also the McGraw-Hill Building and formerly the GHI Building) is a skyscraper in the <a href="/wiki/Hell%27s_Kitchen,_Manhattan" title="Hell's Kitchen, Manhattan">Hell's Kitchen</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. Designed by <a href="/wiki/Raymond_Hood" title="Raymond Hood">Raymond Hood</a> and <a href="/wiki/J._Andr%C3%A9_Fouilhoux" title="J. André Fouilhoux">J. André Fouilhoux</a> in a mixture of the <a href="/wiki/International_Style_(architecture)" title="International Style (architecture)">International Style</a>, <a href="/wiki/Art_Deco" title="Art Deco">Art Deco</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Art_Moderne" class="mw-redirect" title="Art Moderne">Art Moderne</a> styles, the building was constructed from 1930 to 1931 and originally served as the headquarters of <a href="/wiki/McGraw-Hill_Companies" class="mw-redirect" title="McGraw-Hill Companies">McGraw-Hill Companies</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Julius_Kahn_(inventor)" title="Julius Kahn (inventor)">Julius Kahn (inventor)</a> (<small>American inventor</small>) </td> 
         <td>Julius Kahn (March 8, 1874 – November 4, 1942) was an American engineer, industrialist, and manufacturer. He was the inventor of the <a href="/wiki/Kahn_System" class="mw-redirect" title="Kahn System">Kahn System</a>, a reinforced concrete engineering technique for building construction. The Kahn System, which he patented in 1903, was used worldwide for housing, factories, offices and industrial buildings. </td>

         <td>Cone Mills Corporation was a twentieth century <a href="/wiki/Textile_manufacturing" title="Textile manufacturing">manufacturer</a> of <a href="/wiki/Cotton" title="Cotton">cotton</a> fabrics that included <a href="/wiki/Corduroy" title="Corduroy">corduroy</a>, <a href="/wiki/Flannel" title="Flannel">flannel</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Denim" title="Denim">denim</a>. The company headquartered in <a href="/wiki/Greensboro,_North_Carolina" title="Greensboro, North Carolina">Greensboro, North Carolina</a> and had its factory mills in parts of <a href="/wiki/North_Carolina" title="North Carolina">North</a> and <a href="/wiki/South_Carolina" title="South Carolina">South Carolina</a>. The company has its base roots in a family operated <a href="/wiki/Baltimore" title="Baltimore">Baltimore</a> grocery business in that was managed mostly by <a href="/wiki/Moses_H._Cone" title="Moses H. Cone">Moses H. Cone</a> and his brother Caesar. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1997_Central_Texas_tornado_outbreak" title="1997 Central Texas tornado outbreak">1997 Central Texas tornado outbreak</a> (<small>Tornado outbreak in Texas</small>) </td> 
         <td>A deadly <a href="/wiki/Tornado_outbreak" title="Tornado outbreak">tornado outbreak</a> occurred in <a href="/wiki/Central_Texas" title="Central Texas">Central Texas</a> during the afternoon and evening of May 27, 1997, in conjunction with a southwestward-moving cluster of <a href="/wiki/Supercell" title="Supercell">supercell</a> thunderstorms. These storms produced 20&nbsp;tornadoes, mainly along the <a href="/wiki/Interstate_35" title="Interstate 35">Interstate 35</a> corridor from northeast of <a href="/wiki/Waco" class="mw-redirect" title="Waco">Waco</a> to north of <a href="/wiki/San_Antonio" title="San Antonio">San Antonio</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/U.S._Route_63_in_Iowa" title="U.S. Route 63 in Iowa">U.S. Route 63 in Iowa</a> </td> 
         <td>U.S. Highway 63 (US&nbsp;63) is a <a href="/wiki/United_States_Highway" class="mw-redirect" title="United States Highway">United States Highway</a> that runs through the eastern third of <a href="/wiki/Iowa" title="Iowa">Iowa</a>. It begins at the <a href="/wiki/Missouri" title="Missouri">Missouri</a> state line southwest of <a href="/wiki/Bloomfield,_Iowa" title="Bloomfield, Iowa">Bloomfield</a> and travels north through <a href="/wiki/Ottumwa,_Iowa" title="Ottumwa, Iowa">Ottumwa</a>, <a href="/wiki/Oskaloosa,_Iowa" title="Oskaloosa, Iowa">Oskaloosa</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tama,_Iowa" title="Tama, Iowa">Tama</a>, <a href="/wiki/Waterloo,_Iowa" title="Waterloo, Iowa">Waterloo</a>, and <a href="/wiki/New_Hampton,_Iowa" title="New Hampton, Iowa">New Hampton</a>. It ends at the <a href="/wiki/Minnesota" title="Minnesota">Minnesota</a> state line at <a href="/wiki/Chester,_Iowa" title="Chester, Iowa">Chester</a>. Between Ottumwa and Oskaloosa, the highway is a four-lane <a href="/wiki/Controlled-access_highway" title="Controlled-access highway">controlled-access highway</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Shooting_of_Vivian_Strong" title="Shooting of Vivian Strong">Shooting of Vivian Strong</a> </td> 
         <td>On June 24, 1969, Vivian Strong, a 14-year-old African American girl, was killed in Omaha, Nebraska, United States, when a white police officer shot Strong in the back of the head without warning. The white police officer, and his Black partner, had been dispatched to the location because there were "juveniles breaking in." When they arrived at the scene a small group of teens fled out of an abandoned apartment where they had been dancing. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Henry_Fitz" title="Henry Fitz">Henry Fitz</a> </td> 
         <td>Henry Fitz was an American engineer, scientist, locksmith, <a href="/wiki/Optician" title="Optician">optician</a>, and inventor. As a teenager, one of his hobbies was <a href="/wiki/Astronomy" title="Astronomy">astronomy</a>, which led to him making telescopes. Fritz became a manufacturer of telescopes and the first American to make large high-end sophisticated <a href="/wiki/Refracting_telescope" title="Refracting telescope">refracting telescopes</a>. He made telescopes for wealthy individuals, institutions, colleges, and universities throughout the United States, some of which are still in use. </td>

         <td>Flat Top Manor, as it is most commonly known, is also called the Moses Cone Manor, Moses Cone Estate, and the Moses H. Cone Mansion. It is at <a href="/wiki/Milepost" class="mw-redirect" title="Milepost">Milepost</a> 294 of the <a href="/wiki/Blue_Ridge_Parkway" title="Blue Ridge Parkway">Blue Ridge Parkway</a> in <a href="/wiki/Blowing_Rock,_North_Carolina" title="Blowing Rock, North Carolina">Blowing Rock, North Carolina</a>.          <td><a href="/wiki/Resolute_desk" title="Resolute desk">Resolute desk</a> (<small>Oval office desk</small>) </td> 
         <td>The <i>Resolute</i> desk, also known as the Hayes desk, is a nineteenth-century <a href="/wiki/Partners_desk" title="Partners desk">partners' desk</a> used by several <a href="/wiki/President_of_the_United_States" title="President of the United States">presidents</a> of the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> in the <a href="/wiki/White_House" title="White House">White House</a> as the <a href="/wiki/List_of_Oval_Office_desks" title="List of Oval Office desks">Oval Office desk</a>, including the five most recent presidents. The desk was a gift from <a href="/wiki/Queen_Victoria" title="Queen Victoria">Queen Victoria</a> to President <a href="/wiki/Rutherford_B._Hayes" title="Rutherford B. Hayes">Rutherford B. Hayes</a> in 1880 and was built from the <a href="/wiki/Oak" title="Oak">oak</a> timbers of the British Arctic exploration ship . </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Moses_H._Cone" title="Moses H. Cone">Moses H. Cone</a> (<small>entrepreneur and conservationist</small>) </td> 
         <td>Moses Herman Cone (June 29, 1857 – December 8, 1908) was an American businessman, <a href="/wiki/Textile" title="Textile">textile</a> <a href="/wiki/Entrepreneur" class="mw-redirect" title="Entrepreneur">entrepreneur</a>, <a href="/wiki/Conservation_movement" title="Conservation movement">conservationist</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Philanthropist" class="mw-redirect" title="Philanthropist">philanthropist</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Gilded_Age" title="Gilded Age">Gilded Age</a> who was active in the eastern and southern United States. He began his career in sales and became an innovator who offered finished clothing, which was unusual in an era when textiles were normally sold as unfinished cloth. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Doug_Coldwell" title="User:Doug Coldwell">Doug Coldwell</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Doug_Coldwell" title="User talk:Doug Coldwell">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/2016_Famous_Idaho_Potato_Bowl" title="2016 Famous Idaho Potato Bowl">2016 Famous Idaho Potato Bowl</a> (<small>annual NCAA football game</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 2016 Famous Idaho Potato Bowl was a post-season American <a href="/wiki/College_football" title="College football">college football</a> <a href="/wiki/Bowl_game" title="Bowl game">bowl game</a> played on December 22, 2016, at <a href="/wiki/Albertsons_Stadium" title="Albertsons Stadium">Albertsons Stadium</a> in <a href="/wiki/Boise,_Idaho" title="Boise, Idaho">Boise, Idaho</a>. The 20th annual edition of the <a href="/wiki/Famous_Idaho_Potato_Bowl" title="Famous Idaho Potato Bowl">Famous Idaho Potato Bowl</a>, the game featured the <a href="/wiki/2016_Idaho_Vandals_football_team" title="2016 Idaho Vandals football team">Idaho Vandals</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Sun_Belt_Conference" title="Sun Belt Conference">Sun Belt Conference</a> and the <a href="/wiki/2016_Colorado_State_Rams_football_team" title="2016 Colorado State Rams football team">Colorado State Rams</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Mountain_West_Conference" title="Mountain West Conference">Mountain West Conference</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:PCN02WPS" title="User:PCN02WPS"><span style="color:grey;"><b>PCN02WPS</b></span></a> <small>(<a href="/wiki/User_talk:PCN02WPS" title="User talk:PCN02WPS"><span style="color:grey;">talk</span></a> | <a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/PCN02WPS" title="Special:Contributions/PCN02WPS"><span style="color:grey;">contribs</span></a>)</small> </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Darnestown,_Maryland" title="Darnestown, Maryland">Darnestown, Maryland</a> (<small>Census-designated place in the United States</small>) </td> 
         <td>Darnestown is a United States <a href="/wiki/Census-designated_place" title="Census-designated place">census-designated place</a> (CDP) and an <a href="/wiki/Unincorporated_area" title="Unincorporated area">unincorporated area</a> in <a href="/wiki/Montgomery_County,_Maryland" title="Montgomery County, Maryland">Montgomery County, Maryland</a>. The CDP is 17.70 square miles (45.8&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>) with the <a href="/wiki/Potomac_River" title="Potomac River">Potomac River</a> as its southern border and the <a href="/wiki/Muddy_Branch" title="Muddy Branch">Muddy Branch</a> as much of its eastern border. <a href="/wiki/Seneca_Creek_(Potomac_River_tributary)" title="Seneca Creek (Potomac River tributary)">Seneca Creek</a> borders portions of its north and west sides. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:TwoScars" title="User:TwoScars">TwoScars</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:TwoScars" title="User talk:TwoScars">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Queens" title="Queens">Queens</a> (<small>Borough in New York City and county in New York, United States</small>) </td> 
         <td>Queens is a <a href="/wiki/Boroughs_of_New_York_City" title="Boroughs of New York City">borough of New York City</a>, coextensive with Queens County, in the <a href="/wiki/U.S._state" title="U.S. state">U.S. state</a> of <a href="/wiki/New_York_(state)" title="New York (state)">New York</a>. It is the largest borough of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a> in area and is adjacent to the borough of <a href="/wiki/Brooklyn" title="Brooklyn">Brooklyn</a> at the western end of <a href="/wiki/Long_Island" title="Long Island">Long Island</a>, with <a href="/wiki/Nassau_County,_New_York" title="Nassau County, New York">Nassau County</a> to the east. Queens also shares water borders with the boroughs of <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a>, <a href="/wiki/The_Bronx" title="The Bronx">the Bronx</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Staten_Island" title="Staten Island">Staten Island</a> (via the <a href="/wiki/Rockaway,_Queens" title="Rockaway, Queens">Rockaways</a>). </td> 
         <td><b><a href="/wiki/User:-Zai-" title="User:-Zai-"><span style="color: #1ec1fc;">Zai</span></a></b> <sup>(<a href="/wiki/User_talk:-Zai-" title="User talk:-Zai-">?</a> • <a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/-Zai-" title="Special:Contributions/-Zai-">?</a> • <a href="/wiki/Special:UserRights/-Zai-" title="Special:UserRights/-Zai-">??</a>)</sup> </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Tillinghast_L%27Hommedieu_Huston" title="Tillinghast L'Hommedieu Huston">Tillinghast L'Hommedieu Huston</a> (<small>American baseball club owner</small>) </td> 
         <td>Tillinghast L'Hommedieu Huston (July 17, 1867 – March 29, 1938), popularly known as Cap Huston, was an American <a href="/wiki/Civil_engineer" title="Civil engineer">civil engineer</a> and businessman. He co-owned the <a href="/wiki/New_York_Yankees" title="New York Yankees">New York Yankees</a> of <a href="/wiki/Major_League_Baseball" title="Major League Baseball">Major League Baseball</a> with <a href="/wiki/Jacob_Ruppert" title="Jacob Ruppert">Jacob Ruppert</a> from 1915 to 1923, turning them from one of the worst franchises in baseball into a <a href="/wiki/World_Series" title="World Series">World Series</a> contender. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Long_Sault_Parkway" title="Long Sault Parkway">Long Sault Parkway</a> (<small>Scenic parkway of the St. Lawrence River</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Long Sault Parkway is a 10.1-kilometre (6.3&nbsp;mi) <a href="/wiki/Scenic_route" title="Scenic route">scenic</a> <a href="/wiki/Parkway" title="Parkway">parkway</a> connecting a group of eleven islands west of <a href="/wiki/Cornwall,_Ontario" title="Cornwall, Ontario">Cornwall</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Canada" title="Canada">Canadian</a> province of <a href="/wiki/Ontario" title="Ontario">Ontario</a>. The islands, which were created by the flooding of the <a href="/wiki/Long_Sault" title="Long Sault">Long Sault</a> rapids during construction of the <a href="/wiki/Saint_Lawrence_Seaway" class="mw-redirect" title="Saint Lawrence Seaway">St. Lawrence Seaway</a> in the late 1950s, include two public <a href="/wiki/Beach" title="Beach">beaches</a> and three <a href="/wiki/Campsite" title="Campsite">campgrounds</a>. </td> 
         <td><b><a href="/wiki/User:Floydian" title="User:Floydian"><span style="color: #0051BA;">Floydian</span></a></b>&nbsp;<sup><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Floydian" title="User talk:Floydian"><span style="color: #3AAA3A;">?</span></a></sup> <sub><a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/Floydian" title="Special:Contributions/Floydian"><span style="color: #3AAA3A;">¢</span></a></sub> </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Robert_M._La_Follette" title="Robert M. La Follette">Robert M. La Follette</a> (<small>Progressive politician from Wisconsin</small>) </td> 
         <td>Robert Marion "Fighting Bob" La Follette Sr. (June 14, 1855&nbsp;– June 18, 1925), was an American lawyer and politician. He represented <a href="/wiki/Wisconsin" title="Wisconsin">Wisconsin</a> in both chambers of Congress and served as the <a href="/wiki/Governor_of_Wisconsin" title="Governor of Wisconsin">Governor of Wisconsin</a>. A <a href="/wiki/Republican_Party_(United_States)" title="Republican Party (United States)">Republican</a> for most of his career, he ran for <a href="/wiki/President_of_the_United_States" title="President of the United States">President of the United States</a> as the nominee of his own <a href="/wiki/Progressive_Party_(United_States,_1924%E2%80%9334)" title="Progressive Party (United States, 1924–34)">Progressive Party</a> in the <a href="/wiki/U.S._presidential_election,_1924" class="mw-redirect" title="U.S. presidential election, 1924">1924 presidential election</a>. </td> 
         <td><i><b><a href="/wiki/User:JackFromWisconsin" title="User:JackFromWisconsin">JackFromWisconsin</a></b></i> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:JackFromWisconsin" title="User talk:JackFromWisconsin">talk</a> | <a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/JackFromWisconsin" title="Special:Contributions/JackFromWisconsin">contribs</a>) </td>

         <td>The MetLife Building (also 200 Park Avenue and formerly the Pan Am Building) is a <a href="/wiki/Skyscraper" title="Skyscraper">skyscraper</a> at <a href="/wiki/Park_Avenue" title="Park Avenue">Park Avenue</a> and <a href="/wiki/45th_Street_(Manhattan)" class="mw-redirect" title="45th Street (Manhattan)">45th Street</a>, north of <a href="/wiki/Grand_Central_Terminal" title="Grand Central Terminal">Grand Central Terminal</a>, in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. Designed in the <a href="/wiki/International_style_(architecture)" class="mw-redirect" title="International style (architecture)">International style</a> by Richard Roth, <a href="/wiki/Walter_Gropius" title="Walter Gropius">Walter Gropius</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Pietro_Belluschi" title="Pietro Belluschi">Pietro Belluschi</a>, the MetLife Building is 808 feet (246&nbsp;m) tall with 59 stories. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Seagram_Building" title="Seagram Building">Seagram Building</a> (<small>Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Seagram Building is a <a href="/wiki/Skyscraper" title="Skyscraper">skyscraper</a> at 375 <a href="/wiki/Park_Avenue" title="Park Avenue">Park Avenue</a>, between <a href="/wiki/52nd_Street_(Manhattan)" title="52nd Street (Manhattan)">52nd</a> and <a href="/wiki/53rd_Street_(Manhattan)" title="53rd Street (Manhattan)">53rd Streets</a>, in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. The building, measuring 515 feet (157&nbsp;m) tall with 38 stories and a large plaza, was designed in the <a href="/wiki/International_Style_(architecture)" title="International Style (architecture)">International Style</a> by <a href="/wiki/Ludwig_Mies_van_der_Rohe" title="Ludwig Mies van der Rohe">Ludwig Mies van der Rohe</a> and associate architect <a href="/wiki/Kahn_%26_Jacobs" class="mw-redirect" title="Kahn &amp; Jacobs">Kahn &amp; Jacobs</a>. </td>

Built in 1977 to house the headquarters of <a href="/wiki/Citibank" title="Citibank">Citibank</a>, it is 915 feet (279&nbsp;m) tall and has 59 floors with 1.3&nbsp;million square feet (120,000&nbsp;m<sup>2</sup>) of office space. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/550_Madison_Avenue" title="550 Madison Avenue">550 Madison Avenue</a> (<small>Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>550 Madison Avenue (formerly known as the Sony Tower, Sony Plaza, and AT&amp;T Building) is a <a href="/wiki/Postmodern_architecture" title="Postmodern architecture">postmodern</a> skyscraper at <a href="/wiki/Madison_Avenue" title="Madison Avenue">Madison Avenue</a> between <a href="/wiki/55th_Street_(Manhattan)" title="55th Street (Manhattan)">55th</a> and 56th Streets in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. Designed by <a href="/wiki/Philip_Johnson" title="Philip Johnson">Philip Johnson</a> and <a href="/wiki/John_Burgee" title="John Burgee">John Burgee</a> with associate architect Simmons Architects, the building was completed in 1984 as the headquarters of <a href="/wiki/AT%26T" title="AT&amp;T">AT&amp;T</a> and later became the American headquarters of <a href="/wiki/Sony" title="Sony">Sony</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/500_Park_Avenue" title="500 Park Avenue">500 Park Avenue</a> (<small>Skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>500 Park Avenue is an office and condominium building on the southwest corner of <a href="/wiki/Park_Avenue" title="Park Avenue">Park Avenue</a> and <a href="/wiki/59th_Street_(Manhattan)" title="59th Street (Manhattan)">59th Street</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>, composed of the 11-story Pepsi-Cola Building and the 40-story 500 Park Tower. The original Pepsi-Cola Building along Park Avenue was constructed from 1958 to 1960 and designed by <a href="/wiki/Gordon_Bunshaft" title="Gordon Bunshaft">Gordon Bunshaft</a> and <a href="/wiki/Natalie_de_Blois" title="Natalie de Blois">Natalie de Blois</a> of <a href="/wiki/Skidmore,_Owings_and_Merrill" class="mw-redirect" title="Skidmore, Owings and Merrill">Skidmore, Owings and Merrill</a> (SOM). </td>

        <tr> 
         <td class="recent">2021-04-30 03:18 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Canoe_Fight_(Creek_War)" title="Canoe Fight (Creek War)">Canoe Fight (Creek War)</a> </td> 
         <td>The Canoe Fight was a skirmish between <a href="/wiki/Mississippi_Territory" title="Mississippi Territory">Mississippi Territory</a> militiamen and <a href="/wiki/Red_Stick" class="mw-redirect" title="Red Stick">Red Stick</a> warriors that took place on November 12, 1813 as part of the <a href="/wiki/Creek_War" title="Creek War">Creek War</a>. The skirmish was fought largely from canoes and was a victory for the militiamen, who only had one member wounded. The victory held little military value in the overall Creek War but its participants gained widespread notoriety for their actions during the fight. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Dofftoubab" title="User:Dofftoubab">Dofftoubab</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Dofftoubab" title="User talk:Dofftoubab">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Henderson_Hall_Historic_District" title="Henderson Hall Historic District">Henderson Hall Historic District</a> (<small>NRHP-listed historic district in Wood County, West Virginia</small>) </td> 
         <td>Henderson Hall Historic District is a <a href="/wiki/National_Register_of_Historic_Places" title="National Register of Historic Places">National Register of Historic Places</a> (NRHP)-listed <a href="/wiki/Historic_district_(United_States)" class="mw-redirect" title="Historic district (United States)">historic district</a> in <a href="/wiki/Wood_County,_West_Virginia" title="Wood County, West Virginia">Wood County, West Virginia</a>. The primary <a href="/wiki/Contributing_property" title="Contributing property">contributing property</a> is Henderson Hall, a home in the <a href="/wiki/Italianate" class="mw-redirect" title="Italianate">Italianate</a> style from the first half of the 19th century. Other residences at the site are a tenant house from the end of the 19th century and "Woodhaven", the 1877 home of Henry Clay Henderson. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Hog_Farm" title="User:Hog Farm">Hog Farm</a> <sub> <a href="/wiki/User_talk:Hog_Farm" title="User talk:Hog Farm">Talk</a></sub> </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1960_Los_Angeles_Chargers_season" title="1960 Los Angeles Chargers season">1960 Los Angeles Chargers season</a> (<small>Inaugural season for the franchise in Los Angeles</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 1960 Los Angeles Chargers season was the team's inaugural season and also the inaugural season of the <a href="/wiki/American_Football_League" title="American Football League">American Football League</a> (AFL). Head coach <a href="/wiki/Sid_Gillman" title="Sid Gillman">Sid Gillman</a> led the Chargers to the AFL Western Division title with a 10–4 record, in the team's only season in Los Angeles until its <a href="/wiki/2017_Los_Angeles_Chargers_season" title="2017 Los Angeles Chargers season">2017 return</a>, with its home field at the <a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles_Memorial_Coliseum" title="Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum">Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum</a>. </td>

         <td class="recent">2021-05-04 18:08 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/John_Rolph_(politician)" title="John Rolph (politician)">John Rolph (politician)</a> (<small>Upper Canada politician (1973-1870)</small>) </td> 
         <td>John Rolph (4&nbsp;March 1793 – 19&nbsp;October 1870) was a physician, lawyer, and political figure in <a href="/wiki/Upper_Canada" title="Upper Canada">Upper Canada</a>. He was elected to the <a href="/wiki/Parliament_of_Upper_Canada" title="Parliament of Upper Canada">Parliament of Upper Canada</a> in 1824 to represent <a href="/wiki/Middlesex_County,_Ontario" title="Middlesex County, Ontario">Middlesex County</a> and was considered the leader of the Reform faction in the 1820s. In 1837 he helped plan the <a href="/wiki/Upper_Canada_Rebellion" title="Upper Canada Rebellion">Upper Canada Rebellion</a>, but acted as the government's emissary to negotiate a truce once the rebellion began. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Z1720" title="User:Z1720">Z1720</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Z1720" title="User talk:Z1720">talk</a>) </td>

         <td class="recent">2021-05-04 22:18 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Burwell" title="The Burwell">The Burwell</a> (<small>United States historic place</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Burwell building is situated on the landmark corner of Gay Street and Clinch Avenue in <a href="/wiki/Knoxville,_Tennessee" title="Knoxville, Tennessee">Knoxville</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tennessee" title="Tennessee">Tennessee</a> above the majestic <a href="/wiki/Tennessee_Theatre" title="Tennessee Theatre">Tennessee Theatre</a>, and is the oldest of <a href="/wiki/List_of_tallest_buildings_in_Knoxville" title="List of tallest buildings in Knoxville">Knoxville’s historic skyscrapers</a>. Views from the Burwell include the <a href="/wiki/Sunsphere" title="Sunsphere">Sunsphere</a>, <a href="/wiki/Charles_Krutch" title="Charles Krutch">Krutch Park</a>, <a href="/wiki/Gay_Street_(Knoxville)" title="Gay Street (Knoxville)">Gay Street</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Women%27s_Basketball_Hall_of_Fame" title="Women's Basketball Hall of Fame">Women's Basketball Hall of Fame</a>, <a href="/wiki/Clingmans_Dome" title="Clingmans Dome">Clingmans Dome</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mount_Le_Conte_(Tennessee)" title="Mount Le Conte (Tennessee)">Mount Le Conte</a>, and the <a href="/wiki/Tennessee_River" title="Tennessee River">Tennessee River</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Burwell37902" title="User:Burwell37902">Burwell37902</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Burwell37902" title="User talk:Burwell37902">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="recent">2021-05-05 15:33 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Fuller_Building" title="Fuller Building">Fuller Building</a> (<small>Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Fuller Building is a <a href="/wiki/Skyscraper" title="Skyscraper">skyscraper</a> at <a href="/wiki/57th_Street_(Manhattan)" title="57th Street (Manhattan)">57th Street</a> and <a href="/wiki/Madison_Avenue" title="Madison Avenue">Madison Avenue</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. Designed by <a href="/wiki/Walker_%26_Gillette" title="Walker &amp; Gillette">Walker &amp; Gillette</a>, it was erected between 1928 and 1929. The building is named for its original main occupant, the <a href="/wiki/Fuller_Construction_Company" class="mw-redirect" title="Fuller Construction Company">Fuller Construction Company</a>, which moved from the <a href="/wiki/Flatiron_Building" title="Flatiron Building">Flatiron Building</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="recent">2021-05-06 10:07 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Juliana_R._Force" title="Juliana R. Force">Juliana R. Force</a> (<small>American art museum administrator</small>) </td> 
         <td>Juliana R. Force (December 25, 1876&nbsp;– August 28, 1948) was an American art museum administrator and director. Force started her career as a collector of <a href="/wiki/Folk_art" title="Folk art">folk art</a> and as a secretary to <a href="/wiki/Socialite" title="Socialite">socialite</a> art collectors. She initiated the first display of American folk art in the United States. Force became a director of art galleries and of a temporary museum of American art in <a href="/wiki/Greenwich_Village" title="Greenwich Village">Greenwich Village</a> in New York City that became the <a href="/wiki/Whitney_Museum_of_American_Art" title="Whitney Museum of American Art">Whitney Museum of American Art</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Doug_Coldwell" title="User:Doug Coldwell">Doug Coldwell</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Doug_Coldwell" title="User talk:Doug Coldwell">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Harlan_Page_Davidson" title="Harlan Page Davidson">Harlan Page Davidson</a> </td> 
         <td>Harlan Page Davidson (September 15, 1838 – January 20, 1913) was an <a href="/wiki/Education" title="Education">educator</a> in private education. He was a teacher and director of several schools and academies for fifty years. He founded <a href="/wiki/Northwestern_Military_and_Naval_Academy" title="Northwestern Military and Naval Academy">Northwestern Military Academy</a> and was its president for twenty years. </td>

McMahon et al</i> (9:93-cr-01276) is a 1994 <a href="/wiki/United_States_District_Court_for_the_Eastern_District_of_New_York" title="United States District Court for the Eastern District of New York">United States District Court for the Eastern District of New York</a> criminal court case brought against <a href="/wiki/Vince_McMahon" title="Vince McMahon">Vince McMahon</a>, chairman of the <a href="/wiki/WWE" title="WWE">World Wrestling Federation</a> on suspicion of supplying illegal <a href="/wiki/Anabolic_steroids" class="mw-redirect" title="Anabolic steroids">anabolic steroids</a> to his professional wrestlers.          <td><a href="/wiki/Lescaze_House" title="Lescaze House">Lescaze House</a> (<small>House in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Lescaze House is a four-story house at 211 East 48th Street in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">East Midtown</a> and <a href="/wiki/Turtle_Bay,_Manhattan" title="Turtle Bay, Manhattan">Turtle Bay</a> neighborhoods of <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. It is along the northern sidewalk of 48th Street between <a href="/wiki/Second_Avenue_(Manhattan)" title="Second Avenue (Manhattan)">Second Avenue</a> and <a href="/wiki/Third_Avenue" title="Third Avenue">Third Avenue</a>. The Lescaze House at 211 East 48th Street was designed by <a href="/wiki/William_Lescaze" title="William Lescaze">William Lescaze</a> in the <a href="/wiki/International_Style_(architecture)" title="International Style (architecture)">International Style</a> between 1933 and 1934 as a renovation of a 19th-century brownstone <a href="/wiki/Townhouse" title="Townhouse">townhouse</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Epicgenius" title="User:Epicgenius">Epicgenius</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Epicgenius" title="User talk:Epicgenius">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Rockefeller_Guest_House" title="Rockefeller Guest House">Rockefeller Guest House</a> (<small>House in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Rockefeller Guest House is a building at 242 East 52nd Street in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">East Midtown</a> and <a href="/wiki/Turtle_Bay,_Manhattan" title="Turtle Bay, Manhattan">Turtle Bay</a> neighborhoods of <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. Situated on the southern sidewalk of <a href="/wiki/52nd_Street_(Manhattan)" title="52nd Street (Manhattan)">52nd Street</a> between <a href="/wiki/Second_Avenue_(Manhattan)" title="Second Avenue (Manhattan)">Second Avenue</a> and <a href="/wiki/Third_Avenue" title="Third Avenue">Third Avenue</a>, it was designed by <a href="/wiki/Philip_C._Johnson" class="mw-redirect" title="Philip C. Johnson">Philip C. Johnson</a> and completed in 1950. The residence was constructed as a guest house for philanthropist <a href="/wiki/Blanchette_Ferry_Rockefeller" title="Blanchette Ferry Rockefeller">Blanchette Rockefeller</a>, who was married to <a href="/wiki/John_D._Rockefeller_III" title="John D. Rockefeller III">John D. Rockefeller III</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Royal_Page_Davidson" title="Royal Page Davidson">Royal Page Davidson</a> </td> 
         <td>Royal Page Davidson (October 9, 1870&nbsp;– January 16, 1943) was an American scholar, <a href="/wiki/Education" title="Education">educator</a>, professor, and inventor.          <td><a href="/wiki/Potomac_River" title="Potomac River">Potomac River</a> (<small>River in the Mid-Atlantic United States</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Potomac River () is found within the <a href="/wiki/Mid-Atlantic_(United_States)" title="Mid-Atlantic (United States)">Mid-Atlantic</a> region of the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> and flows from the <a href="/wiki/Potomac_Highlands_of_West_Virginia" class="mw-redirect" title="Potomac Highlands of West Virginia">Potomac Highlands</a> into the <a href="/wiki/Chesapeake_Bay" title="Chesapeake Bay">Chesapeake Bay</a>. The <a href="/wiki/River" title="River">river</a> (main stem and North Branch) is approximately 405 miles (652&nbsp;km) long, with a <a href="/wiki/Drainage_basin" title="Drainage basin">drainage area</a> of about 14,700 square miles (38,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>). </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/488_Madison_Avenue" title="488 Madison Avenue">488 Madison Avenue</a> (<small>Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>488 Madison Avenue, also known as the Look Building, is a 25-story office building in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. It is along <a href="/wiki/Madison_Avenue" title="Madison Avenue">Madison Avenue</a>'s western sidewalk between <a href="/wiki/51st_Street_(Manhattan)" title="51st Street (Manhattan)">51st</a> and <a href="/wiki/52nd_Street_(Manhattan)" title="52nd Street (Manhattan)">52nd Streets</a>, near <a href="/wiki/St._Patrick%27s_Cathedral_(Manhattan)" title="St. Patrick's Cathedral (Manhattan)">St. Patrick's Cathedral</a>. 488 Madison Avenue was designed by <a href="/wiki/Emery_Roth_%26_Sons" class="mw-redirect" title="Emery Roth &amp; Sons">Emery Roth &amp; Sons</a> in the <a href="/wiki/International_Style_(architecture)" title="International Style (architecture)">International Style</a>, and it was constructed and developed by <a href="/wiki/Uris_Brothers" class="mw-redirect" title="Uris Brothers">Uris Brothers</a>. </td>

         <td>John Bacon Curtis (October 10, 1827 – June 13, 1897) was an American businessman from <a href="/wiki/Maine" title="Maine">Maine</a>.          <td>The Henry W. Maxwell Memorial is a public memorial located in <a href="/wiki/Brooklyn" title="Brooklyn">Brooklyn</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Grand_Army_Plaza" title="Grand Army Plaza">Grand Army Plaza</a> in New York City. The memorial, designed by sculptor <a href="/wiki/Augustus_Saint-Gaudens" title="Augustus Saint-Gaudens">Augustus Saint-Gaudens</a>, consists of a <a href="/wiki/Bronze" title="Bronze">bronze</a> tablet featuring a <a href="/wiki/Relief" title="Relief">relief</a> of Maxwell, a local philanthropist and park commissioner, affixed to a <a href="/wiki/Boulder" title="Boulder">boulder</a>. The memorial was dedicated in 1903. </td>

         <td>The Dorchester Heights Monument is a large public <a href="/wiki/Monument" title="Monument">monument</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Dorchester_Heights" title="Dorchester Heights">Dorchester Heights</a> area of <a href="/wiki/Boston" title="Boston">Boston</a>, <a href="/wiki/Massachusetts" title="Massachusetts">Massachusetts</a>, <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>. The monument, consisting of a 115-foot (35&nbsp;m) <a href="/wiki/Marble" title="Marble">marble</a> <a href="/wiki/Tower" title="Tower">tower</a>, honors the <a href="/wiki/Evacuation_of_Boston" class="mw-redirect" title="Evacuation of Boston">evacuation of Boston</a> during the <a href="/wiki/American_Revolutionary_War" title="American Revolutionary War">American Revolutionary War</a>, an early American victory in the conflict. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Presidential_transition_of_Richard_Nixon" title="Presidential transition of Richard Nixon">Presidential transition of Richard Nixon</a> </td> 
         <td>The presidential transition of Richard Nixon began when <a href="/wiki/Richard_Nixon" title="Richard Nixon">Richard Nixon</a> won the United States <a href="/wiki/1968_United_States_presidential_election" title="1968 United States presidential election">1968 United States presidential election</a>, becoming the <a href="/wiki/President-elect_of_the_United_States" title="President-elect of the United States">President-elect</a>, and ended when Nixon was <a href="/wiki/First_inauguration_of_Richard_Nixon" title="First inauguration of Richard Nixon">inaugurated</a> at noon <a href="/wiki/Eastern_Standard_Time_(North_America)" class="mw-redirect" title="Eastern Standard Time (North America)">EST</a> on January 20, 1969.          <td class="new">2021-05-20 16:54 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Statue_of_George_H._Perkins" title="Statue of George H. Perkins">Statue of George H. Perkins</a> </td> 
         <td>A <a href="/wiki/Bronze" title="Bronze">bronze</a> <a href="/wiki/Statue" title="Statue">statue</a> of <a href="/wiki/George_H._Perkins" title="George H. Perkins">George H. Perkins</a> stands on the grounds of the <a href="/wiki/New_Hampshire_State_House" title="New Hampshire State House">New Hampshire State House</a> in <a href="/wiki/Concord,_New_Hampshire" title="Concord, New Hampshire">Concord</a>, <a href="/wiki/New_Hampshire" title="New Hampshire">New Hampshire</a>, <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>. The statue was designed by sculptor <a href="/wiki/Daniel_Chester_French" title="Daniel Chester French">Daniel Chester French</a>, with <a href="/wiki/Architect" title="Architect">architect</a> <a href="/wiki/Henry_Bacon" title="Henry Bacon">Henry Bacon</a> designing the remainder of the public <a href="/wiki/Monument" title="Monument">monument</a>. It honors Perkins, a New Hampshire native who had served as an <a href="/wiki/Officer_(armed_forces)" title="Officer (armed forces)">officer</a> in the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Navy" title="United States Navy">United States Navy</a> during the <a href="/wiki/American_Civil_War" title="American Civil War">American Civil War</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:JJonahJackalope" title="User:JJonahJackalope">JJonahJackalope</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:JJonahJackalope" title="User talk:JJonahJackalope">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/River_Works_station" title="River Works station">River Works station</a> </td> 
         <td>River Works station (sometimes written Riverworks) is an <a href="/wiki/MBTA_Commuter_Rail" title="MBTA Commuter Rail">MBTA Commuter Rail</a> station on the <a href="/wiki/Newburyport/Rockport_Line" title="Newburyport/Rockport Line">Newburyport/Rockport Line</a> in <a href="/wiki/West_Lynn,_Massachusetts" class="mw-redirect" title="West Lynn, Massachusetts">West Lynn, Massachusetts</a>. The only <a href="/wiki/Private_railway_station" title="Private railway station">private station</a> on the system, it is only open to <a href="/wiki/General_Electric_Aviation" class="mw-redirect" title="General Electric Aviation">General Electric Aviation</a> employees who work at the adjacent <a href="/wiki/River_Works" title="River Works">River Works</a> plant. The station has minimal facilities – two small sections of platform and several shelters – and is not <a href="/wiki/Accessible" class="mw-redirect" title="Accessible">accessible</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Pi.1415926535" title="User:Pi.1415926535">Pi.1415926535</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Pi.1415926535" title="User talk:Pi.1415926535">talk</a>) </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-21 14:59 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/George_Livermore" title="George Livermore">George Livermore</a> </td> 
         <td>George Livermore (July 10, 1809 – August 30, 1865) was an American <a href="/wiki/Antiquarian" title="Antiquarian">antiquarian</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bibliographer" class="mw-redirect" title="Bibliographer">bibliographer</a>, and historian, known chiefly as a book collector, who had many valuable old books. He developed in his lifetime what was recognized as one of the finest private libraries in the United States. His library included many rare and one-of-a-kind bibles including some printed by <a href="/wiki/Gutenberg" class="mw-redirect" title="Gutenberg">Gutenberg</a>. </td>
