         <td>Gerald Donald Kindall (May 27, 1935 – December 24, 2017) was an American <a href="/wiki/Professional_baseball" title="Professional baseball">professional baseball</a> <a href="/wiki/Baseball_player" class="mw-redirect" title="Baseball player">player</a> and <a href="/wiki/College_baseball" title="College baseball">college baseball</a> player and <a href="/wiki/Head_coach_(baseball)" class="mw-redirect" title="Head coach (baseball)">coach</a>. He was primarily a <a href="/wiki/Second_base" class="mw-redirect" title="Second base">second baseman</a> in <a href="/wiki/Major_League_Baseball" title="Major League Baseball">Major League Baseball</a> who appeared in 742 <a href="/wiki/Games_played" title="Games played">games played</a> over nine seasons for the <a href="/wiki/Chicago_Cubs" title="Chicago Cubs">Chicago Cubs</a> (1956-58, 1960-61), <a href="/wiki/Cleveland_Indians" title="Cleveland Indians">Cleveland Indians</a> (1962-64), and <a href="/wiki/Minnesota_Twins" title="Minnesota Twins">Minnesota Twins</a> (1964-65). </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/John_Adam_Rittinger" title="John Adam Rittinger">John Adam Rittinger</a> (<small>Canadian newspaper editor, humorist</small>) </td> 
         <td>John Adam Rittinger (16 February 1855&nbsp;– 29 July 1915) was a Canadian German-language newspaper proprietor, <a href="/wiki/Editor-in-chief" title="Editor-in-chief">editor</a> and <a href="/wiki/Pennsylvania_Dutch_language" title="Pennsylvania Dutch language">Pennsylvania German</a> <a href="/wiki/Humorist" title="Humorist">humorist</a>. In 1875, he and Aaron Eby purchased <a href="/wiki/Walkerton,_Ontario" title="Walkerton, Ontario">Walkerton, Ontario</a>'s German language newspaper, the <i lang="de" title="German-language text">Walkerton Glocke</i>. Affectionately known by locals as the "<span lang="de" style="font-style: normal;" title="German-language text">Glockemann</span>" ("Bell Ringer"), he became the paper's sole-owner in 1878, renaming it <i lang="de" title="German-language text">Die Ontario Glocke</i> in 1882. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/New_York_Produce_Exchange" title="New York Produce Exchange">New York Produce Exchange</a> (<small>Former building and commodities exchange in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The New York Produce Exchange was a <a href="/wiki/Commodities_exchange" class="mw-redirect" title="Commodities exchange">commodities exchange</a> headquartered in the <a href="/wiki/Financial_District,_Manhattan" title="Financial District, Manhattan">Financial District</a> of <a href="/wiki/Lower_Manhattan" title="Lower Manhattan">Lower Manhattan</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. It served a network of produce and commodities dealers across the United States. Founded in 1861 as the New York Commercial Association, it was originally headquartered at <a href="/wiki/Whitehall_Street" title="Whitehall Street">Whitehall Street</a> in a building owned by the New York Produce Exchange Company. </td>

         <td>The Frontier Central School District is the primary <a href="/wiki/State_school" title="State school">public</a> <a href="/wiki/School_district" title="School district">school district</a> serving the town of <a href="/wiki/Hamburg,_New_York" title="Hamburg, New York">Hamburg, New York</a>.          <td><a href="/wiki/Greenwich_Savings_Bank_Building" title="Greenwich Savings Bank Building">Greenwich Savings Bank Building</a> (<small>United States historic place</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Greenwich Savings Bank Building (also known as the Haier Building and 1356 Broadway) is an office building at 1352–1362 Broadway in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. Constructed as the headquarters of the <a href="/wiki/Greenwich_Savings_Bank" title="Greenwich Savings Bank">Greenwich Savings Bank</a> from 1922 to 1924, it occupies a trapezoidal parcel bounded by 36th Street on the south, <a href="/wiki/Sixth_Avenue" title="Sixth Avenue">Sixth Avenue</a> on the east, and <a href="/wiki/Broadway_(Manhattan)" title="Broadway (Manhattan)">Broadway</a> on the west. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Mountain_Meadows_Massacre" title="Mountain Meadows Massacre">Mountain Meadows Massacre</a> (<small>1857 massacre of California-bound emigrants by Mormon militiamen</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Mountain Meadows Massacre was a series of attacks which resulted in the <a href="/wiki/Mass_murder" title="Mass murder">mass murder</a> of 120 members of the <a href="/wiki/Baker%E2%80%93Fancher_party" title="Baker–Fancher party">Baker–Fancher</a> emigrant <a href="/wiki/Wagon_train" title="Wagon train">wagon train</a>. The massacre occurred September 7–11, 1857 at <a href="/wiki/Mountain_Meadows,_Utah" class="mw-redirect" title="Mountain Meadows, Utah">Mountain Meadows</a> in southern <a href="/wiki/Utah" title="Utah">Utah</a>, and was perpetrated by <a href="/wiki/Mormon" class="mw-redirect" title="Mormon">Mormon</a> settlers belonging to the Utah Territorial Militia (officially called the <a href="/wiki/Nauvoo_Legion" title="Nauvoo Legion">Nauvoo Legion</a>), together with some <a href="/wiki/Southern_Paiute_people" title="Southern Paiute people">Southern Paiute</a> <a href="/wiki/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States" title="Native Americans in the United States">Native Americans</a>. </td>

         <td>The Center Square/Hudson–Park Historic District is located between <a href="/wiki/Empire_State_Plaza" title="Empire State Plaza">Empire State Plaza</a> and <a href="/wiki/Washington_Park_Historic_District_(Albany,_New_York)" title="Washington Park Historic District (Albany, New York)">Washington Park</a> in <a href="/wiki/Albany,_New_York" title="Albany, New York">Albany</a>, New York, United States. It is a 27-<a href="/wiki/City_block" title="City block">block</a>, 99-acre (40&nbsp;ha) area taking in both the <a href="/wiki/Neighborhoods_of_Albany,_New_York#Center_Square" title="Neighborhoods of Albany, New York">Center Square</a> and <a href="/wiki/Neighborhoods_of_Albany,_New_York#Hudson/Park" title="Neighborhoods of Albany, New York">Hudson/Park</a> neighborhoods, and <a href="/wiki/Lark_Street" title="Lark Street">Lark Street</a> on the west. In 1980 it was recognized as a <a href="/wiki/Historic_district_(United_States)" class="mw-redirect" title="Historic district (United States)">historic district</a> and listed on the <a href="/wiki/National_Register_of_Historic_Places" title="National Register of Historic Places">National Register of Historic Places</a>. </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-27 08:04 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Tennessee" title="Tennessee">Tennessee</a> (<small>State of the United States of America</small>) </td> 
         <td>Tennessee (, ), officially the State of Tennessee, is a <a href="/wiki/U.S._state" title="U.S. state">state</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Southeastern_United_States" title="Southeastern United States">Southeastern</a> region of the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>. Tennessee is the <a href="/wiki/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_area" title="List of U.S. states and territories by area">36th largest</a> by area and the <a href="/wiki/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_population" class="mw-redirect" title="List of U.S. states and territories by population">16th most populous</a> of the <a href="/wiki/List_of_U.S._states" class="mw-redirect" title="List of U.S. states">50 states</a>. It is bordered by eight states, with <a href="/wiki/Kentucky" title="Kentucky">Kentucky</a> to the north, <a href="/wiki/Virginia" title="Virginia">Virginia</a> to the northeast, <a href="/wiki/North_Carolina" title="North Carolina">North Carolina</a> to the east, <a href="/wiki/Georgia_(U.S._state)" title="Georgia (U.S. state)">Georgia</a>, <a href="/wiki/Alabama" title="Alabama">Alabama</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Mississippi" title="Mississippi">Mississippi</a> to the south, <a href="/wiki/Arkansas" title="Arkansas">Arkansas</a> to the west, and <a href="/wiki/Missouri" title="Missouri">Missouri</a> to the northwest. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Bneu2013" title="User:Bneu2013">Bneu2013</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Bneu2013" title="User talk:Bneu2013">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Statue_of_Jefferson_Davis_(U.S._Capitol)" title="Statue of Jefferson Davis (U.S. Capitol)">Statue of Jefferson Davis (U.S. Capitol)</a> (<small>Statue of Jefferson Davis by Henry Augustus Lukeman in Washington, D.C., U.S.</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Jefferson Davis</i> is a <a href="/wiki/Bronze_sculpture" title="Bronze sculpture">bronze sculpture</a> of <a href="/wiki/Jefferson_Davis" title="Jefferson Davis">Jefferson Davis</a>, a <a href="/wiki/List_of_United_States_senators_from_Mississippi" title="List of United States senators from Mississippi">US Senator</a>, <a href="/wiki/United_States_Secretary_of_War" title="United States Secretary of War">US Secretary of War</a>, <a href="/wiki/Plantation_complexes_in_the_Southern_United_States#Plantation_owner" title="Plantation complexes in the Southern United States">plantation owner</a> and the only <a href="/wiki/President_of_the_Confederate_States_of_America" title="President of the Confederate States of America">President of the Confederate States of America</a>, by <a href="/wiki/Henry_Augustus_Lukeman" title="Henry Augustus Lukeman">Henry Augustus Lukeman</a>.          <td><a href="/wiki/Bean_Station,_Tennessee" title="Bean Station, Tennessee">Bean Station, Tennessee</a> (<small>Lakeside town in Grainger and Hawkins counties, Tennessee</small>) </td> 
         <td>Bean Station is a town in <a href="/wiki/Grainger_County,_Tennessee" title="Grainger County, Tennessee">Grainger</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hawkins_County,_Tennessee" title="Hawkins County, Tennessee">Hawkins</a> counties in the state of <a href="/wiki/Tennessee" title="Tennessee">Tennessee</a>, United States. As of the <a href="/wiki/2010_United_States_Census" class="mw-redirect" title="2010 United States Census">2010 census</a>, the population was 2,826, and was estimated to be 3,113 in 2019. Settled in 1776, it is considered to be one of the earliest settled communities in Tennessee. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:AppalachianCentrist" title="User:AppalachianCentrist">AppalachianCentrist</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:AppalachianCentrist" title="User talk:AppalachianCentrist">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Statue_of_James_S._T._Stranahan" title="Statue of James S. T. Stranahan">Statue of James S. T. Stranahan</a> (<small>Statue of James S. T. Stranahan in Brooklyn, New York, U.S.</small>) </td> 
         <td>A <a href="/wiki/Statue" title="Statue">statue</a> of <a href="/wiki/James_S._T._Stranahan" title="James S. T. Stranahan">James S. T. Stranahan</a> stands in <a href="/wiki/Brooklyn" title="Brooklyn">Brooklyn</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Prospect_Park_(Brooklyn)" title="Prospect Park (Brooklyn)">Prospect Park</a> in New York City. Designed by sculptor <a href="/wiki/Frederick_William_MacMonnies" title="Frederick William MacMonnies">Frederick William MacMonnies</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Bronze" title="Bronze">bronze</a> statue honors Stranahan, a businessman from Brooklyn who served on the city's park commission and was instrumental in the creation of Prospect Park. It was dedicated in 1891 and stands near the park's entrance at <a href="/wiki/Grand_Army_Plaza" title="Grand Army Plaza">Grand Army Plaza</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Socrates_Nelson" title="Socrates Nelson">Socrates Nelson</a> (<small>American politician (1814–1867)</small>) </td> 
         <td>Socrates Nelson (January 11, 1814 – May 6, 1867) was an American businessman, politician, and pioneer who served one term as a <a href="/wiki/Minnesota_Senate" title="Minnesota Senate">Minnesota state senator</a> from 1859 to 1861. He was heavily involved in the community of early <a href="/wiki/Stillwater,_Minnesota" title="Stillwater, Minnesota">Stillwater</a>, being a founding member of the first <a href="/wiki/Independent_Order_of_Odd_Fellows" title="Independent Order of Odd Fellows">Independent Order of Odd Fellows</a> lodge in Minnesota as well one of the earliest members of the <a href="/wiki/Minnesota_Historical_Society" title="Minnesota Historical Society">Minnesota Historical Society</a>. </td>

         <td>Frances Spatz Ornstein Leighton (September 4, 1919&nbsp;– April 6, 2007) was an American author best known for her <a href="/wiki/Ghostwriting" class="mw-redirect" title="Ghostwriting">ghostwriting</a> of accounts of Washington, D.C., life. Leighton wrote or ghostwrote over 30 books, including <i><a href="/wiki/My_Thirty_Years_Backstairs_at_the_White_House" title="My Thirty Years Backstairs at the White House">My Thirty Years Backstairs at the White House</a></i> (1961) and <i><a href="/wiki/My_Life_with_Jacqueline_Kennedy" title="My Life with Jacqueline Kennedy">My Life with Jacqueline Kennedy</a></i> (1969). </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-29 02:34 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Pacific_Salmon_War" title="Pacific Salmon War">Pacific Salmon War</a> (<small>1990s fishing dispute between American and Canadian fishers</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Pacific Salmon War was a period of heightened tensions between <a href="/wiki/Canada" title="Canada">Canada</a> and the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> over the <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Salmon" class="mw-redirect" title="Pacific Salmon">Pacific Salmon</a> catch. It began in 1992 after the first <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Salmon_Treaty" class="mw-redirect" title="Pacific Salmon Treaty">Pacific Salmon Treaty</a>, which had been ratified in 1985, expired, and lasted until a new agreement was signed in 1999. Disagreements were high in 1994, when a transit fee was set on American fishing vessels using the <a href="/wiki/Inside_Passage" title="Inside Passage">Inside Passage</a> and a ferry was blockaded by fishing boats in <a href="/wiki/Friday_Harbor,_Washington" title="Friday Harbor, Washington">Friday Harbor, Washington</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Eddie891" title="User:Eddie891">Eddie891</a> <small><i><sup> <a href="/wiki/User_talk:Eddie891" title="User talk:Eddie891">Talk</a></sup> <sub><a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/Eddie891" title="Special:Contributions/Eddie891">Work</a></sub></i> </small> </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Lilly_Dach%C3%A9" title="Lilly Daché">Lilly Daché</a> </td> 
         <td>Lilly Daché {1892 – 31 December 1989) was a French-born American <a href="/wiki/Hatmaking" title="Hatmaking">milliner</a> and fashion merchandiser. She started her career in a small bonnet shop, advanced to being a sales lady at <a href="/wiki/Macy%27s" title="Macy's">Macy's</a> department store, and from there started her own <a href="/wiki/Haberdasher" title="Haberdasher">hat business</a>. She was at the peak of her business career in the 1930s and 1940s. </td>

         <td>John Mason Loomis (January 5, 1825 – August 2, 1900) was a nineteenth-century American businessman and <a href="/wiki/Lumber_tycoon" class="mw-redirect" title="Lumber tycoon">lumber tycoon</a> from Chicago who was known for developing the city of <a href="/wiki/Ludington,_Michigan" title="Ludington, Michigan">Ludington, Michigan</a>.          <td>Therapy was a bilevel <a href="/wiki/Gay_bar" title="Gay bar">gay bar</a> and nightclub in the <a href="/wiki/Hell%27s_Kitchen,_Manhattan" title="Hell's Kitchen, Manhattan">Hell's Kitchen</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. He joined with <a href="/wiki/William_Edward_Sawyer" class="mw-redirect" title="William Edward Sawyer">William Edward Sawyer</a> in 1878 to start a company pertaining to incandescent electric lamp development and electric power distribution. </td>

         <td>689 Fifth Avenue (originally the Aeolian Building and later the Elizabeth Arden Building) is a commercial building in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>, at the northeast corner of <a href="/wiki/Fifth_Avenue" title="Fifth Avenue">Fifth Avenue</a> and <a href="/wiki/54th_Street_(Manhattan)" title="54th Street (Manhattan)">54th Street</a>.          <td><a href="/wiki/Rockefeller_Apartments" title="Rockefeller Apartments">Rockefeller Apartments</a> (<small>Residential building in Manhattan, New York</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Rockefeller Apartments is a residential building at 17 West <a href="/wiki/54th_Street_(Manhattan)" title="54th Street (Manhattan)">54th Street</a> and 24 West <a href="/wiki/55th_Street_(Manhattan)" title="55th Street (Manhattan)">55th Street</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Midtown_Manhattan" title="Midtown Manhattan">Midtown Manhattan</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. André Fouilhoux</a> in the <a href="/wiki/International_Style_(architecture)" title="International Style (architecture)">International Style</a>, the Rockefeller Apartments was constructed between 1935 and 1936. The complex was originally designed with 138 apartments. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Battle_of_Byram%27s_Ford" title="Battle of Byram's Ford">Battle of Byram's Ford</a> </td> 
         <td>The Battle of Byram's Ford, (also known as the Battle of Big Blue River and the Battle of the Blue) was fought on October 22 and 23, 1864, during <a href="/wiki/Price%27s_Raid" class="mw-redirect" title="Price's Raid">Price's Raid</a>, a campaign of the <a href="/wiki/American_Civil_War" title="American Civil War">American Civil War</a>. With the <a href="/wiki/Confederate_States_of_America" title="Confederate States of America">Confederate States of America</a> collapsing, <a href="/wiki/Major_General_(CSA)" class="mw-redirect" title="Major General (CSA)">Major General</a> <a href="/wiki/Sterling_Price" title="Sterling Price">Sterling Price</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Confederate_States_Army" title="Confederate States Army">Confederate States Army</a> conducted an invasion of the state of <a href="/wiki/Missouri" title="Missouri">Missouri</a> in late 1864. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Hog_Farm" title="User:Hog Farm">Hog Farm</a> <sub> <a href="/wiki/User_talk:Hog_Farm" title="User talk:Hog Farm">Talk</a></sub> </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="undefined">[Failed to parse] </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/In_God_We_Trust" title="In God We Trust">In God We Trust</a> (<small>Official motto of the United States</small>) </td> 
         <td>"In God We Trust" (sometimes rendered "In God we trust") is the <a href="/wiki/United_States_national_motto" title="United States national motto">official motto</a> of the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> and of the <a href="/wiki/U.S._state" title="U.S. state">U.S. state</a> of <a href="/wiki/Florida" title="Florida">Florida</a>. It was adopted by the U.S. Congress in 1956, replacing <i><a href="/wiki/E_pluribus_unum" title="E pluribus unum">E pluribus unum</a></i>, which had been the <a href="/wiki/De_facto" title="De facto">de facto</a> motto since the initial 1776 design of the <a href="/wiki/Great_Seal_of_the_United_States" title="Great Seal of the United States">Great Seal of the United States</a>. </td> 
         <td>[Failed to parse] </td>

Gallardo began his career in the club's youth divisions, and made his debut in the <a href="/wiki/Argentine_Primera_Divisi%C3%B3n" title="Argentine Primera División">Argentine Primera División</a> at age 17 in 1993. After a six-year period in which he won five local league championships, the <a href="/wiki/1996_Copa_Libertadores" title="1996 Copa Libertadores">1996 Copa Libertadores</a> and the <a href="/wiki/1997_Supercopa_Libertadores" title="1997 Supercopa Libertadores">1997 Supercopa Libertadores</a>, he transferred to France's <a href="/wiki/Ligue_1" title="Ligue 1">Ligue 1</a> <a href="/wiki/AS_Monaco_FC" title="AS Monaco FC">AS Monaco FC</a> and was named French League Footballer of the Year in 2000. </td>

         <td>The Pemon conflict is an ongoing conflict which is a part of the wider <a href="/wiki/Crisis_in_Venezuela" title="Crisis in Venezuela">Crisis in Venezuela</a>. The conflict is centered around mining disputes between the Maduro regime, the <a href="/wiki/Pemon" title="Pemon">Pemon</a> nation, and armed irregular groups. The Pemon nation is divided by the border between Venezuela and Brazil, resulting in Pemon refugees regularly crossing the border into Brazil for safety and medical care. </td>

Bush">George W. Bush</a> during an Iraqi press conference. Bush quickly ducked, avoiding being hit by either of the shoes. The city has a population of 291,667 (as of 2020). Palangka Raya is the largest city by land area in Indonesia. Most of the area is forested (including protected forests, nature conservation areas, and Tangkiling Forest). </td>

         <td>Anushtegin Gharchai (also spelled Anush-Tegin; <a href="/wiki/Persian_language" title="Persian language">Persian</a>: <span lang="fa" dir="rtl"><span class="Nastaliq" dir="rtl" title="Nastaliq" style="font-family: 'Jameel Noori Nastaleeq', 'Urdu Typesetting', 'Noto Nastaliq Urdu', 'Noto Nastaliq Urdu Draft', 'Hussaini Nastaleeq', 'AlQalam Taj Nastaleeq', IranNastaliq, 'Awami Nastaliq', 'Awami Nastaliq Beta3', 'Awami Nastaliq Beta2', 'Awami Nastaliq Beta1', 'Nafees Nastaleeq', 'Nafees Nastaleeq v1.01', 'Pak Nastaleeq', 'PDMS_Jauhar', 'Alvi Lahori Nastaleeq'; font-size: 110%; font-style: normal;">??????? ????</span></span>?, <small><a href="/wiki/Romanization_of_Persian" title="Romanization of Persian">romanized</a>:&nbsp;</small><i lang="fa-Latn" title="Persian-language romanization">An?štigin ?a??a??</i>; died 1097) was a <a href="/wiki/Turkic_peoples" title="Turkic peoples">Turkic</a> slave commander (<i lang="ar" title="Arabic-language text"><a href="/wiki/Ghilman" title="Ghilman">ghulam</a></i>) of the <a href="/wiki/Seljuk_Empire" title="Seljuk Empire">Seljuks</a> and the governor of <a href="/wiki/Khwarazm" title="Khwarazm">Khwarazm</a> from approximately 1077 until 1097. He was the first member of his family to rule Khwarazm, and the <a href="/wiki/Anushtegin_dynasty" title="Anushtegin dynasty">namesake for the dynasty</a> that would <a href="/wiki/Khwarazmian_Empire" title="Khwarazmian Empire">rule the province</a> in the 12th and early 13th centuries. </td>

Farm?nfarm?</i>; 26 August 1789 – 16 January 1835) was the fifth son of <a href="/wiki/Fath-Ali_Shah_Qajar" title="Fath-Ali Shah Qajar">Fath-Ali Shah</a> (<span style="white-space:nowrap;"><abbr title="reigned">r</abbr>.&nbsp;</span>1797–1834), governor of <a href="/wiki/Fars_Province" title="Fars Province">Fars</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Pretender" title="Pretender">pretender</a> to the throne of <a href="/wiki/Qajar_Iran" title="Qajar Iran">Qajar Iran</a>. </td>

         <td class="old">2021-02-05 15:16 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Ink_wash_painting" title="Ink wash painting">Ink wash painting</a> (<small>East Asian painting style using black ink of different concentrations</small>) </td> 
         <td>Ink wash painting is a type of <a href="/wiki/East_Asia" title="East Asia">East Asian</a> <a href="/wiki/Ink_brush" title="Ink brush">brush</a> <a href="/wiki/Painting" title="Painting">painting</a> that uses the same <a href="/wiki/Black_ink" class="mw-redirect" title="Black ink">black ink</a> used in <a href="/wiki/East_Asian_calligraphy" class="mw-redirect" title="East Asian calligraphy">East Asian calligraphy</a> in different concentrations. Emerging in <a href="/wiki/Tang_dynasty" title="Tang dynasty">Tang dynasty</a> China (618–907), it overturned earlier, more <a href="/wiki/Realism_(arts)" title="Realism (arts)">realistic</a> techniques. It is typically <a href="/wiki/Monochrome" title="Monochrome">monochrome</a>, using only shades of black, with a great emphasis on virtuoso brushwork and conveying the perceived "spirit" or "essence" of a subject over the direct <a href="/wiki/Mimesis" title="Mimesis">imitation</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Jujiang" title="User:Jujiang">Jujiang</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Jujiang" title="User talk:Jujiang">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td>Ni Yulan (<span lang="zh" title="Chinese-language text">???</span>, born 24 March 1960) is a civil rights lawyer in the <a href="/wiki/People%27s_Republic_of_China" class="mw-redirect" title="People's Republic of China">People's Republic of China</a>. She has established herself in defending <a href="/wiki/Weiquan_movement" title="Weiquan movement">human rights in China</a> by providing legal aid to persecuted groups such as <a href="/wiki/Persecution_of_Falun_Gong" title="Persecution of Falun Gong">Falun Gong</a> practitioners and victims of <a href="/wiki/Forced_eviction_(China)" class="mw-redirect" title="Forced eviction (China)">forced eviction</a>. </td>

         <td>The Khalili Imperial Garniture is a trio of <a href="/wiki/Cloisonn%C3%A9" title="Cloisonné">cloisonné</a> vases created for a <a href="/wiki/Japan" title="Japan">Japanese</a> Imperial commission during the <a href="/wiki/Meiji_(era)" title="Meiji (era)">Meiji era</a>.          <td><a href="/wiki/Edward_Hewitt_Nichols" title="Edward Hewitt Nichols">Edward Hewitt Nichols</a> (<small>British agriculture and aquaculture official</small>) </td> 
         <td>Edward Hewitt Nichols <span class="noexcerpt nowraplinks" style="font-size:85%;">CBE</span><small><sup class="reference" id="ref_anone"><a href="#endnote_anone">[?]</a></sup></small> (<a href="/wiki/Traditional_Chinese_characters" title="Traditional Chinese characters">Chinese</a>: <span lang="zh-Hant">???</span>, 29 December 1925 – 29 January 2016) was a British colonial <a href="/wiki/Agriculture" title="Agriculture">agriculture</a> and <a href="/wiki/Aquaculture" title="Aquaculture">aquaculture</a> official. Having served in <a href="/wiki/Sierra_Leone" title="Sierra Leone">Sierra Leone</a>, he then worked in <a href="/wiki/Hong_Kong" title="Hong Kong">Hong Kong</a>, where, from December 1965 to January 1980, he was the director of the territory's <a href="/wiki/Agriculture_and_Fisheries_Department" class="mw-redirect" title="Agriculture and Fisheries Department">Agriculture and Fisheries Department</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Japan_National_Route_119" title="Japan National Route 119">Japan National Route 119</a> (<small>National highway in Tochigi Prefecture, Japan</small>) </td> 
         <td>is a <a href="/wiki/National_highways_of_Japan" title="National highways of Japan">national highway</a> located entirely within <a href="/wiki/Tochigi_Prefecture" title="Tochigi Prefecture">Tochigi Prefecture</a>, <a href="/wiki/Japan" title="Japan">Japan</a>. It connects the city of <a href="/wiki/Nikk%C5%8D" title="Nikk?">Nikk?</a> to <a href="/wiki/Utsunomiya" title="Utsunomiya">Utsunomiya</a>, the prefecture's capital, and has a total length of 63.9 kilometers (39.7&nbsp;mi). The present-day highway largely follows the path of the <a href="/wiki/Nikk%C5%8D_Kaid%C5%8D" title="Nikk? Kaid?">Nikk? Kaid?</a>, an <a href="/wiki/Edo_period" title="Edo period">Edo period</a> <a href="/wiki/Kaid%C5%8D" title="Kaid?">road</a> that linked <a href="/wiki/Edo" title="Edo">Edo</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Shrines_and_Temples_of_Nikk%C5%8D" title="Shrines and Temples of Nikk?">Shrines and Temples of Nikk?</a> . </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Japanese_idol" title="Japanese idol">Japanese idol</a> (<small>Japanese type of entertainer</small>) </td> 
         <td>An idol<span style="font-weight: normal"> (<span lang="ja" title="Japanese-language text">????</span>, <i lang="ja-Latn" title="Hepburn transliteration">aidoru</i>)</span> is a type of entertainer manufactured and marketed for image, attractiveness, and personality in Japanese pop culture. Idols are primarily singers with training in acting, dancing, and modeling. Idols are commercialized through merchandise and endorsements by <a href="/wiki/Talent_agent" title="Talent agent">talent agencies</a>, while maintaining a <a href="/wiki/Parasocial_relationship" class="mw-redirect" title="Parasocial relationship">parasocial relationship</a> with a passionate consumer fan base. </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-20 01:02 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Ming_treasure_voyages" title="Ming treasure voyages">Ming treasure voyages</a> </td> 
         <td>The Ming treasure voyages were the seven maritime expeditions undertaken by <a href="/wiki/Ming_dynasty" title="Ming dynasty">Ming China</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Chinese_treasure_ship" title="Chinese treasure ship">treasure fleet</a> between 1405 and 1433. The <a href="/wiki/Yongle_Emperor" title="Yongle Emperor">Yongle Emperor</a> started building the treasure fleet in 1403. The grand project resulted in seven far-reaching ocean voyages to the coastal territories and islands in and around the <a href="/wiki/South_China_Sea" title="South China Sea">South China Sea</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Indian_Ocean" title="Indian Ocean">Indian Ocean</a>, and beyond. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Cold_Season" title="User:Cold Season">Cold Season</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Cold_Season" title="User talk:Cold Season">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Typhoon_Mujigae" title="Typhoon Mujigae">Typhoon Mujigae</a> (<small>Pacific typhoon in 2015</small>) </td> 
         <td>Typhoon Mujigae, known in the <a href="/wiki/Philippines" title="Philippines">Philippines</a> as Tropical Storm Kabayan, was the strongest <a href="/wiki/Typhoon" title="Typhoon">typhoon</a> to strike the province of <a href="/wiki/Guangdong" title="Guangdong">Guangdong</a> in the month of October and the costliest typhoon to impact <a href="/wiki/China" title="China">China</a> in 2015. The typhoon caused widespread damage in the Chinese provinces of Guangdong, <a href="/wiki/Guangxi" title="Guangxi">Guangxi</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Hainan" title="Hainan">Hainan</a> from October&nbsp;3 to 6, 2015; earlier in its existence it impacted the Philippines as a developing <a href="/wiki/Tropical_cyclone" title="Tropical cyclone">tropical cyclone</a>, and later on it brought heavy rain to <a href="/wiki/Thailand" title="Thailand">Thailand</a> and <a href="/wiki/Vietnam" title="Vietnam">Vietnam</a>. </td> 
         <td>~&nbsp;<a href="/wiki/User:KN2731" title="User:KN2731">KN2731</a> <small>{<a href="/wiki/User_talk:KN2731" title="User talk:KN2731">talk</a> · <a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/KN2731" title="Special:Contributions/KN2731">contribs</a>}</small> </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="new">2021-05-30 10:12 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Japanese_cruiser_Naniwa" title="Japanese cruiser Naniwa">Japanese cruiser Naniwa</a> </td> 
         <td>was the <a href="/wiki/Lead_ship" title="Lead ship">lead ship</a> of <a href="/wiki/Naniwa-class_cruiser" title="Naniwa-class cruiser">her class</a> of two <a href="/wiki/Protected_cruiser" title="Protected cruiser">protected cruisers</a> built for the <a href="/wiki/Imperial_Japanese_Navy" title="Imperial Japanese Navy">Imperial Japanese Navy</a> (IJN) in the 1880s. As Japan lacked the industrial capacity to construct such vessels, the ship was designed and built in the <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">United Kingdom</a>. She participated in the <a href="/wiki/First_Sino-Japanese_War" title="First Sino-Japanese War">First Sino-Japanese War</a> of 1894–1895, playing a major role in the <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_the_Yalu_River_(1894)" title="Battle of the Yalu River (1894)">Battle of the Yalu River</a> and lesser roles in the <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_L%C3%BCshunkou" title="Battle of Lüshunkou">Battles of Port Arthur</a>, <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_Weihaiwei" title="Battle of Weihaiwei">Weihaiwei</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Pescadores_Campaign_(1895)" class="mw-redirect" title="Pescadores Campaign (1895)">Pescadores Campaign</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Japanese_invasion_of_Taiwan_(1895)" title="Japanese invasion of Taiwan (1895)">invasion of Taiwan</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Sturmvogel_66" title="User:Sturmvogel 66">Sturmvogel 66</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Sturmvogel_66" title="User talk:Sturmvogel 66">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Shah_Abdul_Latif_Bhittai" title="Shah Abdul Latif Bhittai">Shah Abdul Latif Bhittai</a> (<small>18th-century Sufi writer</small>) </td> 
         <td>Shah Abdul Latif Bhittai (<a href="/wiki/Sindhi_language" title="Sindhi language">Sindhi</a>: <span lang="sd" dir="rtl">??? ????????? ?????</span>?, <a href="/wiki/Urdu_language" class="mw-redirect" title="Urdu language">Urdu</a>: <span lang="ur" dir="rtl"><span class="Nastaliq" dir="rtl" title="Nastaliq" style="font-family: 'Jameel Noori Nastaleeq', 'Urdu Typesetting', 'Noto Nastaliq Urdu', 'Noto Nastaliq Urdu Draft', 'Hussaini Nastaleeq', 'AlQalam Taj Nastaleeq', IranNastaliq, 'Awami Nastaliq', 'Awami Nastaliq Beta3', 'Awami Nastaliq Beta2', 'Awami Nastaliq Beta1', 'Nafees Nastaleeq', 'Nafees Nastaleeq v1.01', 'Pak Nastaleeq', 'PDMS_Jauhar', 'Alvi Lahori Nastaleeq'; font-size: 110%; font-style: normal;">??? ????????? ??????</span></span>?; 1689/1690 – 21 December 1752), commonly known by the honorifics <i>Lakhino Latif</i>, <i>Latif Ghot</i>, <i>Bhittai</i>, and <i>Bhit Jo Shah</i>, was a <a href="/wiki/Sindhi_people" class="mw-redirect" title="Sindhi people">Sindhi</a> <a href="/wiki/Sufi" class="mw-redirect" title="Sufi">Sufi</a> <a href="/wiki/Mysticism" title="Mysticism">mystic</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Poet" title="Poet">poet</a>, widely considered to be the greatest poet of the Sindhi language. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/2013%E2%80%9314_Victory_Day_T20_Cup" title="2013–14 Victory Day T20 Cup">2013–14 Victory Day T20 Cup</a> (<small>Twenty20 Cricket League</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 2013–14 Victory Day T20 Cup was a <a href="/wiki/Twenty20_cricket" class="mw-redirect" title="Twenty20 cricket">Twenty20 cricket</a> competition that was held in Bangladesh. It was played by four teams, during December 2013. Four <a href="/wiki/Dhaka_Premier_League" class="mw-redirect" title="Dhaka Premier League">Dhaka Premier League</a> teams took part in a lottery to determine who picked one each of the Yellow, Blue, Green and Red teams. Announcing the schedule of the tournament at a press conference on 21st of December, the <a href="/wiki/Bangladesh_Cricket_Board" title="Bangladesh Cricket Board">Bangladesh Cricket Board</a> (BCB) confirmed that four teams would participate in the T20 series and AMBER Group would be the title sponsors of the event. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Bengal_tiger" title="Bengal tiger">Bengal tiger</a> (<small>Tiger population in Indian subcontinent</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Bengal tiger is a <a href="/wiki/Tiger" title="Tiger">tiger</a> from a specific population of the <i><a href="/wiki/Panthera_tigris_tigris" title="Panthera tigris tigris">Panthera tigris tigris</a></i> subspecies that is native to the <a href="/wiki/Indian_subcontinent" title="Indian subcontinent">Indian subcontinent</a>. It is threatened by <a href="/wiki/Poaching" title="Poaching">poaching</a>, <a href="/wiki/Habitat_loss" class="mw-redirect" title="Habitat loss">loss</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Habitat_fragmentation" title="Habitat fragmentation">fragmentation</a> of habitat, and was estimated at comprising fewer than 2,500 wild individuals by 2011. None of the Tiger Conservation Landscapes within its range is considered large enough to support an effective population of more than 250 adult individuals. </td> 
         <td><span style="color:#006400">Rush922<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Rush922" title="User talk:Rush922">(talk)</a></span> </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Tala_tank" title="Tala tank">Tala tank</a> (<small>Water tower reservoir in Kolkata, India</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Tala tank or Tallah tank (), is a <a href="/wiki/Water_tower" title="Water tower">water tower</a> of <a href="/wiki/Kolkata_Municipal_Corporation" title="Kolkata Municipal Corporation">Kolkata Municipal Corporation</a> (KMC) situated in <a href="/wiki/Kolkata" title="Kolkata">Kolkata</a> in the <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">Indian</a> <a href="/wiki/States_and_territories_of_India" class="mw-redirect" title="States and territories of India">state</a> of <a href="/wiki/West_Bengal" title="West Bengal">West Bengal</a>. It was inaugurated in May 1911 by the <a href="/wiki/List_of_governors_of_Bengal_Presidency" title="List of governors of Bengal Presidency">Lieutenant Governor of Bengal</a>, after two years of construction. It is connected to the <a href="/wiki/Palta,_North_24_Parganas" title="Palta, North 24 Parganas">Palta</a> Water Works near <a href="/wiki/Barrackpore" title="Barrackpore">Barrackpore</a>. </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-17 18:25 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Vellar_River_(Northern_Tamil_Nadu)" title="Vellar River (Northern Tamil Nadu)">Vellar River (Northern Tamil Nadu)</a> </td> 
         <td>The Vellar River is a river in the <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">Indian</a> state of <a href="/wiki/Tamil_Nadu" title="Tamil Nadu">Tamil Nadu</a>. It originates in the <a href="/wiki/Kalrayan_Hills" title="Kalrayan Hills">Kalrayan Hills</a>, and flows generally eastward through <a href="/wiki/Salem_district" title="Salem district">Salem</a>, <a href="/wiki/Perambalur_district" title="Perambalur district">Perambalur</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Cuddalore_district" title="Cuddalore district">Cuddalore districts</a>, before flowing into the <a href="/wiki/Bay_of_Bengal" title="Bay of Bengal">Bay of Bengal</a> near <a href="/wiki/Parangipettai" title="Parangipettai">Parangipettai</a>. The river has a total length of 150 kilometres (93&nbsp;mi), and its drainage basin covers an area of 7,504.346 square kilometres (2,897.444&nbsp;sq&nbsp;mi) in Cuddalore, Perambalur, Salem, <a href="/wiki/Kallakurichi_district" title="Kallakurichi district">Kallakurichi</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ariyalur_district" title="Ariyalur district">Ariyalur</a>, <a href="/wiki/Namakkal_district" title="Namakkal district">Namakkal</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tiruchirappalli_district" title="Tiruchirappalli district">Tiruchirappalli</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Dharmapuri_district" title="Dharmapuri district">Dharmapuri districts</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Starkenborgher" title="User:Starkenborgher">Starkenborgher</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Starkenborgher" title="User talk:Starkenborgher">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Air_India_Express_Flight_1344" title="Air India Express Flight 1344">Air India Express Flight 1344</a> (<small>2020 plane crash in Kozhikode, India</small>) </td> 
         <td>Air India Express Flight 1344 was a scheduled international flight on 7 August 2020 from <a href="/wiki/Dubai" title="Dubai">Dubai</a>, United Arab Emirates, to <a href="/wiki/Kozhikode" title="Kozhikode">Kozhikode</a>, India, landing at <a href="/wiki/Calicut_International_Airport" title="Calicut International Airport">Calicut International Airport</a>. The flight was part of the <a href="/wiki/Vande_Bharat_Mission" class="mw-redirect" title="Vande Bharat Mission">Vande Bharat Mission</a> to repatriate Indian nationals stranded due to the <a href="/wiki/COVID-19_pandemic" title="COVID-19 pandemic">COVID-19 pandemic</a>. The flight crew <a href="/wiki/Go-around" title="Go-around">aborted two landing attempts</a> because of heavy rain and <a href="/wiki/Headwind_and_tailwind" title="Headwind and tailwind">tailwind</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Barrackpore_Trunk_Road" title="Barrackpore Trunk Road">Barrackpore Trunk Road</a> (<small>Road in Kolkata, India</small>) </td> 
         <td>Barrackpore Trunk Road, commonly known as BT Road, is a <a href="/wiki/Four-lane_undivided_expressway" class="mw-redirect" title="Four-lane undivided expressway">four</a> and six-lane <a href="/wiki/Trunk_road" title="Trunk road">trunk road</a> in <a href="/wiki/Kolkata_metropolitan_area" title="Kolkata metropolitan area">Kolkata metropolitan area</a>, <a href="/wiki/West_Bengal" title="West Bengal">West Bengal</a>, <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a>. It connects <a href="/wiki/Kolkata" title="Kolkata">Kolkata</a> with its suburb <a href="/wiki/Barrackpore" title="Barrackpore">Barrackpore</a>. Built in 1775, it is the oldest <a href="/wiki/Metalled_road" class="mw-redirect" title="Metalled road">metalled road</a> and one of the busiest roads in the country. The 18.1&nbsp;km (11.2&nbsp;mi) long road is a part of both <a href="/wiki/State_Highway_1_(West_Bengal)" title="State Highway 1 (West Bengal)">State Highway 1</a> and <a href="/wiki/State_Highway_2_(West_Bengal)" title="State Highway 2 (West Bengal)">State Highway 2</a>. </td>

         <td class="new">2021-06-05 16:42 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Asikni_(goddess)" title="Asikni (goddess)">Asikni (goddess)</a> (<small>Consort of the Hindu god Daksha</small>) </td> 
         <td>Asikni , also known as Panchajani and Virani, is a consort of <a href="/wiki/Daksha" title="Daksha">Daksha</a>, one of the <i><a href="/wiki/Prajapati_(title)" class="mw-redirect" title="Prajapati (title)">Prajapati</a></i> (agents of creation). Most legends describe her as the daughter of Virana or Panchajana and the mother of various children — 5000 Haryasvas, 1000 Sabalasvas and 60 daughters. Asikni is sometimes equated with Daksha's other wife named <a href="/wiki/Prasuti" title="Prasuti">Prasuti</a>, but many texts mention them as separate goddesses. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:245CMR" title="User:245CMR"><span style="background:maroon;border:solid 1px;border-radius:8px;">.<span style="color:yellow; background:maroon;"><i>245</i><b>CMR</b></span>.</span></a>•<sup><a href="/wiki/User_talk:245CMR" title="User talk:245CMR">?</a><a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/245CMR" title="Special:Contributions/245CMR">?</a></sup> </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Coronation_of_Mindon_Min" title="Coronation of Mindon Min">Coronation of Mindon Min</a> (<small>Initiation rite performed to crown Mindon Min of Burma in 1857</small>) </td> 
         <td>The <a href="/wiki/Coronation_of_the_Burmese_Monarch" title="Coronation of the Burmese Monarch">coronation</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/Abhisheka" title="Abhisheka">abhiseka</a></i>) of <a href="/wiki/Mindon_Min" title="Mindon Min">Mindon Min</a> and <a href="/wiki/Setkya_Dewi" title="Setkya Dewi">Setkya Dewi</a> as <a href="/wiki/List_of_Burmese_monarchs#Konbaung_(1752–1885)" title="List of Burmese monarchs">king</a> and <a href="/wiki/List_of_Burmese_royal_consorts#Konbaung_Dynasty" title="List of Burmese royal consorts">queen</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Konbaung_Kingdom" class="mw-redirect" title="Konbaung Kingdom">Konbaung Kingdom</a> took place at <a href="/wiki/Mandalay_Palace" title="Mandalay Palace">Mandalay Palace</a> on 14 May 1857. Mindon Min ascended the throne upon the abdication of his half brother, <a href="/wiki/Pagan_Min" title="Pagan Min">Pagan Min</a>, on 18 February 1853. Similar to other southeast Asian traditions, the coronation ceremony was a mix of <a href="/wiki/Hinduism_in_Southeast_Asia" title="Hinduism in Southeast Asia">Hindu</a> and Buddhist cultures in which <i>Punna</i> (<a href="/wiki/Brahmin#Outside_India:_Myanmar,_Thailand,_Cambodia,_Vietnam_and_Indonesia" title="Brahmin">Brahmins</a>) played significant roles. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Zin_Win_Hlaing" title="User:Zin Win Hlaing">Zin Win Hlaing</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Zin_Win_Hlaing" title="User talk:Zin Win Hlaing">talk</a>) </td>

Situated along Pasir Ris Central adjacent to <a href="/wiki/Pasir_Ris_Bus_Interchange" title="Pasir Ris Bus Interchange">Pasir Ris Bus Interchange</a> and the <a href="/wiki/White_Sands_Shopping_Mall,_Singapore" title="White Sands Shopping Mall, Singapore">White Sands</a> shopping centre, it is the eastern terminus of the EWL and currently the only MRT station within Pasir Ris. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Esplanade_MRT_station" title="Esplanade MRT station">Esplanade MRT station</a> (<small>MRT station in Singapore</small>) </td> 
         <td>Esplanade MRT station is an underground <a href="/wiki/Mass_Rapid_Transit_(Singapore)" title="Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)">Mass Rapid Transit</a> (MRT) station on the <a href="/wiki/Circle_MRT_line" title="Circle MRT line">Circle line</a> (CCL). Situated in <a href="/wiki/Downtown_Core" title="Downtown Core">Downtown Core</a>, <a href="/wiki/Singapore" title="Singapore">Singapore</a>, it is at the junction of <a href="/wiki/Bras_Basah_Road" title="Bras Basah Road">Bras Basah Road</a>, Raffles Boulevard and <a href="/wiki/Nicoll_Highway" title="Nicoll Highway">Nicoll Highway</a>. As the name suggests, the station serves the <a href="/wiki/Esplanade_%E2%80%93_Theatres_on_the_Bay" title="Esplanade – Theatres on the Bay">Esplanade</a>, alongside various developments such as <a href="/wiki/War_Memorial_Park,_Singapore" title="War Memorial Park, Singapore">War Memorial Park</a>, <a href="/wiki/Suntec_City_Mall" class="mw-redirect" title="Suntec City Mall">Suntec City Mall</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Suntec_Singapore_Convention_and_Exhibition_Centre" title="Suntec Singapore Convention and Exhibition Centre">Suntec Singapore Convention and Exhibition Centre</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Energy_in_Turkey" title="Energy in Turkey">Energy in Turkey</a> (<small>Overview of the production, consumption, import and export of energy and electricity in Turkey</small>) </td> 
         <td>Consumption of energy in Turkey is around the <a href="/wiki/List_of_countries_by_energy_consumption_per_capita" title="List of countries by energy consumption per capita">world average</a> of about seventy <a href="/wiki/Gigajoules" class="mw-redirect" title="Gigajoules">gigajoules</a> (GJ) per person per year. In total, Turkey <a href="/wiki/World_energy_consumption" title="World energy consumption">uses</a> about six billion GJ of <a href="/wiki/Primary_energy" title="Primary energy">primary energy</a> per year: over 80% from <a href="/wiki/Fossil_fuels" class="mw-redirect" title="Fossil fuels">fossil fuels</a>. From 1990 to 2017 annual primary energy supply tripled, but then remained constant to 2019. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Chidgk1" title="User:Chidgk1">Chidgk1</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Chidgk1" title="User talk:Chidgk1">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="old">2021-02-11 19:15 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Climate_change_in_Turkey" title="Climate change in Turkey">Climate change in Turkey</a> (<small>Impact of global warming on Turkey and adaptation to it</small>) </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Climate_change" title="Climate change">Climate change</a> in <a href="/wiki/Turkey" title="Turkey">Turkey</a> includes changes in the <a href="/wiki/Climate_of_Turkey" title="Climate of Turkey">climate of Turkey</a>, <a href="/wiki/Effects_of_climate_change" title="Effects of climate change">their effects</a> and how the country is <a href="/wiki/Climate_change_adaptation" title="Climate change adaptation">adapting to those changes</a>. Turkey's annual and maximum temperatures are rising, and 2020 was the third hottest year on record. Turkey will be greatly affected by climate change,<sup class="reference" style="white-space:nowrap;">:<span>7</span></sup> and is already experiencing more extreme weather, with <a href="/wiki/Drought" title="Drought">droughts</a> and <a href="/wiki/Heat_wave" title="Heat wave">heatwaves</a> being the main hazards. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Chidgk1" title="User:Chidgk1">Chidgk1</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Chidgk1" title="User talk:Chidgk1">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="old">2021-02-12 09:35 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Electricity_sector_in_Turkey" title="Electricity sector in Turkey">Electricity sector in Turkey</a> (<small>Electricity generation, transmission and consumption in Turkey</small>) </td> 
         <td>Each year, about<span class="nowrap">&nbsp;</span>300 <a href="/wiki/Kilowatt-hour#Watt-hour_multiples" title="Kilowatt-hour">terawatt-hours (TWh)</a> of <a href="/wiki/Electricity" title="Electricity">electricity</a> is used in <a href="/wiki/Turkey" title="Turkey">Turkey</a>—a fifth of the <a href="/wiki/Energy_in_Turkey" title="Energy in Turkey">energy used</a> and about 3 kilowatt-hours (kWh) per person per day. The <a href="/wiki/Carbon_intensity" class="mw-redirect" title="Carbon intensity">carbon intensity</a> of generation during the 2010s was about 400 grams of <a href="/wiki/Carbon_dioxide" title="Carbon dioxide">CO<sub>2</sub></a> per kWh (gCO<sub>2</sub>/kWh), slightly less than the global average. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Chidgk1" title="User:Chidgk1">Chidgk1</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Chidgk1" title="User talk:Chidgk1">talk</a>) </td>

         <td>Arab Christians (<a href="/wiki/Arabic_language" class="mw-redirect" title="Arabic language">Arabic</a>: <span lang="ar" dir="rtl">????????? ?????</span>? <i>al-Mas??iyy?n al-?Arab</i>) are <a href="/wiki/Christianity" title="Christianity">Arabs</a> who follow <a href="/wiki/Christianity" title="Christianity">Christianity</a>. The largest group who self-identify as Arabs are <a href="/wiki/Antiochian_Greek_Christians" title="Antiochian Greek Christians">Antiochian Greek Christians</a>, who are estimated to number between 520,000–703,000 in <a href="/wiki/Syria" title="Syria">Syria</a>, 350,000 in <a href="/wiki/Lebanon" title="Lebanon">Lebanon</a>, 221,000 in <a href="/wiki/Jordan" title="Jordan">Jordan</a>, 133,130 in <a href="/wiki/Israel" title="Israel">Israel</a> and 50,000 in the <a href="/wiki/State_of_Palestine" title="State of Palestine">State of Palestine</a>. </td>

         <td>Abdollah Mirza Qajar (<a href="/wiki/Persian_language" title="Persian language">Persian</a>: <span lang="fa" dir="rtl">??????? ??????? ????? ?????</span>?; 25 November 1796 – 18 June 1846) was a <a href="/wiki/Qajar_dynasty" title="Qajar dynasty">Qajar</a> prince of the <a href="/wiki/Shahzada_(title)" class="mw-redirect" title="Shahzada (title)">shahzadeh</a> title and the 11th son of <a href="/wiki/Fath-Ali_Shah_Qajar" title="Fath-Ali Shah Qajar">Fath-Ali Shah</a>, king of <a href="/wiki/Qajar_Iran" title="Qajar Iran">Qajar Iran</a> from 1797 to 1834. Abdollah was the governor of the states <a href="/wiki/Zanjan_Province" title="Zanjan Province">Zanjan</a> and <a href="/wiki/Khamseh" title="Khamseh">Khamseh</a>. He had two children with his wife, Mohsen Mirza and Shams al-Molok. </td>

         <td>The Palestinian enclaves are proposed areas in the <a href="/wiki/West_Bank" title="West Bank">West Bank</a> designated for <a href="/wiki/Palestinians" title="Palestinians">Palestinians</a> under a variety of <a href="/wiki/Israeli%E2%80%93Palestinian_peace_process" title="Israeli–Palestinian peace process">US and Israeli-led proposals</a> to end the <a href="/wiki/Israeli-Palestinian_conflict" class="mw-redirect" title="Israeli-Palestinian conflict">Israeli-Palestinian conflict</a>. By way of the <a href="/wiki/Israel_and_the_apartheid_analogy" title="Israel and the apartheid analogy">popular comparison</a> between Israel and <a href="/wiki/Apartheid" title="Apartheid">apartheid</a>-era <a href="/wiki/South_Africa" title="South Africa">South Africa</a>, the enclaves are also referred to as <a href="/wiki/Bantustan" title="Bantustan">bantustans</a> and figuratively as the Palestinian archipelago, among other terms. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Lev_Levanda" title="Lev Levanda">Lev Levanda</a> (<small>Russian author (1935-1888)</small>) </td> 
         <td>Lev (Yehuda Leyb) Osipovitch Levanda (Russian: <span lang="ru">??? ???????? ???????</span>, <a href="/wiki/Yiddish_language" class="mw-redirect" title="Yiddish language">Yiddish</a>: <span lang="yi" dir="rtl">????? ???? ?????????</span>?; June 1835 – 18 June 1888) was a Russian author, <a href="/wiki/Belles-lettres" title="Belles-lettres">belletrist</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Publication" title="Publication">publicist</a>. His literary work made him a leading figure in the circles of the Russian-Jewish intelligentsia. Originally a vocal proponent of the <a href="/wiki/Jewish_assimilation" title="Jewish assimilation">assimilation of Jews</a> into Russian culture, Levanda became a strong supporter of their <a href="/wiki/Aliyah" title="Aliyah">emigration</a> to <a href="/wiki/Palestine_(region)" title="Palestine (region)">Palestine</a> following the <a href="/wiki/Anti-Jewish_pogroms_in_the_Russian_Empire#1881–84" class="mw-redirect" title="Anti-Jewish pogroms in the Russian Empire">1881–82 pogroms</a> across the <a href="/wiki/Russian_Empire" title="Russian Empire">Russian Empire</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Kyuko" title="User:Kyuko">Kyuko</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Kyuko" title="User talk:Kyuko">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Callimachus" title="Callimachus">Callimachus</a> (<small>Ancient poet and librarian</small>) </td> 
         <td>Callimachus was an <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greek" title="Ancient Greek">ancient Greek</a> <a href="/wiki/Poet" title="Poet">poet</a>, <a href="/wiki/Scholar" title="Scholar">scholar</a> and <a href="/wiki/Librarian" title="Librarian">librarian</a> who was active in <a href="/wiki/Alexandria" title="Alexandria">Alexandria</a> during the 3rd century BC. A representative of <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greek_literature" title="Ancient Greek literature">Ancient Greek literature</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Hellenistic_period" title="Hellenistic period">Hellenistic period</a>, he wrote over 800 literary works in a wide variety of genres, most of which did not survive. He espoused an <a href="/wiki/Aesthetic_philosophy" class="mw-redirect" title="Aesthetic philosophy">aesthetic philosophy</a>, known as Callimacheanism, which exerted a strong influence on the poets of the <a href="/wiki/Roman_Empire" title="Roman Empire">Roman Empire</a> and, through them, on all subsequent <a href="/wiki/Western_canon" title="Western canon">Western literature</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Modussiccandi" title="User:Modussiccandi">Modussiccandi</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Modussiccandi" title="User talk:Modussiccandi">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/William_A._Robson" title="William A. Robson">William A. Robson</a> </td> 
         <td>William Alexander Robson (14 July 1895 – 12 May 1980) was a British academic who was an early and influential scholar of public administration while serving as a lecturer and professor at the <a href="/wiki/London_School_of_Economics" title="London School of Economics">London School of Economics</a>. Upon his death, <i><a href="/wiki/The_Guardian" title="The Guardian">The Guardian</a></i> wrote that Robson was an "internationally renowned authority on public administration". </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Synge_Street_CBS" title="Synge Street CBS">Synge Street CBS</a> (<small>Christian Brothers-founded school in Dublin, Ireland</small>) </td> 
         <td>Synge Street CBS&nbsp;(colloquially&nbsp;Synger) is a boys'&nbsp;non-fee-paying state school, under the auspices of the <a href="/wiki/Edmund_Rice_Schools_Trust" title="Edmund Rice Schools Trust">Edmund Rice Schools Trust</a>, located in the&nbsp;<a href="/wiki/Dublin_8" class="mw-redirect" title="Dublin 8">Dublin 8</a> area of&nbsp;Dublin, Ireland. The school was founded in 1864 by Canon <a href="/wiki/Edward_McCabe_(bishop)" class="mw-redirect" title="Edward McCabe (bishop)">Edward McCabe</a> and Brother Edward O’Flaherty, as part of a mid-nineteenth century programme to expand the provision of Catholic schooling across the city, particularly for poorer boys. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Fob.schools" class="mw-redirect" title="User:Fob.schools">Fob.schools</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Fob.schools" title="User talk:Fob.schools">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Russian_language_in_Latvia" title="Russian language in Latvia">Russian language in Latvia</a> </td> 
         <td>The <a href="/wiki/Russian_language" title="Russian language">Russian language</a> in <a href="/wiki/Latvia" title="Latvia">Latvia</a> is the second most commonly used <a href="/wiki/First_language" title="First language">language at home</a> (37.2% in the 2011 <a href="/wiki/Census" title="Census">census</a>) and 26.9% of the <a href="/wiki/Demographics_of_Latvia" title="Demographics of Latvia">population</a> were <a href="/wiki/Ethnic_Russian" class="mw-redirect" title="Ethnic Russian">ethnic Russians</a> (2011). </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1987_Football_League_Third_Division_play-off_Final" title="1987 Football League Third Division play-off Final">1987 Football League Third Division play-off Final</a> (<small>Football match</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 1987 Football League Third Division play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match contested by <a href="/wiki/Gillingham_F.C." title="Gillingham F.C.">Gillingham</a> and <a href="/wiki/Swindon_Town_F.C." title="Swindon Town F.C.">Swindon Town</a> over <a href="/wiki/Two-legged_tie" title="Two-legged tie">two legs</a> on 22 May 1987 and 25 May 1987 to determine which club would play the next season in the <a href="/wiki/1987%E2%80%9388_Football_League#Second_Division" title="1987–88 Football League">Second Division</a>. Gillingham had finished in fifth place in the <a href="/wiki/1986%E2%80%9387_Football_League#Third_Division" title="1986–87 Football League">Third Division</a> while Swindon finished third. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:ChrisTheDude" title="User:ChrisTheDude">ChrisTheDude</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:ChrisTheDude" title="User talk:ChrisTheDude">talk</a>) </td>

         <td class="recent">2021-04-02 18:17 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/1959%E2%80%9360_Burnley_F.C._season" title="1959–60 Burnley F.C. season">1959–60 Burnley F.C. season</a> (<small>Burnley 1959–60 football season</small>) </td> 
         <td>The <a href="/wiki/1959%E2%80%9360_in_English_football" title="1959–60 in English football">1959–60 season</a> was <a href="/wiki/Burnley_F.C." title="Burnley F.C.">Burnley</a>'s <a href="/wiki/List_of_Burnley_F.C._seasons" title="List of Burnley F.C. seasons">61st season</a> in the <a href="/wiki/English_Football_League" title="English Football League">Football League</a>, and their 13th consecutive campaign in the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_First_Division" title="Football League First Division">First Division</a>. Managed by <a href="/wiki/Harry_Potts" title="Harry Potts">Harry Potts</a>, the team endured a tense season, in which <a href="/wiki/Tottenham_Hotspur_F.C." title="Tottenham Hotspur F.C.">Tottenham Hotspur</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wolverhampton_Wanderers_F.C." title="Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.">Wolverhampton Wanderers</a> were the other protagonists for the league title. Burnley won their second <a href="/wiki/List_of_English_football_champions" title="List of English football champions">First Division championship</a>, and their first since <a href="/wiki/1920%E2%80%9321_Burnley_F.C._season" title="1920–21 Burnley F.C. season">1920–21</a>, on the last matchday with a 2–1 victory at <a href="/wiki/Manchester_City_F.C." title="Manchester City F.C.">Manchester City</a>; they had not topped the table until the last match was played out. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:WA8MTWAYC" title="User:WA8MTWAYC">WA8MTWAYC</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:WA8MTWAYC" title="User talk:WA8MTWAYC">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Peelian_principles" title="Peelian principles">Peelian principles</a> </td> 
         <td>The Peelian principles summarise the ideas that <a href="/wiki/Robert_Peel" title="Robert Peel">Sir Robert Peel</a> developed to define an <a href="/wiki/Criminal_justice_ethics" title="Criminal justice ethics">ethical police force</a>. The approach expressed in these principles is commonly known as policing by consent in the United Kingdom and other countries such as Canada, Australia and New Zealand. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1744_English_cricket_season" title="1744 English cricket season">1744 English cricket season</a> (<small>Cricket season review</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 1744 <a href="/wiki/Cricket" title="Cricket">cricket</a> season in England was pivotal in the sport's history because the earliest known codification of the <i><a href="/wiki/Laws_of_Cricket" title="Laws of Cricket">Laws of Cricket</a></i> was drafted by members of several cricket clubs, though the code was not published until 1755. The season is also notable for the two earliest known surviving match scorecards. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:No_Great_Shaker" title="User:No Great Shaker">No Great Shaker</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:No_Great_Shaker" title="User talk:No Great Shaker">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Crewe_Alexandra_F.C." title="Crewe Alexandra F.C.">Crewe Alexandra F.C.</a> (<small>Association football club in England</small>) </td> 
         <td>Crewe Alexandra Football Club is an English professional <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> club based in the town of <a href="/wiki/Crewe" title="Crewe">Crewe</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cheshire" title="Cheshire">Cheshire</a>, that competes in <a href="/wiki/EFL_League_One" title="EFL League One">League One</a>, the third tier of the <a href="/wiki/English_football_league_system" title="English football league system">English football league system</a>. Nicknamed "The Railwaymen" because of the town's <a href="/wiki/Crewe_Works" title="Crewe Works">links with the rail industry</a>, and also commonly known as "The Alex", they have played at <a href="/wiki/Gresty_Road" title="Gresty Road">Gresty Road</a> since 1906. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1988_Football_League_Third_Division_play-off_Final" title="1988 Football League Third Division play-off Final">1988 Football League Third Division play-off Final</a> (<small>Association football match</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 1988 Football League Third Division play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match contested by <a href="/wiki/Walsall_F.C." title="Walsall F.C.">Walsall</a> and <a href="/wiki/Bristol_City_F.C." title="Bristol City F.C.">Bristol City</a> over <a href="/wiki/Two-legged_tie" title="Two-legged tie">two legs</a> on 25 and 28 May 1988, and then a <a href="/wiki/Replay_(sports)" title="Replay (sports)">replay</a> on 30 May 1988, to determine which club would play the following season in the <a href="/wiki/1988%E2%80%9389_Football_League#Second_Division" title="1988–89 Football League">Second Division</a>.          <td>The 1999 Football League Second Division play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match which was played on 30 May 1999 at <a href="/wiki/Wembley_Stadium_(1923)" title="Wembley Stadium (1923)">Wembley Stadium</a>, London, between <a href="/wiki/Manchester_City_F.C." title="Manchester City F.C.">Manchester City</a> and <a href="/wiki/Gillingham_F.C." title="Gillingham F.C.">Gillingham</a>. The match was to determine the third and final team to gain <a href="/wiki/Promotion_and_relegation" title="Promotion and relegation">promotion</a> from the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_Second_Division" title="Football League Second Division">Football League Second Division</a>, the third tier of <a href="/wiki/English_football_league_system" title="English football league system">English football</a>, to the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_First_Division" title="Football League First Division">First Division</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1873%E2%80%9374_Scottish_Cup" title="1873–74 Scottish Cup">1873–74 Scottish Cup</a> (<small>football tournament season</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 1873–74 <a href="/wiki/Scottish_Cup" title="Scottish Cup">Scottish Cup</a> – officially the Scottish Football Association Challenge Cup – was the first season of Scotland's most prestigious <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">football</a> knockout competition. A total of 16 teams from the west of Scotland entered the competition, however only 14 would play a match after two withdrawals. The competition began on 18 October 1873 and concluded with <a href="/wiki/1874_Scottish_Cup_Final" title="1874 Scottish Cup Final">the final</a> on 21 March 1874. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Stevie_fae_Scotland" title="User:Stevie fae Scotland">Stevie fae Scotland</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Stevie_fae_Scotland" title="User talk:Stevie fae Scotland">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1930%E2%80%9331_Cardiff_City_F.C._season" title="1930–31 Cardiff City F.C. season">1930–31 Cardiff City F.C. season</a> (<small>Cardiff City 1930–31 football season</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 1930–31 season was the 30th season of competitive <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">football</a> played by <a href="/wiki/Cardiff_City_F.C." title="Cardiff City F.C.">Cardiff City F.C.</a>. It the team's second season in the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_Second_Division" title="Football League Second Division">Second Division</a> of <a href="/wiki/English_Football_League" title="English Football League">the Football League</a> since being relegated from the First Division during the <a href="/wiki/1928%E2%80%9329_Cardiff_City_F.C._season" title="1928–29 Cardiff City F.C. season">1928–29 season</a>. They finished bottom of the Second Division after winning only 8 of their 42 league matches and scoring the fewest amount of goals in the league and were relegated to the <a href="/wiki/Football_League_Third_Division_South" title="Football League Third Division South">Third Division South</a>. </td>

         <td class="recent">2021-05-06 10:09 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Alec_Sutherland" title="Alec Sutherland">Alec Sutherland</a> (<small>Aviator with the Royal Air Force and swimming coach</small>) </td> 
         <td>Alexander Ross Sutherland <span class="noexcerpt nowraplinks" style="font-size:85%;"><a href="/wiki/Order_of_the_British_Empire" title="Order of the British Empire">MBE</a></span> (19 August 1922 – 16 April 2014) was a Scottish <a href="/wiki/Royal_Air_Force" title="Royal Air Force">Royal Air Force</a> (RAF) aviator. As a teenager he helped establish the Inverness squadron of the Air Training Corps, becoming their first senior non-commissioned officer. Enlisting with the RAF, he became a bombardier/radio operator, flying ten bombing raids over Germany with <a href="/wiki/No._5_Group_RAF" title="No. 5 Group RAF">No. 5 Group RAF</a> in <a href="/wiki/Avro_Lancaster" title="Avro Lancaster">Avro Lancasters</a> during <a href="/wiki/World_War_II" title="World War II">World War II</a> . </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/EFL_League_Two_play-offs" title="EFL League Two play-offs">EFL League Two play-offs</a> </td> 
         <td>The EFL League Two play-offs are a series of <a href="/wiki/Play-offs" class="mw-redirect" title="Play-offs">play-off</a> matches contested by the <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> teams finishing from fourth to seventh in the <a href="/wiki/EFL_League_Two" title="EFL League Two">EFL League Two</a> table and are part of the <a href="/wiki/English_Football_League_play-offs" title="English Football League play-offs">English Football League play-offs</a>. As of 2021<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=SDZeroBot/GAN_sorting&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, the play-offs comprise two semi-finals, where the team finishing fourth plays the team finishing seventh, and the team finishing fifth plays the team finishing sixth, each conducted as a <a href="/wiki/Two-legged_tie" title="Two-legged tie">two-legged tie</a>. </td>

         <td>The 2011 Football League Two play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match which was played on 28 May 2011 at <a href="/wiki/Old_Trafford" title="Old Trafford">Old Trafford</a> in Manchester, between <a href="/wiki/Stevenage_F.C." title="Stevenage F.C.">Stevenage</a> and <a href="/wiki/Torquay_United_F.C." title="Torquay United F.C.">Torquay United</a>, to determine the fourth and final team to gain <a href="/wiki/Promotion_and_relegation" title="Promotion and relegation">promotion</a> from <a href="/wiki/EFL_League_Two" title="EFL League Two">Football League Two</a> to the <a href="/wiki/EFL_League_One" title="EFL League One">League One</a>. The top three teams of the <a href="/wiki/2010%E2%80%9311_Football_League_Two" title="2010–11 Football League Two">2010–11 Football League Two</a> season, <a href="/wiki/Chesterfield_F.C." title="Chesterfield F.C.">Chesterfield</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bury_F.C." title="Bury F.C.">Bury</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wycombe_Wanderers_F.C." title="Wycombe Wanderers F.C.">Wycombe Wanderers</a>, gained automatic promotion to League One, while those placed from fourth to seventh position took part in <a href="/wiki/2011_Football_League_play-offs" title="2011 Football League play-offs">play-offs</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Hatfield_College,_Durham" title="Hatfield College, Durham">Hatfield College, Durham</a> (<small>Constituent college of Durham University</small>) </td> 
         <td>Hatfield College is one of the <a href="/wiki/Colleges_of_Durham_University" title="Colleges of Durham University">constituent colleges</a> of <a href="/wiki/Durham_University" title="Durham University">Durham University</a> in England. It occupies a city centre site above the <a href="/wiki/River_Wear" title="River Wear">River Wear</a> on the <a href="/wiki/World_Heritage_Site" title="World Heritage Site">World Heritage Site</a> peninsula, lying adjacent to <a href="/wiki/The_Bailey" title="The Bailey">North Bailey</a> and only a short distance from <a href="/wiki/Durham_Cathedral" title="Durham Cathedral">Durham Cathedral</a>. Taking its name from <a href="/wiki/Thomas_Hatfield" title="Thomas Hatfield">a medieval Prince-Bishop of Durham</a>, the college was founded in 1846 as Bishop Hatfield's Hall by <a href="/wiki/David_Melville_(priest)" title="David Melville (priest)">David Melville</a>, a former <a href="/wiki/Oxford_don" class="mw-redirect" title="Oxford don">Oxford don</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Bachelor%27s_Day_(tradition)" title="Bachelor's Day (tradition)">Bachelor's Day (tradition)</a> (<small>Tradition associated with February 29</small>) </td> 
         <td>Bachelor's Day, sometimes known as Ladies' Privilege, is an <a href="/wiki/Irish_folklore" title="Irish folklore">Irish tradition</a> by which women are allowed to propose to men on <a href="/wiki/Leap_Day" class="mw-redirect" title="Leap Day">Leap Day</a>, 29 February, based on a legend of Saint Bridget and Saint Patrick. It once had legal basis in Scotland and England. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Mike_Gapes" title="Mike Gapes">Mike Gapes</a> (<small>Former British Independent politician</small>) </td> 
         <td>Michael John Gapes (born 4 September 1952) is a British politician who served as <a href="/wiki/Member_of_Parliament_(United_Kingdom)" title="Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)">Member of Parliament</a> (MP) for <a href="/wiki/Ilford_South_(UK_Parliament_constituency)" title="Ilford South (UK Parliament constituency)">Ilford South</a> from <a href="/wiki/1992_United_Kingdom_general_election" title="1992 United Kingdom general election">1992</a> to <a href="/wiki/2019_United_Kingdom_general_election" title="2019 United Kingdom general election">2019</a>. Originally elected as a <a href="/wiki/Labour_and_Co-operative" title="Labour and Co-operative">Labour and Co-operative</a> MP, Gapes defected to form <a href="/wiki/Change_UK" title="Change UK">Change UK</a> in February 2019. He is now an <a href="/wiki/Independent_politician" title="Independent politician">Independent politician</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Bangalamania" title="User:Bangalamania">Bangalamania</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Bangalamania" title="User talk:Bangalamania">talk</a>) </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-29 20:18 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/2021_EFL_Championship_play-off_Final" title="2021 EFL Championship play-off Final">2021 EFL Championship play-off Final</a> (<small>Football match</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 2021 EFL Championship play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match which was played on 29 May 2021 at <a href="/wiki/Wembley_Stadium" title="Wembley Stadium">Wembley Stadium</a>, <a href="/wiki/London" title="London">London</a>, to determine the third and final team to gain <a href="/wiki/Promotion_and_relegation" title="Promotion and relegation">promotion</a> from the <a href="/wiki/EFL_Championship" title="EFL Championship">EFL Championship</a>, the second tier of <a href="/wiki/English_football_league_system" title="English football league system">English football</a>, to the <a href="/wiki/Premier_League" title="Premier League">Premier League</a>. The top two teams of the <a href="/wiki/2020%E2%80%9321_EFL_Championship" title="2020–21 EFL Championship">2020–21 EFL Championship</a>, <a href="/wiki/Norwich_City_F.C." title="Norwich City F.C.">Norwich City</a> and <a href="/wiki/Watford_F.C." title="Watford F.C.">Watford</a>, gained automatic promotion to the Premier League, while the clubs placed from third to sixth place in the table took part in <a href="/wiki/2021_English_Football_League_play-offs" title="2021 English Football League play-offs">2021 English Football League play-offs</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:The_Rambling_Man" title="User:The Rambling Man">The Rambling Man</a> <small>(<a href="/wiki/User_talk:The_Rambling_Man" title="User talk:The Rambling Man">Stay alert! Control the virus! Save lives!!!!</a>)</small> </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/2021_EFL_League_One_play-off_Final" title="2021 EFL League One play-off Final">2021 EFL League One play-off Final</a> (<small>Football match</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 2021 EFL League One play-off Final was an <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">association football</a> match which was played on 30 May 2021 at <a href="/wiki/Wembley_Stadium" title="Wembley Stadium">Wembley Stadium</a>, London, to determine the third and final team to gain <a href="/wiki/Promotion_and_relegation" title="Promotion and relegation">promotion</a> from <a href="/wiki/EFL_League_One" title="EFL League One">EFL League One</a>, the third tier of <a href="/wiki/English_football_league_system" title="English football league system">English football</a>, to the <a href="/wiki/EFL_Championship" title="EFL Championship">EFL Championship</a>. The top two teams of <a href="/wiki/2020%E2%80%9321_EFL_League_One" title="2020–21 EFL League One">2020–21 EFL League One</a>, <a href="/wiki/Hull_City_A.F.C." title="Hull City A.F.C.">Hull City</a> and <a href="/wiki/Peterborough_United_F.C." title="Peterborough United F.C.">Peterborough United</a>, gained automatic promotion to the Championship, while the clubs placed from third to sixth place in the table will take part in <a href="/wiki/2021_English_Football_League_play-offs" title="2021 English Football League play-offs">2021 English Football League play-offs</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1928_World_Snooker_Championship" title="1928 World Snooker Championship">1928 World Snooker Championship</a> (<small>Professional snooker tournament</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 1928 World Snooker Championship was a professional <a href="/wiki/Snooker" title="Snooker">snooker</a> tournament held at various venues from 28 December 1927 to 17 May 1928. It was the second staging of the <a href="/wiki/World_Snooker_Championship" title="World Snooker Championship">World Snooker Championship</a>. It was played on a challenge basis with the other six entrants playing off for the right to challenge defending champion <a href="/wiki/Joe_Davis" title="Joe Davis">Joe Davis</a> in the final. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:BennyOnTheLoose" title="User:BennyOnTheLoose">BennyOnTheLoose</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:BennyOnTheLoose" title="User talk:BennyOnTheLoose">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1929_World_Snooker_Championship" title="1929 World Snooker Championship">1929 World Snooker Championship</a> (<small>Professional snooker tournament</small>) </td> 
         <td>The 1929 World Snooker Championship, known at the time as the Professional Championship of Snooker, was a <a href="/wiki/Snooker" title="Snooker">snooker</a> tournament held between 17 December 1928 and 7 March 1929 at various venues in England, with the final taking place from 4 to 7 March 1929 at the Lounge Hall, <a href="/wiki/Nottingham" title="Nottingham">Nottingham</a>. Defending champion <a href="/wiki/Joe_Davis" title="Joe Davis">Joe Davis</a> won the title for the third time by defeating <a href="/wiki/Tom_Dennis_(snooker_player)" title="Tom Dennis (snooker player)">Tom Dennis</a> by 19 <dfn id=""><a href="/wiki/Glossary_of_cue_sports_terms#frame" title="Glossary of cue sports terms"><span title="See entry at: Glossary of cue sports terms §?frame" style="color:inherit;" class="glossary-link">frames</span></a></dfn> to 14 in the final, after securing a winning margin at 17–12. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:BennyOnTheLoose" title="User:BennyOnTheLoose">BennyOnTheLoose</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:BennyOnTheLoose" title="User talk:BennyOnTheLoose">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="old">2021-03-03 15:04 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Fourth_Estate_(painting)" title="The Fourth Estate (painting)">The Fourth Estate (painting)</a> (<small>Early 20th-century proletarian painting by Giuseppe Pellizza</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>The Fourth Estate</i> is an oil painting by <a href="/wiki/Giuseppe_Pellizza_da_Volpedo" title="Giuseppe Pellizza da Volpedo">Giuseppe Pellizza da Volpedo</a>, originally titled <i>The Path of Workers</i> and made between 1899 and 1901. It depicts a moment during a <a href="/wiki/Strike_action" title="Strike action">labor strike</a> when workers' representatives calmly and confidently stride out of a crowd to negotiate for the workers' rights. Its name refers to the <a href="/wiki/Proletariat" title="Proletariat">working class</a> as standing alongside the <a href="/wiki/Estates_of_the_realm" title="Estates of the realm">three traditional estates</a> that divided power between the nobility, clergy, and commoners. </td> 
         <td>—<u><i><a href="/wiki/User:Wingedserif" title="User:Wingedserif">Wingedserif</a></i></u> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Wingedserif" title="User talk:Wingedserif">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>
