         <td><a href="/wiki/%C4%90akovo_internment_camp" title="?akovo internment camp">?akovo internment camp</a> (<small>Internment camp run by the Ustaše in Croatia during World War II</small>) </td> 
         <td>?akovo was an <a href="/wiki/Internment" title="Internment">internment</a> camp for <a href="/wiki/Jews" title="Jews">Jewish</a>, and to a lesser extent <a href="/wiki/Serbs" title="Serbs">Serb</a>, women and children in the town of <a href="/wiki/%C4%90akovo" title="?akovo">?akovo</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Independent_State_of_Croatia" title="Independent State of Croatia">Independent State of Croatia</a> (NDH) that was operational between December 1941 and July 1942, during <a href="/wiki/World_War_II" title="World War II">World War II</a>. </td>

She is the reigning Dutch Women's Internet Chess Champion and has also been an under-16 girls' European Youth Champion. Kazarian has a peak <a href="/wiki/FIDE_rating" class="mw-redirect" title="FIDE rating">FIDE rating</a> of 2320, which she achieved in 2016. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Croatian_Republican_Peasant_Party_(1945)" title="Croatian Republican Peasant Party (1945)">Croatian Republican Peasant Party (1945)</a> (<small>Former political organisation in Yugoslavia</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Croatian Republican Peasant Party (<i>Hrvatska republikanska selja?ka stranka</i>, HRSS) was a political party that split from the <a href="/wiki/Croatian_Peasant_Party" title="Croatian Peasant Party">Croatian Peasant Party</a> (<i>Hrvatska selja?ka stranka</i>, HSS). The HSS was once the most popular political party among the <a href="/wiki/Croats" title="Croats">Croats</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Kingdom_of_Yugoslavia" title="Kingdom of Yugoslavia">Kingdom of Yugoslavia</a>, but after the 1941 <a href="/wiki/Axis_powers" title="Axis powers">Axis</a> <a href="/wiki/Invasion_of_Yugoslavia" title="Invasion of Yugoslavia">invasion of Yugoslavia</a>, it splintered in several groups. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Croatian_Spring" title="Croatian Spring">Croatian Spring</a> (<small>Political crisis in Croatia and Yugoslavia in late 1960s and early 1970s</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Croatian Spring or Maspok was a political conflict that took place from 1967 to 1971 in the <a href="/wiki/Socialist_Republic_of_Croatia" title="Socialist Republic of Croatia">Socialist Republic of Croatia</a>, at the time part of the <a href="/wiki/Socialist_Federal_Republic_of_Yugoslavia" title="Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia">Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia</a>. As one of six republics comprising Yugoslavia at the time, Croatia was ruled by the <a href="/wiki/League_of_Communists_of_Croatia" title="League of Communists of Croatia">League of Communists of Croatia</a> (SKH), nominally independent from the <a href="/wiki/League_of_Communists_of_Yugoslavia" title="League of Communists of Yugoslavia">League of Communists of Yugoslavia</a> (SKJ), led by President <a href="/wiki/Josip_Broz_Tito" title="Josip Broz Tito">Josip Broz Tito</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Tomobe03" title="User:Tomobe03">Tomobe03</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Tomobe03" title="User talk:Tomobe03">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-06-03 19:14 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Holocaust_in_Greece" title="The Holocaust in Greece">The Holocaust in Greece</a> (<small>Systematic dispossession, deportation, and murder of Jews in Greece</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Holocaust in Greece was the deportation and murder of the <a href="/wiki/Greek_Jews" class="mw-redirect" title="Greek Jews">Greek Jews</a>, mostly a result of their deportation to <a href="/wiki/Auschwitz_concentration_camp" title="Auschwitz concentration camp">Auschwitz concentration camp</a>, during <a href="/wiki/World_War_II" title="World War II">World War II</a>. By 1945, between 83 and 87 percent of Greek Jews were dead, among the highest proportion in Europe. </td> 
         <td>(<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Buidhe" title="User talk:Buidhe">t</a> · <a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/Buidhe" title="Special:Contributions/Buidhe">c</a>) <b><a href="/wiki/User:Buidhe" title="User:Buidhe"><span style="color: black">buidhe</span></a></b> </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-06-04 17:33 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Pic-Nic" title="Pic-Nic">Pic-Nic</a> </td> 
         <td>Pic-Nic was a Spanish teenage <a href="/wiki/Folk-pop" title="Folk-pop">folk-pop</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sunshine_pop" title="Sunshine pop">sunshine pop</a> band formed in <a href="/wiki/Barcelona" title="Barcelona">Barcelona</a> in the mid-to-late 1960s, composed of lead singer <a href="/wiki/Jeanette_(singer)" title="Jeanette (singer)">Jeanette</a>, guitarists <a href="/wiki/Toti_Soler" title="Toti Soler">Toti Soler</a> and Al Cárdenas, drummer Jordi Barangé and bassist Isidoro "Doro" de Montaberry. Contrary to popular belief, keyboardist <a href="/wiki/Jordi_Sabat%C3%A9s" title="Jordi Sabatés">Jordi Sabatés</a> does not appear in any of the group's releases, as he joined the band after their only published recordings sessions had taken place. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Fran%C3%A7ois_Coignet" title="François Coignet">François Coignet</a> (<small>French industrialist</small>) </td> 
         <td>François Coignet (10 February 1814 – 30 October 1888) was a French <a href="/wiki/Industrialist" class="mw-redirect" title="Industrialist">industrialist</a> of the nineteenth century. Coignet was a pioneer in the development of structural prefabricated and <a href="/wiki/Reinforced_concrete" title="Reinforced concrete">reinforced concrete</a>, and was the first person to use iron-reinforced concrete to construct buildings. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/R%C3%A9giment_d%27Armagnac" title="Régiment d'Armagnac">Régiment d'Armagnac</a> </td> 
         <td>The Régiment d'Armagnac <i>(Regiment of Armagnac)</i> was an <a href="/wiki/Infantry" title="Infantry">infantry</a> <a href="/wiki/Regiment" title="Regiment">regiment</a> of the <a href="/wiki/French_Royal_Army" title="French Royal Army">French Royal Army</a> which served during the <a href="/wiki/American_Revolution" title="American Revolution">American Revolution</a>, and later the <a href="/wiki/War_of_the_First_Coalition" title="War of the First Coalition">War of the First Coalition</a>, until it was disbanded in 1794. The regiment's successor, the <i>6éme Régiment d'Infanterie</i> would see service during the <a href="/wiki/Napoleonic_Wars" title="Napoleonic Wars">Napoleonic Wars</a>, <a href="/wiki/French_conquest_of_Algeria" title="French conquest of Algeria">Conquest of Algeria</a>, <a href="/wiki/June_Rebellion" title="June Rebellion">June Rebellion</a>, <a href="/wiki/Franco-Prussian_War" title="Franco-Prussian War">Franco-Prussian War</a>, <a href="/wiki/First_World_War" class="mw-redirect" title="First World War">First World War</a>, <a href="/wiki/Second_World_War" class="mw-redirect" title="Second World War">Second World War</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Algerian_War" title="Algerian War">Algerian War</a> before disbanding shortly thereafter the later. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:J-Man11" title="User:J-Man11">J-Man11</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:J-Man11" title="User talk:J-Man11">talk</a>) </td>

         <td>The Lohn Estate is a <a href="/wiki/Manor_house" title="Manor house">manor</a> and <a href="/wiki/Estate_(land)" title="Estate (land)">estate</a> located in <a href="/wiki/Kehrsatz" title="Kehrsatz">Kehrsatz</a>, <a href="/wiki/Canton_of_Bern" title="Canton of Bern">canton of Bern</a>, <a href="/wiki/Switzerland" title="Switzerland">Switzerland</a>. From 1942 to 1994, the Lohn Estate accommodated the official guests of the <a href="/wiki/Swiss_Confederation" class="mw-redirect" title="Swiss Confederation">Swiss Confederation</a>. It is a Swiss <a href="/wiki/Swiss_inventory_of_cultural_property_of_national_and_regional_significance" class="mw-redirect" title="Swiss inventory of cultural property of national and regional significance">heritage site of national significance</a>. </td>

         <td>Roman campaigns in Germania (12 BC – AD 16) were a series of conflicts between the Germanic tribes and the <a href="/wiki/Roman_Empire" title="Roman Empire">Roman Empire</a>. Tensions between the Germanic tribes and the Romans began as early as 17 BC with <i><a href="/wiki/Clades_Lolliana" title="Clades Lolliana">Clades Lolliana</a></i>, where the <a href="/wiki/Legio_V_Alaudae" title="Legio V Alaudae">5th Legion</a> under <a href="/wiki/Marcus_Lollius" title="Marcus Lollius">Marcus Lollius</a> was defeated by the tribes <a href="/wiki/Sicambri" title="Sicambri">Sicambri</a>, <a href="/wiki/Usipetes" title="Usipetes">Usipetes</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Tencteri" title="Tencteri">Tencteri</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Vincent_Figgins" title="Vincent Figgins">Vincent Figgins</a> </td> 
         <td>Vincent Figgins (1766 – 29 February 1844) was a British <a href="/wiki/Typefounding" class="mw-redirect" title="Typefounding">typefounder</a> based in <a href="/wiki/London" title="London">London</a>. After an apprenticeship with Joseph Jackson, he established his own type foundry in 1792. His company was extremely successful and, with its range of <a href="/wiki/Didone_(typography)" title="Didone (typography)">modern serif</a> faces and <a href="/wiki/Display_typeface" title="Display typeface">display typefaces</a>, had a strong influence on the styles of British printing in the <a href="/wiki/Nineteenth_century" class="mw-redirect" title="Nineteenth century">nineteenth century</a>. </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-26 03:59 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Bremer_Marine_Park" title="Bremer Marine Park">Bremer Marine Park</a> (<small>Marine protected area off Western Australia</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Bremer Marine Park area is a protected South-West Marine park extending out from <a href="/wiki/Bremer_Bay" class="mw-redirect" title="Bremer Bay">Bremer Bay</a>. It is located on the South-West Coast of Australia between Albany and Esperance at 34°45’ South and 119°50’ East. It occupies approximately 4,472&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (1,727&nbsp;sq&nbsp;mi) and reaches depths of 5900m. It is zoned by the Australian government under the ‘South West Marine Parks Management plan 2018’ as a <a href="/wiki/National_park" title="National park">national park</a> and hence protects numerous of <a href="/wiki/Flora" title="Flora">flora</a> and <a href="/wiki/Fauna" title="Fauna">fauna</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Alexsurfing" title="User:Alexsurfing">Alexsurfing</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Alexsurfing" title="User talk:Alexsurfing">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="new">2021-05-31 07:24 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Fontainea_venosa" title="Fontainea venosa">Fontainea venosa</a> (<small>Species of tree</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Fontainea venosa</i>, also commonly known as southern blushwood, veiny fontainea, Queensland fontainea and formerly named as Bahrs scrub fontainea is a rare <a href="/wiki/Rainforest" title="Rainforest">rainforest</a> shrub or tree of the family <a href="/wiki/Euphorbiaceae" title="Euphorbiaceae">Euphorbiaceae</a>. It is found in south eastern <a href="/wiki/Queensland" title="Queensland">Queensland</a>, Australia, extending from <a href="/wiki/Boyne_Valley,_Queensland" title="Boyne Valley, Queensland">Boyne Valley</a> to <a href="/wiki/Cedar_Creek,_Queensland_(Logan_%26_Gold_Coast)" title="Cedar Creek, Queensland (Logan &amp; Gold Coast)">Cedar Creek</a> and is considered vulnerable due to several contributing threats (<a href="/wiki/Fire" title="Fire">fire</a>, urban development, and weed infestation). </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Sparklingkull" title="User:Sparklingkull">Sparklingkull</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Sparklingkull" title="User talk:Sparklingkull">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Meatballs_(advertisement)" title="Meatballs (advertisement)">Meatballs (advertisement)</a> (<small>2000 US presidential election campaign political commercial</small>) </td> 
         <td><i>Meatballs</i> (also known as <i>Meatball</i> and <i>For Spanish Press 1</i>) was a <a href="/wiki/Campaign_advertising" title="Campaign advertising">political commercial</a> aired during the <a href="/wiki/2000_United_States_presidential_election" title="2000 United States presidential election">2000 United States presidential campaign</a> in support of <a href="/wiki/Reform_Party_of_the_United_States_of_America" title="Reform Party of the United States of America">Reform Party</a> candidate <a href="/wiki/Pat_Buchanan" title="Pat Buchanan">Pat Buchanan</a>.          <td><a href="/wiki/Cone_Mills_Corporation" title="Cone Mills Corporation">Cone Mills Corporation</a> (<small>American textile manufacturer (1895–2004)</small>) </td> 
         <td>Cone Mills Corporation was a twentieth century <a href="/wiki/Textile_manufacturing" title="Textile manufacturing">manufacturer</a> of <a href="/wiki/Cotton" title="Cotton">cotton</a> fabrics that included <a href="/wiki/Corduroy" title="Corduroy">corduroy</a>, <a href="/wiki/Flannel" title="Flannel">flannel</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Denim" title="Denim">denim</a>. The company headquartered in <a href="/wiki/Greensboro,_North_Carolina" title="Greensboro, North Carolina">Greensboro, North Carolina</a> and had its factory mills in parts of <a href="/wiki/North_Carolina" title="North Carolina">North</a> and <a href="/wiki/South_Carolina" title="South Carolina">South Carolina</a>. The company has its base roots in a family operated <a href="/wiki/Baltimore" title="Baltimore">Baltimore</a> grocery business in that was managed mostly by <a href="/wiki/Moses_H._Cone" title="Moses H. Cone">Moses H. Cone</a> and his brother Caesar. </td>

        <tr> 
         <td class="recent">2021-04-21 03:04 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Permanent_income_hypothesis" title="Permanent income hypothesis">Permanent income hypothesis</a> </td> 
         <td>The permanent income hypothesis (often abbreviated PIH) is the most widely accepted model in the field of <a href="/wiki/Economics" title="Economics">economics</a> to explain the <a href="/wiki/Consumption_function" title="Consumption function">formation of consumption patterns</a>. It suggests consumption patterns are formed from future expectations and <a href="/wiki/Consumption_smoothing" title="Consumption smoothing">consumption smoothing</a>. The theory was developed by <a href="/wiki/Milton_Friedman" title="Milton Friedman">Milton Friedman</a> and published in his <i>A Theory of Consumption Function</i>, published in 1957 and subsequently challenged by <a href="/wiki/Robert_Hall_(economist)" title="Robert Hall (economist)">Robert Hall's</a> inclusion of <a href="/wiki/Rational_expectations" title="Rational expectations">rational expectations</a>.{{Sfn|Friedman|195 ... </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:BasedMises" title="User:BasedMises">BasedMises</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:BasedMises" title="User talk:BasedMises">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="recent">2021-05-05 12:49 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Dot-com_bubble" title="Dot-com bubble">Dot-com bubble</a> (<small>Tech stock speculative craze, c. 1997-2003</small>) </td> 
         <td>The dot-com bubble (also known as the dot-com boom, the tech bubble, and the Internet bubble) was a <a href="/wiki/Stock_market_bubble" title="Stock market bubble">stock market bubble</a> caused by excessive <a href="/wiki/Speculation" title="Speculation">speculation</a> of Internet-related companies in the late 1990s, a period of massive growth in the use and adoption of the <a href="/wiki/Internet" title="Internet">Internet</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:PhotographyEdits" title="User:PhotographyEdits">PhotographyEdits</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:PhotographyEdits" title="User talk:PhotographyEdits">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td>In 2012, members of the <a href="/wiki/International_Longshore_and_Warehouse_Union" title="International Longshore and Warehouse Union">International Longshore and Warehouse Union</a> (ILWU) went <a href="/wiki/On_strike" class="mw-redirect" title="On strike">on strike</a> at the ports of <a href="/wiki/Port_of_Los_Angeles" title="Port of Los Angeles">Los Angeles</a> and <a href="/wiki/Port_of_Long_Beach" title="Port of Long Beach">Long Beach</a> in the <a href="/wiki/U.S." class="mw-redirect" title="U.S.">U.S.</a> state of <a href="/wiki/California" title="California">California</a>. The strike was due to issues over <a href="/wiki/Labor_contract" class="mw-redirect" title="Labor contract">labor contract</a> negotiations between port employers and the ILWU's <a href="/wiki/Local_union" title="Local union">Local</a> 63 Office and Clerical Unit (OCU), which represents about 800 <a href="/wiki/Clerical_workers" class="mw-redirect" title="Clerical workers">clerical workers</a> at the ports. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Hatfield_College,_Durham" title="Hatfield College, Durham">Hatfield College, Durham</a> (<small>Constituent college of Durham University</small>) </td> 
         <td>Hatfield College is one of the <a href="/wiki/Colleges_of_Durham_University" title="Colleges of Durham University">constituent colleges</a> of <a href="/wiki/Durham_University" title="Durham University">Durham University</a> in England. It occupies a city centre site above the <a href="/wiki/River_Wear" title="River Wear">River Wear</a> on the <a href="/wiki/World_Heritage_Site" title="World Heritage Site">World Heritage Site</a> peninsula, lying adjacent to <a href="/wiki/The_Bailey" title="The Bailey">North Bailey</a> and only a short distance from <a href="/wiki/Durham_Cathedral" title="Durham Cathedral">Durham Cathedral</a>. Taking its name from <a href="/wiki/Thomas_Hatfield" title="Thomas Hatfield">a medieval Prince-Bishop of Durham</a>, the college was founded in 1846 as Bishop Hatfield's Hall by <a href="/wiki/David_Melville_(priest)" title="David Melville (priest)">David Melville</a>, a former <a href="/wiki/Oxford_don" class="mw-redirect" title="Oxford don">Oxford don</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/w/index.php?title=User:Leonstojka&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="User:Leonstojka (page does not exist)">Leonstojka</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Leonstojka" title="User talk:Leonstojka">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Mike_Gapes" title="Mike Gapes">Mike Gapes</a> (<small>Former British Independent politician</small>) </td> 
         <td>Michael John Gapes (born 4 September 1952) is a British politician who served as <a href="/wiki/Member_of_Parliament_(United_Kingdom)" title="Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)">Member of Parliament</a> (MP) for <a href="/wiki/Ilford_South_(UK_Parliament_constituency)" title="Ilford South (UK Parliament constituency)">Ilford South</a> from <a href="/wiki/1992_United_Kingdom_general_election" title="1992 United Kingdom general election">1992</a> to <a href="/wiki/2019_United_Kingdom_general_election" title="2019 United Kingdom general election">2019</a>. Originally elected as a <a href="/wiki/Labour_and_Co-operative" title="Labour and Co-operative">Labour and Co-operative</a> MP, Gapes defected to form <a href="/wiki/Change_UK" title="Change UK">Change UK</a> in February 2019. He is now an <a href="/wiki/Independent_politician" title="Independent politician">Independent politician</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/History_of_the_University_of_Texas_at_Arlington_(1917%E2%80%931965)" title="History of the University of Texas at Arlington (1917–1965)">History of the University of Texas at Arlington (1917–1965)</a> </td> 
         <td>The history of the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Texas_at_Arlington" title="University of Texas at Arlington">University of Texas at Arlington</a> between 1917 and 1965 was the period of its existence as a member of the <a href="/wiki/Texas_A%26M_University_System" title="Texas A&amp;M University System">Texas A&amp;M University System</a>. In March 1917, it was organized as Grubbs Vocational College (GVC), a <a href="/wiki/Junior_college" title="Junior college">junior college</a> that was a <a href="/wiki/Satellite_campus" title="Satellite campus">branch campus</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Texas_A%26M_University" title="Texas A&amp;M University">Agricultural and Mechanical College of Texas</a> (AMC), which later became Texas A&amp;M University. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Frontier_Central_School_District" title="Frontier Central School District">Frontier Central School District</a> (<small>School district in Hamburg, New York, U.S.</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Frontier Central School District is the primary <a href="/wiki/State_school" title="State school">public</a> <a href="/wiki/School_district" title="School district">school district</a> serving the town of <a href="/wiki/Hamburg,_New_York" title="Hamburg, New York">Hamburg, New York</a>. The district serves most of the town outside of the <a href="/wiki/Hamburg_(village),_New_York" title="Hamburg (village), New York">village of Hamburg</a>, and is an independent public entity. With authority from the <a href="/wiki/New_York_State_Education_Department" title="New York State Education Department">State of New York</a>, Frontier's seven-member <a href="/wiki/Board_of_Education" class="mw-redirect" title="Board of Education">Board of Education</a> governs the district and selects the <a href="/wiki/Superintendent_(education)" title="Superintendent (education)">superintendent</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Eshmunazar_II_sarcophagus" title="Eshmunazar II sarcophagus">Eshmunazar II sarcophagus</a> (<small>Sarcophagus found in Lebanon</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Eshmunazar II sarcophagus is a 6th-century B.C. sarcophagus unearthed in 1855 in the "Phoenician Necropolis", a <a href="/wiki/Hypogeum" title="Hypogeum">hypogeum</a> in the southern area of the city of <a href="/wiki/Sidon" title="Sidon">Sidon</a> in modern-day Lebanon. The sarcophagus was discovered by members of the French consulate in Sidon and was donated to the <a href="/wiki/Louvre" title="Louvre">Louvre</a>. The Eshmunazar II sarcophagus has two sets of <a href="/wiki/Canaanite_and_Aramaic_inscriptions" title="Canaanite and Aramaic inscriptions">Phoenician inscriptions</a>, one on its lid and the other on its trough, under the sarcophagus head. </td>

         <td>The Crusader states were <a href="/wiki/Feudalism" title="Feudalism">feudal</a> <a href="/wiki/Polity" title="Polity">polities</a> created by the <a href="/wiki/Latin_Church" title="Latin Church">Latin Catholic</a> leaders of the <a href="/wiki/First_Crusade" title="First Crusade">First Crusade</a> through <a href="/wiki/Conquest" title="Conquest">conquest</a> and political subterfuge. Four states were established: the <a href="/wiki/County_of_Edessa" title="County of Edessa">county of Edessa</a> (1098–1150); the <a href="/wiki/Principality_of_Antioch" title="Principality of Antioch">principality of Antioch</a> (1098–1287), the <a href="/wiki/County_of_Tripoli" title="County of Tripoli">county of Tripoli</a> (1102–1289), and the <a href="/wiki/Kingdom_of_Jerusalem" title="Kingdom of Jerusalem">kingdom of Jerusalem</a> (1099–1291). </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Croatian_Republican_Peasant_Party_(1945)" title="Croatian Republican Peasant Party (1945)">Croatian Republican Peasant Party (1945)</a> (<small>Former political organisation in Yugoslavia</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Croatian Republican Peasant Party (<i>Hrvatska republikanska selja?ka stranka</i>, HRSS) was a political party that split from the <a href="/wiki/Croatian_Peasant_Party" title="Croatian Peasant Party">Croatian Peasant Party</a> (<i>Hrvatska selja?ka stranka</i>, HSS). The HSS was once the most popular political party among the <a href="/wiki/Croats" title="Croats">Croats</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Kingdom_of_Yugoslavia" title="Kingdom of Yugoslavia">Kingdom of Yugoslavia</a>, but after the 1941 <a href="/wiki/Axis_powers" title="Axis powers">Axis</a> <a href="/wiki/Invasion_of_Yugoslavia" title="Invasion of Yugoslavia">invasion of Yugoslavia</a>, it splintered in several groups. </td>

         <td class="recent">2021-05-06 10:07 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Juliana_R._Force" title="Juliana R. Force">Juliana R. Force</a> (<small>American art museum administrator</small>) </td> 
         <td>Juliana R. Force (December 25, 1876&nbsp;– August 28, 1948) was an American art museum administrator and director. Force started her career as a collector of <a href="/wiki/Folk_art" title="Folk art">folk art</a> and as a secretary to <a href="/wiki/Socialite" title="Socialite">socialite</a> art collectors. She initiated the first display of American folk art in the United States. Force became a director of art galleries and of a temporary museum of American art in <a href="/wiki/Greenwich_Village" title="Greenwich Village">Greenwich Village</a> in New York City that became the <a href="/wiki/Whitney_Museum_of_American_Art" title="Whitney Museum of American Art">Whitney Museum of American Art</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Doug_Coldwell" title="User:Doug Coldwell">Doug Coldwell</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Doug_Coldwell" title="User talk:Doug Coldwell">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Roman_campaigns_in_Germania_(12_BC_%E2%80%93_AD_16)" title="Roman campaigns in Germania (12 BC – AD 16)">Roman campaigns in Germania (12 BC – AD 16)</a> (<small>Series of military conflicts between Germanic tribes and the Romans (12 BC – 16 AD)</small>) </td> 
         <td>Roman campaigns in Germania (12 BC – AD 16) were a series of conflicts between the Germanic tribes and the <a href="/wiki/Roman_Empire" title="Roman Empire">Roman Empire</a>. Tensions between the Germanic tribes and the Romans began as early as 17 BC with <i><a href="/wiki/Clades_Lolliana" title="Clades Lolliana">Clades Lolliana</a></i>, where the <a href="/wiki/Legio_V_Alaudae" title="Legio V Alaudae">5th Legion</a> under <a href="/wiki/Marcus_Lollius" title="Marcus Lollius">Marcus Lollius</a> was defeated by the tribes <a href="/wiki/Sicambri" title="Sicambri">Sicambri</a>, <a href="/wiki/Usipetes" title="Usipetes">Usipetes</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Tencteri" title="Tencteri">Tencteri</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Callimachus" title="Callimachus">Callimachus</a> (<small>Ancient poet and librarian</small>) </td> 
         <td>Callimachus was an <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greek" title="Ancient Greek">ancient Greek</a> <a href="/wiki/Poet" title="Poet">poet</a>, <a href="/wiki/Scholar" title="Scholar">scholar</a> and <a href="/wiki/Librarian" title="Librarian">librarian</a> who was active in <a href="/wiki/Alexandria" title="Alexandria">Alexandria</a> during the 3rd century BC. A representative of <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greek_literature" title="Ancient Greek literature">Ancient Greek literature</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Hellenistic_period" title="Hellenistic period">Hellenistic period</a>, he wrote over 800 literary works in a wide variety of genres, most of which did not survive. He espoused an <a href="/wiki/Aesthetic_philosophy" class="mw-redirect" title="Aesthetic philosophy">aesthetic philosophy</a>, known as Callimacheanism, which exerted a strong influence on the poets of the <a href="/wiki/Roman_Empire" title="Roman Empire">Roman Empire</a> and, through them, on all subsequent <a href="/wiki/Western_canon" title="Western canon">Western literature</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Modussiccandi" title="User:Modussiccandi">Modussiccandi</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Modussiccandi" title="User talk:Modussiccandi">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/The_Holocaust_in_Greece" title="The Holocaust in Greece">The Holocaust in Greece</a> (<small>Systematic dispossession, deportation, and murder of Jews in Greece</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Holocaust in Greece was the deportation and murder of the <a href="/wiki/Greek_Jews" class="mw-redirect" title="Greek Jews">Greek Jews</a>, mostly a result of their deportation to <a href="/wiki/Auschwitz_concentration_camp" title="Auschwitz concentration camp">Auschwitz concentration camp</a>, during <a href="/wiki/World_War_II" title="World War II">World War II</a>. By 1945, between 83 and 87 percent of Greek Jews were dead, among the highest proportion in Europe. </td> 
         <td>(<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Buidhe" title="User talk:Buidhe">t</a> · <a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/Buidhe" title="Special:Contributions/Buidhe">c</a>) <b><a href="/wiki/User:Buidhe" title="User:Buidhe"><span style="color: black">buidhe</span></a></b> </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Coronation_of_Mindon_Min" title="Coronation of Mindon Min">Coronation of Mindon Min</a> (<small>Initiation rite performed to crown Mindon Min of Burma in 1857</small>) </td> 
         <td>The <a href="/wiki/Coronation_of_the_Burmese_Monarch" title="Coronation of the Burmese Monarch">coronation</a> (<i><a href="/wiki/Abhisheka" title="Abhisheka">abhiseka</a></i>) of <a href="/wiki/Mindon_Min" title="Mindon Min">Mindon Min</a> and <a href="/wiki/Setkya_Dewi" title="Setkya Dewi">Setkya Dewi</a> as <a href="/wiki/List_of_Burmese_monarchs#Konbaung_(1752–1885)" title="List of Burmese monarchs">king</a> and <a href="/wiki/List_of_Burmese_royal_consorts#Konbaung_Dynasty" title="List of Burmese royal consorts">queen</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Konbaung_Kingdom" class="mw-redirect" title="Konbaung Kingdom">Konbaung Kingdom</a> took place at <a href="/wiki/Mandalay_Palace" title="Mandalay Palace">Mandalay Palace</a> on 14 May 1857. Mindon Min ascended the throne upon the abdication of his half brother, <a href="/wiki/Pagan_Min" title="Pagan Min">Pagan Min</a>, on 18 February 1853. Similar to other southeast Asian traditions, the coronation ceremony was a mix of <a href="/wiki/Hinduism_in_Southeast_Asia" title="Hinduism in Southeast Asia">Hindu</a> and Buddhist cultures in which <i>Punna</i> (<a href="/wiki/Brahmin#Outside_India:_Myanmar,_Thailand,_Cambodia,_Vietnam_and_Indonesia" title="Brahmin">Brahmins</a>) played significant roles. </td>

         <td>The Régiment d'Armagnac <i>(Regiment of Armagnac)</i> was an <a href="/wiki/Infantry" title="Infantry">infantry</a> <a href="/wiki/Regiment" title="Regiment">regiment</a> of the <a href="/wiki/French_Royal_Army" title="French Royal Army">French Royal Army</a> which served during the <a href="/wiki/American_Revolution" title="American Revolution">American Revolution</a>, and later the <a href="/wiki/War_of_the_First_Coalition" title="War of the First Coalition">War of the First Coalition</a>, until it was disbanded in 1794. The regiment's successor, the <i>6éme Régiment d'Infanterie</i> would see service during the <a href="/wiki/Napoleonic_Wars" title="Napoleonic Wars">Napoleonic Wars</a>, <a href="/wiki/French_conquest_of_Algeria" title="French conquest of Algeria">Conquest of Algeria</a>, <a href="/wiki/June_Rebellion" title="June Rebellion">June Rebellion</a>, <a href="/wiki/Franco-Prussian_War" title="Franco-Prussian War">Franco-Prussian War</a>, <a href="/wiki/First_World_War" class="mw-redirect" title="First World War">First World War</a>, <a href="/wiki/Second_World_War" class="mw-redirect" title="Second World War">Second World War</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Algerian_War" title="Algerian War">Algerian War</a> before disbanding shortly thereafter the later. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Alec_Sutherland" title="Alec Sutherland">Alec Sutherland</a> (<small>Aviator with the Royal Air Force and swimming coach</small>) </td> 
         <td>Alexander Ross Sutherland <span class="noexcerpt nowraplinks" style="font-size:85%;"><a href="/wiki/Order_of_the_British_Empire" title="Order of the British Empire">MBE</a></span> (19 August 1922 – 16 April 2014) was a Scottish <a href="/wiki/Royal_Air_Force" title="Royal Air Force">Royal Air Force</a> (RAF) aviator. As a teenager he helped establish the Inverness squadron of the Air Training Corps, becoming their first senior non-commissioned officer. Enlisting with the RAF, he became a bombardier/radio operator, flying ten bombing raids over Germany with <a href="/wiki/No._5_Group_RAF" title="No. 5 Group RAF">No. 5 Group RAF</a> in <a href="/wiki/Avro_Lancaster" title="Avro Lancaster">Avro Lancasters</a> during <a href="/wiki/World_War_II" title="World War II">World War II</a> . </td>

         <td>A <a href="/wiki/Bronze" title="Bronze">bronze</a> <a href="/wiki/Statue" title="Statue">statue</a> of <a href="/wiki/George_H._Perkins" title="George H. Perkins">George H. Perkins</a> stands on the grounds of the <a href="/wiki/New_Hampshire_State_House" title="New Hampshire State House">New Hampshire State House</a> in <a href="/wiki/Concord,_New_Hampshire" title="Concord, New Hampshire">Concord</a>, <a href="/wiki/New_Hampshire" title="New Hampshire">New Hampshire</a>, <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>. The statue was designed by sculptor <a href="/wiki/Daniel_Chester_French" title="Daniel Chester French">Daniel Chester French</a>, with <a href="/wiki/Architect" title="Architect">architect</a> <a href="/wiki/Henry_Bacon" title="Henry Bacon">Henry Bacon</a> designing the remainder of the public <a href="/wiki/Monument" title="Monument">monument</a>. It honors Perkins, a New Hampshire native who had served as an <a href="/wiki/Officer_(armed_forces)" title="Officer (armed forces)">officer</a> in the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Navy" title="United States Navy">United States Navy</a> during the <a href="/wiki/American_Civil_War" title="American Civil War">American Civil War</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:JJonahJackalope" title="User:JJonahJackalope">JJonahJackalope</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:JJonahJackalope" title="User talk:JJonahJackalope">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-21 03:09 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Statue_of_William_Francis_Bartlett" title="Statue of William Francis Bartlett">Statue of William Francis Bartlett</a> (<small>Statue in Boston, Massachusetts, U.S.</small>) </td> 
         <td>A <a href="/wiki/Statue" title="Statue">statue</a> of <a href="/wiki/William_Francis_Bartlett" title="William Francis Bartlett">William Francis Bartlett</a> stands inside the <a href="/wiki/Massachusetts_State_House" title="Massachusetts State House">Massachusetts State House</a> in <a href="/wiki/Boston" title="Boston">Boston</a>, <a href="/wiki/Massachusetts" title="Massachusetts">Massachusetts</a>, <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>. The bronze statue was designed by sculptor <a href="/wiki/Daniel_Chester_French" title="Daniel Chester French">Daniel Chester French</a> and honors Bartlett, who had served as a <a href="/wiki/General" class="mw-redirect" title="General">general</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Union_Army" title="Union Army">Union Army</a> during the <a href="/wiki/American_Civil_War" title="American Civil War">American Civil War</a>. The statue was dedicated in 1904. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:JJonahJackalope" title="User:JJonahJackalope">JJonahJackalope</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:JJonahJackalope" title="User talk:JJonahJackalope">talk</a>) </td>

         <td>British logistics in the Siegfried Line campaign supported the Anglo-Canadian <a href="/wiki/21st_Army_Group" title="21st Army Group">21st Army Group</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Second_World_War" class="mw-redirect" title="Second World War">Second World War</a> operations from the end of the pursuit of the German armies from <a href="/wiki/Normandy" title="Normandy">Normandy</a> in mid-September 1944 until the end of January 1945. </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-30 10:12 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Japanese_cruiser_Naniwa" title="Japanese cruiser Naniwa">Japanese cruiser Naniwa</a> </td> 
         <td>was the <a href="/wiki/Lead_ship" title="Lead ship">lead ship</a> of <a href="/wiki/Naniwa-class_cruiser" title="Naniwa-class cruiser">her class</a> of two <a href="/wiki/Protected_cruiser" title="Protected cruiser">protected cruisers</a> built for the <a href="/wiki/Imperial_Japanese_Navy" title="Imperial Japanese Navy">Imperial Japanese Navy</a> (IJN) in the 1880s. As Japan lacked the industrial capacity to construct such vessels, the ship was designed and built in the <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">United Kingdom</a>. She participated in the <a href="/wiki/First_Sino-Japanese_War" title="First Sino-Japanese War">First Sino-Japanese War</a> of 1894–1895, playing a major role in the <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_the_Yalu_River_(1894)" title="Battle of the Yalu River (1894)">Battle of the Yalu River</a> and lesser roles in the <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_L%C3%BCshunkou" title="Battle of Lüshunkou">Battles of Port Arthur</a>, <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_Weihaiwei" title="Battle of Weihaiwei">Weihaiwei</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Pescadores_Campaign_(1895)" class="mw-redirect" title="Pescadores Campaign (1895)">Pescadores Campaign</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Japanese_invasion_of_Taiwan_(1895)" title="Japanese invasion of Taiwan (1895)">invasion of Taiwan</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Sturmvogel_66" title="User:Sturmvogel 66">Sturmvogel 66</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Sturmvogel_66" title="User talk:Sturmvogel 66">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-06-04 23:05 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Battle_of_Byram%27s_Ford" title="Battle of Byram's Ford">Battle of Byram's Ford</a> </td> 
         <td>The Battle of Byram's Ford, (also known as the Battle of Big Blue River and the Battle of the Blue) was fought on October 22 and 23, 1864, during <a href="/wiki/Price%27s_Raid" class="mw-redirect" title="Price's Raid">Price's Raid</a>, a campaign of the <a href="/wiki/American_Civil_War" title="American Civil War">American Civil War</a>. With the <a href="/wiki/Confederate_States_of_America" title="Confederate States of America">Confederate States of America</a> collapsing, <a href="/wiki/Major_General_(CSA)" class="mw-redirect" title="Major General (CSA)">Major General</a> <a href="/wiki/Sterling_Price" title="Sterling Price">Sterling Price</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Confederate_States_Army" title="Confederate States Army">Confederate States Army</a> conducted an invasion of the state of <a href="/wiki/Missouri" title="Missouri">Missouri</a> in late 1864. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Hog_Farm" title="User:Hog Farm">Hog Farm</a> <sub> <a href="/wiki/User_talk:Hog_Farm" title="User talk:Hog Farm">Talk</a></sub> </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="new">2021-06-05 11:52 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/RAF_Elgin" title="RAF Elgin">RAF Elgin</a> </td> 
         <td>Royal Air Force Elgin or RAF Elgin, also known as Bogs of Mayne, is a former airfield operated by the <a href="/wiki/Royal_Air_Force" title="Royal Air Force">Royal Air Force</a> and located approximately 1.5 kilometres (0.93&nbsp;mi) south west of <a href="/wiki/Elgin,_Moray" title="Elgin, Moray">Elgin</a> in <a href="/wiki/Moray" title="Moray">Moray</a>, <a href="/wiki/Scotland" title="Scotland">Scotland</a>. It opened in 1940 as a satellite airfield of <a href="/wiki/RAF_Lossiemouth" title="RAF Lossiemouth">RAF Lossiemouth</a> and was used throughout the <a href="/wiki/Second_World_War" class="mw-redirect" title="Second World War">Second World War</a>, predominately by bomber aircraft of No. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Thx811" title="User:Thx811">Thx811</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Thx811" title="User talk:Thx811">talk</a>) </td>

It is common for the members of a political party to have similar ideas about politics, and parties may promote specific <a href="/wiki/Political_ideology" class="mw-redirect" title="Political ideology">ideological</a> or <a href="/wiki/Policy" title="Policy">policy</a> goals. </td>

Upon his death, <i><a href="/wiki/The_Guardian" title="The Guardian">The Guardian</a></i> wrote that Robson was an "internationally renowned authority on public administration". </td>

Incumbent Republican-turned-Democrat <a href="/wiki/United_States_Senate" title="United States Senate">U.S. Senator</a> <a href="/wiki/Arlen_Specter" title="Arlen Specter">Arlen Specter</a> ran for reelection to a sixth term, but lost in <a href="/wiki/2010_United_States_Senate_Democratic_primary_election_in_Pennsylvania" title="2010 United States Senate Democratic primary election in Pennsylvania">the Democratic primary</a> to <a href="/wiki/Joe_Sestak" title="Joe Sestak">Joe Sestak</a>. Republican nominee <a href="/wiki/Pat_Toomey" title="Pat Toomey">Pat Toomey</a> then won the seat. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Peelian_principles" title="Peelian principles">Peelian principles</a> </td> 
         <td>The Peelian principles summarise the ideas that <a href="/wiki/Robert_Peel" title="Robert Peel">Sir Robert Peel</a> developed to define an <a href="/wiki/Criminal_justice_ethics" title="Criminal justice ethics">ethical police force</a>. The approach expressed in these principles is commonly known as policing by consent in the United Kingdom and other countries such as Canada, Australia and New Zealand. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Robert_M._La_Follette" title="Robert M. La Follette">Robert M. La Follette</a> (<small>Progressive politician from Wisconsin</small>) </td> 
         <td>Robert Marion "Fighting Bob" La Follette Sr. (June 14, 1855&nbsp;– June 18, 1925), was an American lawyer and politician. He represented <a href="/wiki/Wisconsin" title="Wisconsin">Wisconsin</a> in both chambers of Congress and served as the <a href="/wiki/Governor_of_Wisconsin" title="Governor of Wisconsin">Governor of Wisconsin</a>. A <a href="/wiki/Republican_Party_(United_States)" title="Republican Party (United States)">Republican</a> for most of his career, he ran for <a href="/wiki/President_of_the_United_States" title="President of the United States">President of the United States</a> as the nominee of his own <a href="/wiki/Progressive_Party_(United_States,_1924%E2%80%9334)" title="Progressive Party (United States, 1924–34)">Progressive Party</a> in the <a href="/wiki/U.S._presidential_election,_1924" class="mw-redirect" title="U.S. presidential election, 1924">1924 presidential election</a>. </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-20 14:03 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Mike_Gapes" title="Mike Gapes">Mike Gapes</a> (<small>Former British Independent politician</small>) </td> 
         <td>Michael John Gapes (born 4 September 1952) is a British politician who served as <a href="/wiki/Member_of_Parliament_(United_Kingdom)" title="Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)">Member of Parliament</a> (MP) for <a href="/wiki/Ilford_South_(UK_Parliament_constituency)" title="Ilford South (UK Parliament constituency)">Ilford South</a> from <a href="/wiki/1992_United_Kingdom_general_election" title="1992 United Kingdom general election">1992</a> to <a href="/wiki/2019_United_Kingdom_general_election" title="2019 United Kingdom general election">2019</a>. Originally elected as a <a href="/wiki/Labour_and_Co-operative" title="Labour and Co-operative">Labour and Co-operative</a> MP, Gapes defected to form <a href="/wiki/Change_UK" title="Change UK">Change UK</a> in February 2019. He is now an <a href="/wiki/Independent_politician" title="Independent politician">Independent politician</a>. </td>

         <td><i>Fontainea venosa</i>, also commonly known as southern blushwood, veiny fontainea, Queensland fontainea and formerly named as Bahrs scrub fontainea is a rare <a href="/wiki/Rainforest" title="Rainforest">rainforest</a> shrub or tree of the family <a href="/wiki/Euphorbiaceae" title="Euphorbiaceae">Euphorbiaceae</a>. It is found in south eastern <a href="/wiki/Queensland" title="Queensland">Queensland</a>, Australia, extending from <a href="/wiki/Boyne_Valley,_Queensland" title="Boyne Valley, Queensland">Boyne Valley</a> to <a href="/wiki/Cedar_Creek,_Queensland_(Logan_%26_Gold_Coast)" title="Cedar Creek, Queensland (Logan &amp; Gold Coast)">Cedar Creek</a> and is considered vulnerable due to several contributing threats (<a href="/wiki/Fire" title="Fire">fire</a>, urban development, and weed infestation). </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Atlanta_Eagle_police_raid" title="Atlanta Eagle police raid">Atlanta Eagle police raid</a> </td> 
         <td>The Atlanta Eagle police raid was a <a href="/wiki/Police_raid" title="Police raid">police raid</a> targeting the Atlanta Eagle, a <a href="/wiki/Gay_bar" title="Gay bar">gay bar</a> in <a href="/wiki/Atlanta" title="Atlanta">Atlanta</a>, <a href="/wiki/Georgia_(U.S._state)" title="Georgia (U.S. state)">Georgia</a>, <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>. The raid occurred on September 10, 2009, due to anonymous tips alleging that illegal drug use and sex was occurring at the bar. Several dozen officers were involved in the raid, including members of the <a href="/wiki/Atlanta_Police_Department" title="Atlanta Police Department">Atlanta Police Department</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Vice_squad" class="mw-redirect" title="Vice squad">vice squad</a> and the "Red Dog Unit", a <a href="/wiki/SWAT" title="SWAT">SWAT</a>-like unit typically used in high drug use areas. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Climate_change" title="Climate change">Climate change</a> in <a href="/wiki/Turkey" title="Turkey">Turkey</a> includes changes in the <a href="/wiki/Climate_of_Turkey" title="Climate of Turkey">climate of Turkey</a>, <a href="/wiki/Effects_of_climate_change" title="Effects of climate change">their effects</a> and how the country is <a href="/wiki/Climate_change_adaptation" title="Climate change adaptation">adapting to those changes</a>. Turkey's annual and maximum temperatures are rising, and 2020 was the third hottest year on record. Turkey will be greatly affected by climate change,<sup class="reference" style="white-space:nowrap;">:<span>7</span></sup> and is already experiencing more extreme weather, with <a href="/wiki/Drought" title="Drought">droughts</a> and <a href="/wiki/Heat_wave" title="Heat wave">heatwaves</a> being the main hazards. </td>

         <td>Lev (Yehuda Leyb) Osipovitch Levanda (Russian: <span lang="ru">??? ???????? ???????</span>, <a href="/wiki/Yiddish_language" class="mw-redirect" title="Yiddish language">Yiddish</a>: <span lang="yi" dir="rtl">????? ???? ?????????</span>?; June 1835 – 18 June 1888) was a Russian author, <a href="/wiki/Belles-lettres" title="Belles-lettres">belletrist</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Publication" title="Publication">publicist</a>.          <td><a href="/wiki/Tolkien%27s_frame_stories" title="Tolkien's frame stories">Tolkien's frame stories</a> (<small>J. R. R. Tolkien's use of stories to frame his novels</small>) </td> 
         <td>Tolkien's frame stories are the narrative devices that <a href="/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien" title="J. R. R. Tolkien">J. R. R. Tolkien</a> chose to use throughout his <a href="/wiki/Middle-earth" title="Middle-earth">Middle-earth</a> writings, especially <a href="/wiki/Tolkien%27s_legendarium" title="Tolkien's legendarium">his legendarium</a>, to make the works <a href="/wiki/Mythopoeia" title="Mythopoeia">resemble a genuine mythology</a> written and edited by many hands over a long period of time. He described in detail how his fictional characters wrote their books and transmitted them to others, and showed how later editors annotated the material. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Therapy_(New_York_City)" title="Therapy (New York City)">Therapy (New York City)</a> (<small>Defunct gay bar and nightclub in Manhattan, New York, U.S.</small>) </td> 
         <td>Therapy was a bilevel <a href="/wiki/Gay_bar" title="Gay bar">gay bar</a> and nightclub in the <a href="/wiki/Hell%27s_Kitchen,_Manhattan" title="Hell's Kitchen, Manhattan">Hell's Kitchen</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>. Prior to its closure in March 2020 due to the <a href="/wiki/COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_York_City" title="COVID-19 pandemic in New York City">COVID-19 pandemic</a>, it hosted frequent drag shows, some of which featured performers who later rose to prominence on <i><a href="/wiki/RuPaul%27s_Drag_Race" title="RuPaul's Drag Race">RuPaul's Drag Race</a></i>. The venue was a favorite Monday-night stop for off-duty <a href="/wiki/Broadway_(theatre)" class="mw-redirect" title="Broadway (theatre)">Broadway</a> actors, who sometimes participated in that evening's show. </td> 
         <td><span style="font-family:Serifa"><a href="/wiki/User:Armadillopteryx" title="User:Armadillopteryx"><span style="color:#739900;">Armadillo</span></a><a href="/wiki/User_talk:Armadillopteryx" title="User talk:Armadillopteryx"><span style="color:#b3b300;">pteryx</span></a></span> and <a href="/wiki/User:Another_Believer" title="User:Another Believer">Another Believer</a> </td>

         <td>Headroom LGBTQ+ Lounge, also called simply Headroom, was a short-lived <a href="/wiki/Gay_bar" title="Gay bar">gay bar</a> in <a href="/wiki/Jersey_City,_New_Jersey" title="Jersey City, New Jersey">Jersey City, New Jersey</a>. It operated for six months, from November 2020 to May 2021. Though it was open only during the <a href="/wiki/COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_Jersey" title="COVID-19 pandemic in New Jersey">COVID-19 pandemic</a>, the venue proved to be popular and offered an array of live entertainment, including <a href="/wiki/Drag_show" title="Drag show">drag shows</a>, <a href="/wiki/Burlesque" title="Burlesque">burlesque</a> performances and <i><a href="/wiki/RuPaul%27s_Drag_Race" title="RuPaul's Drag Race">RuPaul's Drag Race</a></i> viewing parties. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/M1_(%C4%B0zmir_Metro)" title="M1 (?zmir Metro)">M1 (?zmir Metro)</a> (<small>?zmir Metro line</small>) </td> 
         <td>The M1, also known as the Fahrettin Altay–Evka 3 Line, is the only active line of <a href="/wiki/%C4%B0zmir_Metro" title="?zmir Metro">?zmir Metro</a> in <a href="/wiki/%C4%B0zmir" title="?zmir">?zmir, Turkey</a>. The line runs from <a href="/wiki/Fahrettin_Altay_(%C4%B0zmir_Metro)" title="Fahrettin Altay (?zmir Metro)">Fahrettin Altay</a> station in the west to <a href="/wiki/Evka_3_(%C4%B0zmir_Metro)" title="Evka 3 (?zmir Metro)">Evka 3</a> station in the east. The 19.8-kilometre (12.3&nbsp;mi) long line serves 17 stations. As of May 2021, the line is in the process of being extended a further 7.2 kilometres (4.5&nbsp;mi) west to Narl?dere, with operations expected to start in 2022. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Ahmetlii" title="User:Ahmetlii">Ahmetlii</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Ahmetlii" title="User talk:Ahmetlii">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td><i>China Arrow</i> was a <a href="/wiki/Steamboat" title="Steamboat">steam</a> <a href="/wiki/Tanker_(ship)" title="Tanker (ship)">tanker</a> built in 1920 by <a href="/wiki/Bethlehem_Shipbuilding_Corporation" title="Bethlehem Shipbuilding Corporation">Bethlehem Shipbuilding Corporation</a> of <a href="/wiki/Quincy,_Massachusetts" title="Quincy, Massachusetts">Quincy</a> for <a href="/wiki/Standard_Oil_Co." class="mw-redirect" title="Standard Oil Co.">Standard Oil Co.</a>, with intention of transporting oil and <a href="/wiki/Petroleum" title="Petroleum">petroleum</a> products between <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Far_East" title="Far East">Far East.</a> During the first part of her career the tanker was used to carry oil and gasoline between United States and Asia, later becoming a coastal tanker serving East Coast of the United States. </td>

         <td><i>India Arrow</i> was a steam tanker built in 1921 by <a href="/wiki/Bethlehem_Shipbuilding_Corporation" title="Bethlehem Shipbuilding Corporation">Bethlehem Shipbuilding Corporation</a> of <a href="/wiki/Quincy,_Massachusetts" title="Quincy, Massachusetts">Quincy</a> for <a href="/wiki/Standard_Oil_Co." class="mw-redirect" title="Standard Oil Co.">Standard Oil Co.</a>, with intention of transporting oil and petroleum products between United States and the Far East. After serving for approximately ten years in the Pacific trade, the tanker was moved to intercoastal trade routes in early 1930s where she remained for the rest of her career. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Japan_National_Route_119" title="Japan National Route 119">Japan National Route 119</a> (<small>National highway in Tochigi Prefecture, Japan</small>) </td> 
         <td>is a <a href="/wiki/National_highways_of_Japan" title="National highways of Japan">national highway</a> located entirely within <a href="/wiki/Tochigi_Prefecture" title="Tochigi Prefecture">Tochigi Prefecture</a>, <a href="/wiki/Japan" title="Japan">Japan</a>. It connects the city of <a href="/wiki/Nikk%C5%8D" title="Nikk?">Nikk?</a> to <a href="/wiki/Utsunomiya" title="Utsunomiya">Utsunomiya</a>, the prefecture's capital, and has a total length of 63.9 kilometers (39.7&nbsp;mi). The present-day highway largely follows the path of the <a href="/wiki/Nikk%C5%8D_Kaid%C5%8D" title="Nikk? Kaid?">Nikk? Kaid?</a>, an <a href="/wiki/Edo_period" title="Edo period">Edo period</a> <a href="/wiki/Kaid%C5%8D" title="Kaid?">road</a> that linked <a href="/wiki/Edo" title="Edo">Edo</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Shrines_and_Temples_of_Nikk%C5%8D" title="Shrines and Temples of Nikk?">Shrines and Temples of Nikk?</a> . </td>

         <td>Air India Express Flight 1344 was a scheduled international flight on 7 August 2020 from <a href="/wiki/Dubai" title="Dubai">Dubai</a>, United Arab Emirates, to <a href="/wiki/Kozhikode" title="Kozhikode">Kozhikode</a>, India, landing at <a href="/wiki/Calicut_International_Airport" title="Calicut International Airport">Calicut International Airport</a>. The flight was part of the <a href="/wiki/Vande_Bharat_Mission" class="mw-redirect" title="Vande Bharat Mission">Vande Bharat Mission</a> to repatriate Indian nationals stranded due to the <a href="/wiki/COVID-19_pandemic" title="COVID-19 pandemic">COVID-19 pandemic</a>. The flight crew <a href="/wiki/Go-around" title="Go-around">aborted two landing attempts</a> because of heavy rain and <a href="/wiki/Headwind_and_tailwind" title="Headwind and tailwind">tailwind</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Japanese_cruiser_Naniwa" title="Japanese cruiser Naniwa">Japanese cruiser Naniwa</a> </td> 
         <td>was the <a href="/wiki/Lead_ship" title="Lead ship">lead ship</a> of <a href="/wiki/Naniwa-class_cruiser" title="Naniwa-class cruiser">her class</a> of two <a href="/wiki/Protected_cruiser" title="Protected cruiser">protected cruisers</a> built for the <a href="/wiki/Imperial_Japanese_Navy" title="Imperial Japanese Navy">Imperial Japanese Navy</a> (IJN) in the 1880s. As Japan lacked the industrial capacity to construct such vessels, the ship was designed and built in the <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">United Kingdom</a>. She participated in the <a href="/wiki/First_Sino-Japanese_War" title="First Sino-Japanese War">First Sino-Japanese War</a> of 1894–1895, playing a major role in the <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_the_Yalu_River_(1894)" title="Battle of the Yalu River (1894)">Battle of the Yalu River</a> and lesser roles in the <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_L%C3%BCshunkou" title="Battle of Lüshunkou">Battles of Port Arthur</a>, <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_Weihaiwei" title="Battle of Weihaiwei">Weihaiwei</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Pescadores_Campaign_(1895)" class="mw-redirect" title="Pescadores Campaign (1895)">Pescadores Campaign</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Japanese_invasion_of_Taiwan_(1895)" title="Japanese invasion of Taiwan (1895)">invasion of Taiwan</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Amasa_Holcomb" title="Amasa Holcomb">Amasa Holcomb</a> (<small>American manufacturer of surveying instruments and telescopes</small>) </td> 
         <td>Amasa Holcomb (1787–1875) was an American farmer, surveyor, <a href="/wiki/Civil_engineer" title="Civil engineer">civil engineer</a>, businessman, politician, and <a href="/wiki/Manufacturer" class="mw-redirect" title="Manufacturer">manufacturer</a> of surveying instruments and <a href="/wiki/Telescopes" class="mw-redirect" title="Telescopes">telescopes</a>. From instruments he made he could observe the total solar eclipse of June&nbsp;16, 1806. He made astronomical computations from his observations and published almanacs for the partial solar eclipses of 1807 and 1808 from his work. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Doug_Coldwell" title="User:Doug Coldwell">Doug Coldwell</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Doug_Coldwell" title="User talk:Doug Coldwell">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Josiah_Holbrook" title="Josiah Holbrook">Josiah Holbrook</a> </td> 
         <td>Josiah Holbrook (1788–1854) was the initiator and organizer of the <a href="/wiki/Lyceum_movement" title="Lyceum movement">lyceum movement</a> in the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>. He formed the first <a href="/wiki/Lyceum" title="Lyceum">lyceum</a> school in the United States in 1826. His design and system was duplicated throughout the United states by hundreds of similar associations within a few years and the first nationwide organization of lyceum schools was formed. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Julius_Kahn_(inventor)" title="Julius Kahn (inventor)">Julius Kahn (inventor)</a> (<small>American inventor</small>) </td> 
         <td>Julius Kahn (March 8, 1874 – November 4, 1942) was an American engineer, industrialist, and manufacturer. He was the inventor of the <a href="/wiki/Kahn_System" class="mw-redirect" title="Kahn System">Kahn System</a>, a reinforced concrete engineering technique for building construction. The Kahn System, which he patented in 1903, was used worldwide for housing, factories, offices and industrial buildings. </td>

         <td class="recent">2021-04-16 09:55 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Henry_Fitz" title="Henry Fitz">Henry Fitz</a> </td> 
         <td>Henry Fitz was an American engineer, scientist, locksmith, <a href="/wiki/Optician" title="Optician">optician</a>, and inventor. As a teenager, one of his hobbies was <a href="/wiki/Astronomy" title="Astronomy">astronomy</a>, which led to him making telescopes. Fritz became a manufacturer of telescopes and the first American to make large high-end sophisticated <a href="/wiki/Refracting_telescope" title="Refracting telescope">refracting telescopes</a>. He made telescopes for wealthy individuals, institutions, colleges, and universities throughout the United States, some of which are still in use. </td>

         <td class="recent">2021-04-21 06:31 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Steinitz%27s_theorem" title="Steinitz's theorem">Steinitz's theorem</a> (<small>Characterizes graphs formed by edges and vertices of 3-dimensional convex polyhedra</small>) </td> 
         <td>In <a href="/wiki/Polyhedral_combinatorics" title="Polyhedral combinatorics">polyhedral combinatorics</a>, a branch of mathematics, Steinitz's theorem is a characterization of the <a href="/wiki/Undirected_graph" class="mw-redirect" title="Undirected graph">undirected graphs</a> formed by the edges and vertices of three-dimensional <a href="/wiki/Convex_polyhedron" class="mw-redirect" title="Convex polyhedron">convex polyhedra</a>: they are exactly the (<a href="/wiki/Simple_graph" class="mw-redirect" title="Simple graph">simple</a>) <a href="/wiki/Vertex_connectivity" class="mw-redirect" title="Vertex connectivity">3-vertex-connected</a> <a href="/wiki/Planar_graph" title="Planar graph">planar graphs</a> (with at least four <p>vertices). That is, every convex polyhedron forms a 3-connected planar graph, and every 3-connected planar graph can be represented as the graph of a convex polyhedron. </p> </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:David_Eppstein" title="User:David Eppstein">David Eppstein</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:David_Eppstein" title="User talk:David Eppstein">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="recent">2021-04-21 22:32 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Affine_symmetric_group" title="Affine symmetric group">Affine symmetric group</a> (<small>Mathematical structure</small>) </td> 
         <td>The affine symmetric groups are a family of mathematical structures that describe the symmetries of the <a href="/wiki/Number_line" title="Number line">number line</a> and the regular <a href="/wiki/Triangular_tiling" title="Triangular tiling">triangular tiling</a> of the plane, as well as related higher-dimensional objects. Each one is an infinite <a href="/wiki/Group_extension" title="Group extension">extension</a> of a finite <a href="/wiki/Symmetric_group" title="Symmetric group">symmetric group</a>, the group of <a href="/wiki/Permutation" title="Permutation">permutations</a> (rearrangements) of a finite set. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:JayBeeEll" title="User:JayBeeEll">JBL</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:JayBeeEll" title="User talk:JayBeeEll">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-12 07:55 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Bengal_tiger" title="Bengal tiger">Bengal tiger</a> (<small>Tiger population in Indian subcontinent</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Bengal tiger is a <a href="/wiki/Tiger" title="Tiger">tiger</a> from a specific population of the <i><a href="/wiki/Panthera_tigris_tigris" title="Panthera tigris tigris">Panthera tigris tigris</a></i> subspecies that is native to the <a href="/wiki/Indian_subcontinent" title="Indian subcontinent">Indian subcontinent</a>. It is threatened by <a href="/wiki/Poaching" title="Poaching">poaching</a>, <a href="/wiki/Habitat_loss" class="mw-redirect" title="Habitat loss">loss</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Habitat_fragmentation" title="Habitat fragmentation">fragmentation</a> of habitat, and was estimated at comprising fewer than 2,500 wild individuals by 2011. None of the Tiger Conservation Landscapes within its range is considered large enough to support an effective population of more than 250 adult individuals. </td> 
         <td><span style="color:#006400">Rush922<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Rush922" title="User talk:Rush922">(talk)</a></span> </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Serengeti_National_Park" title="Serengeti National Park">Serengeti National Park</a> (<small>National park in Tanzania, Africa</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Serengeti National Park is a <a href="/wiki/National_park" title="National park">national park</a> in <a href="/wiki/Tanzania" title="Tanzania">Tanzania</a> that stretches over 14,763&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (5,700&nbsp;sq&nbsp;mi). It is located in the <a href="/wiki/Mara_Region" title="Mara Region">Mara</a> and <a href="/wiki/Simiyu_Region" title="Simiyu Region">Simiyu</a> regions and contains 1.5 million ha of <a href="/wiki/Savanna" title="Savanna">savanna</a>. It is well known for the largest annual migration of over 1.5 million <a href="/wiki/Blue_wildebeest" title="Blue wildebeest">blue wildebeest</a> and 250,000 <a href="/wiki/Zebra" title="Zebra">zebra</a> and for its numerous <a href="/wiki/Nile_crocodile" title="Nile crocodile">Nile crocodile</a> and <a href="/wiki/Honey_badger" title="Honey badger">honey badger</a>. </td> 
         <td><span style="background-color: azure"><a href="/wiki/User:TheEpicSnek" title="User:TheEpicSnek"><span style="color: #008080">EpicSnek </span></a> <a href="/wiki/User_talk:TheEpicSnek" title="User talk:TheEpicSnek"><sup><span style="color: RoyalBlue"> Talk to me here </span></sup></a> </span> </td>

         <td>Typhoon Mujigae, known in the <a href="/wiki/Philippines" title="Philippines">Philippines</a> as Tropical Storm Kabayan, was the strongest <a href="/wiki/Typhoon" title="Typhoon">typhoon</a> to strike the province of <a href="/wiki/Guangdong" title="Guangdong">Guangdong</a> in the month of October and the costliest typhoon to impact <a href="/wiki/China" title="China">China</a> in 2015. The typhoon caused widespread damage in the Chinese provinces of Guangdong, <a href="/wiki/Guangxi" title="Guangxi">Guangxi</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Hainan" title="Hainan">Hainan</a> from October&nbsp;3 to 6, 2015; earlier in its existence it impacted the Philippines as a developing <a href="/wiki/Tropical_cyclone" title="Tropical cyclone">tropical cyclone</a>, and later on it brought heavy rain to <a href="/wiki/Thailand" title="Thailand">Thailand</a> and <a href="/wiki/Vietnam" title="Vietnam">Vietnam</a>. </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-30 20:43 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Pick%27s_theorem" title="Pick's theorem">Pick's theorem</a> (<small>Formula for the area of a polygon with integer coordinates</small>) </td> 
         <td>In <a href="/wiki/Geometry" title="Geometry">geometry</a>, Pick's theorem provides a formula for the <a href="/wiki/Area" title="Area">area</a> of a <a href="/wiki/Simple_polygon" title="Simple polygon">simple polygon</a> with integer <a href="/wiki/Vertex_(geometry)" title="Vertex (geometry)">vertex</a> coordinates, in terms of the number of integer points within it and on its boundary. The result was first described by <a href="/wiki/Georg_Alexander_Pick" title="Georg Alexander Pick">Georg Alexander Pick</a> in 1899, and popularized in English by <a href="/wiki/Hugo_Steinhaus" title="Hugo Steinhaus">Hugo Steinhaus</a> in the 1950 edition of his book <i>Mathematical Snapshots</i>. It has multiple proofs, and can be generalized to formulas for certain kinds of non-simple polygons. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:David_Eppstein" title="User:David Eppstein">David Eppstein</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:David_Eppstein" title="User talk:David Eppstein">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>

         <td class="new">2021-06-01 12:35 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Charles_F._Conrad" title="Charles F. Conrad">Charles F. Conrad</a> </td> 
         <td>Charles Frederick Conrad (July 8, 1917 – February 9, 1995) was the founder of the <a href="/wiki/SS_Badger#Lake_Michigan_Carferry_Service" title="SS Badger">LMC Lake Michigan Car Ferry service</a>. He is also known as an industrialist who made environmental test chambers for the aircraft and aerospace industries. His test chambers were also used by the commercial industry, rocket industry, <a href="/wiki/National_Aeronautic_and_Space_Administration" class="mw-redirect" title="National Aeronautic and Space Administration">National Aeronautic and Space Administration</a>, and the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Armed_Forces" title="United States Armed Forces">United States Armed Forces</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Casparian_strip" title="Casparian strip">Casparian strip</a> (<small>Thickening in the root endodermis of vascular plants</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Casparian strip is a band-like thickening in the center of the <a href="/wiki/Root" title="Root">root</a> <a href="/wiki/Endodermis" title="Endodermis">endodermis</a> (radial and <a href="/wiki/Cell_walls" class="mw-redirect" title="Cell walls">cell walls</a>) of <a href="/wiki/Vascular_plants" class="mw-redirect" title="Vascular plants">vascular plants</a> (<a href="/wiki/Pteridophyte" title="Pteridophyte">Pteridophytes</a> and <a href="/wiki/Spermatophyte" title="Spermatophyte">Spermatophytes</a>). The composition of the region is mainly <a href="/wiki/Lignin" title="Lignin">lignin</a>, and its width varies between species. The Casparian strip is impervious to water so can control the <a href="/wiki/Transpiration_stream" title="Transpiration stream">transportation of water</a> and inorganic salts between the <a href="/wiki/Cortex_(botany)" title="Cortex (botany)">cortex</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Vascular_bundle" title="Vascular bundle">vascular bundle</a>, preventing water and inorganic salts from being transported to the [[Stele ... </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Rice%27s_whale" title="Rice's whale">Rice's whale</a> (<small>Species of baleen whale</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Rice's whale (<i>Balaenoptera ricei</i>) is a <a href="/wiki/Species" title="Species">species</a> of <a href="/wiki/Baleen_whale" title="Baleen whale">baleen whale</a> endemic to the northern <a href="/wiki/Gulf_of_Mexico" title="Gulf of Mexico">Gulf of Mexico</a>. It was previously identified as a <a href="/wiki/Population_ecology" title="Population ecology">subpopulation</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Bryde%27s_whale" title="Bryde's whale">Bryde's whale</a> and called the Gulf of Mexico whale. <a href="/wiki/Genetics" title="Genetics">Genetic</a> and skeletal studies found it to be a distinct species by 2021. In outward appearance, it is virtually identical to the Bryde's whale. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Turtle" title="Turtle">Turtle</a> (<small>Reptiles with a bony or cartilaginous shell</small>) </td> 
         <td>Turtles are <a href="/wiki/Reptile" title="Reptile">reptiles</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Order_(biology)" title="Order (biology)">order</a> Chelonia or Testudines . They are characterized by a <a href="/wiki/Bone" title="Bone">bony</a> or <a href="/wiki/Cartilage" title="Cartilage">cartilaginous</a> <a href="/wiki/Turtle_shell" title="Turtle shell">shell</a>, developed from their <a href="/wiki/Rib" title="Rib">ribs</a>, that acts as a <a href="/wiki/Shield" title="Shield">shield</a>. Testudines include both extant (living) and <a href="/wiki/Extinction" title="Extinction">extinct</a> species. Its earliest known members date from the <a href="/wiki/Middle_Jurassic" title="Middle Jurassic">Middle Jurassic</a>. </td>

         <td><i>Fontainea venosa</i>, also commonly known as southern blushwood, veiny fontainea, Queensland fontainea and formerly named as Bahrs scrub fontainea is a rare <a href="/wiki/Rainforest" title="Rainforest">rainforest</a> shrub or tree of the family <a href="/wiki/Euphorbiaceae" title="Euphorbiaceae">Euphorbiaceae</a>. It is found in south eastern <a href="/wiki/Queensland" title="Queensland">Queensland</a>, Australia, extending from <a href="/wiki/Boyne_Valley,_Queensland" title="Boyne Valley, Queensland">Boyne Valley</a> to <a href="/wiki/Cedar_Creek,_Queensland_(Logan_%26_Gold_Coast)" title="Cedar Creek, Queensland (Logan &amp; Gold Coast)">Cedar Creek</a> and is considered vulnerable due to several contributing threats (<a href="/wiki/Fire" title="Fire">fire</a>, urban development, and weed infestation). </td>

         <td class="recent">2021-04-06 01:16 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/CYP4F2" title="CYP4F2">CYP4F2</a> </td> 
         <td>Leukotriene-B(4) omega-hydroxylase 1 is an <a href="/wiki/Enzyme" title="Enzyme">enzyme</a> protein involved in the <a href="/wiki/Metabolism" title="Metabolism">metabolism</a> of various <a href="/wiki/Endogenous" class="mw-redirect" title="Endogenous">endogenous</a> <a href="/wiki/Substrate_(chemistry)" title="Substrate (chemistry)">substrates</a> (mainly the <a href="/wiki/Fatty_acids" class="mw-redirect" title="Fatty acids">fatty acids</a>) and <a href="/wiki/Xenobiotics" class="mw-redirect" title="Xenobiotics">xenobiotics</a> (including <a href="/wiki/Pharmaceutical_drugs" class="mw-redirect" title="Pharmaceutical drugs">pharmaceutical drugs</a>). The most notable substrate of the enzyme is <a href="/wiki/Leukotriene_B4" title="Leukotriene B4">leukotriene B4</a>, a potent mediator of inflammation. The <i>CYP4F2</i> gene encodes the enzyme in humans. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Maxim_Masiutin" title="User:Maxim Masiutin">Maxim Masiutin</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Maxim_Masiutin" title="User talk:Maxim Masiutin">talk</a>) </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-24 16:51 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Radium" title="Radium">Radium</a> (<small>Chemical element, symbol Ra and atomic number 88</small>) </td> 
         <td>Radium is a <a href="/wiki/Chemical_element" title="Chemical element">chemical element</a> with the <a href="/wiki/Symbol_(chemistry)" class="mw-redirect" title="Symbol (chemistry)">symbol</a>&nbsp;Ra and <a href="/wiki/Atomic_number" title="Atomic number">atomic number</a>&nbsp;88. It is the sixth element in <a href="/wiki/Alkaline_earth_metal" title="Alkaline earth metal">group 2</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Periodic_table" title="Periodic table">periodic table</a>, also known as the <a href="/wiki/Alkaline_earth_metal" title="Alkaline earth metal">alkaline earth metals</a>. Pure radium is silvery-white, but it readily reacts with nitrogen (rather than oxygen) on exposure to air, forming a black surface layer of radium nitride (Ra<sub>3</sub>N<sub>2</sub>). </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Keresluna" title="User:Keresluna">Keres?</a>(<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Keresluna" title="User talk:Keresluna">talk</a> • <a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/Keresluna" title="Special:Contributions/Keresluna">ctb</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-06-05 13:57 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Vitamin_B6" title="Vitamin B6">Vitamin B6</a> (<small>Class of chemically related vitamins</small>) </td> 
         <td>Vitamin B<sub>6</sub> is one of the <a href="/wiki/B_vitamins" title="B vitamins">B vitamins</a>, and thus an <a href="/wiki/Essential_nutrient" class="mw-redirect" title="Essential nutrient">essential nutrient</a>. The term refers to a group of chemically similar compounds, "<a href="/wiki/Vitamer" title="Vitamer">vitamers</a>", which can be interconverted in biological systems. Its active form, <a href="/wiki/Pyridoxal_phosphate" title="Pyridoxal phosphate">pyridoxal 5?-phosphate</a>, serves as a <a href="/wiki/Coenzyme" class="mw-redirect" title="Coenzyme">coenzyme</a> in some 100 <a href="/wiki/Enzyme" title="Enzyme">enzyme</a> reactions in <a href="/wiki/Amino_acid" title="Amino acid">amino acid</a>, <a href="/wiki/Glucose" title="Glucose">glucose</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Lipid" title="Lipid">lipid</a> metabolism. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:David_notMD" title="User:David notMD">David notMD</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:David_notMD" title="User talk:David notMD">talk</a>) </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Bucket_queue" title="Bucket queue">Bucket queue</a> </td> 
         <td>In the design and analysis of <a href="/wiki/Data_structure" title="Data structure">data structures</a>, a bucket queue (also called a bucket priority queue or bounded-height priority queue) is a <a href="/wiki/Priority_queue" title="Priority queue">priority queue</a> for prioritizing elements whose priorities are small <a href="/wiki/Integer" title="Integer">integers</a>. It has the form of an array of buckets: an <a href="/wiki/Array_data_structure" title="Array data structure">array data structure</a>, indexed by the priorities, whose cells contain <a href="/wiki/Bucket_(computing)" title="Bucket (computing)">buckets</a> of items with the same priority as each other. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/1997_Central_Texas_tornado_outbreak" title="1997 Central Texas tornado outbreak">1997 Central Texas tornado outbreak</a> (<small>Tornado outbreak in Texas</small>) </td> 
         <td>A deadly <a href="/wiki/Tornado_outbreak" title="Tornado outbreak">tornado outbreak</a> occurred in <a href="/wiki/Central_Texas" title="Central Texas">Central Texas</a> during the afternoon and evening of May 27, 1997, in conjunction with a southwestward-moving cluster of <a href="/wiki/Supercell" title="Supercell">supercell</a> thunderstorms. These storms produced 20&nbsp;tornadoes, mainly along the <a href="/wiki/Interstate_35" title="Interstate 35">Interstate 35</a> corridor from northeast of <a href="/wiki/Waco" class="mw-redirect" title="Waco">Waco</a> to north of <a href="/wiki/San_Antonio" title="San Antonio">San Antonio</a>. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Rice%27s_whale" title="Rice's whale">Rice's whale</a> (<small>Species of baleen whale</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Rice's whale (<i>Balaenoptera ricei</i>) is a <a href="/wiki/Species" title="Species">species</a> of <a href="/wiki/Baleen_whale" title="Baleen whale">baleen whale</a> endemic to the northern <a href="/wiki/Gulf_of_Mexico" title="Gulf of Mexico">Gulf of Mexico</a>. It was previously identified as a <a href="/wiki/Population_ecology" title="Population ecology">subpopulation</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Bryde%27s_whale" title="Bryde's whale">Bryde's whale</a> and called the Gulf of Mexico whale. <a href="/wiki/Genetics" title="Genetics">Genetic</a> and skeletal studies found it to be a distinct species by 2021. In outward appearance, it is virtually identical to the Bryde's whale. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Macrophyseter" title="User:Macrophyseter"><b><i style="font-family: Mistral; color:#000">Macrophyseter</i></b></a> | <a href="/wiki/User_talk:Macrophyseter" title="User talk:Macrophyseter"><span style="font-family: Consolas; color:#000">talk</span></a> </td>

         <td class="new">2021-05-26 03:59 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Bremer_Marine_Park" title="Bremer Marine Park">Bremer Marine Park</a> (<small>Marine protected area off Western Australia</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Bremer Marine Park area is a protected South-West Marine park extending out from <a href="/wiki/Bremer_Bay" class="mw-redirect" title="Bremer Bay">Bremer Bay</a>. It is located on the South-West Coast of Australia between Albany and Esperance at 34°45’ South and 119°50’ East. It occupies approximately 4,472&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (1,727&nbsp;sq&nbsp;mi) and reaches depths of 5900m. It is zoned by the Australian government under the ‘South West Marine Parks Management plan 2018’ as a <a href="/wiki/National_park" title="National park">national park</a> and hence protects numerous of <a href="/wiki/Flora" title="Flora">flora</a> and <a href="/wiki/Fauna" title="Fauna">fauna</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Alexsurfing" title="User:Alexsurfing">Alexsurfing</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Alexsurfing" title="User talk:Alexsurfing">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-31 17:22 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Meteorological_history_of_Hurricane_Iota" title="Meteorological history of Hurricane Iota">Meteorological history of Hurricane Iota</a> (<small>Meteorological history of a Category 4 hurricane in 2020</small>) </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Hurricane_Iota" title="Hurricane Iota">Hurricane Iota</a> was the second-most powerful November tropical cyclone on record in the <a href="/wiki/Atlantic_tropical_cyclone" class="mw-redirect" title="Atlantic tropical cyclone">Atlantic basin</a>. At the end of October 2020, a <a href="/wiki/Tropical_wave" title="Tropical wave">tropical wave</a> emerged off Africa and traversed the Atlantic Ocean with little note. The system later impacted northern South America and the Lesser Antilles before becoming more organized, eventually becoming a tropical depression on November&nbsp;13 over the <a href="/wiki/Caribbean_Sea" title="Caribbean Sea">Caribbean Sea</a>. </td> 
         <td>~ <a href="/wiki/User:Cyclonebiskit" title="User:Cyclonebiskit">Cyclonebiskit</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Cyclonebiskit" title="User talk:Cyclonebiskit">chat</a>) </td>
