         <td>In the design and analysis of <a href="/wiki/Data_structure" title="Data structure">data structures</a>, a bucket queue (also called a bucket priority queue or bounded-height priority queue) is a <a href="/wiki/Priority_queue" title="Priority queue">priority queue</a> for prioritizing elements whose priorities are small <a href="/wiki/Integer" title="Integer">integers</a>. It has the form of an array of buckets: an <a href="/wiki/Array_data_structure" title="Array data structure">array data structure</a>, indexed by the priorities, whose cells contain <a href="/wiki/Bucket_(computing)" title="Bucket (computing)">buckets</a> of items with the same priority as each other. </td>

      <h2><span id="STEM.2FMedicine_.26_Health"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="STEM/Medicine_&amp;_Health">STEM/Medicine &amp; Health</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=User:SDZeroBot/GAN_sorting&amp;action=edit&amp;section=53" title="Edit section: STEM/Medicine &amp; Health">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>

        <tr> 
         <th scope="col" class="date-header">Date </th>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Yoga_using_props" title="Yoga using props">Yoga using props</a> </td> 
         <td>Props such as chairs, <a href="/wiki/Yoga_brick" title="Yoga brick">blocks</a>, belts, <a href="/wiki/Yoga_mat" title="Yoga mat">mats</a>, blankets and bolsters are used in <a href="/wiki/Yoga_as_exercise" title="Yoga as exercise">postural yoga</a> to assist with correct alignment in an <a href="/wiki/Asana" title="Asana">asana</a>, for ease in <a href="/wiki/Mindful_yoga" class="mw-redirect" title="Mindful yoga">mindful yoga</a> practice, to enable poses to be held for longer periods in <a href="/wiki/Yin_Yoga" title="Yin Yoga">Yin Yoga</a>, where support may allow muscles to relax, and to enable people with movement restricted for any reason, such as stiffness, injury, or <a href="/wiki/Arthritis" title="Arthritis">arthritis</a>, to continue with their practice. </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Hepatic_hydrothorax" title="Hepatic hydrothorax">Hepatic hydrothorax</a> (<small>Medical condition</small>) </td> 
         <td>Hepatic hydrothorax is a rare form of <a href="/wiki/Pleural_effusion" title="Pleural effusion">pleural effusion</a> that occurs in people with <a href="/wiki/Liver_Cirrhosis" class="mw-redirect" title="Liver Cirrhosis">liver cirrhosis</a>. It is defined as over 500 mL of pleural fluid in people affected by decompensated liver cirrhosis without being caused by heart, lung, or pleural diseases. It is found in 5-10% of cirrhosis cases and 2-3% of all pleural effusions. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Aeschylus" title="User:Aeschylus">aeschylus</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Aeschylus" title="User talk:Aeschylus">talk</a>) </td>

         <td>The Royal Commission on Animal Magnetism involved two entirely separate and independent French Royal Commissions, each appointed by <a href="/wiki/Louis_XVI" title="Louis XVI">Louis XVI</a> in 1784, that were conducted simultaneously by a committee composed of five scientists from the <a href="/wiki/French_Academy_of_Sciences" title="French Academy of Sciences">Royal Academy of Sciences (<i>Académie des sciences</i>)</a> and four physicians from the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Paris#Faculties" title="University of Paris">Paris Faculty of Medicine (<i>Faculté de médecine de Paris</i>)</a> (i.e., the "Franklin Commission"), and a second committee composed of five physicians from the [[Pa ... </td>

         <td><a href="/wiki/Vitamin_B6" title="Vitamin B6">Vitamin B6</a> (<small>Class of chemically related vitamins</small>) </td> 
         <td>Vitamin B<sub>6</sub> is one of the <a href="/wiki/B_vitamins" title="B vitamins">B vitamins</a>, and thus an <a href="/wiki/Essential_nutrient" class="mw-redirect" title="Essential nutrient">essential nutrient</a>. The term refers to a group of chemically similar compounds, "<a href="/wiki/Vitamer" title="Vitamer">vitamers</a>", which can be interconverted in biological systems. Its active form, <a href="/wiki/Pyridoxal_phosphate" title="Pyridoxal phosphate">pyridoxal 5?-phosphate</a>, serves as a <a href="/wiki/Coenzyme" class="mw-redirect" title="Coenzyme">coenzyme</a> in some 100 <a href="/wiki/Enzyme" title="Enzyme">enzyme</a> reactions in <a href="/wiki/Amino_acid" title="Amino acid">amino acid</a>, <a href="/wiki/Glucose" title="Glucose">glucose</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Lipid" title="Lipid">lipid</a> metabolism. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:David_notMD" title="User:David notMD">David notMD</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:David_notMD" title="User talk:David notMD">talk</a>) </td>

      <h2><span id="STEM.2FPhysics"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="STEM/Physics">STEM/Physics</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=User:SDZeroBot/GAN_sorting&amp;action=edit&amp;section=54" title="Edit section: STEM/Physics">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <table class="wikitable sortable"> 
       <tbody>
        <tr> 
         <th scope="col" class="date-header">Date </th> 
         <th scope="col" class="article-header">Article </th>

        <tr> 
         <td class="old">2021-02-26 07:27 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/T2K_experiment" title="T2K experiment">T2K experiment</a> </td> 
         <td>T2K ("<a href="/wiki/T%C5%8Dkai,_Ibaraki" title="T?kai, Ibaraki">Tokai</a> to <a href="/wiki/Kamioka,_Gifu" class="mw-redirect" title="Kamioka, Gifu">Kamioka</a>") is a <a href="/wiki/Particle_physics" title="Particle physics">particle physics</a> experiment studying the <a href="/wiki/Neutrino_oscillations" class="mw-redirect" title="Neutrino oscillations">oscillations</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Accelerator_neutrinos" class="mw-redirect" title="Accelerator neutrinos">accelerator neutrinos</a>. The experiment is conducted in <a href="/wiki/Japan" title="Japan">Japan</a> by the international cooperation of about 500 physicists and engineers with over 60 research institutions from several countries from <a href="/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">Europe</a>, <a href="/wiki/Asia" title="Asia">Asia</a> and <a href="/wiki/North_America" title="North America">North America</a> and it is a recognized <a href="/wiki/CERN" title="CERN">CERN</a> experiment (RE13). </td> 
         <td><a href="/w/index.php?title=User:Batmann&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="User:Batmann (page does not exist)">Batmann</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Batmann" title="User talk:Batmann">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="new">2021-05-19 09:36 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Standard_Model" title="Standard Model">Standard Model</a> (<small>Theory describing fundamental forces, except gravity</small>) </td> 
         <td>The Standard Model of <a href="/wiki/Particle_physics" title="Particle physics">particle physics</a> is the theory describing three of the four known <a href="/wiki/Fundamental_force" class="mw-redirect" title="Fundamental force">fundamental forces</a> (the <a href="/wiki/Electromagnetism" title="Electromagnetism">electromagnetic</a>, <a href="/wiki/Weak_interaction" title="Weak interaction">weak</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Strong_interaction" title="Strong interaction">strong</a> interactions, and not including <a href="/wiki/Gravity" title="Gravity">gravity</a>) in the <a href="/wiki/Universe" title="Universe">universe</a>, as well as classifying all known <a href="/wiki/Elementary_particle" title="Elementary particle">elementary particles</a>. It was developed in stages throughout the latter half of the 20th century, through the work of many scientists around the world, with the current formulation being finalized in the mid-1970s upon <a href="/wiki/Experimental_confirmation" class="mw-redirect" title="Experimental confirmation">experimental confirmation</a> of the existence of <a href="/wiki/Quark" title="Quark">quarks</a>. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Special:Contributions/2405:201:600B:C02A:65D7:6FF2:9258:F4E2" title="Special:Contributions/2405:201:600B:C02A:65D7:6FF2:9258:F4E2">2405:201:600B:C02A:65D7:6FF2:9258:F4E2</a> (<a href="/w/index.php?title=User_talk:2405:201:600B:C02A:65D7:6FF2:9258:F4E2&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="User talk:2405:201:600B:C02A:65D7:6FF2:9258:F4E2 (page does not exist)">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr>
       </tbody>
      </table>

         <td><a href="/wiki/SpaceX" title="SpaceX">SpaceX</a> (<small>American private aerospace company</small>) </td> 
         <td>Space Exploration Technologies Corp. (SpaceX) is an American <a href="/wiki/Aerospace_manufacturer" title="Aerospace manufacturer">aerospace manufacturer</a>, <a href="/wiki/Space_transportation" class="mw-redirect" title="Space transportation">space transportation</a> services and <a href="/wiki/Telecommunication" title="Telecommunication">communications</a> company headquartered in <a href="/wiki/Hawthorne,_California" title="Hawthorne, California">Hawthorne, California</a>. SpaceX was founded in 2002 by <a href="/wiki/Elon_Musk" title="Elon Musk">Elon Musk</a> with the goal of reducing space transportation costs to enable the <a href="/wiki/Colonization_of_Mars" title="Colonization of Mars">colonization of Mars</a>. </td>

      <h2><span id="STEM.2FTechnology"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="STEM/Technology">STEM/Technology</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=User:SDZeroBot/GAN_sorting&amp;action=edit&amp;section=56" title="Edit section: STEM/Technology">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>

        <tr> 
         <td class="old">2021-01-16 11:11 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Energy_in_Turkey" title="Energy in Turkey">Energy in Turkey</a> (<small>Overview of the production, consumption, import and export of energy and electricity in Turkey</small>) </td> 
         <td>Consumption of energy in Turkey is around the <a href="/wiki/List_of_countries_by_energy_consumption_per_capita" title="List of countries by energy consumption per capita">world average</a> of about seventy <a href="/wiki/Gigajoules" class="mw-redirect" title="Gigajoules">gigajoules</a> (GJ) per person per year. In total, Turkey <a href="/wiki/World_energy_consumption" title="World energy consumption">uses</a> about six billion GJ of <a href="/wiki/Primary_energy" title="Primary energy">primary energy</a> per year: over 80% from <a href="/wiki/Fossil_fuels" class="mw-redirect" title="Fossil fuels">fossil fuels</a>. From 1990 to 2017 annual primary energy supply tripled, but then remained constant to 2019. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Chidgk1" title="User:Chidgk1">Chidgk1</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Chidgk1" title="User talk:Chidgk1">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="old">2021-02-12 09:35 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Electricity_sector_in_Turkey" title="Electricity sector in Turkey">Electricity sector in Turkey</a> (<small>Electricity generation, transmission and consumption in Turkey</small>) </td> 
         <td>Each year, about<span class="nowrap">&nbsp;</span>300 <a href="/wiki/Kilowatt-hour#Watt-hour_multiples" title="Kilowatt-hour">terawatt-hours (TWh)</a> of <a href="/wiki/Electricity" title="Electricity">electricity</a> is used in <a href="/wiki/Turkey" title="Turkey">Turkey</a>—a fifth of the <a href="/wiki/Energy_in_Turkey" title="Energy in Turkey">energy used</a> and about 3 kilowatt-hours (kWh) per person per day. The <a href="/wiki/Carbon_intensity" class="mw-redirect" title="Carbon intensity">carbon intensity</a> of generation during the 2010s was about 400 grams of <a href="/wiki/Carbon_dioxide" title="Carbon dioxide">CO<sub>2</sub></a> per kWh (gCO<sub>2</sub>/kWh), slightly less than the global average. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Chidgk1" title="User:Chidgk1">Chidgk1</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Chidgk1" title="User talk:Chidgk1">talk</a>) </td>
        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td class="old">2021-03-05 06:11 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/GPT-2" title="GPT-2">GPT-2</a> (<small>2019 text-generating language model</small>) </td> 
         <td>Generative Pre-trained Transformer 2 (GPT-2) is an <a href="/wiki/Open-source" class="mw-redirect" title="Open-source">open-source</a> <a href="/wiki/Artificial_intelligence" title="Artificial intelligence">artificial intelligence</a> created by <a href="/wiki/OpenAI" title="OpenAI">OpenAI</a> in February 2019. GPT-2 <a href="/wiki/Machine_translation" title="Machine translation">translates</a> text, answers questions, summarizes passages, and generates text output on a level that, while sometimes <a href="/wiki/Turing_test" title="Turing test">indistinguishable from that of humans</a>, can become repetitive or nonsensical when generating long passages. </td> 
         <td><b><a href="/wiki/User:JPxG" title="User:JPxG">jp</a></b>×<b><a href="/wiki/User_talk:JPxG" title="User talk:JPxG">g</a></b> </td>
        </tr>

         <td>The dot-com bubble (also known as the dot-com boom, the tech bubble, and the Internet bubble) was a <a href="/wiki/Stock_market_bubble" title="Stock market bubble">stock market bubble</a> caused by excessive <a href="/wiki/Speculation" title="Speculation">speculation</a> of Internet-related companies in the late 1990s, a period of massive growth in the use and adoption of the <a href="/wiki/Internet" title="Internet">Internet</a>. </td>

         <td class="old">2020-12-24 03:30 </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/Interlingue" title="Interlingue">Interlingue</a> (<small>International auxiliary language created 1922</small>) </td> 
         <td>Interlingue (; <a href="/wiki/ISO_639" title="ISO 639">ISO 639</a> language codes <i>ie</i>, <i>ile</i>), known until 1949 as Occidental (), is an <a href="/wiki/International_auxiliary_language" title="International auxiliary language">international auxiliary language</a> published for the first time in 1922. Its creator, <a href="/wiki/Edgar_de_Wahl" title="Edgar de Wahl">Edgar de Wahl</a>, devised it to achieve a maximum of both grammatical regularity and natural character. </td> 
         <td><a href="/wiki/User:Mithridates" title="User:Mithridates">Mithridates</a> (<a href="/wiki/User_talk:Mithridates" title="User talk:Mithridates">talk</a>) </td>
